<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO HELP AN ASIA IN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new byline, updating and rewriting throughout)   (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-REPUBS, CHINA-NOTEBOOK)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic on Clinton's China trip is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton said Friday that ``cronyism,
corruption and overextended credit,'' unchecked by competent
financial regulation, had led to the economic maelstrom now
sweeping Asia and has spread to Hong Kong, plunging it into its
deepest recession in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis has touched nearly all the nations and households
of Asia,'' Clinton said in an address at the soaring harbor-front
Hong Kong convention center. ``Restoring economic growth and
confidence will not be easy, but the United States will do all we
can to help any Asian government work its way back to financial
health.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first comment by a U.S. official on the banking reform
measures announced by Japan on Thursday, Clinton Friday endorsed
the proposals that are intended to create an emergency $200 billion
fund to protect businesses and depositors in need of bridge loans
to weather the financial storm. He called Tokyo's program
``potentially quite significant'' and said the United States
welcomed it as a partial means to ease the impact of the crisis on
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also praised Beijing, as he has several times on this
nine-day trip to China, for what he called the ``disciplined and
wise policy'' of resisting the temptation to devalue its currency,
the yuan, to boost exports and hard-currency earnings. Allowing the
value of the Chinese currency to fall, Clinton warned, could lead
to ``competitive devaluations that could threaten China, the
regional economies and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to several hundred business leaders in a morning
event sponsored by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council and the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived here Thursday evening, Clinton pledged that the
United States would do its part to lift Asia out of its economic
quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that the United States considers Hong Kong
vital to the future,'' Clinton said at a banquet where the chief
executive of Hong Kong, Tung Chee-hwa, was the host. ``This present
financial crisis, too, will pass, if we work together with
discipline and vision to lift the fortunes of our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Hong Kong, the first by a sitting U.S.
president, came one day after the former British colony marked the
first anniversary of its return to China. And it gives him the
opportunity to assess one of the grander experiments in modern
political history: China's pledge to let Hong Kong remain a
capitalist enclave in the world's last communist empire.
</P>
<P>
   These days, economics are overshadowing politics here. Hong Kong
is suffering badly from the Asian financial contagion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong is a world symbol of trade, enterprise, freedom and
global interdependence,'' Clinton said, looking weary despite
having relaxed earlier in the day on a two-hour boat trip on the Li
River near Guilin, in south China. He used the visit to Guilin to
discuss China's dire environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   After flying here he praised Hong Kong and China for being
anchors of stability in a region-wide economic storm _ a reference
to the fact that neither government has devalued its currency,
despite the continued weakness of the Japanese yen and a wave of
tit-for-tat devaluations across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Tung, a shipping magnate appointed by Beijing shortly before the
hand over, welcomed the president's show of support, saying that
``what started as a regional crisis has taken on a global
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met privately with Tung for 20 minutes before the
banquet, during which they discussed the economy, according to
White House press secretary Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton also pressed Tung to accelerate the
introduction of democracy to Hong Kong by allowing voters to elect
a larger percentage of legislators directly.
</P>
<P>
   Tung, who long lived in the West, is not known as a champion of
democracy. In his remarks at the banquet, he pointedly reminded
Clinton that Hong Kong was a Chinese city. ``The fact is, we are
Chinese and were brought up in Chinese tradition and values,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Clinton sampled the new Hong Kong _ with a hectic series
of meetings and appearances that brought him in contact with
newly-elected politicians, both friendly and hostile to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   James Steinberg, the deputy assistant to the president for
national security affairs, said the Clinton administration wanted
to demonstrate that the United States ``continues to be active and
involved and concerned about preserving Hong Kong's autonomy and
strengthening democracy there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House has landed in a minor tempest over a meeting
with Hong Kong's most prominent pro-democracy leader, Martin Lee.
Clinton was scheduled to meet alone with Lee on Friday, a move
likely to displease Beijing. The White House barred press coverage
of the meeting, except for a photographer. It said it would issue
no public statements afterward, upsetting Lee and his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the restrictions were ``normal practice'' when
Clinton meets with opposition leaders. Lee's aides said the White
House was seeking to assuage the Chinese, and had originally balked
at a one-on-one meeting, even though Lee has met Clinton before in
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If true, the White House may have ended up irking both sides.
Lee said he found the decision ``very odd, because it seems to me
that President Clinton's whole visit to China has been televised.
Why does he stop with me?''
</P>
<P>
   After that meeting, Clinton was scheduled to sit down with a
group of Hong Kong leaders, including Lee and three other
popularly-elected legislators. Among them was Tsang Yok-sing, a
former high school principal and avowed Marxist who heads the main
pro-Beijing party in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The President also planned to meet with senior civil servants,
and the head of Hong Kong's government-owned broadcasting outlet,
Radio Television Hong Kong, Cheung Man-yee. RTHK has been harshly
criticized by pro-Beijing people here for undermining the local
government and being disloyal to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was among the first passengers to land at Hong Kong's
new $20 billion airport _ touching down 10 hours after Chinese
President Jiang Zemin dedicated the vast complex _ and became its
first departing passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Like some Hong Kong residents, though, Clinton expressed
nostalgia for the old airport, Kai Tak, which was famous for the
rooftop-skimming approaches made by planes as they landed. Clinton,
who sat in the cockpit of a plane as it landed at Kai Tak on a
visit to Hong Kong more than a decade ago, said, ``It was one of
the most exciting and uncertain experiences of my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Before flying to Hong Kong, Clinton spoke on the environmental
hazards confronting China. With the spectacular limestone peaks of
the southern city of Guilin as a backdrop, Clinton said that 5 of
the world's 10 most polluted cities are in China and virtually
every body of water in the country is tainted with human and
industrial waste. But, he said, China did not have to sacrifice its
environment to continue to build its economy.
</P>
<P>
   He urged China to build more energy-efficient cars, homes and
factories. The alternative, he said, was further environmental
degradation and ultimately, slower economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The president, addressing a small, carefully-screened audience
at a park in Guilin, one of China's most popular tourist
destinations, said that not long ago American cities were choked
with smog and many of its urban waterways were seriously polluted.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's extraordinary growth has put the same kind of pressure
on your environment, and the costs of growth are rising right along
with your prosperity,'' the president said. ``You know better than
I that polluted air and water are threatening your remarkable
progress. Smog has caused entire Chinese cities to disappear from
satellite photographs. And respiratory illness is China's No. 1
health problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
