<HEADER>
A9085 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-FINDING     07-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-FINDINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNOPSIS OF FLOYD ABRAMS' FINDINGS CONCERNING CNN REPORT ON NERVE
GAS USE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, the laywer specializing in First Amendment cases,
advised CNN to retract its broadcast of ``Valley of Death,'' after
he had investigated the ``five pillars'' on which the June 7
television report and the subsequent Time Magazine article were
based. The reports had asserted that in Operation Tailwind the U.S.
military had dropped nerve gas on a Laotian village in 1970, while
pursuing American defectors. However Abrams concluded that each of
the report's pillars was flawed:
</P>
<P>
   ADM. THOMAS H. MOORER
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Thomas Moorer, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in
1970, was ``the single-most quoted and shown senior officer on the
broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Though a review of the outtakes of the broadcast demonstrates
that his memory remains satisfactory, his responses are often cast
in hypothetical terms,'' Abrams wrote of Moorer, now 87. ``CNN
itself ceased calling on Admiral Moorer to appear to comment on
ongoing issues in the early 1990s, and CNN's Pentagon correspondent
raised this credibility issue before the broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams concluded, ``that the substance of Admiral Moorer's
interviews do not confirm `that nerve gas was used in Tailwind' or
that the Tailwind `target was indeed defectors.'''
</P>
<P>
   CONFIDENTIAL SOURCES
</P>
<P>
   Three confidential sources were considered key in substantiating
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams said one source who was consulted as the story progressed
did not use actual knowledge in supporting the conclusion that
nerve gas had to have been used in Laos. Abrams found fault with
the indirect way the staff consulted with the second source, and he
concluded that the responses of a third source, ``although
supportive, are ambiguous.'' ``They are, possibly deliberately
blurry,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   THE MEN OF OPERATION TAILWIND
</P>
<P>
   Abrams was critical of whom the broadcast left in and whom it
left out.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Eugene McCarley, who led the Army commando unit that was a
key subject of the report, denounced his treatment on the
broadcast. Abrams wrote: ``He states that after saying that the use
of the nerve gas `was possible,' he then said that it had never
been used by any of his troops.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarley said the mission had nothing to do with killing
American defectors.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams wrote that what McCarley said to the CNN producer, April
Oliver, and she to him ``is a matter of credibility about which we
are unable to pass judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we can judge, however, is the unacceptability of
minimizing McCarley's views on the broadcast,'' he wrote. ``Given
the fact that he led the mission, we do not believe that McCarley's
views, even if rejected by CNN, were given sufficient prominence.
The same is true of others who repeatedly rejected the notion that
nerve gas had been used.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Robert Van Buskirk, the most prominent of the Operation
Tailwind participants, has become, in Abrams's words, the most
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he has in spectacularly self-destructive fashion, stated
that he had repressed memory syndrome, which he only overcame while
speaking with Oliver,'' Abrams wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded: ``It was unacceptable to ignore his medical
history, the inconsistency between his book'' _ written in 1983 _
``and what he said on air, and the ambiguity in his recollections
of the gas. Whatever can be said for using him before June 7, the
added weight of evidence uncovered since the broadcast seriously
diminishes any further reasonable reliance on him.''
</P>
<P>
   OTHER CORROBORATIVE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   This group included veterans of the commando unit in Laos and
pilots who offered ``additional, ancillary support for nerve gas
use.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams wrote: ``This information, however, played a secondary
role. Moreover, it was often ambiguous or conflicting.''
</P>
<P>
   THE EXPERT SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the use of experts to identify the gas dropped by the
symptoms observed by those on the ground below, Abrams wrote:
``While there was supportive information provided by the experts,
the relatively oversimplified manner in which the symptoms were
described raises doubt about the strength of the conclusions that
can safely be drawn from these interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   In his conclusion, Abrams wrote, ``We are lawyers, not
journalists, and it must rest with journalists to determine how
best to avoid in the future the pitfalls illustrated by this
broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the CNN broadcast was not fair; that journalistic
errors led inexorably to more errors, and ``the degree of
confidence approaching certainty of the CNN journalists who
prepared the broadcast of the conclusions offered in it contributed
greatly to the journalistic flaws identified in this report.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision was made by CNN to broadcast accusations of the
gravest sort without sufficient justification and in the face of
substantial persuasive information to the contrary,'' he wrote.
``CNN should retract the broadcast and apologize to the public and,
in particular, the participants in Operation Tailwind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
