r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-RANGERS-T     07-03 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CRUISE PAST SLUMPING RANGERS, 4-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The prospect of a third shutout during the
past 10 games loomed.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' mighty offense refused to allow it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers overcame this potential embarrassment with a clutch,
run-scoring balk in their 4-1 loss to the Los Angeles Dodgers last
night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it a moral victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will enter tonight's game against the Seattle
Mariners hitting .176 (22-for-125) with seven extra-base hits and
seven runs during their past four games.
</P>
<P>
   This latest performance caused the Rangers' team batting average
to sink below .290 for the first time this season since Opening
Day. The Rangers have lost five consecutive games, including all
three in the series with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need someone to step up and get that big hit to drive in
the crucial run, and we're not doing that right now,'' said Rangers
designated hitter Lee Stevens, who collected three of the Rangers'
seven hits against Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park. ``We need to
be aggressive and establish our own luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went 1-for-8 with runners in scoring position and
likely would have stranded first baseman Will Clark at third base
if not for Park's second-inning balk.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and first baseman Will Clark, who went 2-for-3 with two
doubles, collected five of the Rangers' seven base hits against
Park (7-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down right now, and we faced a good pitcher tonight,''
Stevens said. ``With that combination, it's tough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers left-hander Darren Oliver (4-6) surrendered four runs on
nine hits and issued two walks during his five-inning appearance,
but manager Johnny Oates removed his starting pitcher well before
the Dodgers put this game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it would not be the heart of the Dodgers' order
that would be Oliver's undoing. Designated hitter Paul Konerko,
third baseman Adrian Beltre and catcher Charles Johnson entered
this game hitting .214, .192 and .209, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   That trio produced the Dodgers' three-run second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko greeted Oliver with a single to open the second inning
and advanced to third on the ensuing double by Beltre. That brought
Johnson to the plate, who deposited Oliver's 2-2 offering into the
left-field seats for a 3-0 lead. It represented Johnson's first
home run in 87 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been better,'' Oliver said of his second
appearance since being reinstated from the 15-day disabled list
June 26. ``I made a few mistakes that cost me. I hung the curveball
to Konerko, and the curveball to Johnson wasn't a good pitch at
all. I'm still not pitching the way I want to be pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 4-1 lead on a fifth-inning sacrifice fly ball
from Konerko, but the Rangers' bullpen kept the visitors in check
the remainder of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Tim Crabtree allowed only two hits during three
scoreless innings, and right-hander Xavier Hernandez retired the
side in order during the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rangers' offense provided no support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ballclub is down a little,'' Oates said. ``We're not
swinging the bats as well as we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
