easy forehand volley into the bottom of the net. ``McEnroe could
get away with running through his volleys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know I'm not McEnroe,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   When I stepped outside, I found that I got a little more of
Wimbledon than I bargained for. A combination of thunderstorms,
flood watches and as much as two inches of rain gave Newport that
English summer ambiance. Most years, tennis at Wimbledon means a
little tennis and a lot of waiting for the courts to dry out, Boris
Becker meets Samuel Beckett, and this seemed to be my fate, too.
</P>
<P>
   As I would discover, there are few better places to wait out a
rain delay than Newport.
</P>
<P>
   First, I watched a little court tennis, a strange and obscure
indoor hybrid of tennis and squash that dates to the 16th century.
Then I ventured to the International Tennis Hall of Fame, part of
the same complex as the club, and saw a bigger stash of old rackets
than the one in my hall closet _ except that these had once been
owned by Bill Tilden, Don Budge, Maureen Connally and Jimmy Connors
_ and a collection that surpassed even Wimbledon's own.
</P>
<P>
   And even as I turned my attention to Newport's nontennis
distractions, I wasn't deterred from my quest. As I peered out at
the acres of manicured lawn at the Breakers, the palatial
Vanderbilt mansion, I couldn't help but wonder: How many grass
courts could you fit here?
</P>
<P>
   I was ready, but the courts were still wet. So as the drizzle
continued, I stopped by the club to get a little advice about
grass-court tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though people are enthralled by being out there, it's
more demanding to play on,'' said Bill prophetically. ``You've got
to move your feet.''
</P>
<P>
   When the weather finally broke, I found myself on Court 2 with
Joshua Bainton, an associate pro at the club and a college player
at Old Dominion. As we warmed up, the first thing that struck me
was the sound, or more accurately, the lack of it. For the first
time, I could hear myself play tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The ball fairly whispered as it hit the ground. My feet were
slipper quiet on the soft turf. There wasn't even the familiar
CA-CHING of the ball ricocheting off the chain-link fence; it just
nestled silently in the nets separating the courts. The only sound
was the solid THWOCK of a ball hitting the center of my strings, or
the BONK of one sailing wildly off the edge of my frame.
</P>
<P>
   For all its seeming civility, this was a less predictable game
than the one I grew up playing. After the ball hit the ground, it
seemed to have a mind of its own. One time it would skitter beneath
my racket like a white rat escaping from a behavioral-science lab,
the next it would kick erratically into my body, as I stood
flat-footed, pondering the inequity of it all. Played tentatively,
I discovered, grass-court tennis was just a sloppy version of
hard-court tennis. But play it with a gambler's heart, and it
becomes something different.
</P>
<P>
   After a few genteel games, I said to Josh, ``C'mon, let's see
the A serve.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked with a chuckle, ``The A game, too?''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded.
</P>
<P>
   He wailed a flat first serve to my backhand. This time, I got
down as low as Emmanuel Lewis and moved my feet like Fred Astaire.
I blocked it back, right at his feet. My return practically knocked
the racket out of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   This court, I suddenly realized, is a living thing. And living
things are seldom predictable. Grass-court tennis was a game that
rewarded shot-making. Patience didn't pay off here. Attack, the
turf told me, or be attacked. So I let loose and played a set of
lassiez-faire tennis.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEWPORT CASINO LAWN TENNIS CLUB, 194 Bellevue Ave., Newport,
R.I. Newport is 190 miles from New York City, via Interstate 95
through Connecticut, connecting with Route 138 in Rhode Island. The
grass courts at the Newport Tennis Club are open to the public
daily from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. Court time is $25 an hour for each
person and can be reserved up to seven days in advance by calling
(401) 846-0642. The dress code is predominantly white, with
collared shirts for men. Lessons, clinics and ball machines are
also available.
</P>
<P>
   THE INTERNATIONAL TENNIS HALL OF FAME, also at 194 Bellevue
Ave., Newport, is open daily from 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. and shows
memorabilia ranging from the 1874 patent for the game of tennis
that Queen Victoria granted to Major Wingfield, inventor of the
game, to the oversize Sugar Daddy bar brandished by Bobby Riggs in
his Battle of the Sexes match against Billie Jean King. Although
one wing of the museum was severely damaged by a recent fire, most
of the museum's collections were undamaged and remain on display.
Admission is $8;$4 for children 2 to 16; free for children under 2.
Information: (401) 849-3990 or visit the Web site at
www.tennisfame.org.
</P>
<P>
   NEWPORT'S TENNIS WEEK, Monday through July 12. In the Miller
Lite Hall of Fame championships, some of the world's top male
players _ including Todd Woodbridge, Mark Woodforde, Jason
Stoltenberg, Jeff Tarango, David Wheaton and Justin Gimelstob _
will play a post-Wimbleton grass tournament. Tickets range from $13
to $35. Tickets and information: (401) 849-6053.
</P>
<P>
   THE 1998 VIRGINIA SLIMS HALL OF FAME INVITATIONAL, July 10
through 12, features legends of the ladies' game like Tracy Austin,
Virginia Wade, Zina Garrison, Pam Shriver and Rosie Casals. Tickets
range from $18 to $35. Tickets and scheduling information: (401)
849-6053. On July 11, Jimmy Connors and Dwight David, the former
British Davis Cup player and captain, will be inducted into the
Hall of Fame. Tickets for the induction ceremony event are sold
out.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE NEW YORK REGION, the Orange Lawn Tennis Club, in South
Orange, N.J., and the West Side Tennis Club in Forest Hills,
Queens, New York City, also have grass courts, but they are open
only to members and their guests.
</P>
</TEXT>
