</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COBI'S ALLEGIANCE PUT TO ULTIMATE TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The rumors are shadowing Cobi Jones, picking
up where German and Iranian and Yugoslavian defenders left off.
They trailed the flashy forward around the Left Bank in Paris,
where he retreated after the U.S. World Cup soccer team went three
matches and out. They dogged him as he crossed the Atlantic,
returning to L.A. in time to rejoin Major League Soccer's Galaxy
for its game Saturday against the Kansas City Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   If the rumors were any more persistent, they'd be able to pass
themselves off as Eddie Pope. At the Louvre last weekend, the buzz
was the Westlake High product would be returning to France next
year to play for one of its pro teams. Thursday at the Rose Bowl,
word was the former UCLA standout was possibly bound for Germany.
</P>
<P>
   It's all old cap for Jones, whose 110 international matches are
the most of any U.S. soccer player. He reportedly was coveted by
German teams after the U.S. squad of which he was a contributing
member advanced to the second round in the 1994 World Cup. Jones
eventually signed with an English team, Coventry City, for the 1994
season and honed his skills in Brazil in 1995 before gracing the
Galaxy with his presence, starting in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 28, has speed to burn and enough star power to command
the maximum MLS salary (which is around the minimum wage of an NBA
player). That he also has sufficient elan as a playmaker to attract
interest of top-rate clubs overseas has brought Jones to a
difficult crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   As Independence Day weekend unfurls like a U.S. flag, Jones is
having to gauge which way his priorities blow. Does he pursue his
unalienable right to have some German club negotiate his transfer
with MLS or does he continue to serve the best interests of soccer
in the U.S.?
</P>
<P>
   Patriotism or pragmatism, that is the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conflict of interest,'' Jones acknowledged. ``You want
to go overseas and play in the top leagues in Europe and get the
whole soccer experience that you grew up hearing so much about. But
at the same time you want to help soccer to grow in the U.S. I
definitely am going to weigh the options of all the interests; MLS,
U.S. Soccer, my own (goals) ...''
</P>
<P>
   Jones paused for effect, then broke into the grin that launched
his MTV debut a while back, ``and basically wait for Sunil Gulati
(the MLS deputy commissioner in charge of player-related issues) to
make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Jones. From his days at Westlake High he has constantly
challenged himself, not authority. Long before he was lauded for
his speed and his passing, he was a walk-on at UCLA who won
compliments for his coachability. If U.S. coach Steve Sampson had a
few more players with the same respect for authority as Jones, he
wouldn't have had to waste so much of the World Cup looking out for
his back.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, Sampson is looking for a new job, having been
done in by his own 3-6-1 formation but also by the vocal discontent
of a few of his veteran players, Jones' former high school teammate
Eric Wynalda among them.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson's timing on the changing of the guard of U.S. soccer was
curious; right after the World Cup would have made more sense than
during it. But you didn't hear that from Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sampson) was the coach. He was the one who had to make the
decisions,'' Jones said. ``Some players were not happy with those
decisions and they decided to take it to the press. That's not
something I'm going to do. That's not my nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The bellyaching by veterans-turned-benchwarmers Tab Ramos and
Alexi Lalas split the team and created a tension that was as thick
as the coffee served in the corner cafes along the Seine River. Far
from perking the players up, all it did was bring the whole team
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could have been a bit more unity,'' Jones said. ``You
could see some of the players were (discontent). That undermined
the team a little bit. It was a situation that kind of escalated
with the help of the press. It kind of distracted the team from
focusing on the games.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with being a U.S. star in a sport that is
starved for attention stateside. Some of the players saw the media
throngs and they couldn't help themselves; they kept going back to
the banquet table for more attention long after they should have
called it a meal.
</P>
<P>
   The results were hard for everyone to swallow: one goal and zero
points in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that don't need to be said in the press,''
Jones said. But ``the people who were outspoken were the veterans
of the team. They had the outspoken personalities. So what are you
going to do?
</P>
<P>
   What Jones does next will be of great import to U.S. soccer. It
says here the sport will survive the exporting of a couple of its
local-grown stars as long as it continues to import the likes of
Mexico's Carlos Hermosillo and _ dare we say it? _ Germany's Jurgen
Klinsmann.
</P>
<P>
   Let Jones and Pope kick their dreams around for a while. They
will be better for the experience and so, too, by extension, will
future U.S. teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
