<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR'S RESTAURANT DOESN'T CUT MUSTARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County Health Services Department
officials say that Mayor Richard Riordan's Original Pantry
restaurant has received a poor rating for a second time since the
county began issuing letter grades.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown restaurant was closed in November after failing an
inspection. Now it has posted a score of 64 out of 100 because of
problems found in a recent inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors gave the low score May 29. An A is 90 to 100, a B is
80 to 89, a C is 72 to 79, and any lower score does not get a
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Original Pantry staff quickly addressed the
problems, which included excessive flies and kitchen workers not
wearing hairnets, the score must stay up until the next routine
inspection, said Alfonso Medina of the county Health Services
Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
