A9108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-PRAYER-NY     07-03 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-PRAYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRAYER IN A BRONX SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 3:
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of Mildred Rosario for leading a sixth-grade
public school class in prayer last month has brought a predictable
flood of denunciations, and in an odd way performed a valuable
service. Joining Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in defending Mrs. Rosario,
a bilingual teacher in the Bronx, were such luminaries of the
Christian right as Rep. Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, and Gary
Bauer of the Family Research Council, who said ``we need countless
teachers like this.'' In fact, Mrs. Rosario's actions showed
precisely why we need to keep the ban on prayer in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over school prayer has gone on for so long that it
has deteriorated into a clash of empty slogans. Mrs. Rosario has
humanized the situation. She had not yet taken attendance in her
class when the principal asked over the intercom for a moment of
silence in memory of a fifth grader who had drowned. In the anxious
discussion that followed, Mrs. Rosario, a member of a Pentecostal
church, asked ``if anyone would like to accept Jesus as their
Savior,'' and then placed her hands on some children's foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   School-prayer advocates have gone to great lengths to assert
that, by itself, prayer in the classroom need not violate anyone
else's rights. But by Mrs. Rosario's admission, this was a case of
proselytizing. It was carried out, moreover, at a sensitive moment
that was bound to be coercive. The parents of one child, both
Jehovah's Witnesses, objected. They were clearly within their
rights to do so. For the spokesmen of conservative religious groups
to seize on her case as an example of what they would like to see
repeated in other classes around the country is a clear warning
sign.
</P>
<P>
   When the Supreme Court banned prayer in the public schools in
the early 1960s, it recognized that situations like the one in Mrs.
Rosario's classroom would inevitably result from officially
sanctioned prayer. President John F. Kennedy, when asked for his
reaction at a news conference, gave an answer no less applicable
today. He said that those concerned about it at least had an
alternative. They could pray in their homes or churches. Whether or
not it was right to dismiss Mrs. Rosario, it is right to keep the
classroom free of prayer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LEGISLATOR-ARRESTE     07-03 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGISLATOR-ARRESTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SENATOR ARRESTED AFTER ALTERCATION WITH POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An altercation between a New York state senator and a
police officer on Thursday night ended with the senator being
sprayed with Chemical Mace and handcuffed after the police said she
bit the officer in the hand.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, Ada Smith, who represents the 12th District, which
includes sections of Brooklyn and Queens, was driving her car in
the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn around 8 p.m. when the
altercation occurred. She was later taken to a hospital after
complaining of burning eyes and wrist pain.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Joseph Pentangelo, a police spokesman, said the
incident began when Ms. Smith got caught behind a police cruiser
that had stopped another car.
</P>
<P>
   According to officers on the scene, Ms. Smith became annoyed and
told the officers they were blocking traffic at the intersection of
McKibbon Street and Graham Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The argument escalated, and when the police asked the senator to
produce her drivers' license and registration, she refused,
according to the arresting officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith declined to step out of her car, and when the officer
attempted to pull her out, she bit him on the hand, the police
said. One officer then sprayed Chemical Mace in her face,
handcuffed her and took her to the 90th Precinct station house.
</P>
<P>
   While being processed for arrest, Ms. Smith began complaining
that the handcuffs had cut off circulation to her wrists and that
the chemical was burning her eyes, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   When emergency personnel arrived at the station house, Ms. Smith
was still in handcuffs, authorities said. She was taken to Woodhull
Medical Center on Thursday night, where she had her eyes rinsed
with a saline solution.
</P>
<P>
   Although the officer said he was bitten in the hand, the police
said that the officer refused medical attention by emergency
workers who arrived at the scene. But Fire Department officials
said that no ambulance responded to the scene and that they had no
knowledge that an officer had been bitten.
</P>
<P>
   Among her colleagues and constituents in Queens, Ms. Smith is
known for her sharp tongue and no-nonsense demeanor. An independent
thinker, Ms. Smith endorsed the Rev. Al Sharpton in the 1994
Democratic primary against Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, and in
1997, she endorsed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani over the Democratic
candidate, Ruth Messinger.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear on Thursday night whether Ms. Smith had
identified herself as a state senator. She was placed under arrest
on Thursday night, but the charges were pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
