<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNOWBOARDERS-GUILTY-L     07-03 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOWBOARDERS-GUILTY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT-OF-BOUNDS SNOWBOARDERS COULD GET BILL FOR RESCUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Two snowboarders who were lost overnight in
the San Gabriel Mountains above Los Angeles during an El Nino storm
have been convicted of skiing out of bounds _ misdemeanor offenses
that could lead to a $23,600 bill for rescue costs.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Jenks of Glendale, nine miles north of downtown Los
Angeles, and Claudio Maluje of the L.A. suburb of North Hollywood
are believed to be the first Californians to be prosecuted in an
effort to recover the cost of their rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court Thursday, Deputy District Attorney Lonnie Felker
said the case did not indicate that Los Angeles County will go
after every person who makes a mistake and needs emergency service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every criminal prosecution is to set an example,'' Felker
said. ``That goes for (out-of-bounds) snowboarding, speeding and
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Sheriff's Department officials maintained throughout
the case that snowboarders, skiers, hikers and other outdoors
enthusiasts who don't break the law will continue to be rescued
free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   A jury deliberated for about two hours before finding the
snowboarders guilty. Municipal Court Judge Barbara Lee Burke will
sentence 24-year-old Jenks and 28-year-old Maluje on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Felker said prosecutors will seek a small fine and the cost of
their rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Jenks and Maluje got lost at the Snow Crest Ski Resort in
February, eating cactus and sleeping in a cave to survive.
</P>
<P>
   With the rescue coming less than two days after the death of
14-year-old Jeff Thornton _ who was pulled out from the same
mountains _ the defendants became mini-celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, they found out they were being charged with a
misdemeanor crime: ``Knowingly skiing in an area or on a ski trail
which is closed to the public and which has signs posted indicating
the closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Maluje's lawyer, Craig Wormley, claimed the ski resort was
poorly marked, and the men didn't know they were out of bounds.
Before trial, Jenks said the pair had snowboarded only a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a mountain man,'' Jenks said. ``That's probably why I
got lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, jurors marveled at the seemingly endless parade
of signs at the resort, warning patrons to ski within the lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were signs along the road on the way to (the resort),
there were signs on all the lifts and there were signs all along
the boundaries,'' said juror Randy Nieves. ``I don't know how you
miss them unless you close your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jury foreman David Martinez added: ``Even if they were amateurs
they should have known to stay off that run. If you go by a sign
and disregard it, that's your fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Both defendants plan to fight getting stuck with the rescue
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The verdict is an absolute outrage and he will be seeking a
hearing to get the prosecution to prove every cent of restitution
that they want these young men to pay,'' said Wormley's assistant,
Carver Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Deputy Roger Wallace said department officials believe
it is the first prosecution for rescue costs in the state, although
Los Angeles and other counties have sent bills to lawbreakers for
rescue costs before.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an intentional criminal act, we feel taxpayers shouldn't
have to be burdened with the costs,'' Wallace said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
