r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-RANGERS-L     07-03 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-RANGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Last July, Chan Ho Park became a star. A year
later, the Los Angeles Dodgers think the twinkle is back.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy. Shattered confidence and battered breaking
balls have been a big part of this season, but Thursday night's 4-1
interleague victory over the Texas Rangers in front of the 38,514
at the Ballpark in Arlington might be a hint he and the Dodgers
have returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at what he did and what we are doing and you get that
feeling that something good is finally on the way,'' said Bobby
Bonilla, who will be activated for tonight's series opener against
the second-place Giants in San Francisco. ``We're a good team and
he's a good pitcher. Now it's starting to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who went 5-0 last July on his way to a team-high 14
victories, allowed just an unearned run in 81/3 innings to give the
Dodgers their first three-game sweep since mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   He ended a five-game road losing streak an won back-to-back
starts for the first time this season. All this against the Rangers
who came in as the American League's best hitting team.
</P>
<P>
   In three games, the Rangers scored just seven runs. Park, Darren
Dreifort and Dennis Reyes held baseball's top RBI man Juan Gonzalez
to three meaningless hits.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Dodgers send Ismael Valdes, with a two-hit shutout
and a near perfect game in his past four starts, against the Giants
tonight and former ace Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to do this, we're going to do it with these
guys,'' Eric Karros said. ``Chan Ho was so big for us when Ramon
(Martinez) went down last year. Ramon is gone again and Chan Ho is
back in the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the changes on the field and front office, there is
something familiar between this season and last.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were 39-42 after 81 games in 1987. Although their
season ended without a playoff appearance, they went 49-32 the rest
of the way. This year they also were 39-42.
</P>
<P>
   But with three consecutive victories here, the Dodgers reached
.500 for the first time since May 19 and shaved two games off San
Diego's monster lead in the National League West. They are still
11{ back but play their next 10 games against the Padres and
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is an important time,'' Park said. ``We have
struggled so far. I have had problems with my confidence, but that
is over now. As the game went along my confidence really shot up.''
</P>
<P>
   Park (7-5) was spotted an early lead when Charles Johnson hit a
three-run homer off Rangers left-hander Darren Oliver in the second
inning. They added another run in the fifth on Paul Konerko's
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not have a home run since June 2 vs. St. Louis, a
span of 87 at-bats. He also had 15 strikeouts in his previous 31
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two strikes on me and I just wanted to make contact,''
said Johnson, who now has 11 homers. ``I got it up in the air and
it flew out.''
</P>
<P>
   Park had the lead, but it would have been easy to give back on a
96-degree night. But after struggling for the past six weeks, maybe
he had finally learned how to pitch through adversity.
</P>
<P>
   He could have come undone after balking in a run with the bases
loaded in the second. With Fernando Tatis at the plate and two
outs, Park completed his delivery, but never let go of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by what he had done, Park then rolled the ball to
the plate, but home plate umpire Eric Cooper waved in Will Clark,
who doubled and took third on Adrian Beltre's fielding error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw that before,'' Johnson said. ``But that was just
one play. What I remember about that inning was he had the bases
loaded with one out and got out of it with just one earned run. You
could tell he wanted to go nine innings tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Park allowed only one runner to third the rest of the way. He
allowed a second double to Clark to open the fourth, but retired
the next eighth batters.
</P>
<P>
   Park cruised into the ninth, but allowed a single to former
Angel Lee Stevens with one out. Scott Radinsky, who earned the
victory in Wednesday's game, took over and got the final two outs
for his 12th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his last start, he struggled by won,'' pitching coach
Charlie Hough said of Park. ``There are always little spots in a
game that can change everything. Tonight it was the bases loaded in
the second. He really stepped up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
