<HEADER>
A9150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-SWOOPES-HNS &LR;      07-03 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SWOOPES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Swoopes 
stable after 
collapsing
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forward hospitalized; &QL; 
test results incomplete
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Comets forward Sheryl Swoopes collapsed during a practice
Thursday but had stabilized and was resting comfortably at
Methodist Hospital later in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Comets team physician Dr. Jon Divine said the cause of Swoopes'
problem had not been determined but said late Thursday night the
second-year pro was ``awake, she's stable, she's smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She looks a whole lot better than when she came in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes collapsed at about 1:30 p.m. near the end of the Comets'
workout at Westside Tennis Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing a walk-through, getting ready for Sacramento,''
said coach Van Chancellor. ``Sheryl sat down at the end of the
basket, and she began to feel poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, 27, was sweating and on the verge of passing out as she
was being treated by team trainer Michelle Leget.
</P>
<P>
   After being stabilized, she was taken by ambulance to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Divine, who treated Swoopes upon her arrival at Methodist, said
dehydration may have been contributed to her condition. But he said
further testing was necessary before a complete diagnosis could be
rendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we really don't know for sure (what caused the
problem),'' Divine said. ``She is getting better with (intravenous)
fluids. Her cardiovascular system is stable; her breathing is
stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a few more tests cooking. As soon as those results
are back, we'll know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes remained in the hospital overnight for observation. She
could be released as early as today, pending the test results.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes' swoon, said Chancellor, cut short the preparations for
the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems to be a million miles away,'' Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento comes to Compaq Center tonight at 8, having snapped a
five-game losing streak Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   When Swoopes collapsed, Chancellor was in another part of
Westside Tennis Club away from the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to find Leget ministering to Swoopes near the base
of one of the goal standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought I panicked, yeah, you were right,'' he said.
``If you thought it worried me to death, you were right.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, I'm always concerned about individuals. I was very
concerned for Sheryl.''
</P>
<P>
   Leget, who left the University of Houston women's basketball
program last year to become trainer for the Comets, said shortly
after Swoopes collapsed, she had trouble breathing.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation, she said, never appeared grave.
``Fortunately, we were very prepared for the situation,'' Leget
said, adding that Swoopes never fully lost consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe she could still hear me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as spokeswoman for her teammates, center Wanda Guyton,
who is on the injured list because of a back injury, said,
``Everyone is real emotional. Everyone is worried about Sheryl,
what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second physical ailment Swoopes has had since the
beginning of training camp in early May. Just before the start of
the regular season June 13, she strained a hamstring but didn't
miss any playing time.
</P>
<P>
   With Swoopes in obvious trouble Thursday, Chancellor said
Cynthia Cooper and Tina Thompson gathered their teammates in a
circle on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kim Perrot, ``Sheryl is very important to our team, and
that holds true for everyone on our team. We prayed for her, and we
know that she's healed because we have faith. It's always tough to
see anybody with that kind of health problem, but to see someone
that you're with a couple of hours a day, seven days of the week,
it takes its toll on you.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first nine games, Swoopes ranked second on the Comets
in scoring (15.6 points per game) and third in the Women's National
Basketball Association in free-throw percentage (.860).
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes could return to the lineup as early as Monday night when
the Comets travel to Cleveland and face the Rockers for the second
time during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Jerome Solomon contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
