<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-ROCKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLOM KILLS 'EM AS MERCURY WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Cleveland Rockers must plant spies in Gund Arena
for visiting teams' game-day shootarounds.
</P>
<P>
   They had to have seen Mercury center Jennifer Gillom clank a
series of three-point shots in a Thursday afternoon contest that
fattened Bridget Pettis' coffers by $200. Between that and Gillom's
2-of-10 three-point tally for the season, Cleveland did not care to
bother with her out there Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, by admission, is not a practice player. But she is a
gamer. Gillom tied her WNBA career high of 29 points, nailing all
four of her three-point tries, to help Phoenix rock Cleveland,
76-61, to improve its record to 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really shocked,'' said Gillom, who also led the team in
rebounds with and in steals with five. ``No team in the league has
let me stand behind the line and shoot threes. Once I made the
first one, it was all over. I had a rhythm going.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not just her best night of the season. It might have been
the Mercury's top effort, given Cleveland's caliber and home floor.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's defense was as stifling as ever, holding the league's
top shooting team to a 44 percent night and rattling it into 22
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better, not our best,'' Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller
said. ``It wasn't great. It wasn't good. It was better. We've got a
long ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Try those lines on Cleveland (5-4), whose legs buckled to the
intensity coming off a Wednesday win at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers got out to a 16-9 edge with an 8-0 run, but Miller's
first regular-season technical foul, for arguing with the official
that didn't make the call, and a timeout gave the game an
about-face.
</P>
<P>
   A 9-0 retort started with a Gillom three-point post play, and
the Mercury dusted off its three-point arsenal for more. Andrea
Kuklova, Michelle Griffiths and Pettis all dropped bombs to launch
Phoenix to a lead it would never relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury hit 9 of 18 three-pointers. Phoenix averages 11
tries and had hit just 30 percent, but aggressive penetration
designed to tire Cleveland ended up opening the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to match their intensity,'' Miller said. ``It's
a back-to-back game, and we wanted to see if their legs were tired.
The goal was for us to get aggressive and go into a transition
game. Jennifer helped herself by knocking down perimeter shots and
then scoring off the dribble.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom scored the Mercury's final nine first-half points with a
varied menu, including a three-pointer, a fast-break layup, an
off-the-dribble jumper and a driving scoop. Phoenix led at the
break, 35-30, limiting the Rockers to 12.6 points less than their
first-half season average.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was worse offensively in the second half, seldom even
running its triangle offense because of the pressure. The Rockers
scored two points during an early five-minute stretch and then went
scoreless for a six-minute span to trail, 65-45, with 5:00 to go.
</P>
<P>
   The aggression had Phoenix thriving at the free-throw line, even
though it hit only 21 of its 32 chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nice point margin,'' said Pettis, who scored 18. ``I
hope that scares Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, Phoenix's next stop on this rough five-game Eastern
trip, may be a bit scared of the film on Mercury forward Umeki
Webb. Rarely does a player get shut out in the scoring column and
stand out so much.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned Cleveland's versatile 6-3 swing player, Eva Nemcova,
Webb smothered her. Nemcova was held to one field goal and six
points while committing four turnovers. Webb had five steals, seven
rebounds, four assists and a block to excuse her 0-for-4 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best defensive effort I've ever seen,'' Miller
said. ``Nemcova is one of the greatest offensive players ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Rockers that hurt Phoenix offensively were limited in
minutes. Center Isabelle Fijalkowski dominated the low post with 16
points on 8-of-11 shooting but played only 28 minutes because of
foul trouble. Starting guard Merlakia Jones hit 6 of 7 field goals
for 13 points, but got just 23 minutes because of a leg cramp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
