<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOW-BUDGET-RACER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBERS SHOOT FOR BIG TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Before D.J. Rupple even cranks the ignition, he has
already lost money.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how well he drives or how many cars he passes, Rupple
never will recuperate what it cost to park his battered 1977
Oldsmobile Cutlass along Manzanita Speedway's pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost me $20 to get in the back gate,'' Rupple said. ``It'll
cost me another $5 for gasoline to race that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I buy a hot dog or a drink, I'm in the hole because the
most I can get by winning the main event is $25.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to stock-car racing's real world, where there are no
treasure chests, headlines or corporate sponsors pouring untold
dollars into a driver's bank account.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of drivers with empty pockets and dreams of
stardom. Drivers such as Rupple, 26, still cling to hope that his
early success in the appropriately titled bomber stock division
will one day lead to the sport's upper echelon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I'm at right now, it doesn't get any lower,'' said
Rupple, the bomber stock-car leader in the driver's standings.
``But it's a start.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NASCAR Winston Cup Series is the sport's zenith, then the
bomber circuit that Rupple and others compete in on Friday and
Saturday nights in front of mostly small crowds at dirt tracks all
across the country is the nadir.
</P>
<P>
   Although each state usually has its own particular name for the
bomber division, at Manzy it is a snug fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars we drive, they're pretty much beat up,'' said Lyle
Goodwin, a 17-year-old NASCAR wannabe and a senior at Avondale
Westview High School.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike NASCAR's premier racing division _ when scrapes and dents
are smoothed out each week or replaced with a new sleek machine
with shiny new corporate logos _ bombers remain pockmarked forever
with sponsor's names such as Askren's Used Auto Parts slapped on
with a paint brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars you see out here in this division have little or no
value,'' said Phil Hertel who created the class several years ago.
``They're just a bunch of old clunkers. Virgin cars (those without
nicks and dents) get converted very quickly out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the drivers have driven the wheels off them, they just
leave them lay there and go out and find another one. But that's
the idea behind the series. Keep it cheap and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a charter that bomber President Richard Madrid insists on
following.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is designed for beginners, and we want to keep it
as inexpensive as we can,'' Madrid said. ``There's a $350 claim on
each car, meaning if someone else wants to buy your car, you have
to sell it for that amount. If you don't sell, you're barred from
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the claim is so small, that discourages people from
pouring a lot of money into their cars. Why soup up the engine or
try and make it pretty if you're going to lose it, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Madrid makes certain every driver starting the main event
receives some return for a night of racing, even if the return in
some instances barely covers the cost of a sandwich and a cup of
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last place pays $5,'' Madrid said.
</P>
<P>
   But one night a year at Manzy, the stakes are increased
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's Arizona Automotive Recyclers Association 250 at Manzy
is worth $1,200 to the winner, a jackpot in the eyes of most of the
60 drivers expected for the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like $12 billion for me,'' said Rene Madrid, who
regularly competes in the International Motor Contest Association
modified division. ``I could use the money. That's why I'm going
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, however, the bomber association discourages the
better drivers from remaining in the division.
</P>
<P>
   When racers such as Rupple begin to dominate, they are slapped
with penalties that are difficult to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Rupple recently won his fifth race of the season, and for the
remainder of the year, he must tag every main event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind it,'' said Rupple, a construction worker by day.
``I think it's a good rule. But when drivers from the upper
divisions come down and race, I think it becomes a bad rule.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, the division is mostly loaded with
novices. But that doesn't translate into non-competitive racing.
</P>
<P>
   If trading paint and rubbing fenders is what turns you on, the
bomber division is the place to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a dirty class because there's a lot of rough
drivers out there,'' said Goodwin, who drives a 1976 Ford Torino.
``But that teaches you how to stay out of wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream is to go to NASCAR, and this is a way for me to get
some good experience. I know we're not Jeff Gordon and Dale
Earnhardt, but we put as much into our racing as they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupple echoes that thought. And like Goodwin, Rupple hopes to
make a steady climb to stock-car racing's summit.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the road that links the bottom with the top is
long and winding, a road so full of potential potholes and dead
ends, most drivers never will reach its final destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a poor boy right now, but I still look for ways to move up
to factory stocks every week,'' Rupple said. ``A lot of guys are in
this division just to have fun, not to go up to NASCAR or anything
like that. But there's some like myself that dream of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even though we're not NASCAR, we race just as hard and
want to win just as much as those guys.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
