<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CUBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS STRIKE OUT  
 CUBS PITCHERS HANDCUFF HITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For it's one, two, three strikes, you're out at the
old ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   The late Harry Caray sang those words. The Diamondbacks are
living them.
</P>
<P>
   In their three-game series against the Chicago Cubs that ended
with a 3-2 loss Thursday at Wrigley Field, the Diamondbacks struck
out 37 times _ 13, 14 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   Their scratch-and-whiff approach _ scratching for every run they
can get while whiffing most of the time _ isn't a new fad. It's
been going on all season.
</P>
<P>
   They have 648 strikeouts this season. The only team remotely
close is the Cubs, who have 619. The Houston Astros, the
Diamondbacks' opponent for a three-game weekend series that begins
tonight in the Astrodome, have 604.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (29-56) struck out 13 times against rookie right-hander
Kerry Wood in the middle game of the series on Wednesday and once
against closer Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it against Wood, but against the other guys (Game
1 starter Mark Clark and Thursday's starter, Steve Trachsel) . . .
we need to start putting the ball in play more,'' a disgusted
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed Trachsel had a solid effort, tying his career
high in strikeouts with nine and giving up a run on seven hits in 7
innings to raise his record to 7-5. Left-hander Terry Mulholland
got the last out of the eighth, and the right-handed Beck pitched
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Beck struck out Yamil Benitez to end the game after surrendering
a solo homer to Devon White, the Diamondbacks' All-Star
representative, with one out in the inning. Beck earned his second
straight save and 20th overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trachsel pitched well,'' Showalter said. ``I would like to
have seen us do a better job with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel and Arizona right-hander Jeff Suppan traded scoreless
innings through the third, but Suppan clearly was having a more
difficult time of it. He was constantly behind in the count and
issued three walks in that span.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks broke the ice in the fourth for a 1-0 lead.
Trachsel walked leadoff man Travis Lee, who advanced to second on a
single to left by Matt Williams. Trachsel got White and Jorge
Fabregas on pop-ups. Benitez then singled to left to score Lee, but
Williams was thrown out at third after the Cubs cut off the throw
from left fielder Henry Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel settled down, but Suppan continued to labor. It
appeared to be only a matter of time before the Cubs would get on
the board.
</P>
<P>
   That time was in the fifth when Jose Hernandez singled with one
out, Mickey Morandini walked and Mark Grace placed a soft single
into right to score Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs scored what would prove to be the decisive runs in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Alexander doubled to right to lead off. Suppan (1-7) hit
Scott Servais with a pitch, and Trachsel sacrificed them over.
Hernandez followed with a single through the hole between third
base and shortstop to bring home two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan said he threw a slider to Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get it down, but it got away from me a little,''
Suppan said.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan threw 115 pitches in 5 innings, not a good sign of
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have preferred that they hit every first pitch,'' he
said. ``That would have been great. But it didn't work out that
way. The thing I want to do is try and make 'em hit grounders and
keep us in the game, and I think I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight of Suppan's 17 outs were on ground balls, and three came
on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Suppan's highlight of the day came not on the mound, but
with the bat. He singled with one out in the fifth and stole second
on a called third strike to Andy Fox on a 3-2 pitch. It was the
first stolen base by an Arizona pitcher, and the hit was Suppan's
sixth of the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
