<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY-COLANGELO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO DOESN'T GET HATRED OF COLANGELO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO - Here, the sun is shining on Jerry Colangelo, who is
sitting in the first row, dressed in a bright orange shirt, unaware
that a glob of sun block is resting on his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, there was an official tribute attended by the
mayor of Chicago. Today, he will serve as grand master in a Chicago
Heights parade. There are dinners and parties and a posse of
hard-core friends, hard-core faces that will tell you what a great
guy this man happens to be.
</P>
<P>
   And you have to wonder. To be so loved here. To be such a
lightning rod back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the old expression,'' Colangelo says. ``The climb up
the ladder is a lot more enjoyable than the perceived arrival. Once
you arrive, you're a target.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's a target now. A name that draws reverence from his
cronies and suck-ups, genuine appreciation from a silent majority,
careful rhetoric from weak-kneed politicians and pure hatred from a
firecracker group that isn't going away. As Colangelo glances
across the field, there is irony here.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, he attended his first night game at Wrigley
Field. His basketball team was down the street, playing for an NBA
championship. America West Arena had opened to rave reviews. And no
one ever talked smack about him then, not the ambassador of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I watched the game, I had a twinge,'' Colangelo said. ``I
thought, wouldn't it be great if we had something like this in
Phoenix. Two to three weeks later, they came to me.''
</P>
<P>
   That twinge would change Colangelo's life. They would come to
him, and naturally, he would become richer. But the pure corruption
of a backdoor tax changed his standing in the community. Regardless
of his involvement, he became the symbol of forced progress and
pork-barrel politics. And ever since he stepped into the arena of
baseball, that unequivocal love has split off into separate
factions: Jerry backer. Or Jerry basher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circumstances have changed for me personally,'' Colangelo
said. ``If there's a perception that has been created, that's
unfortunate. But if people knew me _ really knew me _ that's not
what they'd think. I tell you why I feel very comfortable when I
come back here. These people really know me intimately, and nothing
has changed for them.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't understand the resentment here. They have Jerry
Reinsdorf and Jerry Krause and Michael McCaskey and Bill Wirtz. An
owner who is breaking up the Bulls and an owner who won't put the
hockey team on television. They think you should feel fortunate to
have Colangelo, and when you mention the taxation without
representation, they laugh.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Chicago was practically built in the back rooms, by
shady politicians cutting deals, by men who got things done in a
unique fashion.
</P>
<P>
   And this is how Phoenix arrived where it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Mayor Daley last night, and we were
discussing projects being done in various cities,'' Colangelo said.
``Bottom line is this: If you're a doer, you will be involved in
controversial issues. But I remember how Phoenix looked 20 years
ago, 15 years ago. I believe we've carried the banner for the city
and the state for three decades. I think we've instilled a little
bit of pride. I'm proud of what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, of course, is another story. The tree is still
sprouting, and soon, other doers will go out on that shaky limb.
They will ask you to help fund an amusement park for the Cardinals,
and down the road, the Coyotes might solicit your spare change. In
the end, the Colangelo backlash will influence the changing face of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment that must've been worth the price of admission,
Colangelo ran into Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill this week. Bidwill
was dining alone when Colangelo approached and offered a ticket to
the game. If there's one thing Bidwill hates more than the dice
game in the Valley, it's the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a White Sox fan,'' Bidwill said, leaving it at that.
</P>
<P>
   So many enemies now. But this is what bothers Colangelo the
most: His gift is his vision, and some of you can't see past the
rage. Once, you couldn't walk through downtown Phoenix at night
without fear of the shadows. Now, there is a stadium that lights up
the sky, police on the corners, a city growing out of its kid
clothes fast enough to make your head spin.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't have voted for this. But when you get by the
emotion, are you thankful it happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm too sensitive, that I'm at the point in my
life where things shouldn't bother me,'' Colangelo said. ``If that
ever happens, then I'm really in trouble. But I've never entered
anything based solely on personal gain. And with all the personal
abuse that has come along with baseball, I really still believe the
majority appreciate it. I really in my heart believe that to be
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, the roof was open at Bank One Ballpark. It was
110 outside, 78 degrees inside. Bottom line is, it works. But when
you continually get beaten upon by a small segment of the
population, well, you can't win that argument.''
</P>
<P>
   As he watches his baseball team lose another game, this is the
crux of the matter. Once, he was the benevolent king, embraced by
all. And just when he reaches the top of the mountain and Phoenix
makes the big leagues, some of you don't trust him anymore. Not
like you used to, and not like they do here.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo will be escorted down the streets of his past today,
soaking in the adulation and unconditional support. And he will
probably wonder: Will it ever be like this again, back home in the
desert, in the city he built? Or is he stuck with his own little
tax, the mighty fall from hero to owner? &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
