<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SULLIVAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST COYOTE AT HOME  
 SULLIVAN JOINS TEAM WITH EASTERN FLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Mike Sullivan has been spared a second frustrating
experience with an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan, the center-left wing whom the Coyotes acquired
from the expansion Nashville Predators this week for a
seventh-round draft pick in next year's NHL entry draft, is hoping
that he and Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk won't be ships that pass
in the night as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, 30, was co-Most Valuable Player and big man on campus
when he played at Boston University. But the Marshfield, Mass.,
native departed school the year Tkachuk, a promising Boston-area
hotshot, joined the Terriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Keith through Boston College,'' Sullivan said, ``but
I've never had the chance to play with him. He's a great player,
and I'm really look forward to playing on the same team with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he gets that chance hinges on whether Coyotes General
Manager Bobby Smith can work out a contract extension with Tkachuk
without acrimony rising to a level that makes a trade the only
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the seven-year NHL veteran will be joining a team
with a distinctly New England flavor. Centers Jeremy Roenick and
Bobby Corkum and defensmen Keith Carney and Deron Quint, in
addition to Tkachuk, all hail from the region.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan has played only with Roenick, on Team USA in the 1988
Junior World Championships in Moscow. Surprisingly, it was Sullivan
who was selected the team's most valuable offensive player.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising because Roenick is a recognized offensive force
in the NHL, having scored more than 90 points in a season four
times, including three 100-plus seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And Sullivan's career-high season came three seasons ago when he
scored 21 points with Calgary, although he had 18 points (five
goals) with Boston last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role thus far has always been in more of a defensive
posture,'' the 6-foot-2, 190-pound Sullivan said. ``Things like
killing penalties and playing on the checking lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``My weakness, I guess, has been offense. But it's been
something I've been working hard on and know that I'm on a team
that is capable of scoring a lot, maybe I can contribute more on
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons he was acquired are many. For openers, the Coyotes
didn't tender an offer to third-line left wing Darrin Shannon and
will lose him via free agency. Also, if the team somehow loses
restricted Group II free agent Corkum, Sullivan can replace him as
center on the checking line and on the penalty kill.
</P>
<P>
   But if Corkum returns, as expected, having fast-skating Sullivan
on his left wing promises to provide a dangerous penalty kill.
During his career, Sullivan has led both San Jose and Calgary in
short-handed goals and points. Corkum was among the league leaders
last year with five short-handed goals and six short-handed points.
</P>
<P>
   The trade ended a hectic time for Sullivan, who swapped jerseys
three times in a week, going from his hometown Bruins, to Nashville
in the expansion draft, to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty I had mixed emotions about going to an
expansion team,'' he said. ``I went to San Jose in its first year.
It was exciting being part of something starting from the ground
floor and being part of the developmental process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed playing in Boston last year. It was the
hometown team, and my family was happy. But Boston told me after
the season I would be made available in the expansion draft and I'd
probably be taken. It's just the reality of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Smith called him with news of the trade to Phoenix, it
was welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to be part of the Phoenix organization,'' he said.
``Bobby told me he was excited to have me, and he thinks I'll help
improve the team. It's a good team. It's a chance for me to be part
of a team that is capable of having a chance to win a Stanley
Cup.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
