<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH GRASS BOTHERS OUT FIELDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ With its emerald-green field and lush ivy clinging to
its brick walls, Wrigley Field is aesthetically pleasing to the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the Diamondbacks outfielders have a different
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not quite as thick as a jungle, the grass is very
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to judge,'' said  &UR; David Dellucci, who
started in right field in Tuesday's first game of the three-game
series and in center field in Wednesday's second game. ``You've got
to really be on top of things. If you don't, the ball could stop 20
feet in front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't exactly enamored with the bleacher bums.
</P>
<P>
   ``They throw orange peels at you,'' Dellucci said. ``And I just
knew that if I got close enough, they'd try to dump a beer on me.
They weren't even into the game. It's a circus, not a baseball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yamil Benitez, who started in left field in all three games of
the series, said the fans near him ``were saying a lot of bad
stuff, but not too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a similar atmosphere at winter-league games in his
native Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really serious about the game,'' he said. &QL; 
On to Houston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci is certain to find the Astrodome more to his liking
when the Diamondbacks begin a three-game series there tonight
against the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   He will have a cheering section of his own, a group of several
dozen friends and family members who will be driving from his
hometown area of Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was joking around the other day that so many people are
going to be going that they'll have to leave at 5 a.m. because of
the traffic jam,'' Dellucci said. &QL; 
Caught in the middle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As one who likes to relax before games by playing cards in the
clubhouse, shortstop  &UR; Jay Bell has been dealt some interesting
hands.
</P>
<P>
   None, however, has been as strange as the one fate has dealt
him.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who wears No. 33, now finds himself placed between a
couple of quirky left-handed pitchers,  &UR; Alan Embree, No. 32, and
 &UR; Brian Anderson, No. 34. Most clubhouse men set up the visitors'
lockers on a numerical basis.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two pitchers like plenty of space, some of their
clothing articles stray into Bell's area. Embree even went so far
as to write his and Anderson's names above Bell's in magic marker.
</P>
<P>
   Bell got revenge, however, on the two pitchers who were
teammates with the Cleveland Indians and have been hanging out
together since Embree's arrival in a trade last week.
</P>
<P>
   He got them to engage in a somewhat heated debate about their
choice of restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' Bell said. ``I knew I was going to end up being a
referee.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Ken Robinson, who was claimed on waivers from
Toronto during spring training, experienced some shoulder problems
and was on his way back to recovery, is out until next spring after
undergoing surgery on his rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, left-hander  &UR; Omar Daal, on the
disabled list because of a strained hamstring, will make his next
start July 14.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks investor  &UR; Jose Canchola, the former mayor of
Nogales, threw one of the ceremonial first pitches Thursday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0153EDT &QL; 
