u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-03 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
More tough luck
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chisox's 4-run inning spoils Lima's outing
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Jose Lima had two words to describe his latest flirtation with
picking up his first victory in nearly a month:
</P>
<P>
   ``No suerte.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to have to do,'' said Lima after
his fifth failed try for win No. 8 in Thursday night's 4-3 loss to
the Chicago White Sox at the Astrodome. ``Sometimes, there is
nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was easy for Lima to pinpoint where things fell
apart. For Lima (7-5), one pitch led to one big inning. Chicago,
outscored 27-6 in the first two games of the series, received all
the run support it needed during a four-run fourth inning,
highlighted by a bases-loaded double by Magglio Ordonez that gave
the White Sox a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros righthander had a career-high 11
strikeouts. But that was little consolation after his latest
setback sent him to his third loss in five decisions. Since
becoming the National League's first six-game winner May 10, Lima
is 1-4 with five no-decisions in his past 10 outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needs to win a game,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said of Lima, who hasn't won since June 6. ``When you go a long
time without a win, sometimes it seems more difficult than it
really is to get one and you start to press forward. He was kind of
unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he had strikeout stuff and he was in command
throughout most of the game. He had one lapse, particularly the one
bad pitch to Ordonez.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Ray Durham reached base to begin the fourth on an
error by second baseman Craig Biggio, then advanced to third on
Mike Caruso's single to right field. Two batters later, Durham
scored on an RBI double by Albert Belle. Lima walked Robin Ventura
to load the bases before Ordonez lined a 1-0 changeup off the
center-field wall to score three runs.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in run production has something to do with Lima's
woes. In his first eight starts, which produced a 6-1 record, the
Astros provided Lima with 8.6 runs per game. They have averaged 4.2
runs in his past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was a matter of Lima starting one day too late. The Astros
had scored in double figures in three straight games before
Chicago's James Baldwin (3-3) limited them to three runs and four
hits in 5 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to complain or blame it on my teammates,'' said
Lima, who retired the first nine batters he faced, five by
strikeout. ``They've scored some runs for me all year. I went out
and battled again and pitched seven good innings. We lost. I lost.
It's nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth inning, Lima settled down and scattered four
hits over the next three innings before being replaced by Scott
Elarton, who pitched two scoreless innings. The 11 strikeouts by
Lima marked the most by an Astros starter this season and surpassed
his previous career best of nine against the Rangers in 1995 when
he was with Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   With Lima cruising, Baldwin appeared to be the one in trouble
with five walks and one hit batsman during the first four innings.
But the Astros had only a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you can get hit around all night long and have a
couple of guys on every inning and never give up more than a run or
two,'' Dierker said. ``Other times, it seems you are practically
unhittable and all of a sudden they score four runs off you.
Ordinarily, I think we could have overcome that, but not tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pulled within 4-1 in the fourth when Carl Everett led
off with a walk, Sean Berry was hit by a pitch and Lima followed
two batters later with his first RBI of the season, a groundout to
third. The Astros, who had their four-game winning streak snapped,
added two runs in the fifth. Derek Bell hit a one-out double, and
Jeff Bagwell hit his 19th homer of the season, a two-run shot off
Baldwin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
