<HEADLINE>
NASH SEES POTENTIAL IN DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Former Phoenix guard  &UR; Steve Nash, who was traded on
draft day to the Dallas Mavericks, said he has mixed feelings about
the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad in some ways because I really love Phoenix, and I was
hoping to play my whole career there, he said. ``But I'm excited
about the opportunity I'll have in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   That opportunity includes the chance to be a starting point
guard. Nash would have been a backup behind  &UR; Jason Kidd with the
Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be a contender right away, but we've got a
good young nucleus of players who can grow together,'' Nash said.
``I know Fin  &UR; (Michael Finley), and  &UR; A.C. (Green) and (assistant
coach)  &UR; Donnie
 &UR; (Nelson), so it's exciting to be back with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns traded Nash for the rights to Notre Dame's  &UR; Pat
Garrity, forwards  &UR; Bubba Wells and  &UR; Martin Muursepp and the
Mavericks' 1999 first-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Nash wanted to be paid starter's money and get
starter's minutes to sign a contract extension with the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Nash wouldn't comment on the specifics of the negotiations, but
he said he only asked that he be assured he was a major piece of
the club's future plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just came down to the fact they weren't sure they
would be able to re-sign me, and they didn't want to lose me to
free agency (next summer),'' Nash said. ``I think they made a
pretty good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the negotiations said reports that Nash
was seeking a contract worth $8 million a year were exaggerated. He
was actually seeking between $4-$5 million a season in an
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Nash wouldn't confirm that number, but said, ``I just wanted
what young, upcoming point guards in the league are getting right
now.'' &QL; 
Back to Flagstaff? &QL; 
General Manager  &UR; Bryan Colangelo said the Suns are contemplating a
return to Flagstaff for training camp this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's if there is a regular training camp. The
league and players are in a labor lockout that could threaten
training camps in October and perhaps the start of the regular
season in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is finalized, but we're considering going back to
Flagstaff,'' Colangelo said. ``We expect to make a decision within
the next week or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have held their camps in such locals as Prescott, Lake
Havasu City and Flagstaff. Last season, the club conducted camp at
America West Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
