<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT PHILLIES, 9-8, IN EXTRA INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a two-out, ninth-inning, game-tying home run
swing on Thursday night, Tino Martinez turned what had been a
dreadful evening for the Yankees into yet another chapter in their
enchanted season.
</P>
<P>
   And afterward, after the Yankees rookie Ricky Ledee had singled
with the bases loaded in the 11th inning to give the Yankees a 9-8
victory over the Philadelphia Phillies, Martinez was asked to
explain how his team sustained its run of memorable moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us,'' Martinez said, ``every time that key at-bat comes up
_ the one that will decide the game _ the guy standing at the plate
is the guy with the hot bat.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Phillies holding a three-run lead in the ninth,
Martinez found himself at the plate. And he could hardly wait to
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you feel good about your swing like I do now,'' he said,
``you want that at-bat. You're rooting for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' closer, Mark Leiter, had yielded a double to Derek
Jeter and a walk to Paul O'Neill in the ninth, bringing Martinez to
the plate as the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a sinker to Martinez that didn't sink,'' Leiter said
of his 2-1 delivery. ``It sunk in the upper deck.''
</P>
<P>
   For Martinez, it was his second home run of the game and his
fourth in five games. He has 11 runs batted in during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th inning against reliever Jerry Spradlin (3-4),
O'Neill hit a leadoff single. Martinez followed with his third hit
of the game, a single to right field, and Spradlin walked Darryl
Strawberry to load the bases. Ledee then hit a ground ball to
center field past a drawn-in infield, giving the Yankees (58-20) a
sweep of their three-game interleague series with the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   The heroics of Martinez and Ledee saved the Yankees' starting
pitcher, Hideki Irabu, from his third consecutive defeat. Irabu,
who less than a month ago led the American League in earned run
average, had another poor outing, giving up five quick runs. Irabu
left the game before he could get an out in the fourth inning,
giving up five hits and walking three.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies hit three home runs off Irabu, who has given up
eight homers in his last 112/3 innings after giving up just five
homers in his first 11 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   By every statistical measure, Irabu's recent slide has been as
dramatic as it has been sudden.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 11 starts this season, Irabu not only had a 6-2
record, but he also led the league with a 1.68 era. Opposing
hitters were batting just .192 against him and had a slugging
percentage of .307. In his last three starts _ two losses and a
no-decision _ opposing hitters have hit .362 against Irabu and have
compiled a slugging percentage of .894.
</P>
<P>
   While Irabu gave up more than two runs in just one of his first
11 starts, he has yielded 14 earned runs in the last three starts,
raising his era to 2.91.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no physical problems,'' Irabu said. ``But I know I'm
letting the team down, and it concerns me.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre said he was concerned about Irabu, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think most of his problems are correctable,'' Torre
said. ``He is just giving the hitters too many good pitches to hit.
Those home runs were pitches that were too fat, too good.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu gave up two home runs to Rico Brogna and another to Mark
Lewis and left the game trailing by 5-0. The Phillies extended that
lead to 7-2, the Yankees' runs coming on Martinez's fourth-inning
home run and a solo home run by Jeter in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   A two-run homer by O'Neill in the eighth inning cut the
Phillies' lead to three runs. And when reliever Yorkis Perez walked
both Martinez and Tim Raines, Jorge Posada went to the plate with a
chance to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   In came Leiter, and Posada singled up the middle to score
Martinez, but Leiter got Chad Curtis to end the inning with a fly
out to center field.
</P>
<P>
   Brogna's second home run was measured at 414 feet and gave him
his third multi-home run game of the season and the seventh of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Jordan followed with a sharp single to center field, and
Irabu walked Bobby Abreu. Lieberthal then singled to left field,
scoring Jordan and bringing Torre from the dugout to remove Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes relieved Irabu and retired three consecutive
batters to quell the Phillies' rally, though Holmes benefited from
a diving stop and throw to first by second baseman Chuck Knoblauch
for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular defense helped keep the Phillies scoreless in each
of the next two innings with Holmes on the mound. Left fielder Tim
Raines chased down a one-out drive by Brogna in the fifth inning,
making the catch at the wall and then throwing to Jeter, the
shortstop, who delivered a strong, one-hop relay throw to first
base to double up Scott Rolen, who had advanced several steps past
second base.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, when Abreu hit a ground ball that ricocheted off
Holmes, Jeter grabbed it near second base and started a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 5-0, the Yankees were scoreless against starter
Tyler Green until the fourth, when Martinez hit his first homer.
Two innings later, Jeter led off the sixth with his 10th homer to
straightaway center, drive estimated at 424 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter tied his career high for homers in a season. In each of
Jeter's two previous seasons with the Yankees, he has hit 10 home
runs.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
