<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FINALLY GIVING FANS A `BRIGHT SIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Somewhere in the Regulation Issue Sportswriters'
Handbook, there exists a passage that stipulates that, on certain
rare occasions, sports scribes must momentarily cease ranting about
why the home team is so stinking lousy and, instead, ``look on the
bright side.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, even when it comes to the 1998 Mariners, now 36-49 and in
last place on your shocking American League West scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for me and the Mariner faithful and the Mariner
semi-faithful _ all those people who secretly continue to watch
televised Mariner games but who refuse to publicly admit they're
still interested _ the M's have gone ahead and provided a rare
opportunity to ``look on the bright side.''
</P>
<P>
   And this right before they head to Texas, where the M's have
made an annual habit of bashing the brains out of the poor,
heat-stroked Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The M's have won two games in a row, starting off July as hot as
a Independence Day firecracker.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, though, how the Mariners winning two games in a row can
spark a rash of optimism so unbridled, you could almost imagine the
M's coming real close to a AL West comeback.
</P>
<P>
   (By suggesting such an improbable comeback, have we officially
gone overboard on the ``look on the bright side'' mandate?)
</P>
<P>
   You would think so. But maybe not. Let's listen to Lou Piniella:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new month,'' the Mariner manager said Thursday, after
the M's clobbered the Rockies 10-3 with a pleasing mix of small
ball and big ball, if you want to consider Ken Griffey Jr.'s 35th
homer of the season a big ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get out of the old month. That was rough. Now we
need to see where it leads. Things can turn around on a dime in
this business. You never know,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion has it, however, that it will take some form of
currency larger than a dime on which the Mariners could turn around
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Like a bucket of Krugerrand or a billfold full of Franklins.
</P>
<P>
   But we applaud Piniella for his newfound optimism, because
frankly, it was getting scary watching Piniella vacillate between
growing good-luck mustaches, kicking dugout water buckets after yet
another Bobby Ayala blown save or muttering exasperated post-game
quotes like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Write whatever you want'' or my personal favorite:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious things aren't working around here,'' which
Piniella screamed back in early June, when a Randy Johnson trade or
an infield shake-up still seemed like it might fix some of the
Mariner woes.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella isn't the only one who had just about given up on the
Mariners, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, let's be honest: The level of suspicion regarding the
Mariners this season had just about reached an all-time high as
June came to a demoralizing end.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on the final day of June, just around the time the M's
were coughing up that 6-4 loss to the Rockies at the Kingdome,
paranoia was (to quote that great baseball sage and Creedence
Clearwater Revival founder John Fogerty) striking deep.
</P>
<P>
   Be honest now. Who out there was not thinking something like:
</P>
<P>
   Could the Mariners really be this bad without trying to be this
bad?
</P>
<P>
   Could Russ Davis and Joey Cora be trying to set some Guinness
Book of World Records benchmark for combined errors between a
second and third baseman?
</P>
<P>
   Did Cora and Davis (34 errors between them) desire to have their
picture in that tome, right next to that Indian guy with the
world's longest fingernails and the world's fattest man, who was so
fat (How fat was he, Laura?) that he had to be buried in a piano
box?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' June tied the club's all-time worst monthly tally
of 8-20, and by the time June 30 rolled around, you really had to
wonder:
</P>
<P>
   Did Johnson, the loser Tuesday against the Rockies, deliberately
throw that wild pitch that allowed a Colorado run to score? It was
too weird the way Johnson never flinched or got mad at himself
immediately after Greg Colbrunn crossed the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The mind plays tricks. You start to hallucinate, because in that
same June finale game, you swear even Griffey brainlocked when he
came up to bat in the bottom of the ninth with two outs, two
strikes and went golfing at a bad pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's totally entitled to do what he wants. Griffey's the
man. But if you're a desperate Mariner fan, thirsting for an RBI
single in that situation, you're starting to wonder when this
Mariner team will ever start to put it all together?
</P>
<P>
   Well, two games into July, we're here to tell you things are
looking up. Remember '95. Put on your rally caps this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we're mandated to perform this civic duty under the
bylaws of the Regulation Issue Sportswriters' Handbook. Enjoy this
dose of the brighter side, since the darker side has been written
to death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-03 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY STAYS IN ZONE, KEYS WIN OVER ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The blue and red T-shirt Lou Piniella wore Thursday is
well worn, and looks it. But the message emblazoned across the
front, at least for this Seattle baseball team, is a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Shut up and play ball.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive outing, the Mariners put on their
game face and slapped around the Colorado Rockies, beating them
10-3 before an afternoon crowd of 32,523 at the Kingdome. In 36
hours, the home club came up with 19 runs, two victories and some
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Mariners (36-49) are in Texas for a final three-game
set before taking their All-Star break, praying that none of this
newfound attitude adjustment has been misplayed while crossing two
time zones. There have been many false signs before in three
troublesome months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to be all right,'' first baseman David
Segui said. ``We're coming out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. continued his most torrid stretch of hitting
this season, homering for the fourth straight game and seventh time
in his last nine. He went 3-for-5 with three RBIs, lacking only a
double for the cycle, one of the few offensive feats that has
eluded him in his career. His homer was his 35th.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, one-time Rockies reject Billy Swift threw seven
strong innings at his former club, walking only one. He picked up
his team-leading eighth victory in 12 decisions. He's the fifth guy
in the rotation, but No. 1 in productivity.
</P>
<P>
   And, for just the 37th time in 85 games, the Mariners went
errorless. Now a daily ritual, the club turned to defensive
replacements in the late innings. It's sort of like a second
bullpen. Left fielder Glenallen Hill and second baseman Joey Cora
were lifted for Rob Ducey and Rico Rossy, respectively, in the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   This combination allowed the club to put together a two-game win
streak for only the second time in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we need some follow-through,'' Piniella said. ``We'll see
where it leads. Things can turn around on a dime in this business.
You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and his big bat, however, remain a constant. He got the
Mariners rolling to a six-run first inning by tripling into the
right-field corner and driving in the first two runs. He hit an
opposite-field homer to left to ignite a four-run second inning,
helping give his club a 10-0 lead after two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, Griffey had extra-base hits in six consecutive
at-bats, tying a club record but falling one shy of an American
League standard.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey also provided an All-Star catch in the seventh. On a
dead sprint to straightaway center, he made an over-the-shoulder
catch, stabbing a well-hit ball by Colorado's Mike Lansing as he
neared the warning track. As Griffey made the long jog in, Lansing
stood at first in disbelief while a pop song centered around the
words ``You're Unbelievable'' appropriately was cued up and blasted
out of the Kingdome public-address system.
</P>
<P>
   Epitomizing this more serious approach, the normally playful
center fielder politely but firmly refused all interview requests
Thursday, something he did throughout the brief homestand. It's as
if he's in a zone, and doesn't want to be disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where he is _ he's locked in,'' Segui said. ``And when
he's locked in, he does tremendous damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Swift of Griffey: ``It's all momentum in this game. One guy
can make everybody feed off him. He's taking that attitude he wants
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Edgar Martinez: ``He's the leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are finally taking out their frustrations on
someone else and getting at least momentary results. Against
Colorado, they looked the like the Seattle teams of old.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, no one's feelings are being spared. Utilityman
Jeff Huson is gone. Pitcher Ken Cloude has been told to spend a few
days in the minors. Hill, Cora and even third baseman Russ Davis,
another defensive liability, often suffer the embarrassment of not
finishing games. Trade talk continues, leaving many in the
clubhouse insecure. It all comes back to the Piniella T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Shut up and play ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
