<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-GIANTS-WRI     07-03 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-GIANTS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL TO GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ J.T. Snow didn't take kindly to the words of Angels
president Tony Tavares a couple of years ago when Tavares said the
Anaheim Angels had too many pretty boys from Newport Beach, or
something to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, who actually lives in the Corona del Mar section of
Newport Beach, was eventually traded to the San Francisco Giants,
but he obviously hasn't forgotten. He hit two home runs, doubled
and drove in four as the Giants beat the Angels 7-4 before 33,272
at Edison Field on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Angels maintained their 3{-game lead over
Texas in the AL West. The Giants picked up a game on San Diego and
now trail by 4{ in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Snow went 5 for 13 in the three game series, and is hitting .379
(11 for 29) with five homers and 12 RBI in seven games against his
former teammates in his two seasons as a Giant. Thursday marked
Snow's eighth career multiple-homer game, five of which came while
with the Angels. He has three as a Giant, and two of those have
come against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets you going,'' Snow said of facing the Angels. ``It's
always nice to do well against those guys. I won't lie. Any player
will tell you, when they go against a team they were traded from or
weren't signed by it's nice to do well against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Snow had a good year with the Giants last season, hitting
.281 with 28 homers and 104 RBI, 1998 has been a struggle. Snow
went into the three-game series against the Angels hitting only
.216 but was obviously affected by the illness of his mother, who
recently died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole situation with my mom was tough to go through,''
Snow said. ``When I came back and joined the team, it was a little
more relaxing. It was time to get back to baseball. All the
worrying and heartache I felt sort of went away.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the player the Angels got for Snow _ pitcher Allen
Watson _ remains on the disabled list with a lacerated wrist, an
injury he suffered opening a beer bottle earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Kirk Rueter (10-3) gave up nine hits in 51/3
innings Thursday, but got the win because he gave up only one run _
Darin Erstad's leadoff homer (No.18) in the first inning. Erstad
and Gary DiSarcina each had three hits for the Angels; Dave
Hollins, Jim Edmonds and Garret Anderson had two hits apiece.
Everyone in the Angels starting lineup except Cecil Fielder had at
least one hit, and they actually outhit the Giants 15-10.
</P>
<P>
   But they left runners on base all night. They stranded 10,
including five in scoring position. The only clutch hit the Angels
came up with was Hollins' three-run homer (No.9) in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the ball good, but we didn't come up with the hit that
could have got us going,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``It
doesn't matter how many hits you get if you don't score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jason Dickson (8-6) had the league's
third-longest winning streak, getting seven victories in a row from
May 16 to June 21. But he lost his previous start _ 6-3 to the
Padres last Friday _ and he struggled again Thursday from the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   With both of his past two starts resulting in losses to N.L.
teams, Dickson is happy that interleague play is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of interleague, it's not for me,'' Dickson said.
``It's such a different game in the National League. They're
hacking in the National League. You throw a fastball close and
they're swinging at it. I should have taken advantage of that
National League strike zone in San Diego the other day, but I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Angel Stan Javier doubled home a run with one out in the
first inning for a 1-0 Giants lead. One out later Snow made it 3-0
with his first homer of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad led off the bottom of the first with his home run, but
that would be as close as the Angels would get in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Snow doubled home Charlie Hayes in the third inning, then led
off the sixth with his second homer of the night _ his ninth of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   When Rey Sanchez singled in two runs later in the sixth, Dickson
was done for the night. His line: 51/3 innings, 7 runs, 9
hits. &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
