<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS NEED NO ENEMIES WITH FRIEND LIKE HIM 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Here's a stat worth knowing: the Red Sox went into the
24th inning in this series against the Expos before going down
1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's incredible,'' said John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' said Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, by the time Anthony Telford retired Darren Lewis,
Reggie Jefferson, and Nomar Garciaparra on, respectively, grounders
to the pitcher, second, and short in the Red Sox eighth, the Red
Sox already had 15 runs and 20 hits. The horse had long ago scooted
away from the barn, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Felipe Alou. All I could think of while watching this
series was how, not so long ago, the Montreal Expos were a monster
team. They were 74-40 in 1994 when the strike ruined both their
season and their franchise. Now this proud baseball savant is stuck
with prospects and suspects, and the last thing they needed to see
Thursday night was the mayor of Pedro City, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is never a welcome sight for any opposing team,
but there is the routine Pedro Martinez and there is the Pedro
Martinez who mesmerized the Expos through the first six innings of
Thursday night's 15-0 Red Sox victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was nasty tonight,'' confirmed catcher Scott Hatteberg.
``He had special stuff. He had a live fastball, his usual changeup,
and tonight he also had his curveball going.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor gave up two hits in six innings. He walked no one. He
threw 67 pitches, 53 of which were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a lot of strike ones,'' observed Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He established the night's ground rules to the very first
batter. F.P. Santangelo walked into the batter's box for what
turned out to be a very short stay. Swinging strike one. Swinging
strike two. Called strike three. Thank you very much. I'd say the
elapsed time of Santangelo's visit with Hatteberg and plate umpire
Greg Kosc was about 17 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor retired the first 13 men in order. The press box was
already talking you-know-what. With Pedro, you've got to. This is a
man who was born with what you call your no-hit stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have that feeling every time I take the mound,'' said
Martinez, who once lost a perfect game in the 10th inning when he
was pitching for the Expos. ``I know the day will come when I will
get a perfect game or a no-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fullmer ended the dream Thursday night with a solid single
to center. The only other hit was a sixth-inning leadoff double off
the wall to fairly deep left-center by Shane Andrews. There were no
regrets, because both were hit off pitcher's pitches. ``The only
bad pitch he threw was to (Rondell) White in the first,'' said
Hatteberg. The Montreal center fielder gave it a long ride to
center, but Darren Lewis hauled it in before crashing into the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case anyone in New England was wondering, we are now
looking at the real Pedro Martinez, not the illness-ridden guy who
gave up those 12 home runs in 24 innings a while back. In his last
four starts the mayor has given up 12 hits and three earned runs in
29 innings. His earned run average during those four starts is
0.93.
</P>
<P>
   The only real problem he had Thursday night was that his
teammates wouldn't let him get back to work. The Red Sox batted
around in both the fifth (six runs) and sixth (four more). All they
really needed were the two supplied by Nomar Garciaparra's fly ball
into the net with Lewis aboard in the first.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the mayor retired to the comfort of the locker room
after the sixth. ``I had a couple of long waits, and I mean long,''
he reported. ``That can affect your arm, and your whole body.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his body, Martinez is only now feeling fit following
that bout with gastritis earlier in the season. ``It took me two
months to get back to normal,'' he said. ``I'm still underweight.
But now I'm feeling stronger. I'm off the antibiotics. I'm eating
right. I'm feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   You might argue that anyone would feel better after facing the
Expos, and you would probably be right. The final Boston totals
included 45 hits and 28 runs during the three-game sweep. The flip
side is that nine Red Sox pitchers issued one walk in three games.
The Expos contributed seven recorded errors, two wild pitches, a
passed ball, and a variety of mental blunders. If you didn't know
better, you'd have thought that Montreal shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek was working off some gambling debt. He should have
been wearing a white jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing Mayor Martinez out there against his old team Thursday
night bordered on cruel and unusual punishment. But it was his turn
to pitch, and he had no choice. He was going to torture his
buddies, and there was nothing they could do about it. ``I feel bad
for those guys,'' he said. ``I have a lot of good friends over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll have a lot of good friends on this team, too, if he keeps
pitching like this. ``He's getting better and better,'' said
Hatteberg. ``You can see his confidence growing. When he's like he
was tonight, he's basically untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the thing of it all: the offense is going to bog down,
sooner or later. But Pedro? What we saw Thursday night was nothing
special, not for him. Just hope you're lucky enough to have a
ticket the night he finally throws the no-no.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0227EDT &QL; 
