<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-CHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN TO GET CALL TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After two days of hemming and hawing that Derek Lowe
was still in the starting rotation, the Red Sox made official what
they've known all along: Lowe is going back to the bullpen, and
Saturday afternoon's starter against the White Sox will be making
history: Jin Ho Cho, a 22-year-old righthander who will be the
first Korean ever to pitch for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Cho is being asked to do what few pitchers have done, regardless
of their nationality: Pitch in the big leagues in their first
season of pro ball. Will he be ready when less than three months
ago he was pitching for the Sox rookie team in the Gulf Coast
League, the lowest rung of the minors?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find out (Saturday),'' said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
``He throws an incredible amount of strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cho, whose signing was announced March 31, the same day the Red
Sox signed Billy Ashley, &UR;  &LR; was a member of the 1996 Korean Olympic
team who pitched for Won Kwang University the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Promoted from Single A Sarasota after going 3-1 in five starts,
Cho was 3-0 with an 0.97 ERA in his first six starts with the
Double A Trenton Thunder. In 37 innings, he had 31 strikeouts and
walked just seven.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox inadvertently tipped off the move on Wednesday, when
they omitted Lowe's name from their list of probable pitchers for
this weekend's series against the White Sox. As late as Thursday
afternoon, manager Jimy Williams insisted that as far as he was
concerned, Lowe was still his starting pitcher Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the day before, Williams already had called Lowe into his
office and told him he was going back to the bullpen. Lowe is 0-7
with a 5.81 ERA as a starter, 0-0 with a 1.14 ERA out of the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' said Lowe, who was in the pen Thursday night.
``We're winning, and if this makes us a better team, I'm all for
it. We're on a pace to win 100 games.''
</P>
<P>
   A roster move is pending. The most likely player to be sent out
would appear to be pitcher John Wasdin, who worked two scoreless
innings Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette raved about Cho, who held opponents
to a .171 batting average. ``He has good command of all of his
pitches,'' Duquette said. ``He's shown some extraordinary control.
He's thrown over 70 percent of his pitches for strikes. He's a big,
strong kid. He's physically mature and mentally mature, and he
throws strikes with all his pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Red Sox and their Asian intermediary, Ray
Poitevint, have had little success with their forays into the Far
East. They signed the Dominican mystery man, Robinson Checo, to a
deal that cost them close to $3 million. Checo has one big-league
win, sustained fractured facial bones in a freak batting practice
accident in Pawtucket, and then injured a side muscle during his
rehab stint in Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also thought they had signed a Korean pro star,
lefthander Sang Lee, but the deal was nullified by Major League
Baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
