<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS &LR;      07-03 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ENDS CHINA VISIT WITH FORECAST OF DEMOCRACY IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton ended a nine-day visit to China
Friday with the prediction that democracy would replace the
hard-nosed communist regime that has ruled in Beijing since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The president also lavished praise on Chinese President Jiang
Zemin in laudatory remarks that may ignite critics back home who
challenge his dealings with Beijing as a naive, one-way street.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks during a 37-minute news conference
before departing on an 18-hour flight for Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent barely 11 hours in face-to-face summitry with
Chinese leaders during his five-city tour, said he expects to see
the transition to democracy and the end of Chinese communism during
his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked if there can ``ever be democracy'' in China?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes,'' Clinton replied. ``I believe there can be and I
believe there will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would like to see ``the present government _
headed by this president and this premier who are clearly committed
to reform _ ride the wave of change and take China fully into the
21st century and basically dismantle the resistance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated: ``Not only do I believe there can be
(democracy in China); I believe there will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he foresees the end of Chinese communism during his
lifetime, Clinton, 52 , replied: ``I certainly hope so. I believe
that leaders of vision and confidence and courage will find a way
to put China on the right side of history _ and keep it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed China's ``remarkable transformation,'' adding
that Chinese leaders are beginning to share his conviction that
democracy is ``the right course practically as well as morally,
yielding more stability and more progress'' in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he is as confident about the emergence of democracy
in China as he is about the eventual election of a woman to serve
as president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I believe that a woman will be elected president of the
United States? I do,'' Clinton said. ``Do I think it will be a good
thing? I do. Do I know when it will happen? No. Who will make the
decision? The American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he has ``very high regard'' for the ability of
China's Soviet-trained 71-year-old leader to lead the nation of 1.2
billion through a tumultuous transition from a command economy
without western-style political freedoms to a free enterprise
system with democratic liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang is ``a man of extraordinary intellect, very high energy
and a lot of vision for his age _ and indeed for any age,'' Clinton
said.``I think he has a good imagination; he has vision; he can
visualize; he can imagine a future that is different from the
present.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``There is a very good chance that China has the
right leadership at the right time and that they understand the
daunting, massive nature of the challenges they face.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Jiang showed ``a personal expression of
confidence'' with his willingness to permit a nationally-televised
debate with an American president last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton acknowledged that Jiang faces resistance within the
Chinese leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there were ``powerful forces resisting change'' in
China, including factions that permit ``continuing governmental
restrictions on free speech, assembly and freedom of worship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everyone else, he (Jiang) has constituencies with which
he must work,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hoped his trip would help Jiang fend off
hard-liners. Clinton adopted a low-key approach on hot button
disputes with Beijing. He did not meet personally with any Chinese
dissidents, despite criticism from the dissidents here and critics
back home, in an effort to avoid antagonizing hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that more of them (hard liners) understand that America
wishes China well; that we're not bent on containing China; and
that our human rights policy is not some excuse for some larger
strategic motive,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the cause of human rights would make progress as
the result of his private appeals to Chinese leaders to free 150
Chinese imprisoned for non-violent offenses in connection with the
Tiananmen Square pro-democracy protests of 1989 and other Chinese
serving prison time for crimes that have been wiped off the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have a strategic partnership with a country with whom
we do not have a perfect relationship,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met with Martin Lee, leader of pro-democracy
activists in Hong Kong. Clinton also addressed Hong Kong business
leaders, warning that the United States cannot continue to bolster
Asia's troubled economies with disproportionate U.S. imports of
Asian-made products without Asian imports of U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very limited time period in which we can absorb all
the exports to try to do our part to keep the Asian economy
going,'' Clinton cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that he may have been a bit too harsh
during the 1992 presidential campaign when he accused President
George Bush of ``coddling'' Bejing's dictators after their
crackdown on pro-democracy activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any president would say that once you serve in this
job, you understand a little bit more of the nuances of all
policies than you do before you get in,'' Clinton said. ``But I
believe, on balance, that we have a stronger human rights component
to our engagement strategy than was the case before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 0944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
