<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-STEEL-ART-2TAK     07-03 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-STEEL-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FLEXING OF MUSCLE IN AMERICAN STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ind., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic showing production, employment of steel indus;try
and S&AMP;P steel index will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Production at American steel companies is booming, with the
mills cranking out tonnages not seen in decades. Manufacturers are
building new plants using new technology and methods that produce
efficiencies never dreamed of in the factories that once stood in
places like Pittsburgh and Youngstown, Ohio, and still symbolize
the industry's rust-belt image for many people.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, mills in the United States produced 107.5 million
tons of raw steel, a 22.3 percent increase over 1991, the low point
of the decade, according to the American Iron and Steel Institute,
a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Production is expected to be as good or better this year, and
the outlook for the next few years is promising, too, with a peak
of 110 million tons expected in 2001, according to a survey
conducted by Locker Associates, a steel consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The sector of the industry that makes steel by melting scrap _
rather than treating ore in the standard old-fashioned blast
furnace _ has been gaining market share, accounting for 46.4
percent of total production last year, up from the mid-30 percent
range early in the decade. Its share is eventually expected to
exceed 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The scrap-based operations were once known as mini-mills, but
they are not so mini anymore. Indeed, if the mini-mill leader, the
Nucor Corp., proceeds with planned and expected expansions, it will
emerge as the largest steel producer in the country, eclipsing the
USX Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, the steel industry has encountered some speed
bumps, and it faces the possibility of longer-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   The strike at the General Motors Corp. is cutting demand for
high-quality sheet steel, the principal product of the remaining
integrated companies _ those that make steel from raw materials
forward, using blast furnaces to process iron ore.
</P>
<P>
   Power shortages in the Midwest are affecting scrap-based
companies, which use electric furnaces that require vast amounts of
power to liquefy scrap.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowing the industry are the economic problems in Asia and
the weakening of Asian currencies, which has made Asian steel
cheaper to buy. The fear is that if large amounts of steel at low
prices flood this country, domestic producers will cut prices,
hurting profits.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the steel industry is vastly different now than it
was in the 1980s, when mills deemed obsolete were closed, throwing
tens of thousands of people out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the impurities in scrap, older steel companies
thought the mini-mills could never produce the high-quality sheet
steel used in appliances and interior car parts. Nucor proved them
wrong with its plant in Crawfordsville, Ind., in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the former general manager of that plant, Keith E. Busse,
and some of those who worked with him there are no longer part of
Nucor. They are the top executives of Steel Dynamics Inc., the
fastest-growing company in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   To further improve quality and to help protect themselves
against rising scrap prices, many scrap-based companies are
developing methods of separating iron from ore without using a
blast furnace. (Steel is iron with a small percentage of carbon and
other additives.)
</P>
<P>
   The integrated companies, meanwhile, are using the symbol of
their old ways, the blast furnace, to retain key customers, like
makers of the exterior parts of automobiles and light trucks.
Because they work with raw materials, these companies can more
closely control the chemistry and metallurgy of their products.
</P>
<P>
   Their newer methods have produced lighter, stronger types of
steel. The Bethlehem Steel Corp., which helped build the Golden
Gate Bridge and 1,100 World War II ships, is now known for products
that were not even made 10 years ago, like ultra-light sheet steel
for auto bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Steel scientists have calculated that if the 24-year-old Sears
Tower in Chicago were erected today, it would require 35 percent
less steel because of advances in steel strength.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These improvements have made foreign auto makers that assemble
cars in this country, including Mercedes-Benz, BMW, Toyota, Honda
and Nissan, happy to use locally produced steel, avoiding the
expense of importing it from home. Some studies show that American
steel mills have lower costs than those in Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The lower costs are a result of improvements in productivity in
the American steel industry. One key measure is the amount of labor
needed to manufacture a ton of steel. The industry has more than
doubled labor productivity, to 3.59 hours of employee work per ton
in 1995, the last year for which figures are available, from 10.1
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   But this understates what has happened. Some new scrap-based
mills are so automated they can make a ton of steel with less than
a half-hour of a worker's labor.
</P>
<P>
   All of this said, there does not seem to be much money to be
made by investing in steel stocks, at least at this time. Many are
currently trading near their 52-week lows, with little to excite
buying interest.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bethlehem Steel, considered a model industrial comeback
story, has suffered recently. Its stock, which doubled in value
from January to April, has since fallen more than 20 percent, to
trade at the $12.75 to $13 level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia is the biggest wild card out there,'' said Robert
Schenosky, a metals analyst with Merrill Lynch. He said prices of
steel produced in Asia are looking increasingly attractive to
potential buyers in the United States, putting pressure on domestic
steelmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the stocks will be cheap enough to create trading
opportunities, but that point hasn't arrived. ``The market dynamics
are very difficult for steel stocks,'' Schenosky said. ``Not all
the bad news has been built into steel stock prices yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel imports have already begun to climb. R. Wayne Atwell, an
analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said imports rose 21 percent
in April after falling in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   He sees an exception to the pessimistic near-term outlook for
steel stocks in Steel Dynamics, which began commercial operations
in January 1996. It is increasing production capacity to 2.4
million tons a year from 1.4 million tons, and is adding
higher-priced offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Steel Dynamics shares have fallen sharply on expectations of
weak second-quarter earnings. This last week they reached a low for
the year of $13.75, off 57 percent from their 1998 high of $23.375
on April 15, closing the week $14.125.
</P>
<P>
   Atwell said the company's problems were temporary and ``the
price more than discounts the likely earnings disappointment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
