<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9384 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-CAR-LEASE-ART-2     07-03 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CAR-LEASE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMAGE CONTROL HELPS AVOID SURPRISE ENDINGS TO AUTO LEASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Conn., Fla., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic showing websites for car leasing information will be sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Returning a leased car or truck is often thought to be a
turn-in-the-keys deal, but it can result in stunning, unanticipated
charges. Consumers can minimize the likelihood of wallet-stinging
damage, though, with some strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   How unpleasant can returning a vehicle be? Consumer Reports
magazine surveyed 203 people in August 1997 who had returned a
leased car in the prior year. It found that 38 percent would not
lease again, 25 percent faced lease-end charges and 30 percent
failed to recoup their security deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the back end, there's lots of subjective factors,'' said
Paige Amidon, manager of Consumer Reports' car-pricing services.
``You have very little control.''
</P>
<P>
   Lease experts say the largest unexpected charges are for
``excessive wear and tear'' _ a judgment assessed strictly by the
dealer. A close second are excess-mileage charges. Most leases also
require a ``disposition fee'' to cover the dealer's cost of selling
the car.
</P>
<P>
   Even customers who decide to buy their leased cars face fees.
Most leases require a fee to prepare paperwork if you plan to buy
and require you to notify the dealer in advance, typically a month
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Taterka, a lawyer in Kingston Springs, Tenn., said he was
shocked that a colleague had to pay a $400 fee to buy a Mazda sedan
from a dealer when its three-year lease ended in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a $400 provision, I would have disputed it at the
time,'' said Taterka, who reviewed the deal for his friend. ``But I
can't disprove it without a contract,'' he said, adding that his
friend had lost the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   One way around unreasonable charges for wear and tear is to get
more than one opinion, as Ms. Amidon learned. Before the contract
ended on her Nissan Maxima, she had taken the car to the dealer
that had issued the lease and asked for a written estimate of
anticipated repairs. But she moved to a different city before
repairing the damage, which was limited to a minor dent in a
bumper.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked another dealer near her new home for a similar
estimate, the itemized bill included new tires, a chipped
windshield and a hole in an armrest. ``The second guy found all
kinds of things wrong the first one didn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all leases allow the car to be returned to any authorized
dealer, so a good strategy might be to effectively play dealers off
against each other. A lessee might have the car inspected a month
before the lease is up, obtaining a written estimate of any repairs
from one dealer, as Ms. Amidon did. Then she might get another
estimate elsewhere, making sure that the repairs meet the
requirements of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to document the vehicle's condition when returning it
is to photograph the vehicle's interior and exterior and including
in the picture a current daily newspaper in the photo to
substantiate the date. The lessee should also insist that the
dealer sign off on the vehicle's condition upon its return, said
Richard Blumenthal, the Connecticut attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are getting bills months later for damage over and
above usual use,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of documentation led to a nightmare for Leigh Gold of
West Hartford, Conn. Ms. Gold said she had thought she was buying a
Volvo station wagon from Mitchell Auto Group in Simsbury, Conn.,
and was simply making loan payments on it.
</P>
<P>
   But when, after making the last payment on her 36-month
financing, she sought the title to the car, she said she was told
she actually had been leasing it from a company called Auto-Tech,
of Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gold said the dealer had never sent her the promised
paperwork on the deal, and she refused the leasing company's demand
for an additional $1,000 to buy a car she thought she already
owned. When it was towed from her driveway six months later, Ms.
Gold said, she reclaimed her vehicle after paying $6,000 in
additional penalties to Auto-Tech, which is the subject of three
complaints with the Connecticut attorney general, including Ms.
Gold's.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mitchell Auto Group said he was unaware of Ms.
Gold's situation and could not respond to questions about it. A
lawyer for Auto-Tech said it was common for people in disputes with
leasing companies to take the position that they were unaware they
were leasing, not buying, a car. But he described Ms. Gold's
contentions as ``unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mileage can also be a source of problems, said Michael S.
Kranitz, president of Leasesource Online Inc., which operates an
Internet site that helps consumers shop for competitive lease rates
and vehicle prices. Exceeding the mileage allowance in the contract
can cost 8 cents to 30 cents a mile.
</P>
<P>
   If the mileage costs are too high, it might be better to buy the
car at the end of the lease instead of turning it in. One factor is
whether the contract purchase price accurately reflects the car's
value in the used-car market as indicated in used-car guides like
those available on line. If the end-of-lease costs are high and the
vehicle has retained its value, a consumer might save hundreds of
dollars by buying it and then selling it independently.
</P>
<P>
   If the retail value is less than the purchase price in the
contract, the dealer may be willing to negotiate. But if the dealer
won't sell for less, and the excess-mileage charges are not too
high, the consumer should probably turn the vehicle in.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to minimize unanticipated fees when a vehicle lease
ends is to negotiate them at the contract's outset. But consumers
should be careful not to miss the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the elements in a financial transaction, the most
important single factor is that consumers have to negotiate the
purchase price,'' Ms. Amidon said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say the biggest penalties come when customers
end a lease early, as 40 percent to 50 percent of them do. ``Some
think, `The most I could owe is the balance of the lease,' '' said
Aurora Harris, a consumer laywer in Orange, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, contracts have complex, often sizable
penalties for ending early. Besides levying an early-termination
fee, like the $200 charged by Ford Motor Credit, many contracts
also recalculate a vehicle's depreciation, resulting in charges
that can be more than keeping the lease full term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies use the same formula for early termination as
for default,'' said Nancy Barron, a lawyer in San Francisco who
recently settled a class-action lawsuit against a Japanese auto
maker over its leasing practices. (The settlement prohibits her
from disclosing which company.)
</P>
<P>
   Companies can terminate leases if a customer gets too many
traffic tickets _ or dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``So your poor wife is charged as if she defaulted and a lien is
put on the estate,'' Ms. Barron said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
