<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     07-03 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKYLIGHTS: ASSETS, OR PAIN IN THE NECK? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 05 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My daughter is installing new interior walls and insulation
in her house, and is wondering if skylights are a good idea. Do
they work, or are they just a pain?
</P>
<P>
   BRENDA DELANEY, Jupiter, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure they work, if properly installed. Skylights are for
letting in more light, which is fine, but letting in light is also
letting out heat in winter, or bringing in heat in summer, whether
they are double-glazed, low E, or any other kind of so-called
insulating glass. Skylights may have to be shaded in winter to
reduce heat loss, and in summer to prevent excessive heat gain.
Keeping them open in summer is one way to prevent excessive heat
gain and to release heat.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively new are so-called roof windows, flat and movable and
equipped with shades. This is the type to buy. The flat ones may
tend to collect debris, particularly if installed on a shallow
roof. If the roof is shallow, you could build up the walls of the
opening so that when the roof window is installed, it is steeper
than the roof, allowing that debris to run off.
</P>
<P>
   More important to a skylight's function and to your peace of
mind is its installation. And that means the flashing, the metal or
other material that goes around the sides, bottom, and top of the
frame. In the handyman's opinion, the flashing on the sides of the
frame should be step flashing, a type that goes under each row of
roof shingles for a permanent, watertight installation. No other
kind will work as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm building a fence, and am in a quandary as to how to keep
the sections level. Would a string level be OK?
</P>
<P>
   JOE ZERMANI, Rockport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. So far you're on the right track, in wanting to keep a fence
level. Any fence that follows the contours of the property will
look dumb. If your property slopes, step the fence, making each
section at a different height, but level.
</P>
<P>
   So, you can use a string level, a little gizmo with hooks that
attach onto a taut twine. For this purpose, buy surveyor's twine, a
tough twine that pulls quite tight. You can't get it not to sag a
little, but this may not be terribly important when leveling a
rigid board. However, a regular level will be more accurate. Use a
four-foot mason's level. And, you can use the top rail of a fence
section as a level by taping the level onto it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I clean my hardwood floors that have a white dusty
film from heavy sanding of a bathtub before refinishing it? I wipe
a wet sponge on the floor and it looks great wet, but when it dries
the film remains. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's an old recipe for cleaning plaster dust from a floor,
and which should work for the bathtub sanding dust as well. Mix one
tablespoon of oil _ any kind will do: lubricating, linseed, cooking
_ in a bucket of warm water. Mix thoroughly (it won't mix, but try
to keep it mixed anyway. Dip a sponge into this mess, squeeze it
out, and wipe it on the floor. The result will be a shiny and clean
floor. The shine won't last very long, but dust will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Both the faucets in my shower valve are leaking, and I can't
get any hot water. How can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   BILL BROWN, Saugus, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sounds as if something is wrong with the cartridges. If you
can pull the cartridges out, take them to a plumbing supply shop
for replacement. And make sure they are designed for individual
faucets _ hot and cold. If you get no hot water, it might be
because the hot-water cartridge is defective or there is a
cold-water cartridge in its place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new double hung vinyl windows, the tilt-in type, are hard
to raise and lower. How can I loosen them? Would WD40 or silicone
lube help?
</P>
<P>
   JACK MARTIN, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. WD40 or silicone lube might work; spray it on the jamb where
the window moves. The oil won't hurt the vinyl, but be sure to wipe
off excess lube with a dry cloth; left on the surface, the material
will attract dirt. If that doesn't work, you might be able to
adjust the springs.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the window is in any kind of warranty, the manufacturer
or the installer should come back and adjust the springs and free
them up for free.
</P>
<P>
   Windows are a big pain, in my opinion. They have to be tight
enough so they won't leak air. They have to be loose enough so they
will move. So a compromise is reached; not too tight and not too
loose. As with most compromises, it doesn't work very well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having a new roof installed. I received several
suggestions, including fiberglass shingles and hand nailing. My
husband asked for organics (shingles that have a felt core instead
of a fiberglass core). The roofer said you can't get organics any
more. What shall I do?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DOROTHY SHUSTER, Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Fire the roofer; you can indeed get organic shingles. There
is no excuse for that kind of lying. I know you can get organics
because I had my roof redone this spring with them. Hand nailing is
good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
