<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL'S ART WORK IS STILL A MAN'S WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ Look up at the ceiling in the west corridor of
the art-gorged US Capitol, and you'll find one of the building's
few images of women: a mural of suffragettes marching for equal
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Then look down and you'll find the words ``MEN ONLY'' in bold
capital letters. The sign is on the saloon-style doors of a men's
bathroom, but it also captures the essence of the congressional art
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 451 works of art in the Capitol, only 12 are individual
portraits or statues of women, according to Barbara Wolanin,
curator for the architect of the Capitol. One more portrait hangs
in a House office building, that of Representative Edith Nourse
Rogers, the Republican lawmaker from Lowell who served in Congress
from 1925 to 1960, the longest of any woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have made major contributions in education, health care,
social work, agriculture, literature, the arts _ you name it _ but
you would never know that by walking through the Capitol,'' says
Representative Marcy Kaptur, a Democrat from Ohio. ``Women are very
shortchanged in terms of their contributions being displayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaptur is on a campaign to give women their due. She managed to
insert language in the 1999 legislative spending bill calling
attention to the underrepresentation of women in the Capitol art
collection and requiring a congressional plan to correct it. The
bill passed the House next week.
</P>
<P>
   The next step would be for a House-Senate conference committee
to adopt the measure. Even then, some argue, it will be difficult
to get women literally into the picture on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand what they're trying to do, but we can't go down
there and repaint the signing of the Declaration of Independence to
get women in there,'' said Jason Poblete, communications director
for Representative Bill Thomas, a California Republican who chairs
the Joint Committee on the Library of Congress and the House Fine
Arts Board.
</P>
<P>
   Kaptur says she isn't asking that historical art be doctored or
distorted. But she is determined that Capitol curators be more
conscious about gender when they select or commission art for
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some portraits of women are even locked away in storage
somewhere, and I can't understand why they have them but they don't
bring them out,'' Kaptur said.
</P>
<P>
   That recalls a spirited, four-year campaign by a coalition of 78
women's groups to get a 13-ton statue of suffragettes Lucretia
Mott, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, and Susan B. Anthony moved out of the
Capitol crypt and into a much more prominent location in the
central Rotunda. In 1996, Congress approved a one-year relocation.
The bulky statue, the 1921 work of Adelaide Johnson, was moved last
year to the Rotunda, where, according to the curator's office, it
likely will have an indefinite stay.
</P>
<P>
   There in the Rotunda, statues of presidents George Washington,
Abraham Lincoln, Andrew Jackson, Thomas Jefferson, Ulysses Grant,
and James Garfield stand proud. The only painting in the Rotunda
spotlighting a woman is ``Baptism of Pocahontas,'' by John Chapman.
It shows the Powhatan Indian princess, who wears a white formal
dress, kneeling before men and being blessed.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Washington and her granddaughters stand in a dark balcony
looking on in John Trumbull's painting of ``General George
Washington Resigning His Commission.'' Mrs. Washington and the
girls were not actually at the event, but ``the artist felt it
important that they be depicted on this occasion,'' a text in the
Rotunda explains.
</P>
<P>
   A tour of the Capitol artwork shows notable women are
outnumbered by nameless women in submissive or domestic roles _
Indian squaws shrieking in fear as explorers plunder their
villages; women praying, embracing men sent off to battle, and
carrying baskets of bread or spinning thread.
</P>
<P>
   In National Statuary Hall, the only woman represented is
Florence Rena Sabin, a Colorado physician. That statue stands in
the wings, behind a marble column.
</P>
<P>
   Poblete said the Capitol architect can't solve Kaptur's problem
with the statues, since they are selected and donated by the
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wants anything done about it, (Kaptur) has to call the
50 states' governors, some of which are women themselves,'' Poblete
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have asked the Joint Committee on the Library to do is
to actively promote increasing the number of women in the
artwork,'' Kaptur said. ``Just because the Committee on the Library
doesn't pick the statues, that's no excuse not to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The language in the House spending bill calls for the House Fine
Arts Board, the library committee and the Architect's office to
prepare a plan for the Capitol and the House office buildings
``that is more fully representative of women's contributions to
American society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't cost any more to do this,'' Kaptur said. ``It's
just a matter of trying to commission works that feature women
instead of men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
