<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SPICE-BOS &LR;      07-03 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SPICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIFFERENT SPICE, THOUGH JUST AS NICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The morning of May 29, day of the meltdown but we don't know
that yet.
</P>
<P>
   Phone rings. It's a Spice Girl, as arranged. It should be Geri
Halliwell, aka Ginger Spice, formerly known as Sexy Spice, the
leader of this pack. But it's not. It's Emma Bunton, the tiny,
21-year-old lollipop-licking pigtailed blonde known as Baby Spice.
It's a last minute switcheroo. We're told that Halliwell is ill,
but, otherwise, all is well.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, the bombshell drops: Ginger Spice had jumped
ship, leaving Baby, Melanie Brown (Scary Spice), Melanie Chisholm
(Sporty Spice) and Victoria Adams (Posh Spice) to fend for
themselves. The elder stateswoman, the boss lady, the former
topless model-turned-multimillionaire pop star, has bolted.
</P>
<P>
   The market crashed, governments fell, and the world shook.
</P>
<P>
   All right. Maybe not. But in the universe that is Spice World _
mostly a world of preteen females _ panic set in. Was it ... over?
In their native England, the voracious tabloid press sharpened its
claws. Having helped build the Spice machine, they decided it had
turned into a monster and was in need of tearing down. Hadn't the
Spice Girls been booed in Barcelona? Didn't they fire their manager
_ Simon Fuller (Svengali Spice?) _ under shadowy circumstances?
Didn't their movie and their second album, both called ``Spice
World'' tank? Wasn't their bloody 15 minutes up?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. What started early in 1996 with ``Wannabe,''
continues to roll forward. The second album has sold 32 million
copies worldwide. Their Boston concert sold out within 45 minutes.
In England, they endorse virtually every consumer product made _
chips, wallpaper, dolls, watches, cups. Now, touring America for
the first time, they've sold out the arenas and sheds in a flash,
including a Great Woods date Wednesday. We attempted to discuss the
post-Ginger Spice Girls scenario, but their representatives said
they were unavailable. (See sidebar below.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here's Baby Spice. Her favorite adjectives are
``amazing'' and ``brilliant.'' Her favorite adverbs are
``actually'' and ``obviously.'' She's got as much love for you _
her fans _ as Barney does for his.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it scary talking to journalists? Or are they coming to
terms with your success now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think hopefully. I mean, with the backlash thing we've sort
of taken it in our stride now. I think that happens with every band
that does quite well. Our fans have been really supportive, just
brilliant, and it's like you sort of just let it go over your head,
take it in our stride now. But I'm not scared about talking to you,
as long as you're not horrible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'll try not to be too horrible. I've got to say I respect
your sassiness. It seems real.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah. I think I think that's one of our messages: You have to
be yourself. We're just being ourselves. We're having a lot of fun
with it, and I think we're optimistic but realistic at the same
time, and I think you know we just enjoy every minute of it. And I
think especially for us coming to America to do this tour you know
all five of us, our dream is to come over to America and tour the
US. And our fans are brilliant as well in America. The last time we
came over for our (movie) premiere, it was amazing, fans all
outside the cinemas, just amazing, absolutely amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do they relate to?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I think that's very hard (to answer). A lot of people
say, `Why do you think you became so famous?'...For me it is that
we're quite positive. We think there's enough negativity in the
world. We just want to bring some good music, a bit of fun, and,
you know, a few messages to people. It's like one of our messages
is to go and have some fun. You know, the girl-power thing,
everyone wants to talk about girl power _ it's actually about
people power, it's about having strength within yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long do you think it can last?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I think, personally, fundamentally, us five are best
friends, and I think that's one of the main things. You know why
we're together: It's 'cause we're all good friends and we enjoy
every minute of the day, we appreciate every second.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ah, but people wonder if this a fake friendship?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it's quite easy on everybody's part, to be negative
about things, but we're just so pleased that our fans are so
supportive. I mean a lot of the backlash has been the press _ `We
can set you up and we can bring you back down.' But we feel that
only our fans can do that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's a quote I love from one of you guys: ``The Spice
Girls are like heroin, you can't help but absorb them till you're
sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A: Do you know what that was, actually? That was a joke by a
presenter at the MTV awards. We were there and it was quite a
funny, actually. I wouldn't say something like that. I'm quite
strict with the girls, that they're not too rude. That's my part.
Make sure nothing's falling out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the platform shoes? How can you walk to say
nothing of dance?
</P>
<P>
   A: The shoes. You have to be careful with the shoes. Don't be
falling off in the shoes. Actually, I got my first pair of Buffalos
_ that's what they are, the big shoes _ I bought them about five
years ago. I've always been quite short, you see, so I've always
needed a bit of height. But you do have to be careful with the
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you always in them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, no, I've calmed down with the shoes. While we've
been in Italy and things, I've been buying some designer stuff as
well, so yeah, I've calmed down a little bit with the Buffalos. But
you'll see a few on the show, I'm sure you will.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tell me about the show. You did a lot of preparation for this
tour, your first.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-WOMEN-BOS &LR;      07-03 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL'S ART WORK IS STILL A MAN'S WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ Look up at the ceiling in the west corridor of
the art-gorged US Capitol, and you'll find one of the building's
few images of women: a mural of suffragettes marching for equal
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Then look down and you'll find the words ``MEN ONLY'' in bold
capital letters. The sign is on the saloon-style doors of a men's
bathroom, but it also captures the essence of the congressional art
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 451 works of art in the Capitol, only 12 are individual
portraits or statues of women, according to Barbara Wolanin,
curator for the architect of the Capitol. One more portrait hangs
in a House office building, that of Representative Edith Nourse
Rogers, the Republican lawmaker from Lowell who served in Congress
from 1925 to 1960, the longest of any woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have made major contributions in education, health care,
social work, agriculture, literature, the arts _ you name it _ but
you would never know that by walking through the Capitol,'' says
Representative Marcy Kaptur, a Democrat from Ohio. ``Women are very
shortchanged in terms of their contributions being displayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaptur is on a campaign to give women their due. She managed to
insert language in the 1999 legislative spending bill calling
