<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD LANDS JUICY ROLE IN OCEAN SPRAY DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arnold Communications will create the first ads for Wellfleet
Farms, the premium 100 percent juice line launched by Ocean Spray
Cranberries Inc. six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray, which spent an estimated $50 million last year on
advertising, uses two ad agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Arnold produces ads for Ocean Spray beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Ads from Campbell Mithun Esty of Minneapolis promote cranberry
sauce and new Ocean Spray products.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Wellfleet Farms label is new, initial ads will be
created by Arnold, Ocean Spray said from its Lakeville, Mass.
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision follows Ocean Spray's recent appointment of Lynn A.
Rotando as senior vice president of brand development.
</P>
<P>
   Rotando had been a general partner at Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray says it has already shipped 400,000 cases of
Wellfleet Farms juices, such as Cranberrry &AMP; Georgia Peach, to
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Given the response of such big chains as Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
and the Kroger supermarket chain, Ocean Spray is calling the debut
of Wellfleet Farms the most successful product launch in its
68-year history. Look for Wellfleet Farms ads to begin running in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the many products that basketball star Michael Jordan has
plumped over the years is Ball Park Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dog companies can certainly afford high-priced pitchmen.
</P>
<P>
   During July, US consumers will buy an estimated $165 million
worth of frankfurters, 41 percent more than in an average month,
according to Information Resources Inc., a Chicago firm that tracks
scanning data at retail stores that sell groceries.
</P>
<P>
   In the next four weeks, consumers will buy $76 million worth of
barbecue-style condiments, $49 million worth of baked beans, and
about $1.5 billion worth of soft drinks and beer, IRI says.
</P>
<P>
   With numbers like those, it's no wonder soda makers and beer
companies are among the nation's biggest advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America Online Inc. likes to throw around statistics, too,
including the fact that the families of its more than 12 million
customers buy $37 billion worth of groceries a year.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why AOL just announced an interactive marketing
agreement with Unilever NV/PLC, the conglomerate known for such
products as Lipton tea, Ragu pasta sauce, Popsicles, and Dove (the
soap, not the ice cream bars).
</P>
<P>
   According to AOL, such products will now ``benefit from a
prominent presence throughout the AOL service, with a focus on
popular and contextually relevant areas covering such topics as
cooking, entertainment (and) health &AMP; fitness.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an all-points bulletin to curable romantics, the Diagnostic
Center for Men ran print ads this week featuring a photo of an
impotence doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The ad's tag line: ``Appointment today, Viagra tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that ad slogan as crudely direct as the one from the Maryland
plumber who boasts, ``We're Number One in the Number Two
business''?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Boston ad agencies, it was a good year at Cannes _ not the
film festival but the prestigious International Advertising
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos learned this week it won a
bronze lion for its work on behalf of John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. The same campaign was honored at Cannes last year.
</P>
<P>
   The previous week, Arnold Communications claimed one of the
festival's most coveted awards: a Grand Prix for print ads that
helped launch Volkswagen's updated Beetle.
</P>
</TEXT>
