<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATINGS-INTERNATIONAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BONDING FIRMS ENCOUNTER OVERSEAS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was once the stuff of local political drama: the
humorless officials at Moody's or Standard &AMP; Poor's cut a city's
bond rating and the mayor went on a rampage against Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era of global finance, when American business customs
are now embraced world-wide, it is no longer just mayors who
explode; so do the leaders of India, Russia, even Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrational,'' fumed Japanese Embassy official Mitsutaka
Inagaki of a Moody's warning in April that it might downgrade his
government's debt. ``A witch-hunt,'' fulminated Indian commentator
Mahatir Sabnavis of a Standard &AMP; Poor's decision in May to slash
his country's bond rating.
</P>
<P>
   Bond ratings have gone global. With them have gone the problem
of figuring out which way economies are headed and, for the
countries involved, coping with the consequences of rating
reductions. Even a tiny reduction in a bond rating can cost an
issuing country millions in increased interest costs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ``AAA+'''s and ``Ba1-'''s affixed to virtually
every bond in this country for a century are no more than educated
guesses about the likelihood a bond issuer will repay his or her
debt, they have come to mean much, much more, especially to the
emerging countries of eastern Europe, Asia and Latin America that
now depend on bond debt for development.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're viewed as kind of a report card on a country,'' said
Hendrik J. Kranenburg III, the executive vice president of Standard
&AMP; Poor's Ratings Services in New York. As such, they ellicit
powerful emotions, often to the surprise of the people who do the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Kranenburg remembers a newspaper reporter camping outside his
hotel room during a visit to Stockholm some years ago. The reporter
thought the S&AMP;P executive was preparing to cut Sweden's bond
rating, a move the reporter's paper was convinced would bring down
the government. (Neither happened.) More recently in Asia, rating
agencies have found themselves lumped in with currency speculators
and the austerity-endorsing International Monetary Fund as economic
devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to discourage people from seeing us as report card
writers,'' Kranenburg said. ``We're really kind of nerdy,'' he
explained, ``like accountants.''
</P>
<P>
   The rating agencies have never had a lot of success staying
safely behind their nerdy image. But with the Asian crisis, their
efforts to remain in the background have fallen completely apart.
That's because the agencies' traditional critics have been joined
by a new group &UR;  &LR; _ institutional investors who use bond ratings to
decide what foreign countries, companies and projects to invest in.
</P>
<P>
   These pension and mutual fund managers and corporate executives
charge that the agencies cost them mammoth sums by failing to warn
them in advance of the crisis, then failing to cut ratings quickly
enough to reflect the dimensions of the trouble, and finally
swinging to the opposite extreme and cutting them too abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   Among the critics' chief exhibits: Korea. As late as last
September, S&AMP;P and other agencies maintained the country's ``AA-''
bond rating, the same as Italy's and Sweden's. Then in a matter of
weeks, they dropped it below the ratings for countries like
Kazakhstan, Lebanon and Paraquay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't their finest hour,'' said Luis R. Luis, a managing
director with Scudder Kemper Investments in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the crisis, one rating agency, London-based Fitch
IBCA, issued an unusual admission that it had made mistakes; S&AMP;P
and a second US agency, Duff &AMP; Phelps Credit Rating Co., altered
the factors they examine in setting a rating, and Moody's is said
to be studying similar changes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating agency executives said that such changes should not come
as a surprise. The modern business of rating countries is still in
its infancy. Although S&AMP;P and Moody's have issued so-called
``sovereign'' ratings for decades, they were only of such stable,
creditworthy countries as the US and Canada and therefore did not
make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of junk bonds in the early 1980s and the 1982
foreign debt crisis, which discouraged banks from lending to
developing countries, investors were offered foreign bonds for the
first time and demanded ratings to guide their purchases. As the
financial revolution has reached into the riskiest corners of the
globe in recent years, some of the trickiest problems with ratings
have begun to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Among countries whose bonds have been recently rated or about to
be: Bolivia, Bulgaria and Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, agencies studied a narrow set of issues in coming
up with a rating, like how well a country's economy was running,
whether its government was balancing the budget and whether it was
running a trade surplus. But as they have moved into the developing
world, they have had to answer increasingly controversial and
hard-to-measure questions like whether a regime was likely to hold
onto power or be overthrown.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal turns on raters' decisions. According to executives
at several agencies, the difference of a single ``notch'' in a
rating -- for example, that between between ``B'' and `BB'' -- can
raise or lower the interest rate that developing countries have to
pay on their bonds by 1.5 percentage points to 5 or more percentage
points, or tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The result is predictable: ``It can get pretty volatile'' with
government officials, said S&AMP;P's Kranenburg. ``We've had finance
ministers get pretty upset with us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost anytime there's a downgrade, people blow up,'' added
Daniel L. Bond, vice president and chief economist with Duff &AMP;
Phelps in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The fight that the rating agencies are now engaged in over the
Asian crisis goes beyond these kinds of routine disputes. The issue
now is whether the rating agencies were looking in the right places
for potential trouble _ the stability of a country's banking
system, for example. Many critics jabe concluded they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that they were monitoring weren't what caused the
problem,'' said Joyce Chang, emerging markets director with Merrill
Lynch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the agencies correct this problem, however, executives
acknowledge there is still a danger that some country or region
will fail to pay its debts someday. ``No one in the modern bond
market has ever experienced a sovereign default,' said Kranenburg.
``Nobody really knows what it looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   If investors ever find out, they are likely to throw a tantrum
to match that of any big city mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
