<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SMOKE-BOS &LR;      07-03 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SMOKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATTER-DAY COWBOYS AND INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SMOKE SIGNALS 
Directed by: Chris Eyre 
Screenplay by: Sherman Alexie 
Starring: Adam Beach, Evan Adams, Irene Bedard, Gary Farmer, Tantoo
Cardinal, Cody Lightning, Simon Baker, Monica Nojica 
Running time: 89 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some intense images) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've heard from the 'hood. Now, with ``Smoke Signals,'' we have
begun to hear from the rez _ as the inhabitants of the Cour d'Alene
Reservation in Idaho refer with breezy irony to the patch of turf
onto which they have been herded. It's also where they survive the
daily assaults to their self-esteem with subversive wit and a kind
of upbeat mockery that is far from self-sparing. When the dour
Victor tells his nerdy lifelong buddy, Thomas, to stop spinning
``Dances with Wolves'' fantasies, the resilient Thomas, alluding to
their tribe's emphasis on fishing, replies that ``Dances with
Salmon'' doesn't quite have the same cachet.
</P>
<P>
   The bumpy but nourishing friendship between the 22-year-old men
is the film's mainspring. Adam Beach's Victor is the more
physically imposing one. Evan Adams's Thomas, with his goofy smile,
singsong vocal lilt, and natural ability to demolish the stereotype
of Indians as silent by nature, is the storyteller, smiling
unstoppably through rejection after rejection. They're linked as
well by more than the usual bonds of extended tribal family.
Victor's father saved Thomas from a house fire that killed his
parents. When Victor gets word that his father has died alone in a
trailer in Arizona, Thomas insists on accompanying him there.
</P>
<P>
   Their real journey, of course, is not to Arizona, but to
closure. Victor has been disabled by the rejection he felt when his
father deserted him and his mother years ago, and by the anger that
began by being directed at his father, and has spread to the white
world that repeatedly and sometimes assaultively denies him
respect. When two cowboys steal their seats on a bus, Victor is so
clenched he can barely speak. Thomas defuses the moment, though, by
making up a song insulting John Wayne's teeth as the film
trenchantly reminds us of the second-class citizenship forced on
Indians by a cowboy culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mockery, and even self-mockery, as a weapon is only one of the
things that causes you to pick up your ears at the rightness that
emanates from Sherman Alexie's script and Chris Eyre's direction.
Cour d'Alene Indian Alexie brings a poet's soul to his fiction,
including the story from which this film was drawn. He never makes
grand pronouncements about the pain and the love his characters are
trying to reconcile; he just lets us see both, jostling each other,
and Eyre, an Arapaho, never hits the material too hard. Between
them, we hear everything Victor's silences are saying. We also
sense the deep reserves of healing energies Thomas is reaching into
with his compulsive chatter.
</P>
<P>
   As the friends make their way from the top of the country to the
bottom and back again _ their journey to and from the archetypal
underworld _ they learn a few secrets about Victor's father, learn
what he was haunted by, thanks in part to his strong, wise and
spiritually radiant neighbor, played by Irene Bedard. They return
more complete than when they left, although there are no facile
intimations that human and generational mysteries are to be easily
resolved with a convenient cathartic insight.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Farmer and Tantoo Cardinal are authoritative, too, as
Victor's estranged but far from mutually indifferent parents.
Proceeding from an insider's vision, Alexie never makes the mistake
of dealing in stoic stereotypes. His characters are always alive,
always, they convince us, themselves. And being themselves means
they appreciate the small details of life on the rez _ such as a DJ
accompanying a sunny weather report with an aside that it's a good
day to be indigenous, or a woman who drives her car in reverse
because the forward gears are shot and she hasn't the money to get
them fixed. ``Smoke Signals'' is a disarming little gem of a film,
shining with heart and an idiosyncratic will to wholeness. In its
quiet, personalized, intimately scaled way, it's a landmark _ the
first film to be written, directed, and coproduced by Indians. But
then part of its charm is that it would make fun of the landmark
label.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
