<HEADER>
A9547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      07-03 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SAYS: COMMERCIAL IS NOT A DIRTY WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Does a melody immediately pop into your head when you read
these words? ``That's the way _ uh-huh, uh-huh _ I like it.'' Let's
try another: ``Do a little dance, make a little love, get down
tonight!'' Yes, I thought so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work in a retail record store,'' says KC (ne: Harry
Wayne Casey), the brains, voice, and hook-meister of KC and the
Sunshine Band, a man who knows the joy of repetition. ``People
would be coming in not knowing the songs and asking me. And I
thought: `They're gonna know the name of my song if it kills me.'
In reality, that commercialism of a song is what makes it a
commercial hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you never can expect that to happen,'' continues KC,
the most successful white artist of the disco era, ``but when it
does, it's a terrific thing, and kind of gives some credibility to
the idea. When I look back at music history, when I first started
out writing, the thing that gave me a lot encouragement was the
Beatles, although I wasn't a Beatles fan at all. But one night I
was at a friend's house and she had some Beatles albums and I
looked at the lryics and said, `Damn, this is what I'm doing.' It
was simplistic and commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, of course, if it were that easy everyone would sell 75
million albums, which KC has. He wrote about shakin' booties and
the all-night boogie. Camp? Sure, a little, 'fesses KC. The
effervescent singer celebrates 25 years in the biz Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   KC hit a rut during the early '80s: death of disco, death of his
dad, a serious car crash, strident business disputes, alcohol and
other drug addictions. ``I was in `retirement,''' he says, ``doing
all the crap. After you've done it all, where do you go? I started
missing what I loved the most, the performing and musical part of
it. The two _ drugs-and-booze and performing _ did not work well
together. It was not doing anything for me anymore. It got to a
point where, you start with one glass, and then you drink a fifth
and you're not any drunker. You say, `This is no fun, I'm tired and
not all together.'''
</P>
<P>
   KC's music has never really gone away. It has helped sell cars
by General Motors, fast food by Burger King and McDonald's,
semi-fast food by Denny's. It's made him a pile of cash. Pillsbury
wanted to market Old El Paso cheese salsa and so KC re-recorded
``I'm Your Boogie Man'' with a twist: ``I'm Your Cheese Boogie
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some writers do not want their music that way,'' waxes KC. ``I
don't think it hurt. The songs are commercial and why not tie them
in with a commercial? Especially since they're 25 years old.
Although, for `I'm Your Boogie Man,' I had to think about a minute
for `Cheese' _ I thought it would be OK. (The spot) wasn't gonna
run for that long.''
</P>
<P>
   He was influenced by early Motown, James Brown, Aretha Franklin,
and the Animals, the funkier side of early to mid-1960s pop. His
songs have been covered by the Spin Doctors and White Zombie.
They've been in about 15 movies, including ``Private Parts,''
``Devil's Advocate,'' and, of course, ``Boogie Nights.'' Which he
hasn't seen. Doesn't get out much to movies, he says, and even
though he's got the videocassette and DVD versions, he hasn't
screened either yet.
</P>
<P>
   Anything on the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on an album for two years,'' KC says, ``and
I'm finally getting to the point where I think it's right. It's
definitely a funky dance sound.'' Is it magic? ``You never can
tell, but I think so. I do feel it. I don't think I've lost that
thing I've been blessed with, that gift for the melodies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's talk about death. Isabel Monteiro, singer of
England's Drugstore, has written this sad, sweet gorgeous song,
``Funeral (But Most of All),'' about what happens at her funeral
(``sad-looking faces surrounding my bed ... heartbreaking tales of
passion and pride'') and what the afterlife might be like (she gets
to bring her friends and treasured possessions).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can't help but think about death, people who love
life as much as I do,'' she says from London, in the midst of
packing for a US tour. ``You can't not be aware that this fantastic
movie is going to end.'' She feels, though, the song is pure
fantasy. ``I wish there was an afterlife. I wish I could believe in
something; death is too cruel. But as far as I can tell, this is
it. Being alive, that's what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Monteiro, a native Brazilian who moved to London 10 years ago
with a backpack and the intent of staying six months, formed
Drugstore with her mates in 1992. She moved to England not to be a
pop star, but to escape a ``fairly oppressive, conservative
family,'' she says, ``to go to the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore tosses lot of cool elements into its brew: pop,
art-rock, alt-rock, mariachi. It's buoyant and dark. A cellist, Ian
Burdge, is part of the band. On Drugstore's latest, second disc,
``White Magic for Lovers,'' Radiohead's Thom Yorke joins Monteiro
on ``El President,'' an elegaic song about assassinated Chilean
President Salvatore Allende. But the CD is far from dour. It opens
with ``Say Hello,'' a call to, and an embrace of, people everywhere
_ junkies, sinners, and thieves, too. It's propulsive, upbeat.
Monteiro writes personal songs, but she's no navel-gazer. ``I
wouldn't want to bore people as to (writing a musical) diary....
What fantastic stories can you have if you're not 65?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many different ways to live life,'' she continues.
``Some of us are luckier than others, that's very clear. But we're
all trying to go through it the best way we can. I'm moved by
people _ I can imagine their disappointment. and am moved by that
stuff.'' For all the dark edges in Drugstore's sound, the overall
effect is anything but downbeat. In concert, she says, ``the people
we talk about in the songs come to life. It's very positive _ with
sad moments _ but most nights people walk home uplifted.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; sods: Listen for even more of Gary Glitter's ``Rock 'n'
Roll (Part 2)'' in the movie ``Small Soldiers.'' Speaking of
movies, Newsweek found that the ``Armageddon'' soundtrack hit a
louder-than-rock level 117 db. I cover rock for a living and my
ears rang for three days. ... Checking on the charts, we find Pink
Floyd's ``Dark Side of the Moon'' is in its 1,108th week on
Billboard's chart (Top Pop, Catalog). Do the math and it'll put you
back in the Mesozoic Era. Floyd's ``The Wall,'' a baby, has been
there but 480 weeks. ... New England: It's not just a region; it
was once a band. Ex-drummer Hirsh Gardner, long a producer, reports
the the former bandmates established a Web site ``as a goof'' only
to get a worldwide response for their three albums, now on CD. ``I
never realized we had so much imapct after 20 years.'' The former
members bought back the rights from various labels and are selling
CDs via www.newenglandrocks.com.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
