<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-TITANIC-BOS &LR;      07-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-TITANIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANIC ARTIFACTS APPEAL TO BOTH BUFFS, LEO'S FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M. R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is too small to be a spectacle, too large to be a
mere curiosity, this modestly titled show, ``Titanic _ the
Exhibition,'' open daily from here to the eternity of Nov. 1. In
its first days, it is attracting a ready-made audience of Leonardo
DiCaprio fanlets with parents and au pairs in tow. The remainder of
the crowd seems to be an older sample of citizens who were
fascinated by the disaster long before the movie ``Titanic''
reached its vast, young audience. Adults were recruited by books,
several previous public television and museum documentaries, and
press coverage of the discovery and exploitation of the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable saga _ the world's largest ocean liner sinks on
its maiden voyage _ is embedded in the American psyche. No other
ship has entered the common speech. Every hapless bureaucrat and
incompetent executive has been described as ``social director on
the Titanic.'' More important, they always will be. If this year
were not the 100th anniversary of the Spanish-American War, only
Trivial Pursuit virtuosos would still ``Remember the Maine!''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit itself at Boston's World Trade Center _ about 70
stands and glassed-in pedestals _ probably does contain the touted
several hundred artifacts (is the deck of cards one thing or 52
plus jokers?). And the simple fact is that almost nothing on
display would attract attention except for its temporary 80-year
storage on the floor of the Atlantic, 2 1/2 miles deep. People
would have to be paid money to make their way to lower Congress
Street (``New Congress Street'' in Big Dig parlance) to look at a
safety razor and a paper box of double-edge Gillette blades.
</P>
<P>
   With very few exceptions, the show consists of such mundane
things made into relics by inadvertent baptism in salt water. There
is, for example, a corroded aluminum and brass megaphone, identical
in size and shape to every high school cheerleader's acoustic
device. It certainly looks like it was rescued from 2,200 fathoms
under the sea, but in case the visitor is not awed, a sign
suggests:
</P>
<P>
   ``This aluminum megaphone, with its brass frame, might have been
used by Captain Smith in giving orders to abandon ship.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that curiously retrieved objects gained at
great expense and risk of life are not fascinating. Lines still
form in museums to look at moon rocks, which look exactly like
rocks, only smaller. Pebbles from Mars will, if anyone is still
alive, require extended hours and increased security if some come
back in the year 2525.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing particularly ghoulish about the exhibit; if
anything, it errs on the side of reverence, or perhaps bathos. A
pedestal supports two playing marbles, one intact, one rather badly
broken: ``A childhood dream, soon to be shattered, can perhaps be
seen in these marbles,'' the visitor is advised. Given the age of
the DiCaprio contingent, such advice can perhaps be seen as
necessary to create the proper mood. It does keep one from
remarking out loud that in the big scheme of things, a marble is
just a marble, and in this case, not even an aggie, let alone a
cat's eye.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of the exhibit, there seems to be a shortage
of signage; several cases are either expected to tell their own
story (possible in most examples) or the label is in the mail. One
of the unlabeled exhibits (as of Thursday morning) is a single
piece of sheet music, probably the second page of a folio. With
difficulty (compounded for the bifocal wearers, who have to enlist
the aid of literate pre-teens to read the uppermost lyrics), it can
be determined that the music is not only authentically Titanic, but
is itself an icon of the straw-boater, striped-shirt, world of
1912. The song is used to this day in movies to establish with a
few bars the time period of 1910 (and it was revived, oddly, during
World War II):
</P>
<P>
   ``Put your arms around me honey, hold me tight, cuddle up and
cuddle me with all your might'' a Leonardo fan read aloud, and
added: ``It says something funny, something like `Oh Babe won't you
roll dem eyes,' and then it ends.'' So it goes.
</P>
<P>
   In an academic exhibit (if one can be imagined), the label might
give you the title (not surprisingly, ``Put Your Arms Around Me
Honey,'') and might even, if it were a Harvard exhibit, inform the
visitor that the lyrics were by Junie McCree and the music was by
Albert Von Tilzer. (Readers who have never heard of Von Tilzer
should know he is also the composer of ``Take Me Out to the Ball
Game.'')
</P>
<P>
   The saddest objects, like most of the personal belongings, were
brought up from the depths in suitcases or valises. Near the exit,
unfolded like a very flattened patient etherized on a table, is a
pressed double-breasted men's suit and socks to match.
</P>
<P>
   The most engaging article, both in size (some 15 feet in length)
and in its organic shape, is what appears from a distance to be
something like a sperm whale's lower jawbone. It is the steel davit
_ a ship's small hoisting crane for a life boat. Elegantly curved,
its function perfectly expressed in its form, the davit fairly
shouts at the visitor: ``This show is about lifeboats, this is all
about death.''
</P>
<P>
   That fact is not lost on the younger visitors. Allison
Ustynoski, 9, of Wilkes-Barre, Pa., (where she has been taken out
to the Scranton-Wilkes-Barre Red Barons ballgames) very much wanted
to see the show. ``And then,'' she said, with that pure certainty
of young women of that age, ``I think they should put everything
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9554 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARAMETRIC-TURBULENCE     07-03 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARAMETRIC-TURBULENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAMETRIC WOES SPARK NOSE DIVE; SHARES FALL 35% 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parametric Technology Inc.'s growth over the past decade has
been nothing short of spectacular. It has had 40 consecutive
quarters of improved sales and operating profits.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only thing more astounding about the Waltha, Mass.
software company is the breathtaking nose dive its shares have
taken in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare that investors can wipe out $4.5 billion of a
company's market value in less than a week, but that's what
happened to Parametric, the leading provider of software that helps
engineers design new products.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Parametric shares plunged as much as 40 percent after
the company warned late Wednesday that glitches in its shift to a
promising new product would hurt sales and profits for its
third-quarter ending Saturday, July 4. The warning prompted at
least four investment analysts to downgrade the stock Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric shares, which had been trading at about 35 in
mid-April, fell 8 3/4 Thursday to close at 161/16. Nearly 40
million shares traded hands, making it the second-most active US
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The tumble came on the heels of another big plunge earlier in
the week, after an analyst at Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill downgraded the
stock amid worries that its core software product was being hurt by
lower-priced competitors that are nibbling away at the lower end of
Parametric's customer base.
</P>
<P>
   The slide began Friday on concerns that the economic crisis in
Asia was choking demand for Parametric's software among Japanese
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-third of the world's economy is taking a holiday, and that
can really hurt a company,'' said Charles Foundyller, president and
chief executive of Daratech Inc., a Cambridge, Mass. market
research firm that tracks the computer-aided design industry.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric makes sophisticated three-dimensional modeling
software that helps engineers design everything from cars to
airplanes to cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Its core product, called ProEngineer, features breakthrough
technology that allows an automotive designer, for instance, to
tinker with one feature of the vehicle, and the software will
automatically recalculate the relative dimensions of the rest of
the automobile. That greatly speeds the time it takes for an
automaker to bring new cars to market.
</P>
<P>
   But competitors have discovered that some mid-sized customers
are willing to do without all of the bells and whistles in
Parametric's design software if they can save money. So they're now
offering design software that costs just $5,000 to $8,000, far less
than Parametric's ProEngineer, which sells for an average of
$19,000.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts, and even Parametric executives themselves, say the
company's biggest problem is its own doing.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to begin selling a promising new Web-based software that
works in conjunction with its original program, Parametric shifted
its best sales people _ 25 percent of its sales force _ to the new
product, called Windchill.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, sales of its core product, ProEngineer, dropped
unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts Wednesday afternoon,
Parametric officials said they expect revenue for the quarter
ending Saturday to be 15 percent below analysts' estimates, which
had ranged from $292 million to $300 million, and that earnings
will also fall below analysts' estimates of 26 cents a diluted
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``This result is something of a surprise to us,'' said chairman
and chief executive Steven Walske, who called the shortfall
``embarrassing.'' The company will announce its third-quarter
results July 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
