<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE RIGHT ON TARGET WITH SAVINGS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 05 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 33 years old and are saving for our
retirement and for the college education of our future children.
Our retirement investments include $30,000 in Fidelity Growth and
Income fund and $1,000 in T. Rowe Price Equity Income fund, to
which we add $624 and $162 a month respectively. We also have these
mutual fund accounts to which we are no longer making
contributions: $22,000 in Vanguard Windsor II, $5,300 in Fidelity
Contrafund, $4,400 in Scudder International, $1,700 in Vanguard
Institutional, and $1,500 in AIM Constellation. Investments
designated for the college expenses are $6,100 in Scudder Large
Company Value fund, $4,800 in Janus Growth and Income fund, and
$3,900 in PBHG Growth, and $1,600 in Oakmark fund. We add $100 a
month to each account, except we add $200 a month to Janus Growth
and Income. We hope to have the first of two children in the next
two years, and to retire at age 62. Are we being sufficiently
aggressive in saving for our goals?
</P>
<P>
   K.G., Scituate, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, my tally shows a likely retirement pool of $2,511,435
after 29 years (based upon an assumption of 10 percent average
annual returns and contributions at your current level). And my
guess is that you may be slightly overfunding the college accounts.
So you're doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   My calculation is that after 18 years of ongoing contributions
to the college account, you will have amassed $421,367, again
assuming 10 percent average returns.
</P>
<P>
   If we follow the experts who project 6 percent annual inflation
in college costs, the ticket for the freshman year in a private
college in 18 years would be about $56,000. When we carry the
ongoing contributions through a six-year period -- I'm guessing
that the second child might be two years younger than the first --
you'll have plenty to meet the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there are two additional factors. One is that it seems
to me probable that at some stage the escalation in educational
costs will have to slow down, lest we either produce a generation
that's uneducated because so few can afford college, or in the
alternative, a generation that will be saddled with $150,000 or so
in college loans by the time they get their first jobs. The second
factor is that almost everybody qualifies for some form of
financial aid -- especially if their parents have planned ahead so
as to maximize eligibility. So it's likely the real costs will be
less than that horrifying $56,000 for the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a few points about the portfolios. First, you don't say
whether or not the retirement money is in tax-deferred accounts
such as 401(k)s , IRAs, or similar instruments. If they are not, I
suggest you investigate the variable annuities offered by most
major fund families, which will provide you with tax-deferral, at a
cost of only about one half of one percent less than the returns
for comparable traditional mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Next, one of the funds you list -- Vanguard Institutional --
leaves me a bit at a loss -- precisely what is it? Vanguard offers
two institutional funds that track the Standard and Poor's 500
Index, and my guess is that it's one of these. If that's so, I
tally that eight of your total 11 funds -- and all of those in
which your largest positions are lodged -- are large-cap funds. AIM
Constellation and PBHG Growth both fall in the mid-cap arena, and
International find is a small position. That's not enough: I think
you have too much reliance on large-caps, and I suggest a bit more
diversification for the retirement portfolio -- certainly adding a
small-cap fund, perhaps increasing the commitment to the mid-caps,
and even adding smaller positions in funds in the health care and
technology sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, once your children are born, I suggest you take full
advantage of the new educational IRAs, which will give you a little
tax advantage on the college-savings side (and shouldn't eventually
amount to so much that they would seriously affect eligibility for
financial aid).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife is 58 1/2 years old and I am 59 1/2. We plan retiring
in June of 1999. My wife has a small pension plan with which she
has a choice of a $24,000 lump sum or a $450 monthly annuity. Which
should she take? I have a $525,000 retirement portfolio, consisting
of $225,000 in money markets and CDs, almost $25,000 in common
stocks, and the rest in income-oriented mutual funds. What changes
should I make? I am trying to be as conservative as possible. I
need to take out approximately $3,200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   C.M., Beaumont, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your wife's pension options sound too good to be true. If the
numbers are right, there's no question that the annuity is more
attractive than the lump sum. If your wife were to take the cash
and invest it so as to produce a $450 monthly income stream for 20
years, she would have to achieve a 24.78 percent average annual
return. Either her employer is offering a very powerful incentive
to take the annuity, or there's something wrong with the terms as
you have stated them. Anyway, if you've got it right, take the
annuity with a glad cry. But check.
</P>
<P>
   As for your portfolio, I worked it out on a spreadsheet and
estimated a portfolio average 6.26 percent yield; I say estimated
because you provided yields for everything but your common stock,
and I plugged a very conservative 1 percent number in there. This
brings you an annual income stream of $32,862, or $2,738 a month.
If you can add your wife's annuity to that amount, it takes you
within 12 bucks of the target $3,200. If you consider the annuity
as separate money, you could simply stick with the portfolio as it
is, counting on it to last about 30 years -- and probably a little
more, because that calculation didn't account for growth within
that small stock portfolio. But if we estimate 8 percent growth in
the stock portfolio over those 30 years (using a lower figure than
usual because you are taking the dividends in cash) that segment of
the portfolio would grow to about $251,000 - - enough to keep you
going for another eight years or so.
</P>
<P>
   That all works out tidily on paper, but not if you worry about
inflation. The value of $3,200 a month is certain to be
dramatically less in a decade or so than it is now. So what you
need is something to deliver capital growth as well as income. I
usually find myself advising people your age to cut back on stocks;
in your case, it's the opposite. You hold less than 5 percent
stocks, and I think at a minimum that figure should be doubled --
and given your relative youth, it should probably be tripled. You
can do this in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   One would be to try to trim your budget by $200 to $300 a month,
transferring funds (slowly) from your lowest-yielding investment
(the money market) to a middle-of-the-road stock fund, such as one
tracking the Standard and Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   Another option, provided you and your wife will be eligible for
Social Security checks in a few years, is to proceed with the
current portfolio until those checks kick in; once that happens,
keep your income stream as it is and use the Social Security checks
to build up the stock position.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, once Social Security does kick in, it will represent
the last substantial ``raise'' you're likely to see in retirement,
so you'll want to use as much of it as you can to protect yourself
against future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 67 with a monthly income of about $3,000 from pensions
and Social Security. I have a total of $209,000 invested, with the
lion's share in fixed-income securities. Since retiring I realize
our investments were too conservative, and now I want to invest
$30,000 which is now in a 3.04 percent savings account, plus
another $10,000. Do you suggest putting this money in higher-risk
funds?
</P>
<P>
   J.H., Woodville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, I think it's a good idea -- but move slowly. I suggest
you start with the $30,000, investing it over a 36-month period. At
the end of that time, you can decide whether you want to go
further; a $30,000 stock investment would represent a little less
than 15 percent of your portfolio; another $10,000 would bump it up
to a little more than 19%.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you begin by putting $3,000 of the money in a fund I
have long admired -- Vanguard Index Value, which holds about two
thirds of the Standard and Poor's 500 stocks -- those with the
lowest price-to-book value ratios, and also those that tend to pay
the heaviest dividends. Then put the other $27,000 in Vanguard's
Prime Money Market fund, with instructions to move $800 into Index
Value every month.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming a 5 percent yield from the money fund, this will mean
you'll be fully invested in about 36 months. This technique, called
dollar cost averaging, protects you from a sudden marked downturn
(because you buy later shares at lower prices) and is basically a
conservative approach to establishing a position in a stock fund.
I'm running out of space, but see the letter from C.M. above to
understand why I think a modest stock position is a good idea in
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
