<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV05-BO     07-03 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME AGAIN _ AND GLAD OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, July 05 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (When last we left the intrepid columnist, he was asleep in a
diesel truck somewhere near Rochester, N.Y., with almost 2,000
miles remaining to his destination and three days to get there.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Day Three begins at 5:05 a.m. with a check of the load _ the
steamer is still secure _ a check of oil and engine coolant, and a
spot of what passes for breakfast under the arches. I have spare
oil and coolant in one of the storage bins behind the seat _ this
is not an extended cab, but there is plenty of storage space
nonetheless, with shelves and a net to secure stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The road west to Buffalo is lightly traveled, but traffic picks
up as I head southwest toward a corner of Pennsylvania and into
Ohio. Ohio, without doubt, has the best rest stops of any state
along its highways _ clean, nicely landscaped, offering picnic
areas, facilities for pets, weather info, and maps. I pull into one
for lunch _ peanut butter on oatmeal bread and my private-recipe
lemonade (add limes for extra zest).
</P>
<P>
   The wind is still brisk, and every time a semi passes, it sets
up a venturi effect between us that pulls the Ram toward it. I turn
off I-90 and head southwest across Ohio via I-71 to I-70. At
Montville, Ohio, I pull off for fuel, enter a Sunoco station, cut
too close to an overhead sign. I back, take the corner wider _ a
bystander signals that I am clear. I am not, and nudge the overhead
sign, one of four, and it slips its moorings. I back away from it
and it slides along the forward edge of the brand new trailer.
Damn!
</P>
<P>
   A couple of bystanders help me take the dangling sign down _ it
is held by a single bolt, thumb tight! _ lest it fall on someone.
In the process, the sign gets bent, the only damage to it. The
woman tending the counter is very sympathetic, very upset. She must
have an accident report; she will call the maintenance man to
assess things. I figure I'll slip the maintenance guy a few quid
for his trouble and be off.
</P>
<P>
   But maintenance guy doesn't show; a police officer does, who has
still more paperwork. From the sound of things, he is, if not the
sole proprietor, at least part of the ownership. ``Don't worry,''
he says, ``this is why we have insurance.'' Indeed, we have
Chrysler's insurance, the museum's insurance, and my insurance _
this could be a paperwork nightmare over a dented sign and a
scratched trailer. Refueled and properly recorded, I hit the road
again. Now it is raining.
</P>
<P>
   Construction looms everywhere. I-70 is a nice road where it
exists. I exit Ohio under the welcoming arch, enter Indiana. I-70
through Indianapolis is a maze. Public Radio keeps me company, but
changing stations as I move in and out of range is exasperating _
the guy who designed the radio (it had to be a man; no woman would
do this) forgot that somebody might have to use it in a moving
vehicle. Rockers and tiny buttons far removed from the driver are a
nuisance. Fortunately, the heater/AC controls were designed by
somebody else _ keeping comfortable in the Ram is a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   More fuel, another peanut butter break as we roll on into
Illinois. I shift to a northerly route to bypass St. Louis and
forgo the grand arch to save time and distance _ the Mississippi is
impressive. The Cummins diesel is singing to me; my eyes are
getting heavy as I cross into the hilly eastern end of Kansas _ nap
time.
</P>
<P>
   Once past the border hills, Kansas is a vast flat expanse broken
only by silos and oil derricks _ yes, they pump oil in Kansas. The
state has wheat and, as the signs proclaim for hundreds of miles in
advance of the place, it is _ in Russell, to be precise _ the home
of Bob Dole. Somewhere west of Teutopolis, Kan., I pull into a
motel with the trip odometer showing 1,333.4 miles traveled. I will
treat myself to a cold manhattan, a Kansas steak, and a good
night's sleep. Oh, yeah?
</P>
<P>
   The sign says beer and wine only, but the waitress announces
``there's none of that, either.'' Nor is there steak. I settle for
iced tea and roast beef _ it is an end cut the size of a small dog,
dry as a chip. Revelers in the night make me long for the peace of
the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling across Kansas next morning, I come upon the beaver. It
is dead on the side of the highway, the nearest tree more than half
a mile behind it, the nearest water a quarter mile ahead of it. I
figure it died of the commute. My God, Kansas goes on forever!
</P>
<P>
   Lunch sees the end of the lemonade, and the truck drones on
through the flat countryside _ uphill. I can find no telephones,
few places of habitation. At 1,994.6 miles, I pull into a rest area
for a long snooze. Another day done.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 a.m., it's back on the road and into Colorado; eastern
Colorado is more of Kansas, high plains but with cows and suicidal
tumbleweeds. At 7:33 a.m., I pull into Seibert, Colo., which is
mainly a truck stop, park next to a semi, wave to the driver, and
enter a restaurant seeking breakfast. Some locals are having
coffee, two people are in a booth eating. I make eye contact with
the serving person and sit down. Nothing happens. More serving
persons appear, but do not serve _ nor speak to me. The locals are
eyeing me now, so I assume I have not become invisible. After 20
minutes, I walk out _ the serving persons watch me leave.
</P>
<P>
   It occurs to me that the truck driver parked outside is a black
man. Is this their problem? Did they refuse to serve him? Do they
think I'm with him? Does this stuff go on in Colorado? I decide to
ask him _ too late; his truck is showing tail lights as I exit.
</P>
<P>
   I refuel down the road from Seibert, breakfast on a peanut
butter sandwich. Roll on!
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the front range of the Rockies looms out of the mist
shrouding Denver, and I know I'm close. At Denver, I turn north on
38, heading for Estes Park; it is steep going now, but the Ram is
pulling _ gaining _ in overdrive. This truck is a pullin' fool.
</P>
<P>
   It is 11:45 a.m. Sunday, 2,331.4 miles distant and 7,500 feet
high as I park near the Stanley Hotel with the other carriers of
steam cars. For the next week, I will be ``treated'' to sun, snow,
rain, wind, and hail in an open steamer _ I elect to do the Trail
Ridge crossing over the Continental Divide (at 12,000-plus feet) in
an enclosed sedan.
</P>
<P>
   I plot the trip back on a more northerly route via I-80, and it
will prove uneventful _ I will be behind the raging thunderstorms
in Nebraska, ahead of the flooding in Iowa, and will beat the
Indiana train wreck by a whisker, battered only by the
kidney-killer washboard of concrete I-80 from Nebraska to Indiana.
But at a Denny's on I-90, I will again become invisible to servers,
this time in my quest for a cup of tea. Not at a table nor at the
counter will I prevail for service. I leave sans tea.
</P>
<P>
   In Portsmouth, N.H., at the traffic circle, I will stop once
more for breakfast, my last attempt on the trip, and be overwhelmed
by the rapidity _ and the friendliness _ of the service. Tell me
again about cold New Englanders!
</P>
<P>
   The round trip encompasses 4,562.7 miles, consumes 379.797
gallons of 40 octane diesel fuel. The Ram, over 4,328.7 miles
measured, averages 11.974 miles per gallon pulling some 5,000-plus
pounds. In the course of it, I have increased my respect for
over-the-road truckers and Dodge trucks cum Cummins diesels. I have
seen a lot of America _ and I'm damn glad to be home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9661 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV05-BO     07-03 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME AGAIN _ AND GLAD OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, July 05 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
