shrouding Denver, and I know I'm close. At Denver, I turn north on
38, heading for Estes Park; it is steep going now, but the Ram is
pulling _ gaining _ in overdrive. This truck is a pullin' fool.
</P>
<P>
   It is 11:45 a.m. Sunday, 2,331.4 miles distant and 7,500 feet
high as I park near the Stanley Hotel with the other carriers of
steam cars. For the next week, I will be ``treated'' to sun, snow,
rain, wind, and hail in an open steamer _ I elect to do the Trail
Ridge crossing over the Continental Divide (at 12,000-plus feet) in
an enclosed sedan.
</P>
<P>
   I plot the trip back on a more northerly route via I-80, and it
will prove uneventful _ I will be behind the raging thunderstorms
in Nebraska, ahead of the flooding in Iowa, and will beat the
Indiana train wreck by a whisker, battered only by the
kidney-killer washboard of concrete I-80 from Nebraska to Indiana.
But at a Denny's on I-90, I will again become invisible to servers,
this time in my quest for a cup of tea. Not at a table nor at the
counter will I prevail for service. I leave sans tea.
</P>
<P>
   In Portsmouth, N.H., at the traffic circle, I will stop once
more for breakfast, my last attempt on the trip, and be overwhelmed
by the rapidity _ and the friendliness _ of the service. Tell me
again about cold New Englanders!
</P>
<P>
   The round trip encompasses 4,562.7 miles, consumes 379.797
gallons of 40 octane diesel fuel. The Ram, over 4,328.7 miles
measured, averages 11.974 miles per gallon pulling some 5,000-plus
pounds. In the course of it, I have increased my respect for
over-the-road truckers and Dodge trucks cum Cummins diesels. I have
seen a lot of America _ and I'm damn glad to be home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
