<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV05-     07-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORING THE SHADE WITH UNFAMILIAR FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
 (JT)  
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many shade gardens demonstrate the popular misconception that if
you don't have hostas or impatiens, you can't have color after
trees leaf out. And yet, if you look closely when you walk through
native woodlands, you are bound to see colorful splashes of
flowers, foliage and berries scattered throughout the forest
greenery from summer well into fall.
</P>
<P>
   These native plants flourish without any fertilizers, pesticides
or pruning. I like that. So much so that I now decorate my shaded
beds and borders in central New Jersey with an abundance of natural
shade color. From Memorial Day to Thanksgiving, there is a
changing, attractive garden display that requires very little
maintenance, primarily watering during dry spells.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, however, many of these plants are unfamiliar to
gardeners. This is a shame, for they are widely adaptable and
provide color and interest over a long period of time. If you would
like more variety with less work in your shade garden, consider the
addition of one or more of the following.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUMPET HONEYSUCKLE &LR;  (Lonicera sempervirens) is a constant
throughout the growing season. After a lush spring bloom, its red
flowers open sporadically until struck by frost. Reaching 12 to 15
feet in shade, this vine is happy to clamber up a trellis fence or
scramble over a stone wall.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I mention the word ``honeysuckle'' to visitors,
however, they gasp. Who would ever want such an invasive plant?
Well, I wouldn't and this isn't. Unlike the white-flowered Japanese
species, American honeysuckle is a very well-behaved presence in
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an old-fashioned one: George Washington grew it at
Mount Vernon. In full sun, it attracts scores of aphids, but they
do not like the coolness of shade. You should find that the less
direct the sun, the fewer the aphids on this handsome vine.
</P>
<P>
   The most regal plant in my garden is Snow Queen. It is a
six-foot-tall  &UR; OAKLEAF HYDRANGEA &LR;  (H. quercifolia) cultivar,
descended from a seedling spotted about 25 years ago by the
plantsman William Flemer 3d in Kingston, N.J. I use Snow Queen as a
focal point in a back corner area. In late June, gleaming white
flower cones shine among its large, oaklike leaves. By August, the
cones have aged to a light pink. In September, they turn a light
chestnut brown just as the foliage metamorphoses into a dark wine
red.
</P>
<P>
   Because my plant anchors a right angle created by fences, it is
protected from wind, and both the colorful leaves and the dried
flower heads hold on through much of winter.
</P>
<P>
   Montrose Ruby, a &UR; PURPLE HEUCHERA &LR;  hybrid with maroonish-purple
leaves mottled with silver, is another serendipitous plant. It was
discovered about 10 years ago by Nancy Goodwin on the grounds of
her former nursery in North Carolina. She believes it is a
spontaneous cross between flats of Heuchera americana Dale's Strain
and Heuchera Palace Purple.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, many other purple heuchera hybrids have been
created, often with Montrose Ruby as a parent. All bear tiny summer
flowers on one- to two-foot-tall wiry stalks. While some are quite
beautiful for two or three years, they are short-lived in my
gardens. None in my experience have matched the longevity and ease
of care of Montrose Ruby.
</P>
<P>
   This plant is handsome from spring through fall and blends with
many different whites. In one of my beds, Montrose Ruby is at the
foot of the ivory-splashed leaves of  &UR; VIRGINIA TOVARA &LR;  (T.
virginiana Variegata). Thriving in sun or shade, the foliage on
this perennial emerges in late spring and forms two- to
three-foot-tall mounds that soften dark areas. In September, wiry
wands, flecked with tiny scarlet petals, appear.
</P>
<P>
   In another bed, the rich foliage of Montrose Ruby provides a
stunning complement to two perennials that bear bright white
flowers during the heat and humidity of August. These are  &UR; BIG
LOBELIA &LR;  (L. siphilitica Alba), which send up sturdy two- to
three-foot spikes that appear as restrained forms of foxgloves, and
 &UR; NODDING ONION &LR;  (Allium cernuum minor alba), a more diminutive
plant, reaching slightly more than a foot. When in bud, a clump of
nodding onion resembles a cluster of swans, with their long slim
necks and arching heads. The buds then open to umbrella sprays of
dainty flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WREATH GOLDENROD &LR;  (Solidago caesia) provides a final, colorful
touch to my shade garden's year. From mid-September well into
October, it produces upright two- to three-foot-tall golden wands
that form dancing slashes as they weave back and forth in autumn
breezes. Also known as blue-stemmed goldenrod, this little-known,
noninvasive perennial has purplish-blue stems that add subtle color
accent in summer.
</P>
<P>
   With all this natural color _ and the plants described here are
but a small sample _ you too may find that there is little room for
either hostas or impatiens in your shade borders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
