<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-DRESS-DEMISE-$A     07-03 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-DRESS-DEMISE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BLACK, AND NO PLACE TO HIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
 (JT)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a female disaster of the first order, up there
with meeting someone really cute and realizing you have lipstick on
your front teeth. Invited to the Museum of Modern Art's ``Party in
the Garden,'' one of the last blowouts on the spring black-tie
calendar, I decided to try my gown on ahead of time to check the
fit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very clingy number from three seasons past. But the
dress, once fashionably sexy, seemed badly out of date. Unlike this
year's sheaths that discretely skim the body, my hip-hugging,
low-cut design left nothing to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In a panic, and with only nine hours to go before the party, I
raced to Bergdorf Goodman, arriving just as the store opened at 10
a.m. I bolted to the escalator and landed at the Chanel boutique, a
safe haven for the fashionable in desperate straits.
</P>
<P>
   And as if the deity of good taste was smiling on me, the perfect
little black dress appeared before my eyes. It was a variation on
Audrey Hepburn's gown in ``Breakfast at Tiffany's,'' made of wool
crepe with slender straps and a trumpet-flared skirt. It not only
fit to a T, but was also on sale.
</P>
<P>
   I sashayed into the museum that night with utter confidence, a
green cashmere sweater over my shoulders for an added touch of
oh-so-trendy nonchalance. But as the air kisses started to fly, my
self-assurance suddenly cracked. All around were radiant young
women in sugary-colored, diaphanous confections, the antitheses of
my little black look. You could practically hear the ``oohs'' and
``ahs'' around the 20-something sisters Jane Lauder and Aerin
Lauder Zinterhofer, both in Oscar de la Renta chiffon creations.
Aerin was a portrait in lemon yellow; Jane, in yellow and hot pink.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like a black hole in a galaxy of bright young sparklers.
The little black dress, I realized, might be suffering the same
fate of many great stars, collapsing under the weight of its own
history. Nearly 75 years after it was first introduced by Coco
Chanel _ a style that Vogue predicted would become the Ford of
fashion _ the little black dress is nothing more than a basic Ford
Taurus. Even though my dress was Chanel, without a color or even a
camellia to set it apart, it might as well have been from the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black dress is gone,'' Samantha Boardman, a medical
student who wore a knockout lavender Versace dress that night, told
me a few days later. ``You do get buried in black. You can
disappear in it. You are anonymous in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Walch, director of the Color Association of the United
States, which tracks color trends, put it succinctly: ``Black is
like Perrier, which did itself in.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the color issue has flip-flopped since the last time I
dressed up. Hothouse tones used to be a sure sign that either a
tourist or an aging socialite was on the loose. But these days,
festive evening finery is neither provincial nor passe. Like their
mothers before them, a younger generation of trend-setting social
women are now decked out in rainbow hues, infusing color with new
cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For evening clothes, there has been a change,'' said Brooke de
Ocampo, 31, an associate at Sotheby's and a chairwoman of the New
York Botanical Garden's junior fund-raising committee. ``For day,
there's still a black T-shirt and khaki clam diggers. But when I
think of the last five black-tie events I've been to, I can't think
of any black dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, I don't get out enough.
</P>
<P>
   But I do read fashion magazines, and it is true that there
hasn't been a black evening gown on the cover of Vogue, W or
Harper's Bazaar in at least six months. At Bergdorf, I later
discovered, there was a full selection of black Versace and Armani
gowns on sale, but the colorful Oscar de la Renta racks had been
picked clean.
</P>
<P>
   Like the appearance of Christian Lacroix's pouf dress of 1987,
the last high point of conspicuous consumption before the current
pecuniary frenzy, this season's fashion extravaganzas seem an
expression of the bubbly economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rebirth of parties and festivities, our generation is
enjoying the glamour of dressing up,'' Ms. de Ocampo said. ``Black
does wonders for everybody, but it doesn't require much thought.
You tend to put on a color, it shows more imagination and
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodness. Now my black dress was not only out of style, but also
a sign that I lacked guts. And all along I had thought that black
was a statement of female strength. It is no coincidence that the
black dress first emerged in the 1920s after the suffragist
movement won women the vote. Again in the '80s, as women ascended
the corporate ladder, black dresses were on the rise, their
popularity soaring in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 10 to 12 years, you've had the `Armani'
phenomenon, not that he isn't a wonderful designer,'' de la Renta,
the longtime standard-bearer of color, told me. ``When a
professional woman wanted to dress, she wanted to be taken
seriously, which meant not being noticed. Black is the least
memorable color. Women have outgrown all that. There is a whole new
generation of girls dressing in a pretty manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Aerin Lauder Zinterhofer, director of creative product
development for Estee Lauder, called the recent explosion of color
a reaction against years of androgyny. ``People are maxed out on
minimalism,'' she said. ``They are looking for something feminine.
Floral fragrances and fabrics are popular. Pink chiffon, pink
lipstick, high heels and long hair are back.''
</P>
<P>
   As color returns, the daughters of the ladies who lunch have
rediscovered their mothers' favorite designers _ namely, de la
Renta, Bill Blass and Carolina Herrara, longtime devotees of a
luscious palette and feminine styles. ``For nighttime, Oscar and
Bill have very sleek and sexy things for me, as well as things that
would appeal to my mom,'' Ms. de Ocampo said. ``They'll do
something in a silk jersey, which is a sort of semi-retro Halston
look that has a certain moderness appealing to our age.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, de la Renta, Blass and Ms. Herrara are taking a cue
from their younger customers, particularly those who are family
members. ``My sister, Carolina Jr., is my mother's muse,'' said
Patricia Herrara, 24, a daughter of Carolina Herrara. ``Her designs
haven't exactly changed, but the fabrics are more fluid and there's
no more hard construction, which gives them a younger look.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Renta acknowledged the influence of his 29-year-old
stepdaughter, Eliza Reed. ``Eliza is very feminine, and she
influences my eye,'' he said. ``She has so many young friends, and
they all wear my clothes. I have these young customers, and I am
thinking of them. They're a whole new consumer and a very important
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone is convinced of the rightness of pink, nint
green and baby blue after dark. ``All these women who are wearing
these sherbety colors, they're going to splash something like
summer strawberries on their light-colored dresses or look in the
mirror and say, `Oh my God, I look so fat,''' Amy Edelman, author
of ``The Little Black Dress,'' said. ``Color is a blip in fashion
history. There's been `death to black' before, but the black dress
will never go away.''
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, am glad to hear it. Because even though my Chanel
dress was 40 percent off, it cost plenty. I can justify the price
as an investment in a classic. But the best way to get my money's
worth, I figure, is to wear it to death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
