<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-03 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAVAJO CONTRIBUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. -- Formed by time and the wind, the majestic
50-foot stone circle for which this town is named overshadows
workers finishing a World War II monument. The memorial is also
circular, an eternal flame surrounded by a low sandstone wall and
flags of the US, the military services, and the Navajo Nation. The
names, now listed on cardboard, await enscription in stone.
</P>
<P>
   They were heroes long ago and the memorial has been slow
abuilding, but Navajos share two notable traits of that remarkable
World War II generation: a reluctance to boast and a refusal to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   No single group was more essential to victory than the ``code
talkers,'' Army and Marine Navajos who communicated in their own
language, baffling Japanese eavesdroppers in the Pacific. On
Guadalcanal, Guam, Saipan, Tarawa, Iwo Jima, and Okinawa,
code-breakers could not decipher this guttural language with a
complicated syntax and no known alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the enemy had known the language was Navajo, an inner
code disguised military movements. A tank was a turtle, a submarine
an iron fish, a hummingbird a fighter plane, a buzzard a bomber,
and bombs were eggs. Code-breakers could have thought the
conversation was about breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The heroic ranks are dwindling. Narciso Platero Abeyta died in
Albuquerque June 22. After the war, he took up art and his
watercolors are displayed in museums in the Southwest and at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington. Another code talker, Carl
Nelson Gorman, who also became a renowned artist and taught art at
colleges, died in February. His son, R.C. Gorman, is a an artist in
Taos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Navajo art, famed in rugs and pottery, is based on a
centuries-old love of nature so mystically powerful that it has
helped Navajos resist assimilation. Carl Gorman was born on the
reservation and was punished at a mission school when he spoke his
native language instead of English. His studio was in nearby Fort
Defiance, the headquarters of Kit Carson's expedition against the
Navajos in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   The famed Army scout starved out 8,000 Navajos in Canyon de
Muerto, then herded them 300 miles to a reservation at Fort Sumner
in New Mexico. The ``long walk'' has remained vivid in the Navajo
tribal memory. Yet in World War II, when the Marine Corps set up a
recruiting station in Window Rock, capital of the Navajo Nation,
the response was enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Pendleton in California, all-Navajo platoons trained,
then shipped out with their rifles and radios to the Pacific island
assaults. ``I thought I was going to die,'' Gorman said. He later
learned that ``Marines never die. They just go to hell and
regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Government policy kept the saga of the code-talkers secret until
1969, when they were finally recognized. In 1990, Kenji Kawano, the
son of a Japanese soldier, published ``Warriors,'' a photo essay on
the code talkers. David E. Patterson, a Marine code talker, told
Kawano, ``When I was inducted into the service, one of the
commitments I made was that I was willing to die for my country _
the US, the Navajo Nation, and my family. My language was my
weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Navajos still resist assimilation but prosperity complicates the
effort. Petty scandals plague the tribal council, which now has a
symbol of the curse of modernity, a special prosecutor. At tribal
headquarters here, parking spaces are reserved for various
officials, an unhealthy sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Rez,'' as the reservation is called, covers 15 million
acres, the size of West Virginia. Policing it is hard work and Tony
Hillerman, the novelist whose mysteries make heroes of Navajo
Tribal Police, dedicates his latest book, ``The First Eagle,'' to
six tribal policemen killed in the line of duty. Hillerman helps
explain the respect for mystery in Navajo life. Bravery is part of
that mystery. The code talkers were true first eagles. Their
bravery helped preserve America's freedom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9688 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KARAOKE-NIGHTLIFE-ART     07-03 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARAOKE-NIGHTLIFE-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARAOKE: ONCE MORE, WITH IRONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (JT)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On karaoke night recently at the Lansky Lounge on the
Lower East Side, a strange thing happened. A young woman in a
halter top who calls herself Princess was on stage finishing a
heartfelt performance of David Lee Roth's take on ``Just a
Gigolo,'' when out of the crowd, as if from a dream, emerged Roth,
the icon of pop metal rock himself.
</P>
<P>
   The former Van Halen crooner ascended the makeshift stage and
belted out the lyrics to his band's cover version of the classic
Beach Boys tune ``California Girls.'' Wearing tight leather
motorcycle chaps, blond mane streaming, he even unleashed a few of
his signature high kicks as the lyrics scrolled on a giant video
monitor behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd loved it. Russell Steinberg, the awestruck emcee,
broke in over the cheers. ``This is better than Pop-Up Video!'' he
said, referring to the VH-1 program that pokes fun at outdated
rockers like Roth.
</P>
<P>
   This truly odd moment _ a rock star performing a karaoke version
of his own recording _ was part of a reawakened interest among New
York hipsters in the sing-along pastime imported from Japan. Adam
Yauch of the Beastie Boys had a karaoke machine at his Manhattan
wedding in May, and the actors Mark Wahlberg, China Chow, Joaquin
Phoenix and Ben Affleck have all been washing up at the Wednesday
night karaoke party at Lansky Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed the loose-tie recreation of the 1980s had
been safely put to rest in church basements and suburban strip-mall
bars, karaoke is being revived by young downtown scene-makers,
along with so many other retro relics of the Reagan era. They are
frequenting new karaoke clubs, as well as infiltrating traditional
ones with a largely Asian clientele, partly as a rebellion against
the guest lists and staid lounges associated with 1990s night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the downtown culture is about pretension and
artifice,'' said Moby, a techno musician who likes to perform
karaoke versions of children's standards like ``Farmer in the
Dell.'' ``It's so nice to get together and be really stupid. Plus,
karaoke is cheaper than performing live because I don't have to pay
a drummer or a bassist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Bernstein brought karaoke to the Lansky Lounge, a small
club behind Ratner's restaurant on Delancey Street, two months ago.
``I got so sick of going out all the time and hearing people
network about their upcoming film or album,'' said Ms. Bernstein,
who originated her karaoke nights at SoHo's upscale Spy bar. She
moved to the more laid-back Lansky Lounge after Spy's owners
complained that her raucous crowd was scaring away the European
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   That raucousness, some say, is also causing problems with some
Asian karaoke patrons. The keg-party antics of some Western patrons
at traditional Asian karaoke bars has led to friction between the
two groups. Patterson Beckwith, a conceptual artist who belongs to
the collective Art Club 2000, recalled an evening when he and 30
friends were ejected from a Chinatown karaoke club after
improvising a hip-hop beat to Bon Jovi's ``Wanted Dead or Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hostess told us beat-boxing was not allowed and took the
mike away, even though I thought it sounded pretty good,'' Beckwith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmar Fillipson, 24, a deejay from Iceland, recalled a hostile
incident at Winnie's, a traditional karaoke club on Bayard Street
in Chinatown, where his mother was nearly pushed offstage by an
Asian woman for singing Neil Diamond's ``Sweet Caroline'' in the
wrong key. Fillipson said the Asian customers seemed antagonized
when he and his entourage started disco dancing to a karaoke opera
being sung by Asian customers.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Liu, the karaoke jockey, or kayjay, at Winnie's, could not
recall the incident and said it didn't sound like something that
would happen at the club. She added, however, that Western
customers' behavior sometimes alienates Asian clients. ``Americans
get really drunk and like to swing the microphone and
break-dance,'' Ms. Liu said. ``Last year, there used to be more
Asians than Americans, and now it's the other way around. Most of
the regulars only come down during the week, because it's too rowdy
and crowded when there's a big group of Westerners on the weekends.
Asians like to sing very quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   Village Karaoke, a club that opened last month at 27 Cooper
Square, on the corner of Fifth Street, hopes to attract both
groups. ``We're hoping to get customers from New York University,
the bars around St. Marks Place and the Japanese section of Ninth
Street,'' said James Sato, a co-owner, who runs several karaoke
bars in Koreatown in midtown Manhattan and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   His sprawling East Village establishment has 16 private rooms,
each painted a different color and decorated with the kind of
generic living room furniture often featured in a typical karaoke
video. Lyrics can be ordered in Japanese, Korean, Chinese and
English. At the end of each performance the screen flashes a score,
rating the performance from 1 to 100.
</P>
<P>
   Separate rooms may be one way to limit karaoke conflicts. Many
arise because Asians take karaoke more seriously than Americans,
said Casey Man Kong Lum, the author of ``In Search of a Voice:
Karaoke and the Construction of Identity in Chinese America''
(Lawrence Erlbaum Associates, 1996). ``If someone doesn't try to
sing their best, Asians view that as letting down the entire
group,'' Lum said. ``So, if Westerners purposely mess up a song,
Asians might view that as selfish and disrespectful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lum also stressed that it would be against karaoke etiquette to
become aggressive. ``It's more likely that it was just a case of
simple drunken stupidity and invading someone else's turf,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bernstein said that frayed nerves were the exception, rather
than the rule, at her parties. And when tensions do flare, she
said, the cause is most likely simply mangled vocals. ``Karaoke is
a release, and people tend to get very emotional without even
realizing it,'' she said. ``Of course, drinking doesn't help
matters, but the reality that your song may not be well received is
a risk you have to be willing to take.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
