<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9701 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALLS-DISCOUNTS-$ADV0     07-03 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALLS-DISCOUNTS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYE BYE BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
 (JT)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shoes are the mirror of the soul, according to many a
fashionista, but when a pair of Gucci horse-bit loafers sell for
$315, the price of self-revelation is, for many, tragically out of
reach.
</P>
<P>
   That is why there is outlet shopping _ for fashion lovers with
more time than money, who don't mind journeying an hour or so out
of town to seek deep discounts in out-of-the-way designers'
clearinghouses.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that is the promise that has fueled the outlet craze,
driving the industry to a record $13 billion in sales last year and
luring designers with the toniest of images, like Gucci, Giorgio
Armani and Prada, to join outlet pioneers like London Fog and Ann
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But in practice the imagined savings are increasingly an
illusion, especially around New York City, where outlet malls like
Woodbury Common Premium Outlets in Central Valley, N.Y., and Tanger
Outlet Center in Riverhead, N.Y., are expecting throngs this
holiday weekend who would rather bargain-hunt than barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey of New York-area outlets over the last
several months, combined with interviews with shoppers and retail
analysts, shows that outlet prices are often no better than sale
prices at Manhattan department stores and boutiques, and in some
cases, no better than full retail.
</P>
<P>
   That trademark Gucci women's loafer, for example, was priced at
$179 last week at the Gucci outlet at Woodbury Common, 55 miles
north of New York City. Meanwhile, at the Gucci store on Fifth
Avenue, the same shoe was on sale for $159. Moreover, the outlet
stocked the popular loafer only in navy and size 4{ _ suitable for
the smallest of women. The Manhattan store had a variety of colors
and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Brooks Brothers was selling a cotton dress shirt for
the same price, $39.90, at both Madison Avenue and Woodbury Common.
And at the Polo Ralph Lauren store at Clinton Crossing Premium
Outlets in Clinton, Conn., just off I-95, a twin sheet in the
Charlotte pattern cost $9.99 last week; at Bloomingdale's in New
York, it was $5.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've noticed that the outlets are getting worse and worse,''
said Margaret Ryan, who was shopping at Clinton Crossing. In the
Liz Claiborne outlet, Ms. Ryan, a legal secretary, spotted the same
sandals selling for $34.95 that she had bought at Liz Claiborne on
Fifth Avenue for $34.95. Her only purchase: chocolate for the car
ride home. ``By the time you pay for tolls and gas, it's really not
worth it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Mona Elba, also a legal secretary, displayed two
white Gap T-shirts she had just purchased for $4.99, which a hang
tag said would fetch $6.99 at retail. But she pointed out that the
V-neck T-shirts were of a style not sold at regular Gap stores _ an
increasingly common outlet strategy, in which the outlets have
clothes custom-made, in less-expensive fabrics and styles, that
never appear at retail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no bargains in the outlets anymore,'' Ms. Elba said.
``You're really better off waiting for sales at Macy's or Lord &AMP;
Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Many retail analysts would agree. ``Prices are escalating in the
outlets,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend
Report, a company in Upper Montclair, N.J., that tracks consumer
spending habits. ``It used to be that outlet prices were expected
to be, and in fact were, between 25 and 40 percent below what you
expected to pay in conventional department and speciality stores.
But over the years that spread between what you paid in the regular
stores and what you paid in the outlet stores has shrunk so much
that in some cases it's not even 10 percent below what you find in
ordinary stores.''
</P>
<P>
   This holiday weekend, outlet stores are promising discounts
deeper than usual, as they do on all major holidays, to attract
vacationing shoppers. (Most outlets are near resort areas, to take
advantage of consumers' relaxed mood and full wallets.) But what
consumers might forget is that regular retail stores are also
holding big holiday sales. In many cases, the bargains are every
bit as good, especially considering that outlet-store merchandise
is often not the same quality.
</P>
<P>
   How has this come about? What has happed to erode the savings?
</P>
<P>
   In a word, success.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, when outlet mania first took hold, stores tended
to deliver on their promises of deep discounts. But with millions
of shoppers responding to the lure of bargains, the clearinghouses
have boomed _ there are some 350 designer outlet malls in the
United States, up from 300 in 1995. Woodbury Common, which began
with 100,000 square feet in 1985, added 70 new stores in just the
last year.
</P>
<P>
   And explosive growth has meant that there is no longer enough
true outlet merchandise to go around _ unsold garments left over at
season's end in traditional stores, or designers' samples and
manufacturers' oversupply and canceled orders.
</P>
<P>
   True outlet merchandise fetches a higher price than it once did,
simply because of supply and demand. ``It's gotten more and more
competitive; everyone is trying to buy a bigger and bigger piece of
the pie,'' said Marcia Wilson, president of Daffy's, a 10-store
off-price chain in the New York area, which was one of the pioneers
in the business of buying manufacturers' overstock, along with
Loehmann's and Filene's, long before the outlet centers.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the demand for clothes for clearinghouses, designers and
other outlet chains have taken to making merchandise of lower
quality directly for outlets. The 39-store chain Off Fifth, a
spinoff of Saks Fifth Avenue, relies on the cachet of the Saks name
to lure customers, who may not realize that most of the goods in
the outlets have never graced a department store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that 70 percent of the merchandise for Off
Fifth has never been in our retail store and is purchased directly
from the vendors,'' a Saks spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Saks is one of the only companies to publicly acknowledge this
widespread practice. Its spokeswoman said that outlet shoppers can
recognize merchandise from its retail stores if the price tags are
printed on both sides; tags printed on only one side indicate an
item has been bought directly from a manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Direct-to-outlet goods, often carrying famous designers' labels,
are usually made of lower-quality materials or out-of-date fabrics.
Other corners are cut by using cheaper buttons and flimsier heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donna Karan has been doing that for years,'' Barnard, the
retail analyst, said. Ms. Karan's company declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Polo Ralph Lauren store on 72d Street and Madison Avenue,
a navy-and- white loafer called the Cambridge boasts a thick brown
sole. It normally costs $350, and is on sale for $299.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Polo Ralph Lauren outlet at Woodbury Common, a
loafer of almost identical styling is $149. But the upper is
thinner, as is the sole, and the heel seems less solid. A salesman
said the shoe was made expressly for the outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Most designers and retailers contacted declined to speak about
their outlet business, and analysts said this was largely from fear
of tarnishing their high-fashion images, like a blue blood's
disdain for a poor cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Polo Ralph Lauren did not return calls seeking comment. Gucci
and Burberry's declined to comment. At Donna Karan, a public
relations assistant said, ``We don't want to participate in an
outlet story.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of a major retail company with a chain of outlet
stores, who said that if her name was used she would loose her job,
acknowledged, ``The prices in the outlets are no better than the
sales, and in lots of cases, the retail prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even my friends all talk about it,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
