   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-FREEDOM-COX (Undated) _ The Million Man March organized
by the Nation of Islam's Louis Farrakhan and the Promise Keepers'
Stand in the Gap rally of Christian men put religion symbolically
in the center of the nation's capital. But actions in the
legislative halls and courtrooms have been changing and refining
the definition of what freedom of religion, as expressed in the
First Amendment to the Constitution, really means. Here's a
snapshot of recent and pending legislation and court cases
affecting religious liberty. By Gayle White. Moved 7-2 for 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-MARRIAGE-NYT (White Plains, N.Y.) _ A Roman Catholic
school in Cortlandt Manor, N.Y. agreed Thursday to rehire a teacher
who was dismissed from her job because she had married a divorced
Episcopalian who had never had his previous marriage annulled. By
Joseph Berger. Moved 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-DRUGS-NYT (Philadelphia) _ Abner King Stoltzfus, 23, and
Abner Stoltzfus, 24, are anomalies in the federal criminal justice
system. They are the first two members of Pennsylvania's Amish
community to be arrested for involvement with cocaine and
methamphetamine. By Michael Janofsky. Moved 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-LETTER-NYT (Rome) _ In one of his sharpest rebukes to
liberal Catholics to date, Pope John Paul II on Tuesday made
changes to canon law aimed at stamping out debate on a wide range
of passionately discussed issues, including euthanasia and the
ordination of women. By Alessandra Stanley. Moved 6-30.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-REACT-BOS (Undated) _ Pope John Paul II's effort to end
debate on such controversial issues as the ordination of women
through changes he made this week in canon law, will not succeed in
forcing obedience from the many Roman Catholics alienated from the
church, several theologians and scholars interviewed said. By Diego
Ribadeneira. Moved 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ARCHAEOLOGY-HNS (Jerusalem) _ Breaking ancient clay pots
and carrying protest signs, dozens of angry archaeologists
demonstrated Wednesday over reports that Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has promised an ultra-Orthodox party effective control
over the country's excavations. Archaeology has been at the center
of debate in Israel for years with the ultra-Orthodox vehemently _
and sometimes violently _ opposed to excavations in which they
believe Jewish graves have been found. By Deborah Horan. Moved 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   GREEK-ORTHODOX-BOS (Undated) _ Two years ago the nation's 2
million Greek Orthodox cheered the news that Metropolitan Spyridon
had been chosen to be their new archbishop. Today, however, there
is revolution within the Greek church, with people who once
supported Spyridon now formally demanding his resignation. What
started last year as criticism by some church activists of what
they considered Spyridon's autocratic style, has ballooned into a
full-fledged attempt by many deep-pocketed Greek Orthodox to force
the archbishop to step down. By Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-RELIGION-NYT (Undated) _ For most of the century people
have espoused the view that science and religion should be kept
apart to avoid the inevitable combustions. But to rational minds it
has always been troubling that there could be two opposing ways to
explain what is the same universe. Science and religion both spring
from the human obsession to find order in the world. But surely
there can be only one true explanation for reality: Life was either
created or it evolved. Prayer is either communication with God or a
psychological salve. The universe is either pervaded by spiritual
forces or ruled by nothing but physical laws. Now various groups
are seeking a resolution, including those involved in a recent
conference that provided a heavy religious bent. By George Johnson.
Moved 6-29.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIBET-NYT (Beijing) _ The director of the Religious
Affairs Administration calls the Dalai Lama a traitor who planned
to split the motherland and restore feudal serfdom in Tibet. By
Erik Eckholm. Moved 6-26.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-STATE-REVIEW-NYT _ If the separation of church and state
mandated by the First Amendment means anything, surely it bars
state-paid teachers from evangelizing to public schoolchildren in
state-provided classrooms during school hours. By Ethan Bronner.
Moved 6-27.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-TEENS-COX (Banner Elk, N.C.) _ Teens from a rainbow of
backgrounds learn to share pride and pain while gaining a world of
insight. By Gayle White. Moved 7-2 for 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JAKES-COX (Undated) _ Profile of T.D. Jakes, a preacher
who reaches across cultural lines. By John Blake. MOved 7-2 for
7-4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Rome) _ A conference was held to
begin an ongoing dialogue between journalists and religious leaders
to improve the quality of religion coverage. It not only included
religion writers but also influential editors and publishers. By
Jim Jones. Moved 6-26.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (New York) _ Doesn't Sir Sigmund Sternberg,
the British businessman, Jewish philanthropist and inveterate
promoter of interfaith understanding, ever get tired of receiving
awards? He is being honored at the U.N. for receiving the $1.23
million Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion. By Peter
Steinfels. Moved 6-26.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Too many parents are missing
what local author Mimi Doe believes is a key to childhood _
spirituality. All children have it, says Doe, co-author of a
just-released book, ``10 Principles for Spiritual Parenting.'' The
problem is not enough parents take steps to cultivate their child's
spirituality. By Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 7-1.
</P>
