<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-MEDICAL-SAVINGS-     07-03 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-MEDICAL-SAVINGS-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL ACCOUNTS: MIXED REVIEWS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Ind., Md., Ill., Texas)   (af)  
 By MARGARET O. KIRK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When medical savings accounts became available last year, Eric
R. Bryen, Matthew C. Dailey and Julie A. Griswold all signed up,
eager for the chance to save tax-free dollars for medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year later, the reviews are mixed. For Bryen and
Dailey, both self-employed, the accounts have worked well. Ms.
Griswold's experience has been decidedly less pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Bryen, 39, a lawyer in Farmington Hills, Mich., has watched his
medical savings account grow tax-free because he has opted not to
tap into it for medical expenses. ``I love it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey, 36, an insurance broker in Indianapolis, has not been
able to build up any money because his family's medical expenses _
for the birth of a baby, as well as for some unexpected surgery for
his wife, Kathryn, 39 _ exceeded the amount he can deposit each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what the account did was save me federal and state income
tax on that money,'' Dailey said. ``It's definitely the program to
have if you are self-employed.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Ms. Griswold, 40, the plan has been a financial
disaster. One of four employees who signed up for the plan last
year at the Fields Group, an Indianapolis company that plans
corporate sales trips, Ms. Griswold had both pneumonia and
unexpected surgery in her first year, with expensive follow-up
treatments early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because her medical expenses began piling up before her account
accumulated much money, and because her yearly deductible for
coverage is $2,250, Ms. Griswold has already had out-of-pocket
expenses of roughly $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are healthy or if you make a lot of money, it's a great
plan,'' said Ms. Griswold, who earns about $26,000 a year and has
had to postpone further tests because of her medical bills. ``But
if things start to go wrong and you don't have a high income, it's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of these three people are important because
Washington is considering changes to the four-year pilot project,
created by the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which took effect at the beginning of 1997, was
intended for the self-employed and for companies with 50 or fewer
employees; it allows tax-deductible contributions to accounts that
can be tapped only for medical expenses. The accounts are set up at
banks or insurance companies and packaged with high-deductible
insurance to cover serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   Initial interest was high _ the Employers Council on Flexible
Compensation once received as many as 1,700 phone calls in a week
requesting information. Consumers, however, have not rushed to
convert to the program.
</P>
<P>
   The law allowed as many as 375,000 people to participate by
April 1, 1997. But the Treasury Department estimates that only
100,000 accounts have been established.
</P>
<P>
   The profile of the participants has surprised industry experts,
too. Far fewer than expected small businesses are participating,
but more self-employed and empty-nesters starting home businesses
are, said Greg Scandlen, managing partner of Health Benefits Group,
a consulting firm in Frederick, Md.
</P>
<P>
   At the Golden Rule Insurance Co. in Lawrenceville, Ill., nearly
72 percent of the 29,000 medical savings accounts are for families
with self-employed adult, said Tenna Merchent, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Early supporters of the concept, who saw it as a way for
consumers to help control health costs and have more choices, now
conclude that there are serious problems _ including the complexity
of the program's administration, the 50-employee cap at eligible
businesses and the high deductibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program is not doing well,'' said Jack Strayer, vice
president for external affairs at the Washington office of the
National Center for Policy Analysis, a Dallas research organization
that helped originate the concept. ``I predicted that a million
policies would be sold by now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed,'' said David Wilson, president of the
Flexben Corp., of Troy, Mich., which manages benefits plans for
employers. Wilson is a director of the Employers Council on
Flexible Compensation, which lobbied for the initial legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the legislation was drafted for small employers only,
and the restrictive nature of the legislation itself, meant that it
was presented to the health care marketplace in an upside-down
approach,'' he said. ``The big players generally lead the
marketplace. That never happened in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical savings accounts (which have been available since the
early 1990s, but without the federal tax benefits) work like this:
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The consumer buys health insurance with a high deductible _
between $1,500 and $2,500 annually for an individual, and $3,000 to
$4,500 for a family.
</P>
<P>
   The policyholder must then establish a medical savings account
at a participating bank or mutual fund company. Contributions for
individuals can be a maximum of 65 percent of their deductible, or
75 percent for families. Either an employer or an employee can
contribute, but not both. Payments can be made in monthly
installments or in a lump sum at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Using checks drawn on those accounts, policyholders pay medical
bills and submit claims to insurers. Once the deductible is met,
plans often pay up to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the year, any money remaining in the account is
carried over to the next year. All contributions are deductible on
federal tax returns, and 25 states offer deductions, too. Interest
accumulates tax-deferred up to age 65 and in most cases is entirely
tax-free if used for medical care.
</P>
<P>
   After 65, money can be withdrawn with no penalty, though tax
will be due if it is not used for medical care. If the money is
withdrawn early for nonmedical expenses, there is a 15 percent
penalty and income taxes must be paid.
</P>
<P>
   In Bryen's case, he and his wife and two children are covered by
a Blue Cross Blue Shield of Michigan plan with a $3,000 deductible;
each year, he can save 75 percent of that, or $2,250, tax-free in
his medical account.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance costs him $369 a month, a little higher than most
plans because he has several expensive options, like annual
physicals with no deductibles. And even though his family had about
$1,300 in medical expenses last year, Bryen paid for them out of
his own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just letting it build up,'' said Bryen, who earns more
than $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Griswold also thought her program would be a forced savings
plan. Her individual policy carries a yearly deductible of $2,250,
which means she could save 65 percent of that, or $1,463, tax-free.
Her employer pays for the insurance and contributes monthly to her
medical account.
</P>
<P>
   But constant medical problems made her wish she had never
switched from traditional health insurance. Her expenses for
pneumonia and surgery more than met her deductible for 1997 and
outpaced her employer contributions; she figures she paid at least
$2,000 of her own money for medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   And after January, when she again had to meet the deductible,
tests and treatments caused her to owe $2,250 more. ``I had to pay
all of that out of pocket, too, or work out payment plans,'' she
said. ``And now I'm putting off having another sonogram because I
don't have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Both examples reflect one of the main arguments against these
accounts _ that they are only for those healthy enough not to need
extensive care or wealthy enough to afford the steep deductibles.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and Strayer agree that some program failings are
reflected in Ms. Griswold's case: the deductibles can be too high,
and they are the same for each participant, regardless of income.
</P>
<P>
   To address some of these issues, several proposals are working
their way through Congress. Various changes being debated by the
House Ways and Means Committee and the Republican Health Care Task
Force would lower the deductible limit for both families and
individuals; allow both employer and employee to contribute
tax-free dollars, as with 401(k) accounts, and lift the restriction
on the size of businesses that can offer the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes, said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Ways and
Means Committee, ``would make the existing pilot a workable
pilot.'' Other changes under consideration would encourage banks
and insurers, which have been slow to market the plans, to
participate, Strayer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Balanced Budget Act of 1997 also created a medical savings
account for Medicare recipients, scheduled to begin in October,
which could give a higher profile to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a brand-new concept,'' Scandlen said. ``It is not
an easy thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
