<SLUG> BC-CANADA-HISTORY-REVIEW-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HISTORICAL AMNESIA: HAPPY 4th OF JULY, CANADA!  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (For release Sunday, July 5)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Graphics are is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It's been fairly well demonstrated that Americans
aren't too swift when it comes to their own history _ as, for
example, when surveys show that most students can't place the Civil
War in the right century. Last week came striking new evidence that
Canada has historical amnesia, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably alarming enough, but true irony lay in one of
the reasons why Canadians forget: Many are confusing their heritage
with that of their famously forgetful yet culturally dominant
neighbor to the south.
</P>
<P>
   A new national survey showed that not only were half of
Canadians in the dark about basic facts of Canadian civics and
history _ some thought the singer Gordon Lightfoot wrote the
Canadian national anthem _ but that many misapprehensions by
Canadians were a result of cross-border cultural seepage.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who said, ``The medium is the message,'' some said it
was Bill Gates of Microsoft rather than the Canadian academic
Marshall McLuhan. And when asked in a multiple-choice question to
cite a phrase from Canada's Constitution, fewer than half correctly
picked ``peace, order and good government,'' while one in four
selected ``life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness,'' from the
American Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in a week when many Canadians tend to meld Canada Day
(July 1) and the Fourth of July into one long holiday, the results
could not have been more worrisome to those in Canada who see
themselves as Dutch boys with fingers in a crumbling dike against
the flood tides of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame? Penny-pinching school boards, dull history
teachers, the collapse of Western civilization _ many of the same
culprits familiar to Americans are targeted here. But in Canada the
criticism of media comes with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Rudyard Griffiths, executive director of the Dominion Institute,
which sponsored the history survey, said the myths put out by
Hollywood and the American entertainment industry are so powerful
that Canadians unwittingly adopt them as their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the cultural leverage to tell our own stories,''
Griffiths said, ``and as a result you see a willowing of Canadian
cultural capital.''
</P>
<P>
   France, Britain and other nations have expressed similar
concerns about American cultural imperialism, but it was Canada
that organized an international conference of culture ministers
last week, and stubbornly refused to invite the United States to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers from 19 countries felt that only by acting in
concert could they fend off the forces that threaten cultural
diversity _ i.e., the folks who bring the world Mickey Mouse and
Rambo. Still, Canada received more sympathy than support from its
guests, who after all could go back to countries separated from the
United States by a wide ocean or a different language or both.
</P>
<P>
   Most Canadians, or course, have neither buffer. Not only do most
speak English, but upwards of 90 percent of them live within a
two-hour drive of the United States border. TV Guide and Time are
among the most popular magazines they read, and when a Canadian
foundation tried to boost Canadian heritage last year, it gave away
historical comic books at McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest issue, Maclean's, the national news magazine,
takes a further stab at Canadian cultural heritage. And boy, it has
to hurt, though this was no doubt unintentional. From the 55
million Canadians who have ever lived (fewer than the number of
living Californians), the magazine selected as the single most
important one of all Gen. George Philias Vanier, a one-legged,
bilingual World War I hero and representative of the queen whose
entry in the authoritative Canadian Encyclopedia is but two
paragraphs long.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Vanier, the magazine seemed to have trouble rounding out
its top 10 list of heroes. Terry Fox, a one-legged runner who
raised funds to fight cancer, and Roberta Bondar, the first
Canadian woman in space, made it, as did an American Indian (!) and
two hockey players. When real-life heroes seemed to run short, the
magazine padded the list with imaginary Canadians: Evangeline,
Wordsworth's tragic Acadian heroine, and the ever perky Anne of
Green Gables.
</P>
<P>
   One consolation, if there is any here, is that cultural swords
cut both ways, especially when cultures are cheek by jowl. Jim
Carrey, Peter Jennings and countless other Canadians have risen to
the top of American entertainment and media. With free trade and
communications systems that ignore borders, the United States and
Canada can't help but get more entangled.
</P>
<P>
   And while Toronto routinely stands in for New York in Hollywood
productions, bags of trash no longer need to be spread around
Toronto's streets to give them that authentic look _ now that the
Big Apple has become more like Toronto and cleaned up its act.
</P>
</TEXT>
