(EDITORS: Due to the July 4 holiday, all scheduled material from
The New York Times Week in Review section will move Friday. All
stories are embargoed for Sunday, July 5.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-HISTORY-REVIEW (Toronto) _ A new national survey showed
that not only were half of Canadians in the dark about basic facts
of Canadian civics and history _ some thought the singer Gordon
Lightfoot wrote the Canadian national anthem _ but that many
misapprehensions by Canadians were a result of cross-border
cultural seepage. By Anthony dePalma. (Wih graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-JOKERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Why's everybody so down on
the Internet? Sure, it's a refuge for conspiracy theorists, bigots
and perverts, but look at the bright side: It also preoccupies
jokesters and assorted knuckleheads with entirely too much time on
their hands. By Tom Kuntz.
</P>
<P>
   INFERTILITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ A 40-year-old woman struggling to
conceive a baby is told by her doctor that the quality of her eggs
is poor and the lining of her uterus doesn't replenish itself well
enough to sustain a pregnancy. Is she fairly average, or is she
disabled? By Esther B. fein.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECONOMY-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ Den Fujita, one of Japan's most
successful and iconoclastic businessmen, is reveling in Japan's
economic woes. As the owner of half of McDonald's Japan, Fujita has
so relentlessly slashed prices of burgers, shakes and fries that
it's now cheaper to buy a Big Mac in Tokyo than in New York _ even
without the yen's recent tumble. Profits are soaring, and
Fujita-san is crowing. ``These bad times are a good thing for me,''
he said. ``No problems at all for us, not one.'' Fujita is a rare
bird these days, when most economists and world leaders see nothing
redeeming in Japan's skid into a recession that took hold last
winter and now threatens to undermine the already faltering
economies of the rest of Asia. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Meet Kosovo, the World's Biggest
Little Tinderbox. By Michael T. Kaufman. (With Graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REVIEW (Undated) _ A monopolist is big and bad. He has
the muscle to dictate prices and bully competitors and consumers,
both of whom are powerless to resist the monopolist's will. Enter
the Microsoft Corp., accused by the government of being a
monopolist, and its new computer operating system, Windows 98,
which will play a starring role in the monopoly case that the
Justice Department will present to a federal judge in September. By
Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-REVIEW (Washington) _ By substantial majorities that cut
across the ideological spectrum, the justices in the term that just
ended essentially rewrote the law of sexual harassment in the
workplace, which is governed by, but nowhere described or even
mentioned in, Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. They
defined the scope of the attorney-client privilege, which Congress
addressed only implicitly in Rule 501 of the federal Rules of
Evidence. And the justices effectively immunized police officers
for the consequences of reckless high-speed chases, in lawsuits
brought for constitutional deprivations under the ancient Civil
Rights Act of 1871. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-REVIEW (Undated) _ In 1888 an American
diplomat-turned-adventurer named William Woodville Rockhill set out
to explore Tibet, a territory he described in his journal as ``a
very imperfectly known portion of the Chinese Empire.'' It still
is. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISING-REVIEW (Seaside Heights, N.J.) _ Eventually,
somebody is going to figure out a way to implant advertising
messages directly into the human cerebral cortex. Meanwhile,
Patrick Dori has come one small step closer to a universe of
ubiquitous advertising. He has invented a device to print ads
directly onto a beach. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WELFARE-REVIEW (New York) _ With a wave of a wand and a
mayoral proclamation, New York City's welfare system is vanishing.
By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-FRIENDSHIP-REVIEW (Washington) _ The ruptured relations
between Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp, who became acquainted
while both were working at the Pentagon in 1996, is but one of many
friendships blown to smithereens during Kenneth Starr's six months
of digging into allegations of White House sex and cover-up. By
Jill Abramson.
</P>
</TEXT>
