<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST FOR THE TREASURE QUEST WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You think finding the correct answer hidden in Treasure Quest
that would win $1 million was difficult?
</P>
<P>
   You should try finding the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who spent the last two years playing the Sirius
Corp.'s CD-ROM game would like to find that person.
</P>
<P>
   But Sirius won't say if the person is a male or female, or give
out any other information. Moreover, it appears the winner wasn't
the first person to submit the correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, I wrote about a software program that
contained a $1 million prize: Treasure Quest from Sirius Corp. of
Scottsdale, Ariz. Players who bought the $50 game had to solve an
intricate puzzle, made up of an estimated 1,200 clues, to find the
mystery hidden in Professor Jonathon William Faulkner's 10-room
mansion. Players went through the mansion collecting clues.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the game's buyers are searching for something even more
elusive than the hidden treasure: the winner of the $1 million
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Sirius President Richard Gnant has refused to fully identify the
winner, saying only that the prize was won by ``P. Dreizen of San
Francisco, California.'' The announcement was made in mid-May, and
a Web site which allowed players to pass along ideas about solving
puzzles and exchange clues was closed down soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Those who purchased the game might want to contact the Arizona
Attorney General's Office (602-542-4266). A story by Dennis Wagner
of The Arizona Republic reported recently that a complaint has been
filed with the office. The office will not confirm or deny that,
but if there is legal action taken, purchasers of the game may have
recourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that it's a scam,'' Paul Wigowsky, told The
Republic. Wigowsky is an Oregon schoolteacher who filed the
consumer-fraud complaint. ``Unless we see the winner with our own
eyes, we won't believe it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no press release about the winner. No
picture-taking session. No address or no other confirmation. A note
was posted on the Treasure Quest Web site from the company saying
the answer to the mystery is, ``The Tree of Life.'' Searches for a
P. Dreizen in San Francisco's telephone books turned up a Pamala
Dreizen, who did not return a reporter's telephone calls over a
period of several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gnant insisted the Treasure Quest winner is a real person.
Losers, he told The Republic, ``are miffed because they didn't win.
We've maintained the integrity of this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he said the game rules don't require a public
notification of the winner, the rules clearly allow the company to
release the name: ``Entry constitutes permission (except where
prohibited) to use winner's name, likeness, hometown, biographical
information and any comments about the contest for publicity
purposes without compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that Gnant also refused to say whether
the winner was male or female, or how many others, if any, were
involved on Dreizen's winning team. He also would not release the
date of when the winning entry was submitted.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that ``P. Dreizen'' wasn't really the
first winner: ``Last week, Gnant acknowledged that Wigowsky solved
the riddle before Dreizen, but was disqualified because he did not
place a contest registration number in the appropriate place. `The
guy didn't follow the rules, so he didn't win Treasure Quest. I'm
sorry,' Gnant added. `Maybe I should have told him.' '''
</P>
<P>
   Gnant said the New York firm of Ventura Associates Inc., which
has handled contests for major companies, confirmed P. Dreizen as
the winner. The Republic article said Gnant's company has since
switched form computer games to marketing CD-ROM movies (which have
also been written about in this column) ``and he didn't want to
spend money on a victory bash.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the people who play these intricate puzzle games to
quickly figure out something else about the ``P. Dreizen'' winner:
Rearranged, the letters of his/her name spell out, ``End Prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? Possibly so. Words anagram into many phrases, some
of which seem to fit a theory. ``Sirius Corporation'' anagrams into
``So, I air corruptions.'' But the fact that the disgruntled
Treasure Quest players found ``End Prize'' in the prize-winner's
game is an indication of how resourceful and thorough they can be
when checking out leads.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic story said that now the contest is over, players
have started looking at Sirius' business. They've found the staff
has been reduced to a third of what it was _ a downsizing Gnant
said resulted from the change in the business (from gaming software
to CD-ROM movies). It has also closed its business offices and
moved its operations to a warehouse. Another Gnant business went
into bankruptcy several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other players found it odd that the name of the player who won
never popped up in the various chat rooms or bulletin boards where
players swapped information and hints. And they also wonder how a
complex game can be won by just one person. If more were involved,
it would seem they would want to come forward for the credit.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzle solvers are wound up after working on Treasure Quest
for two years _ then being told they won't be able to learn much at
all about the winner. They have another puzzle to solve, and I'll
bet they'll work until they find out the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
</TEXT>
