<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JULY4-HISTORY-NYT &LR;      07-03 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULY4-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENCE DAY ONCE DIVIDED AMERICANS RATHER THAN BRING THEM
TOGETHER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hottest holiday argument this weekend may be
over whether a day at the beach is worth half a day spent in
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But there were Independence Days two centuries ago when the
consummate celebration of American nationalism decayed into bitter
disputes between rival political parties, exceeding even the
political passions that the early Republic displayed for the other
364 days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   At a lecture this week in the National Archives, historian Len
Travers of the Massachusetts Historical Society described how the
day became ensconced as a central rite of the emerging republic.
And in his book, Celebrating the Fourth (University of
Massachusetts Press, 1977), he recollects an era from the
ratification of the Constitution until the War of 1812 when, in
some cities, there was nothing nonpartisan about the Fourth of
July.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, a fellow could be beaten for wearing the wrong
party's colors on his hat, and Boston routinely threw two separate
celebrations, each controlled by one of the two contending
political parties of the day.
</P>
<P>
   It was like if today's Republicans, being the majority in
Congress, sponsored the nationally televised orchestral performance
this Saturday on the Capitol's west lawn (with pops conductor Erich
Kunzel, to be sure, plus Sha Na Na and other entertainers), while
President Clinton and the Democratic National Committee sang the
blues with Koko Taylor downtown by the Washington Monument
(supported in the parade by any marching bands that fell under
control of the commander-in-chief).
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years ago, the parties were the Federalists, who
viewed the revolution as beginning with the Declaration of
Independence and ending neatly with the Constitution, and the
emergent Republicans, who saw a dynamic, continuing revolution and
who thrilled at its echoes in France.
</P>
<P>
   Although most American revolutionaries had hoped to avoid a
slide into partisanship, these parties, much like today's, often
sharply disagreed over economic and international policies. The
debate colored America's relations with England and France as those
foreign powers, still entrenched on the American continent, fought
for global dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston especially, these groups organized competing
celebrations, to a large degree transforming the Fourth of July
into an occasion for boisterous rallies for the party faithful,''
Travers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the rhetoric became more confrontational, July 4
sometimes carried with it an atmosphere of potential violence. By
1794, during negotiation of the Jay Treaty, which would have cast
in America's lot with Britain rather than with rival France,
something that Republicans opposed, Philadelphia's celebrations
verged on mayhem. But marching Republican tradesmen ultimately
retreated rather than fight the fully armed Federalist cavalry that
mobilized to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Boston was edgy, as crowds ransacked a British
vessel in the harbor two weeks before the Fourth. Had news of the
terms of the Jay Treaty not been delayed until July 6, Travers
wrote, bloodshed might not have been avoided there in 1795.
</P>
<P>
   The war of words, symbols and sometimes fists went on for years.
One year, a Boston merchant with Federalist sympathies roughed up a
French diplomat who wore a tricolor cockade on his hat. The scrap
of cloth was a provocative political symbol.
</P>
<P>
   According to Travers, the very idea of making the Fourth a
holiday took hold in part because the political parties wanted more
people at liberty to attend the contending rallies.
</P>
<P>
   By 1800, the year of Thomas Jefferson's election to the
presidency, the Federalists were in disarray, but they still
controlled Boston's city government and the city's official
celebrations. By 1802, the Republicans were mounting regular
counter-celebrations and the competition persisted for the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Federalist oratory reverberated in the Old South Meeting House;
the Republicans, not to be outdone, held their events at Faneuil
Hall, complete with Republican militia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1806, after the Republicans trounced the Federalists in
statewide elections, Boston's Federalist selectmen took revenge on
the victors with the news that Faneuil Hall was ``preengaged by the
federalists'' for Independence Day that year and the next year and
every year after. Driven out of Boston, the Republicans crossed the
Charles River and celebrated thereafter on Bunker Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Only with the War of 1812, and the peace of 1815, did the
political winds shift enough to abate this partisanship. From then
on, Independence Day was mainly a nationalist event, Travers says.
</P>
<P>
   But he told his audience to listen carefully and think hard
about what modern Democrats and Republicans _ or for that matter,
speakers from third parties _ might say through the smoke of
Saturday's supposedly neutral barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The non-partisan was always the ideal,'' he told his audience
today. ``However, the subtext was often partisan, and I submit that
it often is, even today. Rituals have a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
