u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REVIEW-ART-$AD     07-03 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REVIEW-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET KOSOVO, THE WORLD'S BIGGEST LITTLE TINDERBOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (For release Sunday, July 5)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic map of Balkans showing ethnic groupings is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `a' code)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the heart of the Serbian province of Kosovo, not so far from
Albania and pretty close to Macedonia, lies a hamlet called Kijevo.
Like other settlements in the area, it was a place where men spent
hours watching the traffic between Pristina and Pec while they
sipped coffee from little cups and ate sausages and yellow peppers.
Nearby, goats chewed the grass along the roadside.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a very dramatic place, which is why the pronouncement
last week from Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. diplomat who brought the
fragile peace to Bosnia, was so jarring: ``The most dangerous place
in Europe,'' Holbrooke called it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, two dozen Yugoslav policemen and 220 Serbian civilians were
besieged by Albanian rebels there, and the standoff was clearly
incendiary _ as is the larger conflict between the authorities in
Belgrade and the overwhelmingly Albanian population of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it is not hard to envision how loss of Serbian life
in Kijevo might spur a punitive expedition by Yugoslav forces, an
intensification of guerrilla warfare and perhaps terrorism by
Albanians. And once fully ignited, violence in Kosovo, where two
million people live, could well grow into prolonged fighting as
devastating as that which shattered adjoining Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But the most dangerous place in Europe? What could Holbrooke
have been thinking?
</P>
<P>
   There was a suggestion in his comments that the dangers now
focused in Kijevo were so broad in scope that Americans should take
a break from the indulgence of prosperity and the joys of
interleague baseball to pay attention to this peculiar corner of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Absurd as it seemed, tiny Kijevo was being portrayed as a
tinderbox that could inflame all Kosovo, and Kosovo was being cast
as the tinderbox that could bring fire and sword to the entire
Balkans. And this, the implication went, could endanger European
peace and accelerate a clash of religiously defined civilizations
that was predicted in the early 1990s by the Harvard political
scientist Samuel Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there was a hint that world order and stability
might be imperiled by this standoff between Albanians and Serbs in
a global backwater. That may appear preposterous to Americans,
particularly those who saw the film ``Wag the Dog'' and watched as
a fictitious U.S. president engineered a fictitious war with
Albania to divert attention from his personal woes. But, in fact,
there is logic, and plenty of history, behind the notion, which
serious analysts have been developing now for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The first link in the chain of events leading to widening
prospects of disorder is usually rendered as the speech by Serbian
leader Slobodan Milosevic in 1987, when he set Yugoslavia on the
path to its wars of dismemberment by urging the tiny minority of
Serbs in Kosovo to claim it as their own land, vital to their
history. According to the gloomiest analysts, the following events
are likely to flow from any full-scale war in which Kosovo's
Albanians, deprived of autonomy, now fight for independence:
</P>
<P>
   The first impact would be felt by Bosnia. Faced with the
possible loss of Kosovo, Serbia would be tempted to absorb the
Serbian entity within Bosnia, which is now an extremely fragile
balance of two ethnic units _ a Serb republic and a Bosnian-Croat
federation.
</P>
<P>
   Once Bosnia's Serbs left, Bosnia's Croats would presumably not
be far behind, taking their own lands and joining them to Croatia.
That would leave just a sliver of a state, mostly Muslim, in
Bosnia, and it would presumably have no place to look for support
but to the primarily Muslim Albanians and Turks, and to the Islamic
world in general.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if the Albanian rebels in Kosovo gained independence,
or even if they sustained their resistance, there would be great
consequences for all Albanians beyond Kosovo. In Albania, there
would certainly be strong impulses to help embattled ethnic kin.
</P>
<P>
   Albania is poor, divided and weak, but with its mountains and
long seacoast it has a long tradition of moving contraband. So the
involvement of Islamic forces in Kosovo would not be inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, too, has a large Albanian minority and, as in Kosovo
and Albania, the Albanians there have had one of the highest birth
rates in Europe. This has brought a demographic upsurge, and with
it a national awakening. In multi-ethnic Macedonia, the Albanians
have clamored for a university of their own and greater guarantees
of language rights. An impulse toward a greater Albania, uniting
the lands where Albanians live, would intensify in the event of an
independence struggle in Kosovo. Macedonia might even break up.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario could lead to a long-feared general Balkan war,
recalling the two Balkan Wars between 1911 and 1913 that set the
stage for World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Other analytic strands of the contemporary slide into a Balkan
doomsday envision the military involvement of Greece, which does
not want a divided Macedonia on its borders, and Turkey, which has
been training Albania's army. Finding themselves on opposing sides
of a shooting war would have obviously momentous consequences for
Greece and Turkey. The next domino, in this line of thinking, is
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Further compounding the dangers is the perceived role of
religious blocs in the unfolding tensions. In a controversial book,
``The Clash of Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1996), Huntington forecast a world in which
religiously based divisions would become the fault lines of new
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Since most Albanians are Muslim, those hostile or suspicious of
them have tended to think of them and portray them as Islamic, even
though there are Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Albanians,
too. At the same time, the largely Orthodox Russians have
gravitated toward traditional support for their fellow Orthodox
Serbs. On the other side, the growing alliance of Turks and
Albanians also at some level reflects the coming together of
coreligionists.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the claim that a small town in the middle of
Kosovo that hardly anybody had ever heard of was the most dangerous
place in Europe _ more dangerous than Belfast, more dangerous than
Chernobyl, more dangerous than Moscow or Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Absurd? Probably. Unrealistic? Not at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
