<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-REVIEW-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEACH-BLANKET BABEL: ANOTHER REASON TO STAY AT THE POOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: East Coast)   (The Week in Review)  
 (For release Sunday, July 5)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEASIDE HEIGHTS, N.J. _ Eventually, somebody is going to figure
out a way to implant advertising messages directly into the human
cerebral cortex. Meanwhile, Patrick Dori has come one small step
closer to a universe of ubiquitous advertising. He has invented a
device to print ads directly onto a beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my best idea ever _ 5,000 imprints of Skippy Peanut
Butter jars covering the beach!'' Dori crowed the other day, as the
first wave of July 4 beachgoers gawked at his brainchild: a
steamroller-like contraption, towed behind a municipal
sand-grooming tractor, that stamps a continuous four-foot-wide
strip of ads in the sand like a notary public gone berserk with his
seal.
</P>
<P>
   Dori had to yell to be heard above the shriek of sea gulls and
the lawn-mower mutter of a Piper Cub airplane drifting up the coast
towing a banner advertising a long-distance phone deal. On the
boardwalk behind him, more advertising glared like battle colors.
</P>
<P>
   Billboard advertising was invented around the turn of the
century to siphon disposable income from the masses pouring into
East Coast seashore havens like Brooklyn's Coney Island and New
Jersey's Atlantic City. (Airplane ads became popular in the 1950s.)
So perhaps it was appropriate that Dori christen his invention at
this bustling seashore town on the central New Jersey coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dori, the owner of an advertising and promotion company called
Beach'n Billboard, said the idea of building a rolling machine to
impress messages in the sand ``came to me literally in a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I woke up and started drawing,'' he continued. ``Of
course, I then had to consider, who are you going to get to pay for
this?''
</P>
<P>
   After making a prototype machine, he approached Bestfoods, the
New Jersey-based food giant that owns the Skippy brand, and got a
contract. Seaside Heights was the first municipality to agree to
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now a swath of panels alternating the messages ``Skippy Peanut
Butter'' with ``Please Do Not Litter'' seem to stretch into
infinity on the town's long beach _ that is, until the crowds
trample it back into sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us an opportunity to deliver a message in a way that
no one has ever done before,'' said Mike Lyon, the promotion
director for the company's grocery brands, who attended last week's
launch. ``I'm here looking at thousands of families with kids. If
they're on the beach thinking of Skippy, that's just what we
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Dori said other big commercial beach towns around the country
have expressed interest, and Lyon said Bestfoods was game for
beach-ad expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many seashore towns disdain the kind of commercialism
that runs rampant in New Jersey's boardwalk towns and other
beach-front meccas like Myrtle Beach, S.C., and Ocean City, Md. The
California Coastal Commission, for example, recently vetoed a plan
to erect so-called sun-shelter kiosks on beaches in Los Angeles
County, which would have been paid a fee for beach maintenance by a
company that planned to cover the kiosks with ads.
</P>
<P>
   Ads in the sand would seem to offer competition for airplane
banners. But the flyboys and flygirls shrugged off the new
diversion on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be competition, except that people walk all over
the ad,'' said Bob Bunting, the owner of Ocean Aerial Advertising
in Ocean City, Md., which uses about a dozen modified Piper Cub
aircraft to tow banners _ some as big as 30 feet by 100 feet _ over
seashore towns in Maryland, Delaware and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beach, people hear an airplane and they look up,'' he
added. ``That's what people always have done. Who looks down to see
an ad being stepped all over?''
</P>
<P>
   James Butler, vice president of Aerial Sign Co. in Hollywood,
Fla., which has 45 aircraft and books most of the big national
brand accounts that now dominate the airborne business, also
scoffed. ``You mean the sand ads aren't in color?'' he asked. ``I
was picturing something you could actually see.''
</P>
<P>
   Dori, who received a patent last week for his sand-embossing
device, takes the ribbing jovially. ``When I first told people
about this, they laughed and said I was out of my mind,'' he said.
``They aren't laughing now. I'm ready to roll.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
