<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE WINS IN SHOOTOUT, 4-3, AS LAST ITALIAN KICK HITS CROSSBAR  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. DENIS, France _ Luigi Di Biagio's penalty kick ricocheted
off the crossbar, and as the Italian midfielder tumbled backward
with an anguished expression on his face, the French players rushed
forward to share their relief with goalkeeper Fabien Barthez.
</P>
<P>
   After 120 minutes of sophisticated defensive soccer, a handful
of legitimate opportunities and no goals, this fratricidal World
Cup quarterfinal between the host nation and the nation where many
French soccer stars earn fine livings in lira had come down to
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted,'' said French coach Aime Jacquet Friday night,
moments after his team had beaten Italy, 4-3, on penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Only Italian coach Cesare Maldini will have the chance to rest.
The French will play again on Wednesday in the semifinals against
the winner of Saturday's quarterfinal match between Germany and
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Italians must face the fact that for the third
consecutive World Cup they were eliminated after faltering in the
nerve-jangling, oft- unsatisfying exercise _ the shootout. In 1990,
Argentina defeated them in the semifinals after penalty kicks. In
the 1994 final against Brazil, Roberto Baggio was the last Italian
to shoot and sent the ball flying over the crossbar. Di Biagio, who
has been one of the Squadra Azzurra's finest performers in France,
came closer to his target, but the result was the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose three times on penalty kicks is a travesty,'' said
Baggio, who made his penalty kick Friday night but still ended up
on the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   Di Biagio was not the only player to miss. Defender Bixente
Lizarazu, the second French player to shoot, had his tentative shot
stopped by Italian goalkeeper Gianluca Pagliuca. But Italy's
advantage would prove very brief, because on its next attempt,
Barthez smothered a shot by Demetrio Albertini.
</P>
<P>
   ``That put the counter back at zero,'' said Barthez, a relaxed
sort who was laughing with a French assistant coach before the
first penalty kicks were taken. ''I didn't get worried. I just knew
we were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   After French defender Laurent Blanc beat Pagliuca to give France
a 4-3 advantage, Di Biagio, the last of Italy's five designated
penalty shooters, walked forward. Di Biagio, a 27-year-old late
bloomer who stars for AS Roma, struck the ball with his right foot
toward the center of the goal. Barthez had guessed wrong and dived
to his left. The crowd of 80,000 was screaming too loudly for
anyone but Barthez and Di Biagio to hear the sound of the ball
striking the crossbar, but a groan was surely heard throughout
Italy and a roar throughout France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' Di Biagio said. ``It doesn't make me feel any
better to know that other great players have done the same thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Perhaps we are cursed a little bit,'' Cesare Maldini said.
``But I'm proud of my players. They gave everything they had.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no fourth World Cup title for Italy, the nation
whose first division has been the sport's most important and
competitive laboratory in recent decades. The question is whether
France can win its first. Though two French administrators were
instrumental in launching the World Cup in 1930, their nation has
never advanced past the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   This will be France's fourth chance, having failed in 1958, 1982
and 1986. The pivotal player for France in 1982 and 1986, Michel
Platini, is now president of the World Cup organizing committee,
and he watched Friday night's match from the stands with French
president Jacques Chirac at his side. What the two presidents saw
was a team with a serious problem _ the inability to put the ball
in the net.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over the French team in 1994, after their stunning
failure to qualify for the last World Cup, Jacquet has been
searching for strikers capable of capitalizing on the opportunities
that Zidane is so adept at creating. Though the French scored nine
goals in their first-round matches, they have managed to score only
one goal against stronger second-round opposition, Paraguay and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, despite Jacquet's decision to start a third defensive
midfielder, Christian Karembeu, the French did not play as
conservatively as their opposition. They pushed forward from the
start, sending defenders into the Italian half regularly and asking
Karembeu to play a more offensive role than usual with the national
team. They had two good chances in the first six minutes, and their
best chance of the match at the end of the first half when Youri
Djorkaeff found himself alone in front of Pagliuca, his teammate at
Inter Milan, but shot wide left.
</P>
<P>
   Djorkaeff and Pagliuca had been teasing each other about this
potential matchup since the World Cup draw was conducted in
December, and there were many such reunions on the field Friday.
During regulation, Zidane was marked by Gianluca Pessotto, his
teammate at Juventus of Turin. In all, 11 of the 22 players on the
French roster have played or are still playing in Italy, and it is
clear that the likes of Desailly, Lilian Thuram and French captain
Didier Deschamps have put their grand tour to practical use.
</P>
<P>
   The French no longer play like the ``Brazilians of Europe,'' as
Platini's generation was dubbed. But they play defense superbly,
and they won the majority of the duels against the Italians, whose
best chance came at the end of the first period of overtime when
Baggio got underneath a lobbed pass near the French goal.
</P>
<P>
   But Baggio, who had replaced an ineffective Alessandro Del Piero
in the 67th minute, sent his volleyed, right-footed shot wide of
the goal, and the French crowd roared on. France had not lost to
Italy in 20 years _ not since the 1978 World Cup in Argentina _ and
that surprising streak would not come to an end on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have equaled what the older generation did: the generation
of Platini,'' said Deschamps. ``Now, we all hope we can do
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
