<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDONA, FLAGSTAFF HOPE TO START NEW `ASHLAND' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EMBARGOED FOR USE SUNDAY JULY 5)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Two cities, asking the same question, a little
afraid of the answer they'll hear. Can Arizona's high country
support a pair of Shakespeare festivals?
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour's drive through some of the West's most spectacular
scenery separates Flagstaff and Sedona but, in many ways, they are
planets apart. Flagstaff is pines and lingering snowfields on
14,000-foot peaks. Sedona is brilliantly colored monoliths erupting
from a high desert garden of yucca and ground-hugging juniper.
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff is a university town where the nightlife throbs to a
blues and country beat, while crowds jostle their way from brew pub
to pizza joint. Sedona is an upscale destination resort, priding
itself on glitzy shops and more than 40 art galleries, but
reluctantly admitting that the sidewalks swallow themselves along
with the setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   Both claim an affinity for the arts, neither would be adverse to
a little more coin finding its way into civic coffers.
</P>
<P>
   But a theatrical festival is a theatrical festival: an
amalgamation of plays, directors, actors, designers, cultural
snobbism and P.T. Barnum antics. If you've seen one, you haven't
seen them all, but you've seen their like _ and is it worth braving
Oak Creek Canyon's switchbacks to double-cast your collection
during a vacation or a weekend getaway from Phoenix?
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, ``competition'' is not a word that muscles its way
into conversation with the principals of Flagstaff's Grand Canyon
Shakespeare Festival, which began its third season Friday, and
Sedona's Shakespeare Sedona, which kicks off its inaugural event
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But it lingers at the edge of hearing, an echo of nervousness.
Even in its third year, the Flagstaff celebration is a financial
babe in comparison to the West's great classical fiestas: the
Oregon Shakespeare Festival in Ashland, Ore., and the Utah
Shakespearean Festival in Cedar City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   And if Sedona doesn't at least break even by summer's end, its
second season could be a stillborn dream.
</P>
<P>
   If neither thinks of the other as a threat, each is aware that
seats must be filled _ and if someone's must be empty, well, better
yours than mine.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the atmosphere is upbeat and optimistic. Actors,
artistic directors and chamber managers talk about building a
cultural state of mind in northern Arizona that will produce a sort
of circle tour of the arts. Tourists will be steered from the Grand
Canyon's vistas to Sedona's red rocks, with a stop for a lively
comedy here, a stirring tragedy there.
</P>
<P>
   And seriously big revenues everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Dunlop of the Flagstaff Chamber of Commerce points out that,
last season, the Ashland festival attracted 364,602 patrons, the
majority of whom were tourists. Overall, the area's economy
benefitted in the amount of $90.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ashland started with nothing, unless you count sagebrush.
Flagstaff and Sedona are on the doorstep of one of the country's
most popular national parks. Both towns have airports, Flagstaff
has an Amtrack station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering what has happened elsewhere, the potential here is
enormous,'' Dunlop says.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't escaped the attention of Frank Miller, president of
the Sedona-Oak Creek Chamber of Commerce, as to just who patronizes
these things. Statistics for Ashland and Cedar City indicate that
audience members are predominately middle-to-upper-management,
well-educated types who spend money. A great deal of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very target-specific in our promotions . . . we are
looking for those extended-stay, high-value visitors who have the
time and will take the time to spend money in our community,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that a festival will encourage this, and at the
same time enhance the reputation Sedona has as a center for the
arts in the Southwest.''
</P>
<P>
   He breaks into a grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, if we're telling people they should stay here for
four or five days to do the area justice, we'd better have
something for them to do on those four or five nights that go along
with the days.''
</P>
<P>
   If planning were performing, the Sedona event would have a
slight edge on the Flagstaff festival, but while Sedona's founders
were lining up backers, the Flagstaff people stopped talking and
started doing.
</P>
<P>
   Building on the bones of the defunct Northern Arizona University
Repertory Theatre, the Grand Canyon Shakespeare Festival welcomed
its first audiences in 1996. Initially, it was a university
endeavor, staffed primarily by faculty members and students.
</P>
<P>
   This year, NAU's president Dr. Clara Lovett, an avid supporter
of the festival concept, brought in Wayne Watkins to head up the
event. Watkins, a NAU grad, returned to Flagstaff to found Arizona
TheatreWorks, an Equity operation that is one of the state's arts
success stories. Known for his almost obsessive professional
standards, Watkins immediately set about hiring a staff of actors,
directors and designers from Phoenix, New York, Los Angeles and
other stage centers.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Kubzansky was brought from Los Angeles to direct
``Twelfth
</P>
<P>
   Night,'' Daniel Bryan Cartmell from the same city to helm
``Macbeth'' and Roger Michelson from New York to supervise ``The
Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   As often is the case with festivals, the directors have multiple
responsibilities, with Cartmell playing Prospero in ``The Tempest''
and Michelson portraying the title role in ``Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Other actors include the Phoenix area's Kathy Fitzgerald, who
met and married Michelson while she was starring in ``Swinging On A
Star'' on Broadway; and Tucson's Ben Stewart, familiar for his many
roles with Arizona Theatre Company.
</P>
<P>
   Like Watkins, Sedona's Jared Sakren has impeccable connections
to the theater world. A founding member of John Houseman's Acting
Company and later one of the Alabama Shakespeare Festival's
whiz-kids, he made good use of his Rolodex in luring Greg Leaming,
associate artistic director of New Haven's Long Wharf Theatre, to
create ``The Macbeth Project,'' along with actor Patrick Page
(``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``Dracula``) to play the witch-bedeviled
Scottish chief in what promises to be an innovative reassessment of
Shakespeare's thriller.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sakren will direct ``The Comedy of Errors'' and
Page will present ``Passions' Slaves,'' his one-man revue of
Shakespearean characters, to round out Sedona's playbill.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Sakren's most important connection may prove to be
his partnership with Jill Patterson, director of theater at
Sedona's Verde Valley School, one of the Southwest's most
prestigious boarding institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, a Yale graduate, had been hired by Verde Valley's
headmaster Saul Benjamin to enhance the school's already impressive
arts program. It soon was decided that one of the best ways to do
that would be to establish a summer festival that included among
its attractions a conservatory whose faculty would include the
festival staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Shakespeare Sedona Institute, which makes its debut this
week (week of July 5) along with the festival, has been accredited
by Prescott College and already is attracting an international
student body.
</P>
<P>
   The scheming isn't all serious. Flagstaff has the edge on Sedona
for goofy promotions: among Grand Canyon marketing director Cindy
Wynn's ``talker-uppers'' are a contest to choose the pet that looks
the most like Shakespeare and a competition to find the man whose
legs look the best in a kilt.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, Flagstaff seems the most festival-conscious of the
two cities, which Wynn admits is, to some degree, a reflection of
its seniority. Banners hang from lamp poles along the main streets
and every other shop window seems to display a poster.
</P>
<P>
   Community cooperation is extensive. The Aboretum at Flagstaff
has planted a garden outside the theater that contains plants
mentioned in Shakespeare's plays; Bookman's Used Books and Records
is sponsoring a series of lectures and a sonnet competition; the
Late for the Train Cafe is baking Bard Tarts and GingerBard Cookies
for wenches to sell during the greens show that precedes each
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case anyone misses the message, Wynn is organizing noisy
opening night parades to lead playgoers to the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the West's other Shakespearean festivals, which boast
open-air stages, the Arizona events are indoors _ at least for now.
Flagstaff's performances are at the Clifford E. White Theatre on
the NAU campus. Sedona is dividing its run between the theater at
Verde Valley School and the auditorium at Red Rock High School.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling dice with the weather, as Wynn wryly puts it, is still
very much a dream for Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk is slight. Everyone agrees it would be a great idea
but that's as far as it gets,'' she says. ``They want to wait and
see if the festival grows.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk is more substantial in Sedona, perhaps because Verde Valley
School is no stranger to outdoor events. It is home to the annual
Sedona Jazz on the Rocks Festival and, every summer, singer Jackson
Browne stages a concert to raise funds for the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it would take money to build a suitable amphitheater
and that's money we would rather spend on high-quality casts and
productions,'' Patterson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our goal is to convince people they don't have to
go to Cedar City or Ashland to see great Shakespeare. They can see
it right here in Arizona. You don't need a fancy stage when you've
got Cathedral Rock right outside.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
