<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-VICTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT FRENCH LOOK AHEAD AND DREAM OF WORLD CUP GLORY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Victory is sweet, even as a result of penalty kicks, and
for the French soccer team it is particularly so because to win
against Italy in the World Cup is to begin to overcome the nagging
inferiority complex that stems from never having won this trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The French players did their best to hide their self-doubt
before Friday's match, but it was obvious enough. After all, Italy
had won the trophy three times. Italy has what is almost certainly
the best league in the world. In the striker Christian Vieri, Italy
had the tournament's most prolific scorer. And, quite simply, ``la
squadra'' is a soccer-playing myth while ``les bleus'' have often
been a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Dessailly, France's commanding central defender, summed
up his team's sense of having proved a point. ``The fact is the
Italians are just a touch pretentious,'' he said after the game.
``We wanted to show them something. We wanted to prove to them that
our game has real quality too.''
</P>
<P>
   Vieri in tears. Italian captain Giuseppe Bergomi in tears. The
man who missed the last penalty, Luigi di Biagio, paralyzed with
grief. The agony of a nation for which soccer is more of a passion
than it will ever be in France. All this meant nothing to Dessailly
and the other French players basking in the glow beyond Italy's
long shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Dessailly, like several members of the French side, has honed
his game in Italy, playing five seasons for AC Milan, where he was
known simply as ``il gigante negro'' _ the black giant. During a
bad season for Milan this year, he was much criticized, but, like
the entire French defense, he has been magnificent since the World
Cup began.
</P>
<P>
   France has conceded just one goal in five matches _ a record of
which even Italy, long reputed to run the most watertight defenses
in the world, would approve. Friday, Dessailly and his fellow
defenders _ Laurent Blanc, Lilian Thuram and Bixente Lizarazu _
shut out Vieri, something no team had done up to now. They turned
star Italian striker Alessandro Del Piero into a pale and lonely
figure who was eventually substituted. And they allowed the great
Roberto Baggio just one chance that he sent inches wide of the
post.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is a defense that yields goals as readily as a
desert yields water. In a sense it was crafted in Italy: Blanc once
played there, Thuram still does and Dessailly is only now moving
from Milan to England's Chelsea. Can it at last secure France its
coveted trophy? Several French players remarked Friday that the
team had now reached the same stage in the competition _ the
semifinal _ that the great French side of the 1980s twice reached.
``We have now equaled our elders,'' said captain Didier Deschamp
with quite evident relief.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a very different French squad. In the 1980s France
was led and inspired by brilliant midfielder Michel Platini, now
the president of the French organizing committee for this
tournament. It was a team full of fantasy, originality and
outrageous talent, a side that readily scored goals but was
inclined, at the crunch, to concede too many.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, in the semifinals of 1982 and 1986 against Germany,
France bowed out, conceding five goals in the two matches. The
hosts of this year's tournament seem unlikely to be as generous
this year. But a terrible doubt lingers over the French ability to
score.
</P>
<P>
   Zinedine Zidane, who plays for the Italian club Juventus, has
taken over from Platini as the French playmaker. He is as creative
as Platini, but, unlike Platini, he seldom scores goals. Up front,
France has tried a succession of strikers, without settling on a
lineup. Young Thierry Henry and David Trezeguet have both scored
goals against lesser opponents in the opening games, but the only
came on as substitutes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   What France needs is a Vieri. Short of that, it needs its
veteran goalscorer, Yuri Djorkaeff, who plays for Inter Milan, to
recover his touch and stop squandering good chances as he did twice
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But with its new Italian realism, learned by many in the Italian
league, France may find just one goal per game is enough to get the
team home. Before a home crowd, and with the old doubts fading like
bad dreams, that may not be asking too much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
