<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NIGHTCLUBS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED AN ISM? TRY TARANTINISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 5)  
 (JT)  
 By VIJAI MAHESHWARI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a Thursday night at From Dusk Till Dawn, a nightclub that
takes its name and inspiration from the 1996 vampire western
written by Quentin Tarantino, much of which unfolds in a topless
bar south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   A pouty, curvaceous woman in a white gown leaned against one of
the Mayan-inspired columns that dot the upscale Moscow club, while
on a screen behind her ran a tape loop of selections from the work
of Tarantino, Russia's favorite American auteur.
</P>
<P>
   When the images segued to a scene from the final reel of ``From
Dusk Till Dawn'' _ showing topless dancers morphing through special
effects into blood-sucking ghouls _ the pouty woman, a stripper,
went into action. She led a middle-aged businessman out of the
audience and undressed him to his underwear while a deejay cranked
up the volume. Instead of sprouting fangs, she capped off her act
by casually opening her gown to stand fully naked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose this place because of the name _ we loved the film,''
said a physician who was celebrating his 20th wedding anniversary
at the club with his wife. Earlier, a male dancer had partly
disrobed the wife, a schoolteacher. ``We've been living together
for 20 years, but we can still enjoy a strip show,'' she said.
``Now that's very Tarantino, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Moscow night life in the late 1990s. America might
have Elvis; Russia has found Tarantino, the writer and director who
has been embraced for his dark irony, gaudy violence and
glamorization of hoodlums with awful taste. Many Russian lovers of
his work say it is more reflective of their own country's culture
than America's.
</P>
<P>
   Theaters from the island of Sakhalin near Japan to Orenburg in
the Urals show Tarantino's more obscure films, while the ``Pulp
Fiction'' soundtrack is piped into trains and planes. Teen-age
girls lop their hair into Uma Thurman bobs and dance the twist from
the ``Pulp Fiction'' scene in Jack Rabbit Slim's diner. Moscow
hipsters imitate Tarantino's nerdy, owl-eyed look. Most notably,
the director's world has inspired a generation of nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Cater-corner from the Kremlin is a smoky basement speak-easy
called Four Rooms, named after the 1995 film starring Tim Roth as a
Hollywood bellboy, to which Tarantino contributed one of four
segments. Although the club has few links to the film other than
its name and layout _ it has four rooms arranged railroad style _
the cachet of the name alone has served it well. One Friday night,
the disco was packed with a cross section of Moscow's bright young
things.
</P>
<P>
   A young man in a ``Reservoir Dogs'' T-shirt and dark sunglasses
made two V's with his fingers across his eyes as he danced. ``He is
not American _ he's got a Russian soul,'' the man said of
Tarantino, shouting to be heard over the Dick Dale surf-guitar
soundtrack. His dance partner, a spandex-clad young woman with a
heroin chic look and skyscraper platform shoes, added, ``His
characters like to wander, shout and shoot _ just like us
Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Valery Novak, an owner of the club, who came up with the name,
was less in thrall to the director. ``It was just accidental,'' he
said of the club's name. ``The name just happened to fit our
original design concept for the club.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though he discounted the Tarantino connection, Novak
admitted trying to lure the director to last year's grand opening.
Sasha Markvo, a publicity agent and model who persuaded Alexander
McQueen to show his fall collection in a Moscow subway station last
year, went so far as to call an assistant to Tarantino in Los
Angeles. ``I told him Moscow was even crazier and bloodier than his
films,'' Ms. Markvo said. ``But he couldn't come. He had to go to
Cannes.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Russia seems to have an opinion about Tarantino.
``He made bad taste hip,'' said Aleksandr Kulish, the editor in
chief of the Russian edition of Premiere, the film magazine. ``And
for a country where `trash culture' was taboo for almost 70 years,
his ironic films were an eye-opener.''
</P>
<P>
   Kulish noted that Tarantino's influential ``Pulp Fiction''
opened in 1994, just as many Russians began to revere lowbrow over
highbrow culture _ Solzhenitsyn lost favor to pulpy detective
writers, for example, and gaudy mafiosi in gold chains and flashy
German automobiles replaced dissidents as underground heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fit right in with the zeitgeist,'' said Max Friedman, an
American party promoter who has spent five years in Moscow. ``He
made all the greasy, sly characters of the new Russia _ kiosk
owners, drug dealers, gangsters, molls _ feel glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   From Dusk Till Dawn, which opened in November in central Moscow
and serves Cognac at $250 a glass, is contemplating a Tarantino
fashion show. Dmitri Troitsky, a Russian filmmaker, pointed to
bull-neck gangsters with wafer-thin dates, some of whom were
snickering at scenes from ``Reservoir Dogs'' playing on the club's
screen. ``Russian gangsters are works in progress, just like their
Tarantino counterparts,'' Troitsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarantino's latest film, ``Jackie Brown,'' was promoted in
Moscow almost as heavily as ``Godzilla'' in New York. Bootleg
videos circulated in the weeks before the American premiere of
``Jackie Brown'' on Christmas in 1997. At one private viewing in an
apartment, the picture was so streaked and grainy that Los Angeles
looked more like Moscow _ dark, snowy, chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, ``Jackie Brown'' was a box-office flop in Russia.
``It was too plot-driven _ not quite edgy or funny enough for
Russians,'' said Kulish, the Premiere editor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Tarantino craze may have crested. On the outer edge
of Moscow, Jack Rabbit Slim's, the city's first Tarantino-theme
nightclub, is well past its heyday. One weekend night it was nearly
deserted. When the first line of ``Pulp Fiction'' _ ``Everybody
move _ this is a robbery!'' _ was broadcast over the sound system,
nobody stirred.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to come here just because of the name,'' said
Andrei Malinkov, the manager. ``Now they hardly come at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at From Dusk Till Dawn, business is considerably better.
Still, the owners seem to be anticipating a change in fashion. They
are planning to convert part of their establishment to take
advantage of another American style _ the cigar bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
