<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-QUARTER-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE STRATEGIES, ONE OUTCOME: A SPRING THAT CAME UP ROSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a bitter spring quarter for many a mutual fund manager,
but it was a very sweet season for others. How did some managers
land at the top of the fund performance lists? Different tacks
worked well for different managers.
</P>
<P>
   Here, some of the winners talk about their strategies _ from
short-selling to big bets on technology and European stocks _ as
well as their outlooks for the rest of the year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael B. Orkin, manager of Caldwell &AMP; Orkin Market
Opportunity, might be called Doom-and-Gloom. His fund, based in
Atlanta, landed the No. 12 position on the list of best-performing
United States diversified funds in the second quarter, with a 10.1
percent return.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is attributable to Orkin's short-selling, which
involves betting on a decline, rather than an increase, in the
price of a stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a short sale, investors sell shares that they have borrowed
from a broker, betting that they can replace the stock at a lower
price. Orkin has benefited so much from the practice that he plans
to raise the 40 percent cap on short positions in his fund to 50
percent or 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe eventually the stock market will have a significant
and long-lasting setback,'' Orkin said. ``I'm talking about bear
markets that happen once in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Why so downbeat? Orkin faxed a reporter a 10-page missive to
explain his reasoning. The gist of it? ``People don't believe the
markets can drop,'' he said. ``Massive complacency is becoming
firmly established.''
</P>
<P>
   Orkin's solution is to mix stock purchases with short sales.
``The criteria for both is we look for change; an acceleration in
earnings growth; management change, usually correlated with
restructuring, or industry changes like supply or demand for
semiconductor chips or oil exploration and development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A long position, Ames Department Stores, which rose 24.6
percent, helped his second-quarter return. Orkin calls Ames, which
accounts for 1.9 percent of the $247.1 million fund, ``a discount
retailer that's executing its strategy well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ames emerged from bankruptcy, reorganized under new management
and is faring well because economic growth has left consumers with
money to spend, he said. Ames sells for 16 times 1998 earnings,
which analysts expect to grow 15 to 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Orkin declined to name companies that the fund is shorting but
said he was playing two themes: companies with exposure to Asia and
companies that offer subprime loans.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum investment for the fund was just raised to $100,000,
from $10,000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big technology bets did the trick for the Janus 20 portfolio,
which, as its name implies, holds just 20 stocks. The fund is
managed by Scott W. Schoelzel, who took over when Thomas F. Marsico
left Janus Capital to open his own shop in January.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer, which surged 37 percent in the second quarter,
helped push Janus 20 up to first place for the quarter among
diversified funds, and Schoelzel remains bullish on the company: It
now accounts for 8 percent of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the systemic advantage that they enjoy from their
direct-sales model,'' Schoelzel said. ``The company also has
negative working capital, because they get their customers' money
immediately but they don't have to pay their suppliers for 60 to 90
days.''
</P>
<P>
   And Schoelzel is also excited about the fact that Dell is moving
into selling higher-margin servers and notebook computers.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which ran up 53.9 percent, also played a big
part in the outperformance of Janus 20. It accounts for 6 percent
of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like America Online because of the rate at which it's
signing up subscribers, advertisers and E-commerce partners,''
Schoelzel said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also been able to increase some of its
advertising rates, which Schoelzel said would help drive up America
Online earnings more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Schoelzel's winners weren't all of the wired variety. Home
Depot, at 3 percent of the fund, rose 22.8 percent in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the large stores, Home Depot is on the verge of
rolling out Expo stores, a high-end format for clients of designers
and architects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schoelzel remains bullish on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're in a secularly declining inflation environment
and, as a result, a fairly benign interest rate environment,'' he
said. ``The move in financial assets has many years to run.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A love affair with Europe landed the $420.8 million Federated
International Small Co. fund, managed by Tracy P. Stouffer, in
third place on the list of diversified international stock funds
for the second quarter. The fund returned 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stouffer's charter is flexible. She must only stick with
companies with capitalizations of $1 billion or less and stay
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 35 percent of the fund was invested in emerging
markets. This year, the total is zero, which, of course, served her
well as those markets swooned. The fund's holdings in Europe teeter
at 96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this mix, or lack thereof, has to do with Ms. Stouffer's
mandate to hold small-capitalization stocks, which are suffering
mightily outside of developed nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting any small-cap effect in emerging markets
because all the companies are becoming smaller and smaller, the
result of shrinking prices and currency erosion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   European small-cap stocks have thrived, Ms. Stouffer said,
because of a general flight to smaller-sized companies in reaction
to the Asian problems. ``Small companies tend to do business
locally, so they're somewhat of a safe haven,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They also tend to have low levels of debt, if for no other
reason than that few lenders will give them loans. Moreover, they
are benefiting from a trend toward outsourcing among big companies
of their noncore businesses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stouffer plans to stay invested in Europe for now. ``I don't
think it's time to move into the emerging markets,'' she said. ``I
don't think the Asia problems will be resolved quickly, and small
companies are beneficiaries of European growth and the EMU,'' she
added, referring to European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
   The fund holds 185 companies. Among the largest, all well under
2 percent of the fund's assets, are Cofir, a Spanish holding
company with hotel and wine businesses; Creyf's, a temporary
employment company in Belgium, and Telepizza, a Spanish pizza
delivery chain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
