<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT NECESSARY TO BE JAPANESE AT YAOHAN PLAZA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 (JT)  
 By RUTH LA FERLA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Badtz Maru pops up everywhere at Yaohan Plaza, the
riverfront Japanese mall in Edgewater, N.J. His pudgy cartoon
features glower on miniaturized note pads and canvas backpacks, and
he puffs himself up importantly on a child's lunch box, where he
caught the eye of Yeohlee Teng, the Malaysian-born New York
designer, who goes professionally by her first name only.
</P>
<P>
   She was instantly smitten by the doughty Japanese warrior
penguin, and in no time at all she whisked him from his shelf and
whirled him off in a merry little waltz.
</P>
<P>
   Badtz Maru is one of myriad attractions at Yaohan Plaza, a mecca
for homesick Japanese residents of Scarsdale, N.Y., and Greenwich,
Conn., which appeals as well to New York City shoppers, who need
only to cross the George Washington Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are drawn by the Food Plaza, the cavernous, hypertidy
supermarket that anchors the mall, its aisles lined with okono
miyaki, a savory cabbage; shrimp-filled pancakes, which are Japan's
fast-food equivalent to hamburger; sticky rice balls wrapped in
seaweed; pickled ginger and plums, and what may be the largest
assortment of Japanese snack foods outside Tokyo, from curly
salmon-color fritters to roasted green peas.
</P>
<P>
   Novelty hunters are just as likely to enjoy the Specialty Plaza,
with its compact mini-boutiques of Shiseido and Poli cosmetics and
the promise of ferreting out any number of hot fashion commodities:
knee-length kimonos that might have marched straight off Dries van
Noten's runway, loose-fitting drawstring judo pants, or the
thick-soled thongs that inspired Prada's high-end versions of a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But today, fashion was surprisingly low on Yeohlee's agenda. A
passionate recreational shopper, she approached an afternoon's
outing at Yaohan like a tourist on a photo safari. ``What I like
about shopping is the feeling of discovery, the sense that you
might find something, stumble on it unexpectedly,'' she said.
``It's that emotional element of fun and surprise that conventional
stores have taken away _ they're so vigorously directed toward
consumption.''
</P>
<P>
   Canon Elph in hand, she stalked her quarry: the exotic, the
eccentric and the surreal. At Mars New York, a toy shop, she
snapped a spark-spewing tin dragon and an assortment of doll-size
hair ornaments, before buying a pair of white cotton socks
embroidered with the features of a polar bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably wear these to work and see who notices,'' the
designer said, straight-faced, never mind that her day-to-day
uniform, a close-fitting T-shirt or turtleneck, black trousers and
work boots, is devoid of fanciful touches.
</P>
<P>
   She sailed on past small cylinders of gift wrap no larger than
tall candlesticks, past wands of hair mascara in strident shades of
violet, gold and orange _ ``We'll try these out later,'' she said _
and on toward three bath-toy babies arranged on a shelf next to a
white ceramic chick on the lid of a cookie jar.
</P>
<P>
   She considered this composition. ``Very Jeff Koons,'' she said
deadpan, before moving on to the adjacent handbag store.
</P>
<P>
   There, her eyes lighted up at the sight of a patent-leather
shoulder bag stenciled with the motto ``Ethos Is a Group of
Fashion, Ethos Our Mode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah-ha, a Jenny Holzer bag,'' she announced, a winking allusion
to the artist famous for her provocative slogans on billboards.
</P>
<P>
   There's a surprising loopiness in Yeohlee's choices, coming as
they do from a designer better known for her rigorous simplicity
and disciplined cut than for her sense of the burlesque. She treats
fashion as a form of soft architecture, and her fluid, minimalist
creations are perfectly at home in pristine gallery spaces.
(Several, in fact, were in Berlin this summer for ``Clothes and
Enclosures,'' an exhibition that will travel to Rotterdam, the
Netherlands, next month.)
</P>
<P>
   But Yeohlee herself was at home in the mall, darting as giddily
as Eloise among the shelves, riveted by their meticulously
engineered displays no less than by their contents. Her taste for
geometry propelled her from pyramids of teapots, cups and saki
pourers to a rack of thongs trimmed in velvet and polka-dot ribbon.
``I love the graphics of these,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was on to Kinokuniya, a bookshop that also carries
novelties like sumo-wrestler trading cards and Japanese fashion
magazines. Postcard-size paperback books momentarily caught her
eye, their cryptic English titles _ ``Angel Baby Cupid,'' ``Loose''
and ``Seven'' _ making her laugh. Near the shop's exit she stopped
in her tracks, fascinated by a display of origami paper. The small,
squarish sheaves of blue, green and orange reminded her of her
girlhood in Penang. ``I used to make little origami boats out of
these and float them in the monsoon rains,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear she had retained that toddler's sense of play when,
moments later, arriving at the Food Plaza, she zigzagged down
aisles so wide that a small aircraft could have landed in them.
``Just look at these,'' she exclaimed, snatching up clear
self-sealing plastic packets of ringo kyuri and kyo no kaori
(pickled cucumber), tinted, respectively, in green and inky purple.
``I love the colors.'' She was fascinated, too, by the festive
pastries: rice and bean confections sculptured like irises, and
sweetened rice balls elegantly cloaked in cherry leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Energized after sampling a few, she headed for Washu, a bedding
store, attracted by stacks of futons, five-toed cotton
slipper-socks and audaciously patterned kimonos. Plucking a
knee-length, fan-decorated kimono from a rack, she draped it on
Vanessa Verbeeck, her design studio model and companion of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as cabana wear, don't you?'' Yeohlee said, stepping
back to admire her handiwork. ``You'd put it on to lounge by the
pool while you waited for someone to bring you one of those
cocktails with a little paper umbrella stuck in it.''
</P>
<P>
   She had spent the best part of the afternoon indulging her inner
child, but now the pragmatist in her took over. ``This kimono is
pure cotton,'' she said. ``It has pockets, and it's
one-size-fits-all, very efficient. I like that. For me it fulfills
a lot of requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   She applies similar standards to her own collection, most
tellingly her gently structured urban nomad coat, made of
stormproof nylon bonded to alpaca. Cut to wrap like a komono, it is
simple and ample enough to be worn by a man or a woman. ``I really
pump into the things that I make as many uses as possible,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She was captivated by subtleties that revealed themselves only
on close inspection. Pouncing on a red-rim black-lacquer tray, she
announced: ``See, this one has a nice grain. Not every one does.''
And then she added in a stage whisper: ``Look, $12.50. I'll take
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the mall's food court, with its view across the Hudson
River to Riverside Park, Yeohlee pondered her latest acquisition
over a bowl of tempura and soba noodles. Rather than matching the
tray with something as obvious as a set of red lacquer bowls, she
decided, she would use it as an accent beneath her collection of
1950s Finnish glassware.
</P>
<P>
   As much fun as she had at Yaohan Plaza, she was not certain
which, if any, of the afternoon's impressions would filter into her
designs. ``You might go to western Pennsylvania, but you wouldn't
come back and do an Amish collection,'' she said. ``Still, you
might do a narrow black pant that is slightly cropped,''
</P>
<P>
   A fashion influence, when it does occur, tends to turn up in the
details. ``Who knows?'' she said, grinning broadly. ``Maybe I'll
have Badtz Maru in my clothes next season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
