<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (For release Sunday, July 5)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Rebuke and Setback For Starr's Inquiry
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that surprised even the defendants, a federal
judge decided that Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr went too far
when he obtained the indictment of Webster Hubbell, his wife and
two tax advisers on tax evasion charges.
</P>
<P>
   Judge James Robertson dismissed the criminal case, ruling that
prosecutors had both exceeded their jurisdiction and reneged on a
pledge to grant Hubbell, a former close aide to President Clinton,
immunity in exchange for thousands of records about Hubbell's
business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   A Hint of Leniency in Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's new military leader took what may be the most
significant step so far to reverse the abuses of his predecessor,
the late Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   The current leader, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, promised United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan that all remaining political
prisoners would be freed, including Moshood K.O. Abiola, who most
Nigerians think won a presidential election in 1993 that Abacha's
government aborted.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, one of Nigeria's sharpest critics, announced
that a high-level U.S. delegation would travel to Nigeria for talks
with Abubakar this weekend. _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Blame Enough for All
</P>
<P>
   The pilot and navigator of the warplane that hit a ski lift
cable near Cavalese, Italy, in February broke many rules, but
convicting them at a court martial could be difficult, a Marine
Corps hearing officer said. The reasoning: The rest of the Marine
Corps, the Air Force and federal map-makers made too many
contributory errors.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   The Verdict: Suicide
</P>
<P>
   Slavko Dokmanovic, 48, was approaching the end of his case
before the United Nations tribunal on war crimes in the Balkans. A
former mayor of Vukovar, Croatia, he was charged with helping Serb
soldiers organize a 1991 massacre of more than 200 Croats. His
verdict was due July 7. But Dokmanovic's body was found hanging
from a door hinge in his cell early Monday morning. The case is now
closed.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MARLISE SIMONS
</P>
<P>
   Florida, the Firestorm State
</P>
<P>
   Fires burning across Florida since Memorial Day raged out of
control, literally casting a pall over the Fourth of July. More
than 100 homes were burned and tens of thousands of people were
forced to evacuate. Damage along the ravaged north and central east
coast of the state was certain to rise as firefighters were
thwarted by gusty winds and temperatures of more than 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The fires closed nearly 100 miles of Interstate 95, the major
highway along the East Coast, and a smoky haze obscured the sky as
far away as Miami, 250 miles to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, severe summer storms wreaked havoc.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern half of the United States, from Vermont to
Minnesota, Georgia to Iowa, was bullied floods, tornadoes or
mudslides. At least 26 people died. A West Virginia mother had her
4-month-old baby swept out of her arms by a raging flood. A
Minnesota farmer died when lightning struck his pitchfork. And an
Ohio woman whose car was submerged in water managed to use her
cellular phone to call her husband in the minutes before she died.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone Want This Factory?
</P>
<P>
   The federal government wants to sell off its 40-year business of
processing uranium for civilian power reactors, but is having
trouble finding the right buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups, one including the private companies that run the
factories now, have submitted proposals, but the Treasury decided
it did not like the offers and would sell stock directly to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   In about a month, private investors will get a chance to show
their opinion of the industry's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   A Threat to Shut Puerto Rico
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of labor unions threatened to paralyze Puerto Rico
with a 48-hour work stoppage starting Tuesday. They support
striking telephone workers opposed to the sale of the
government-owned telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIREYA NAVARRO
</P>
<P>
   Republican Strategy Split
</P>
<P>
   A parade of prominent Republicans, notably the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, have stepped up their criticism
of homosexuality recently. These Republicans, apparently trying to
energize the religiously conservative base of the party, have
described  &QL; 
homosexuality as a sin.
</P>
<P>
   But the criticism has prompted some party leaders to warn that
the oratory might turn off voters and make Republicans appear
intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   A new national poll of voters conducted for the Human Rights
Campaign, a gay political organization, found that most Americans
believe homosexuality is an inherent trait, rather than a chosen
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Basketball Bargaining
</P>
<P>
   The NBA braced for its most contentious labor battle ever as the
owners of the 29 teams locked out the players and effectively
halted league-related business until a new collective bargaining
agreement can be signed.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the players' union president, accused the owners
of spending too freely, while the league's deputy commissioner,
Russ Granik, said player salaries were out of control. _ By MIKE
WISE
</P>
<P>
   CNN and Time Apologize
</P>
<P>
   In the latest in a string of embarrassments for journalism,
Cable News Network and Time magazine apologized for falsely
reporting last month that the U.S. military had used lethal nerve
gas in a secret 1970 mission in Laos meant to kill American
defectors.
</P>
<P>
   The story was broadcast during the inaugural airing of
``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time.'' Time had published a modified version in
its pages.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the Cincinnati Enquirer apologized to Chiquita
Brands over what the paper said were ``untrue'' stories based on
stolen voice mail. The paper dismissed the lead reporter and agreed
to pay Chiquita more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Boston Globe columnist resigned after admitting to
fabrications. Before that, it was disclosed that a writer at The
New Republic had made up material in dozens of articles.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer Coaches Under Fire for Lighting Up
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't send the gendarmes in,'' Keith Cooper, a Briton who
is a spokesman for soccer's world governing body, said in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   His grievance? No, it's not rough World Cup play. Or what goes
on when British fans get out of control. It's what goes on on the
sidelines: Coaches don't just fume, they smoke _ constantly, and in
full view of TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   In the victory over England, Argentina's coach, Daniel
Passarella, even ran toward the field holding a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's group worries that this sort of thing will tarnish
soccer's reputation. But they bump smack into the fact that ``no
smoking'' simply doesn't translate into most languages.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Fernand Sastre, who led the drive to bring the World
Cup to France? He recently died at 74 of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   No Longer Unknown
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years ago, President Ronald Reagan placed the remains
of an unidentified American killed in Vietnam into the Tomb of the
Unknowns at Arlington National Cemetery. But now, the Pentagon
announced, new genetic tests have made his identity known.
</P>
<P>
   The serviceman was 1st Lt. Michael Blassie, an Air Force pilot
shot down over South Vietnam in 1972, near a village called An Loc.
</P>
<P>
   There are still 2,087 Americans missing from the war, but with
science making identification of even the smallest remains
possible, it now seems unlikely that any of them will take
Blassie's place in the Tomb.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
</TEXT>
