<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV05-B     07-03 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT RECESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 05 1998)  
 (Includes ``A century of American business cycles'' text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great certainties of life at the end of the 20th
century is the flow and ebb of the business cycle. Every once in a
while, somebody proclaims that a new era has arrived, or, better
yet, that the cycle is ended. But the pattern of expansions and
contractions, recognizable in its essentials, rolls along
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   The main uncertainty: What event will trigger the next downturn?
The Asian crisis? Is it already in the works?
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Shocks: What Causes Business Cycles?'' was the subject
of a conference held by the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston last
month on Cape Cod. These regional Federal Reserve Bank meetings are
getting harder and harder to conceptualize, as conferences
proliferate and competition among host organizations heats up. No
serious researcher wants to write a paper to be tucked away in a
volume published by the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   So the regional banks must either choose high-brow topics
(e.g., &UR;  &LR; the San Francisco bank, whose 1996 conference proceedings
on ``Managing Capital Flows and Exchange Rates,'' has just been
published by Cambridge University Press); or make them very
practical (e.g., the Chicago Fed's regular May conference on bank
deregulation); or simply make them topical (e.g., the Kansas City
Fed's August junket to Jackson Hole, Wyo., where the schmoozing and
silly-season maneuvering in the press is more important than
anything that's written down).
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Cod conference last month was a model of how the Boston
bank fits into the system. With Boston's dense university network _
Harvard, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Boston University,
Northeastern University, and Boston College, plus the headquarters
of the National Bureau of Economic Research _ the city is
economics' Mecca, not to mention a world center of money
management. The bank's idea was to connect the top end of the
banking community to developments at the frontiers of economic
research, however briefly.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it was the ``real business cycle'' literature that
for a decade has pursued the possibility that economic fluctuations
stem from restructuring among production technologies instead of
traditionally identified fiscal and monetary factors.
</P>
<P>
   Thus conference-goers heard a report on a highly sophisticated
thought-experiment by Yale University's Christopher Sims designed
to gauge the ability of monetary policy to affect the course of
events. They heard, too, an historiographic essay by MIT economic
historian Peter Temin on the causes of American business cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Few newspaper readers need to worry much yet about Sims's work,
though in due course it is likely to prove invaluable in
scrutinizing the rules that central banks adopt to pursue their
policies. ``The overall conclusion might be that the aim of good
monetary policy should be to make monetary policy unimportant to
the business cycle, and that postwar US monetary policy has largely
succeeded in this respect,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Temin, in sorting though the causes ordinarily assigned to
each of the 24 recessions since 1890, produced a model of writing
about economics for the intelligent layperson that deserves a wide
circulation. He prepared the kind of table (which appears with this
column) that makes for good Sunday newspaper reading as well.
</P>
<P>
   With data produced by Christina Romer of the University of
California at Berkeley, he divided the history of the business
cycle during the last century into three periods of eight cycles
each, then proceeded to classify their causes.
</P>
<P>
   His ostensible target was the laugh-line caricature of his
colorful MIT colleague, Rudiger Dornbusch: ``None of the US
expansions of the past 40 years died in bed of old age; every one
was murdered by the Federal Reserve.'' His deeper topic was that
thorny question: How much discretion does a central banker really
have?
</P>
<P>
   Temin divided his busines cycles into four distinct types.
Either they were real shocks _ domestic ones (such as the
debt-ceiling recession of 1958, the Vietnam winddown recession of
1970), or foreign (such as the Armistice depression of 1921 and the
two oil price hikes of the 1970s). Or else they were monetary
shocks _ domestic (such as the budgetary stringency following the
payment of the second Soldier Bonus of 1937, the unanticipated
monetary tightening of 1960, the Volcker battle against inflation
in 1981) or foreign (such as the Panic of 1907 or the external gold
drain that led the Fed to tighten sharply in 1931).
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, each of the three periods exhibits its own special
characteristics: Those from 1890 until World War I tended to be
frequent and abrupt; those of the years between the wars were
unprecedented in their severity, ``contractions'' rather than
``panics.'' The business cycle of the postwar years lived up to its
reputation: gentler, less frequent events, in general deserving of
the term ``recession.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper itself dwells mainly on the four largest cycles: the
short, sharp depression following 1920, and the three phases of the
Great Depression of the 1930s. The next largest cycle occurred in
1973, when the oil-producing nations quadrupled the price of crude
oil overnight, and the Fed tightened to limit the resulting
inflation. A useful appendix contains short narratives of the 10
smallest cycles of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   Temin's punchline had to do with adding the cycles up after
enumerating them. There are about the same number of real and
monetary causes, slightly more real, he found. When he added up the
lost production (the number of months it took for production to
return to its previous peak) stemming from each, the balance was a
little less even: Real shocks, domestic and foreign, led to 25.8
months of lost production, while monetary shock of both sorts cost
the economy a total of 44 months of output. His conclusion: There
is no support at all in the literature for Dornbusch's harsh
indictment of the Fed. There are many causes of the business cycle,
not just one.
</P>
<P>
   As the economists went on debating the intricacies of
interpreting time-series data, I found my mind wandering back to
the present day. What clue did Temin's table offer those of us who
are worried mainly about the current expansion, now into its eighth
year? Suppose that the world economy entered a new and different
era starting about 1989, for example, as different from the past as
was the period beginning in 1945 from that of 1914; what might be
conjectured about the pattern the business cycle is likely to
exhibit during the next 25 years?
</P>
<P>
   The best recession, it is generally agreed, is a short and
shallow one, like the still-mysterious decline that accompanied the
Gulf War in 1991. Suppose the US economy is in for a widely spaced
series of these _ three or four relatively mild events in the next
quarter century?
</P>
<P>
   What, then, about the timing of the next event? At one point, I
doodled in 1999 on my table. Benjamin Friedman, a wiser man than me
_ he was at Morgan Stanley before he returned to Harvard as
professor of money _ looked quizzical, penciled 2001, and shrugged.
It seemed as good a guess as any, and better than most.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A CENTURY OF AMERICAN BUSINESS CYCLES
</P>
