<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 4, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flood watches were posted Friday morning for southeast Texas as
a tropical disturbance over the Gulf of Mexico came ashore.
Saturday, the moisture-laden system will douse parts of central and
south Texas with heavy rains, heightening the risk of flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms, possibly severe, will erupt from western Nebraska
to eastern Montana and Wyoming as moist air flowing from the
southeast behind a cool front stalled over the Middle West is
forced to ascend the sloping terrain. Farther east along the front,
clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop from south
Nebraska to the lower Ohio Valley as humid, warm air rises rapidly
after intercepting the front.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms, some heavy, will forge
east from the upper Ohio Valley into West Virginia and western
Pennsylvania on Saturday afternoon as a jet stream disturbance
lifts increasingly humid air arriving on southerly winds. Showers
and storms will then scale the central Appalachians and head toward
the Middle Atlantic Seaboard later this evening and tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers and thunderstorms will escort a slow-moving
cool front into western New England and western New York on
Saturday afternoon and evening. The phalanx of showers and storms
will press toward the New England Coast on Saturday night and early
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hit-or-miss showers and thunderstorms will erupt along a
sea-breeze front pressing into eastern Florida from the Atlantic.
Rains will be spotty and lightning from storms could spark
additional wildfires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Record Peak Wind &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A severe thunderstorm lashed the airport at Jacksonville, Fla.,
with a gust of 77 mph Thursday, setting an all-time record peak
wind for July. Despite Jacksonville's coastal location, hurricanes
do not figure prominently on the city's list of strongest winds.
Like a turtle withdrawing into its shell for protection, the
coastline near Jacksonville bows as far west as any point on the
entire East Coast. Indeed, Jacksonville lies farther west than
Pittsburgh, Pa. Thus, most northward-curving hurricanes either hit
south Florida or pass safely to the east over the ocean.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
