<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO FOLLOW YOUR DREAM _ AND STILL EAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday being Independence Day, imagine being free to follow
your heart's desire when it comes to a career.
</P>
<P>
   Each of us has tucked away a mental picture of the work we'd
really like to do _ if only we didn't feel obligated to bring home
a certain salary.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in fact, a whole cottage industry of books, tapes and
seminars on finding your true calling.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you already know what your true calling is, you just
don't know how to make enough money to live while doing it? How do
you ``follow your bliss'' and still eat?
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Jacobson can tell you. A New York-based singer, writer,
Cantorial student and mother, she is also a self-taught expert at
the art of the ``survival job.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jacobson, 31, has parlayed her experiences into a guide
called, ``Survival Jobs; 154 ways to make money while pursuing your
dreams.'' (Broadway Books, 1998, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always looking for something more interesting,
high-paying and flexible than waiting tables,'' she said, of her
days as a starving artist. During one period, she was so broke
she'd walk 40 or 50 blocks to save subway fare.
</P>
<P>
   By her count, Jacobson has already worked at about 27 part-time,
flexible jobs while pursuing her creative interests.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she talked to dozens of other artists, actors, and
creative types to gather other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a book that includes jobs from seasonal accounting
to secret shopping that are flexible, and even fun. But most
importantly, they leave you time to do your ``real work.'' The key
is to find jobs that match your personality and your needs using
skills you've already got, or can get quickly, she said. If you
need your days free for auditions, or you do your best writing in
the morning, then look for jobs you can do in the evenings. Some
jobs with maximum scheduling flexibility include limousine driver,
airport employee, real estate appraiser, concierge, or focus group
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   If you're trying to break into show biz and want to network, try
being a script reader, casting session camera operator, location
manager, cruise ship performer, box office manager, or personal
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   There are jobs for all personality types. If you're not shy, you
could be an audience recruiter, city tour guide, food demonstrator,
makeup artist, or _ for the truly uninhibited _ an artist's model.
If you'd rather be your own boss, try managing apartments, becoming
a massage therapist, operating a mail-order business, or doing
event-planning.
</P>
<P>
   The guide tells people how to break in, how much they can expect
to earn, and the pros and cons of each job.
</P>
<P>
   Take catering, for example. The benefits of working for a
caterer are a decent salary (up to $18 an hour) and the chance to
see varied locations, and meet interesting people. The food is
good, too. Hours are flexible, usually nights and weekends.
Drawbacks are the physical demands, and unsteady nature of the
work. To break in you usually need restaurant or food experience,
and a tuxedo uniform.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not your cup of tea, you could try open-house sitting
for Realtors. Sitters hand out information about the property to
visitors. The pay is $8 to $10 an hour. Hours are usually weekends.
Benefits _ you can catch up on your reading or correspondence
during slow times. Contact real estate companies to get started.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Jacobson did time as a karaoke performer for
corporate parties and even a stint as a matchmaker's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a glorified telemarketer,'' she said. ``I had to ask
people all kinds of personal questions and get them to sign up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those interviews, however, that gave her the idea
for one of her favorite survival jobs _ walking dogs for other
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can easily make $500 per week, part-time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson's experiences led her to self-publish a book and lead
seminars, (survival job no. 96) on making money for actors. Her
self-published venture ended up as a Book of the Month Club
selection, and eventually landed her a publisher (Survival job no.
136 _ freelance writer.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, when she talks about survival jobs, it's not just to
starving artists. There are all kinds of people who want more
flexible work arrangements, she said. Students, new parents, and
retirees are all looking for ways to make money without
compromising their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Many people start a survival job, and discover they love it
enough to do it full-time, she said. Others work several survival
jobs at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of freedom from having your income from more
than one source,'' she said. ``Never give up on your dreams. There
are so many fun, creative, interesting ways to make money, there's
no reason to work at a job you despise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
