<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S HOT ON THE STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 5) 
(JT) 
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Sandal Chase
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a mad scramble,'' said Ellen Tien, a writer in
Manhattan, who is the envy of her friends for snaring not one, but
two pairs of Hermes' most sought-after sandal _ the Quebrar. The
wooden-heel sandal, a luxury take on the classic Dr. Scholl's, came
out this season in black, gold, maroon and natural for $195 at
Hermes boutiques. By now, they're virtually sold out. But hopeful
shoppers still drop by the store at 57th Street (Fifth Avenue) to
scoop up a returned pair or dial Hermes shops from California to
Paris. Ellen Niven, Hermes' publicity director, suggests calling
the Hermes help line, (800) 441-4488, to track down Quebrars ``in
whatever corner of the world they're left,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For a Snip and a Snack
</P>
<P>
   ``One part salon, one part cafe, one part cocktail lounge.''
That's the official description of Tonic, a mixture of unisex hair
salon and cafe, which opened six months ago at 107 Norfolk St.,
between Delancey and Rivington Streets. It is the latest consumer
space turned into a place to hang out, like gym restaurants and
bookstore-coffee bars. John Sarefield, an owner of Tonic, explained
the logic of making a salon the first and last destination of an
evening. ``You go to a salon or a cafe to gossip,'' he said. ``You
go to a salon to look good, then to a cafe to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   A glass wall separates the sipping from the snipping. Haircuts
are $55, and a lunch of a turkey Reuben sandwich and chips is $5.
Besides Indian-style tea spiked with St. John's wort, the cafe also
offers movies on Mondays, comedy on Tuesdays and music Wednesdays
through Fridays. There are weekly swing-dance lessons, tarot and
numerology readings, massages and book groups.
</P>
<P>
   The patrons include locals, who showed up one recent movie night
in anything from Rollerblades to suede clam diggers, and uptowners
drawn by this summer's sold-out jazz series. Nor is Tonic alone.
White, a salon in Miami Beach has a sidewalk cafe, and so does the
Burke Williams Salon in Los Angeles. Tonic's hair-salon is open
Wednesday through Friday, 11 a.m. to 9 p.m.; weekends, 10 a.m. to 6
p.m. Appointments: (212) 358-7501.
</P>
<P>
   Online Shop With Attitude
</P>
<P>
   For those times when a style-minded young woman has nothing to
wear and no time to trek to the stores, Laura Eisman created
Girlshop, a new Web site with nine online ``boutiques''
(www.girlshop.com). Ms. Eisman offers only her favorites: Pixie
Yates, Amy Chan Handbags, Selima Optique, Ellen for Le Corset
Lingerie, Tony &AMP; Tina nail polish and other designers who appeal to
``stylish urban girls ages 18 to 35,'' she said. ``It's like making
a trip to SoHo without leaving your office.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike more staid online shopping sites, Girlshop projects a
sassy charm with clothing descriptions like ``cleavage city for
anyone with a generous bra size'' for a strapless dress by Jussara
Lee. The site's logo shows a bemused shopper wearing only blue
underwear, floral shoes and a red purse. For fashion emergencies,
there is same-day delivery service in Manhattan. A ``Show a
Friend'' feature allows browsers to e-mail an image of a possible
purchase for a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Online sample sales are in the works, and by the end of summer,
a registry will be available to inform loved ones of good ideas for
gifts, along with a search feature, which will scan boutiques
looking for, say, the perfect black bootleg pants.
</P>
<P>
   The Message Is the Logo
</P>
<P>
   Stylish urbanites are turning toward Mecca. Mecca, U.S.A., that
is, a line of T-shirts, jeans and other sportswear that is winning
over young logo lovers once faithful to Tommy Hilfiger and Polo.
</P>
<P>
   Emmett Harrell, 26, head designer of Mecca, said the brand name
is not a religious statement. ``We look at Mecca as a state of
mind,'' he said. ``Our customers like to affiliate themselves with
status. You get tired of seeing Polo and Tommy. We filled that
void.'' Mecca, started in 1995, has been followed by other
urban-inspired lines like FUBU (For Us, By Us) and Enyce. Mecca
began by selling hip-hop clothes in Brooklyn and Harlem and spread
from there. ``They're worn by snowboarders and surfers,'' said Ting
Mintz, a fashion commentator on ``Inside Design,'' a cable
television show. Harrell said Mecca is also popular in London and
Japan. T-shirts sell in New York for $22 to $28 at Foot Locker,
Champs, Dr. J's, Jimmy Jazz, and Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   A Peep Into the Pi Perplex
</P>
<P>
   Why pi? New Yorkers may be forgiven if they're perplexed to see
that the mathematical symbol used for calculating the area of a
circle has been stamped on sidewalks all over the city. The
graffiti are the work of Darren Aronofsky, a filmmaker, who has
found an unusual way to promote ``Pi: the Movie,'' his thriller,
which opens July 12. The film, about a mathematician who unlocks
the secret of the stock market, is only one piece of an unlikely pi
trend. ``The Joy of Pi,'' a book by David Blatner (Walker &AMP; Co.,
1997) includes a history of attempts to calculate the infinite
number (3.14159265 etc.), pi jokes and odd factoids. For instance,
Spock of ``Star Trek'' once foiled an evil computer by ordering it
to ``compute to the last digit the value of pi.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to smell like the president of the math club,
Parfums Givenchy is releasing Pi, a men's fragrance, in the United
States in the fall. The French perfumer describes it as ``a salute
to the sex appeal of intelligence.'' Still baffled by the pi craze?
``People are looking for keys to uncover the secrets of life,''
Aronofsky offered. ``Pi is being rediscovered as a way to look at
the universe and find possible answers to the eternal questions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
