<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-IAI-BALANCED-     07-03 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-IAI-BALANCED-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESS THAN MEETS THE EYE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., Conn., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Graphic showing net asset value for IAI Valaue and
balanced fund will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second quarter was pretty rocky for equity managers, but not
for Investment Advisers Inc. of Minneapolis and two of its
previously obscure and undistinguished mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   From out of nowhere, the IAI Balanced fund gained 10.8 percent,
making it the seventh-best performer in the quarter of all stock
funds listed in the tables in The New York Times and the best
domestic hybrid fund over all. A sister fund, IAI Value, which is
too to be listed, did even better, rising 24.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, numbers like those would prompt a fund manager to
crow. Yet the managers in Minneapolis have refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons for their silence, the sudden spurt in the
fortunes of IAI, which is owned by Lloyd's TSB Group PLC, should
serve to remind investors of a mutual fund truism: numbers alone
rarely tell the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of these funds, the sharp rise seems to stem largely
_ and perhaps almost entirely for the Value fund _ from investments
in a tiny, money-losing telecommunications company, Pathnet Inc.,
which filed a proposal in early May with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to offer shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   That filing holds great potential for shareholders of the IAI
funds, but also a great deal of peril.
</P>
<P>
   When IAI managers recalculated the worth of their Pathnet
holdings to reflect the possibility of the initial public offering,
IAI Value's net asset value ballooned by 28 percent (italics)in a
single day.(end italics) IAI Balanced rose by 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But putting a value on stock not issued is problematic and the
estimate used by the fund managers could be way off. Moreover, the
stock offering may not occur at all. And if it does, the terms of
the funds' investments restrict managers' ability to quickly sell
their stakes and thus their chances to capitalize on any early
bounce in the stock's price.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as of early May, Pathnet securities represented 26
percent of the Value fund's holdings, an extraordinarily high
percentage for one security, let alone an illiquid one.
</P>
<P>
   The IAI managers seem to understand the delicacy of their
situation. Value fund shareholders were told of the increased
valuation of the Pathnet holdings in a May 12 supplement to their
prospectus that was crammed with caveats. They were also told that
the Value fund was closed to new investors. The Balanced fund,
which has a much smaller holding in Pathnet, remains open.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Pathnet filing, Value had generally underperformed its
peer group of small-cap value funds since its inception in 1983.
Balanced had more or less tracked its peers over its life.
</P>
<P>
   The Value fund, which invests primarily in equities that its
managers see as undervalued, had about $27 million in assets at the
end of March. The Balanced fund, which has a diversified portfolio
of stocks, bonds and short-term money instruments, had just over
$32 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The funds' share prices shot up in early May, after Pathnet's
proposal to offer to the public as much as $100 million worth of
stock in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Although no target prices were mentioned in the filing, board
members at both funds felt compelled to restate the value of their
Pathnet holdings, although they have not disclosed specific
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Pathnet is not the only closely held security in the Value
fund's portfolio. As of May 11, the fund said, just over 36 percent
of its assets were nonpublic securities, and thus illiquid.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's managers went to great lengths detailing just how
risky the position in Pathnet is. The supplement listed 15 risk
factors, including the possibility that the public offering, to be
managed by Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Bear,
Stearns, might not happen.
</P>
<P>
   All of these points raise questions. Investors might find it
useful to know, for example, how the IAI managers got interested in
Pathnet in the first place, not to mention the other illiquid
securities in the Value fund's portfolio. (Pathnet is the only such
holding in the Balanced fund.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The managers of the funds, however, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   IAI is no stranger to venture capital investing. The company has
been raising money for such investments for 15 years, including
about $200 million for private venture funds, and it has placed
another $74 million of venture capital in some of its 15 mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   R. David Spreng, who heads the venture capital operations at
IAI, manages the private equity investments in the Value and
Balanced funds. He also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing with the SEC, Pathnet identifies IAI as having
been a stockholder from the moment of its birth as a company, in
August 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Investors might also wonder why a public fund is investing in
private placements. The IAI funds are hardly the first to do so.
``I can think of a number of funds, like Third Avenue Value, Equus
2 and Warburg Pincus Post Venture Capital, that have 5 to 10
percent of their assets in venture capital investments,'' said
Russel J. Kinnel, equity editor of Morningstar Mutual Funds. But
such funds have had uneven track records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they work out well; sometimes they don't,'' said A.
Michael Lipper, president of Lipper Analytical Services. ``The key
is to know your fund and to see if it has a history of successfully
investing in these sorts of products. If it does, then you could
perhaps say there is a repeatable skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what happens to the two IAI funds, and to IAI Value in
particular, will depend on how effectively the funds' boards have
valued the Pathnet securities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prospectus supplement, the Value fund said it
used a ``fair value'' methodology to assess its holdings in Pathnet
and other illiquid securities. A spokeswoman declined to provide
further details.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Killian, a portfolio manager at Renaissance Capital in
Greenwich, Conn., said fund boards are under no obligation to
disclose their valuation techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fair value is the amount the fund might reasonably expect to
realize upon its current sale,'' she said. ``There is no single
standard'' for determining that value, she added. In other words,
it may be a shot in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that investors who choose to hold onto their IAI
funds will be left sitting with the current, sharply higher
valuation for some time. Yet there is little prospect that the
funds will be able to cash out in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The Value fund prospectus notes ``substantial
restrictions'' regarding its sale of Pathnet stock. The offering
underwriters ``have the ability to request that the fund not sell
or otherwise transfer stock during the 180-day period following the
effective date of the IPO,'' the supplement said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnel of Morningstar, said, ``It is quite unusual for a fund to
have this amount of its assets tied up for this long a period.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the IAI funds turn out to be more than one-quarter wonders?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the boards' minutes show this was a thoughtful pricing
decision, and that they had ample evidence to back it up,'' Lipper
said. ``If they don't, they could be wide open to potential
lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   This much is sure. Investors in IAI Value, who in early May held
a diversified portfolio, now have a quarter of their money tied up
in what appears to be a speculative initial public offering, one
that may be effectively tethered to the fund for the near term.
There is nothing wrong with that, of course, as long as the
investors are aware of the risks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
