<SLUG> BC-ROCK-DIFRANCO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANI DIFRANCO REMAINS FULL OF SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ani DiFranco won't admit to any hidden messages in her new
album, ``Little Plastic Castle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not really the way I write or think,'' DiFranco says.
``In my songs, I'm really just chronicling my experiences and
perceptions as I stumble through the world. Each album is like a
year in the life of Ani DiFranco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any message, it's about questioning everything in
the world and coming up with your own answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover of DiFranco's new CD depicts three goldfish, one
bearing the smiling face of DiFranco, swimming around a tiny
plastic castle in a fish bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say goldfish have no memory,'' DiFranco sings. ``I guess
their lives are much like mine/ And the little plastic castle/ Is a
surprise every time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Plastic Castle'' is the 12th album DiFranco has
released on Righteous Babe Records, the tiny label she founded at
age 20 in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   DiFranco's grass-roots feminism and her powerful, poetic blend
of folk and rock have brought her an ever-widening audience.
Collectively, her albums have sold more than 800,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Her self-made career could be a model for the giant recording
labels she has spurned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen-year-old girls are basically what made the Beatles,''
DiFranco said. ``The people who market music have strayed from that
demographic for a long time, but now they're getting back to it.
They're realizing what a market force it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the 13-year-old girls of today are a lot different than
they were in the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   DiFranco's last album, ``Living in Clip,'' was a stunning
collection of live recordings. If ``Living in Clip'' taught her
anything, it was that her studio albums lacked the dynamic punch of
live concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of putting together the live album was very
enlightening,'' DiFranco said by phone from a tour stop in
Pennsylvania. ``After listening to a whole lot of really
rough-and-ready live tapes, I realized that my songs sound much
better on stage than they do on albums.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Little Plastic Castle,'' DiFranco also invited more
collaboration with guest musicians. Among them was trumpeter and
avantgarde composer Jon Hassell, who has worked with the Talking
Heads, Brian Eno and k.d. lang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge fan, so I called him and said, `Hi, it's little
Miss What's-her-face. Wanna play on my record?' ''
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise, Hassell said yes. In the studio, DiFranco let
the tape run for a half hour while she and Hassell performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about a 30-minute jam that went down, during which I
spoke the words to a poem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Pulse,'' the album's 14-minute closing track.
</P>
<P>
   Other collaborators on ``Little Plastic Castle'' included
bassist Sara Lee and drummer Jerry Marotta of the Indigo Girls'
band, as well as bassist Jason Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer is backing DiFranco on her current tour, along with
drummer Andy Stochansky and organist and accordionist Julie Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   While DiFranco is on the road, a dedicated staff keeps Righteous
Babe Records running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army back in Buffalo has really grown in ranks the last
couple of years,'' DiFranco said. ``There really are a lot of cool,
talented people there that kind of make it happen. (Fans) don't
realize what goes down at that place, just to keep a teeny little
record label running.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
