<SLUG> BC-FOGERTY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN FOGERTY: COUNTERCULTURE ROCKER RECLAIMS HIS HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANN POWERS   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Northern California has a river delta, but it's
nothing like the one depicted in the stage set John Fogerty used
here at Radio City Music Hall on Thursday night. As evocative of
humidity as the Sacramento River delta near Fogerty's hometown, El
Cerrito, replete with friendly-looking alligators, tin shacks and a
devilish moon, the scene was also unabashedly fake.
</P>
<P>
   It served as a tacit acknowledgment that the mythic Southern
narrative Fogerty has explored since the late 1960s, the riverboat
dream of ``Proud Mary'' and the voodoo hallucination of ``Born on
the Bayou,'' was a tall tale from beginning to end.
</P>
<P>
   This admission hardly diminished Fogerty's commitment to that
landscape, which he is celebrating with a new live album and a tour
dominated by classic songs from his years leading Creedence
Clearwater Revival. As the counterculture's most avid roots rocker,
Fogerty understood that the blues-based language of the crossroads
was mobile enough to penetrate the consciousness of any American.
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty made blues-based rock his own by matching
bluegrass-inspired speed with juke joint languor, taking both up a
notch with a young rocker's passion. He excavated the Southern
themes that connected to his own life in a working-class community
and the alienation that led to the tumult of the 1960s. A song like
``Green River,'' one of many he performed from the Creedence era,
is typically universal: Fogerty may have been imagining Louisiana
when he wrote its riff, reminiscent of the 12-bar blues, and its
lyric about dank magical waters, but he touched on the menacing
mysteries at the edge of every town where the privileged and the
dispossessed uneasily reside.
</P>
<P>
   The menace in Fogerty's writing enriches it, but in concert he
emphasized its brighter tones. Partly, he was toasting himself.
After many years during which legal conflicts over ownership and
personal bitterness caused him to ignore his greatest songs, he has
reclaimed them.
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty's awareness of his own talents as a songwriter and
guitarist was obvious; his band stayed almost entirely in the
background as he took extended solos on nearly every song,
strutting around the stage and unleashing killer leads that
recalled another resilient counterculture hero, Neil Young.
</P>
<P>
   Often his act grew too heavy, for example, when he mugged and
gestured, pretending to take requests, or led fans through a
sing-along on ``Those Old Cotton Fields Back Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty could use some onstage time in the foggier corners of
the bog, since that's where myths grow richest. Yet the crowd of
New Yorkers who cheered his corny comments didn't miss the shadows.
They were just happy to be transported back to the swamps of
Fogerty's, and their own, invention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0171 </DOCNO>
