<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9819 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-CLOSED-END-AR     07-03 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-CLOSED-END-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWS OR VALUE IN CLOSED-END FUNDS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Graphic showing four top closed end funds' stock prices
and Net asset value will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By RICK GLADSTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With closed-end funds developing a reputation as a dysfunctional
branch of the fund family tree, shareholder activists have grown
restive. That's fine with some analysts, who feel that helps make
many such funds look like bargains as of late.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their mutual fund cousins, which continually offer new
shares for sale, closed-end funds issue a fixed number of shares
that trade in the same way as the stocks of ordinary companies.
</P>
<P>
   For many reasons _ high management fees, tax liabilities, lack
of marketing or just generally poor performance _ the market value
of closed-end fund shares is often less than the net asset value, a
gap known as the discount.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, even as the stock market has advanced, that
discount has stubbornly remained or widened at many equity funds,
goading activist shareholders to rebel with lawsuits and proxy
fights seeking to evict managers. Closed-end funds that invest
abroad, particularly in economically ravaged Asia, have suffered
steep losses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is precisely because of these problems that the $150
billion closed-end fund industry appears to offer interesting
opportunities for investors. In the view of some market
strategists, the industry's problems have left the shares
underpriced.
</P>
<P>
   Following are four closed-end fund situations _ and selected
funds _ in which industry experts say investors may find bargains: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like many other funds with the words ``emerging markets'' in
their names, the Emerging Markets Infrastructure fund was hurt in
the latest round of Asian economic problems and is trading near its
52-week low, at a discount of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the slide is based more on perception than reality. The fund
has little money in Asia, but has more in Eastern Europe, the
Middle East and particularly Latin America, with heavy emphasis on
Brazil, where privatization of telecommunications and energy
companies is expected to reward investors.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's chief investment officer, Richard Watt, is credited
with minimizing its Asian exposure _ the fund has more money in
Israel than in Taiwan, its biggest Asian holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he has managed to steer clear of the downdraft,
with the exception of the contagion effect,'' said Doug Beck,
senior global equity funds analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Porter, a senior analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said
the discount, combined with increased potential for growth in
places where the fund has invested, meant that ``there's almost a
double discount.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In April, the board of the Mentor Income fund cut the monthly
dividend for the first time in 36 months to reflect declines in
seven-year Treasury bonds. The cut, to 6 cents from 7 cents a
share, alarmed investors who had bought the fund because of its
concentration in high-quality debt securities and its objective of
producing high monthly income.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders reacted by selling aggressively. As a result,
Mentor's discount increased to more than 14 percent. Thomas
Herzfeld, chairman and president of a Miami investment firm that
specializes in closed-end funds, said he expects the discount to
narrow to 5 percent as investors conclude that the selloff was
unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we had here was very typical behavior when a dividend is
cut,'' he said. ``Investors immediately sell shares, thinking
something's wrong, and they generally wind up selling them too
cheap.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year-old Dessauer Global Equity fund, founded by John
Dessauer, a fund commentator, offers a unique provision, known as a
``hard trigger,'' aimed at eliminating any discount. The fund will
automatically convert to a mutual fund if, starting in December,
the shares trade at a discount of at least 5 percent on the last
business day of any week and for each of the next 14 business days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is that the fund's share price cannot linger
at a deep discount for long,'' Dessauer, who is also co-manager of
the fund, wrote in the annual report.
</P>
<P>
   The discount was recently as wide as 8.1 percent, which may
prompt investors to buy in, knowing that it is guaranteed to go to
zero. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes the Herzfeld Caribbean Basin fund, run by
Herzfeld, is that it invests entirely in companies likely to
benefit from economic advances in the Caribbean, particularly if
relations between Cuba and the United States are normalized.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's biggest investment is Florida East Coast Industries,
which has risen 20 percent this year. The company operates a
railway that, after normalization, would virtually monopolize
shipments of Cuba-bound American goods to Florida ports.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is highly sensitive to news events. Last March, for
example, when President Clinton eased some provisions of the
35-year-old ban on commerce and financial aid to Cuba, the shares
shot up, going from a 10 percent discount to a 13 percent premium.
</P>
<P>
   The shares have since weakened to a 6.8 percent discount. But
Herzfeld said he was confident that the shares would go to a
premium again.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested that Herzfeld might be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund invests in a way that no other fund invests and that
no index can possibly measure,'' said Gregg Wolper, the closed-end
fund editor at Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in
Chicago. ``But it hasn't done a bad job of stock-picking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
