<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-FORBES-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIRMAN SEEKS TO END UNCERTAINTY OVER CENDANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the time Cendant Corp. announced in mid-April that it had
uncovered accounting irregularities that would reduce 1997 earnings
by as much as $115 million, Walter Forbes, Cendant's chairman, has
kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   And because Forbes' former company, CUC International, which was
merged with HFS Inc. to form Cendant, was responsible for the
problems, investors have been questioning whether Forbes will take
over as chief executive in the year 2000. That is when he is
supposed to switch jobs with Henry Silverman, the chief executive
of Cendant and former chairman of HFS. The unusual agreement was
part of the merger of the two companies in December.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes said in an interview this week that speculation about
changes in Cendant's management succession was needlessly weighing
down the stock, which has recovered little since it dropped in
mid-April by 46 percent in one day, wiping out about $14.4 billion
in value. On Thursday, the shares closed at $21.5625, well below
their closing 52-week high of $41.375 in early April, shortly
before the announcement of the accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, questions remain about the accounting irregularities,
and they are expected to be answered by an audit report to be
completed this summer that will determine exactly how much the
company's 1997 earnings will be reduced. But Forbes said there
should be no question about his role in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong to assume that I'm going anywhere, and I intend to
be CEO,'' said Forbes, a soft-spoken executive, who added that he
had maintained his low profile because that has always been his
style. ``I will be out talking more now.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people will be listening. Some Cendant shareholders have
said they are uncertain who will be running the company in two
years. David Brady, a senior portfolio manager at Stein Roe &AMP;
Farnham, an investment firm that owns 5.5 million Cendant shares,
said that at a meeting with institutional shareholders in Chicago
in late May, Cendant managers said Forbes had indicated that he
might not be interested in the chief-executive job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, there is a lot of ambiguity as to who is going to
run the company in the year 2000, and I think that is true with
many institutional investors,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Cendant, James Fingeroth, said the company
``could not account for why institutional investors may have
received that impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he had never suggested that he might not want the
chief executive job. To deprive him of the job, 80 percent of
Cendant's 28 directors _ 14 each from CUC and HFS _ would have to
vote to dismiss him. In that event, Forbes would be entitled to a
severance package that includes a lump-sum payment of $25 million
in cash, as well as a $10 million cash retirement benefit. Forbes,
however, said that he had the support of all the former CUC
directors on the Cendant board.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Silverman said the board ``has taken
zero action on any issues of governance or succession pending the
report of the audit committee,'' which is due this summer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Opinion varies among Cendant investors about whether Forbes
should become chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sit, a vice president at Sit Investment Associates in
Minneapolis, which owns 1.3 million Cendant shares, said there
should be no change in the current succession plan, although he,
like many others, said he was awaiting results of the audit to
learn the exact nature and extent of the accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott Vergin, a portfolio manager for the Lutheran
Brotherhood, which owns 1 million Cendant shares, said he would be
skeptical about the company's prospects if Forbes were to take over
as chief executive as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to believe that he's going to come back and
run the company after this,'' Vergin said, referring to reports of
the accounting problems. ``It was his company, and he should have
known about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said last week that he did not know about the accounting
problems, which involved the way certain parts of Cendant's
business, formerly run by CUC, booked revenues and expenses. He
added that Cendant was not the first company to restate earnings,
and that such problems were difficult if not impossible to spot
from his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody who really thinks about it would expect
anybody at my level to know about it,'' Forbes said. ``I'm not an
accountant.''
</P>
<P>
   Cendant dismissed Cosmo Corigliano, a Cendant executive vice
president and former chief financial officer of CUC, shortly before
the accounting problems were announced. The company also announced
in April that two other top former CUC executives would resign from
Cendant: Kirk Shelton, one of the company's six vice chairmen, and
Amy Lipton, executive vice president and deputy general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he and Silverman continued to have a productive
business relationship. They decided to switch jobs in the year
2000, rather than follow the practice at other merged companies,
where co-chief executives are appointed, because ``we just felt
that co-anything is difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes added that at the time of the merger he expected to stay
with the company for five years, during which an internal candidate
would likely emerge as a logical successor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
