<HEADER>
A9827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-03 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS, IVANISEVIC BATTLE THEIR WAY TO SEMIFINAL VICTORIES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ They did it differently, but both had to do
it the hard way when it came time to fight their way into the
Wimbledon finale, a showplace where Pete Sampras and Goran
Ivanisevic last sent and stared daggers at each other back in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras buckled down and broke the host nation's heart by
ruining its dream of sending a homegrown gladiator on to ultimate
glory at Wimbledon. With his emotional 6-3, 4-6, 7-5, 6-3 semifinal
defeat of Tim Henman, Sampras, already the custodian of four
Wimbledon trophies, is now one victory from equaling Bjorn Borg's
record five titles here, as well as tying Borg and Rod Laver's
overall collection of 11 slam crowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was playing Tim and the crowd, so obviously I
was going to show a little emotion,'' said Sampras, who hurled a
racquet into the stands after a Henman serve caused it to crumple
in the second game of the third set and later let go with a war
whoop after breaking Henman to claim that pivotal third set in its
12th game.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras' friendly battle with Henman, who failed in his
attempt to become Britain's first male finalist in 60 years but did
manage to steal the first set of the tournament from the defending
champion, was a minor epic compared to the three-hour, 22- minute
war with Richard Krajicek that sent Ivanisevic into his first slam
final in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, not known for his staying power in long matches,
refused to wilt and wound up breaking the spirit of Wimbledon's
1996 champion in a five-set potboiler that didn't end until the
Croat forced his victim to net a backhand volley on match point of
the final set's 28th game. Weary but wired after testing his
survival skills in a 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 6-7(5-7), 15-13 semifinal, the
esoteric Ivanisevic, who talks to God when net cords fall in his
favor, is now one victory away from capturing his first slam
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to play in the finals, I've been there, and I know
I just have to keep up with him, keep up and not let my mind go,''
said Ivanisevic, who insists he's armed himself mentally, with an
infusion of self-control, and physically, with the usual arsenal of
aces, to invalidate his reputation as the most talented player
never to collect a slam.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras leads his rivalry with Ivanisevic by a 10-6 margin and
hasn't lost to the Croat on a grass court since the 1992 Wimbledon
semifinal.In their straight set 1994 Wimbledon final and again in
the 1995 semifinals, Sampras had the last word.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't daunt the 26-year-old Croat: ``I want to play
Pete in the final,'' he said. ``He's going for the record, I'm
going for my first one, so he wants to win as badly as me. And I
think he's going to be nervous like me.'' But after his two-hour,
24-minute demolition of the 23-year-old Henman, Sampras isn't
likely to be as tired as the Croat.
</P>
<P>
   Friday it took Ivanisevic 28 aces, 120 successful sprints to the
net, three match points, and a 5-for-6 conversion rate on his break
chances to finally foil Krajicek, whose revival from the cusp of
extinction in the 4th set, where the Croat blew two match points on
his own serve, produced a 5th set that was, in Ivanisevic's
opinion, ``a horror thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic was serving for the match at 5-4, 40-15 of the 4th
set when, after having an apparent ace recalled as a let cord, he
glared up at the sky and stuck out his tongue and briefly lost his
tunnel vision. Krajicek saved the first match point with a slashing
backhand volley, and Ivanisevic undermined himself on the second
with a doublefault and went on to lose the game and the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Goran; the only thing that's predictable about him is
that he's unpredictable,'' said Krajicek, who was already on his
way to the net to shake Ivanisevic's hand when the unofficial ace
at match point was downgraded to a let cord.
</P>
<P>
   Once the 9th-seeded and sore-kneed Krajicek, who came into this
semifinal complaining that he ``wasn't a Marine'' but started to
play like one in the tie breaker, won the fourth set with a crisp
forehand volley, he found himself back on level ground in the match
for the first time since it started. And then, when he broke
Ivanisevic to take a 3-2 fifth set lead, he found himself in front
after two hours, 22 minutes of scrambling. But Krajicek's supremacy
was shortlived: four points later, Ivanisevic had broken the
Dutchman and knotted matters at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the final set, where Ivanisevic had the edge by serving first
but made life rough for himself with seven doublefaults, it was
Krajicek who encountered smoother sailing during his service games:
23 of his 42 aces were delivered there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke me, I broke him, and since then I never saw somebody
serving like that in my life,'' said Ivanisevic, who set a
Wimbledon record last year with 46 aces in the second round. ``I
mean, it was just `Boom!' and I couldn't even react; even when I
picked the right side, I couldn't reach it. And I just said to
myself, `he has to miss a couple of first serves' and that's what
happened at 14-13.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final game, Ivanisevic crackled out a down-the-line
backhand pass to gain his third match point, and Krajicek, who
appeared discouraged about his ability to sneak out of a crisis at
15-40, netted a backhand volley and shook the Croat's hand for
real. Unlike Sampras, who tactfully refrained from joyful racquet
tosses and the like after downing the poker-faced Henman, the
exhausted yet exhilarated Ivanisevic hoisted his racquet, his
towels, and everything else that was within reach into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to hang in there mentally, and that's maybe the
difference between Goran this year and a couple years ago,'' said
Sampras, who sensed his own match with Henman was virtually over
once he took a two sets to one lead. ``When I won the third set, I
knew I had him,'' said Sampras, who broke Henman for the set with a
full-blown backhand pass that forced a netted backhand volley.
After building up an untroubled 5-3 lead in the final set, Sampras
used a 134 mph ace, his 16th of the match, to pound his point home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the finals, so my form has to be pretty good,'' said
the four-time champion, who complimented Henman as a future
Wimbledon champion. ``He'll eventually win this tournament one
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But not this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
