A9829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-550&AMP;ADD-NY     07-03 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOKYO TALKS OF TAX CUTS, BUT VAGUELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto suggested Friday that
Japan might adopt permanent tax cuts in an effort to revive the
economy and calm the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto's suggestion, coming one day after Japan announced a
plan to cleanse onerous debts from its banking system, would
delight many investors. It would also please the U.S. government,
which has urged permanent tax cuts and other far-reaching measures
to strengthen the Japanese economy and reduce the risk that the
recession here will spread around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   But Hashimoto's comment was vague, and on Wednesday, Kanezo
Muraoka, chief Cabinet secretary, temporarily chilled expectations
of a tax cut by saying that it would be discussed only after
parliamentary elections on July 12. Many foreign officials have
also learned to be wary, believing that Hashimoto sometimes is in a
position to promise more economic measures than he can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that tax-system reform will be implemented on a
permanent basis, rather than in the form of a temporary tax cut,''
Hashimoto told a news conference in Kumamoto, where he was
campaigning for July 12 elections in southwestern Japan. ``I
believe this will materialize.''
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto said in April that the government would carry out a
one-time income tax cut of about $15 billion, atop a similar tax
cut earlier this year and another one effective in a couple of
months. On Friday, however, Hashimoto made no mention of the size
of the possible new tax cut, or whether the government would simply
turn the current temporary cuts into permanent ones. Some
economists are also skeptical that any tax cuts will be permanent,
because they say the government will be forced to raise taxes in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hashimoto's comments lifted the benchmark Nikkei
225 stock-market index, which was down at the opening by 160
points, the morning after the government disclosed a blueprint to
tackle the nation's bad debt problem. The index closed Friday at
16,511.24, up 39.66 points, or 0.24 percent, from Thursday's close.
Other Asian markets finished lower, but the turnaround in Japan
helped European stock markets rally. U.S. markets were closed in
observance of Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   The yen zigzagged, rising to 138.20 yen against the dollar after
Hashimoto's remarks. The yen had weakened to 141.03 at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's stock market has risen for eight straight days, partly
in anticipation of a tax cut and hopes that the government's
blueprint, called the Total Plan, will clean up the bad loan mess
in much the same way that the United States solved the crisis in
the savings and loan industry in the 1980s. Indeed, the plan
resembles the mechanism established by Resolution Trust Corp. in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   But doubts began to arise Friday about exactly how much the
program will accomplish. Japanese newspapers expressed concern that
the bridge bank system, the centerpiece of the Total Plan, may not
apply to large banks at the heart of Japan's financial system.
Instead, the plan, which envisions the creation of government-run
banks that would temporarily take over the business of failed banks
to help prevent chaos in the system, may be used only in regional
areas, for medium-sized or small financial institutions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mainichi Shimbun, a major daily newspaper, said in an analysis
Friday that it was not so clear if there would be series of bank
failures. It said that a bridge bank might only be used in the
failures at the regional level, with assets of several tens of
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the United States, bridge banks were never applied to
major bank failures,'' it said. It added that one reason was that
it would be extremely hard to find a buyer for a financial
institution with assets of several hundred billion dollars in a
short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Finance Ministry officials Friday reaffirmed the
government's policy of ``too big to fail,'' which is essentially an
assurance that it will not let large institutions go under. The
government has bad memories of the collapse last November of
Hokkaido Takushoku Bank, an event that provoked a sudden shortage
of money in the nation's banking system and fanned fears of a
financial meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge bank system would work in two stages. The government
would first appoint special administrators to run a failed
institution and to support healthy borrowers of the failed bank
while it searched for a merger partner. If that did not work, then
the collapsed bank's business would be taken over by a bridge bank
created with public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said Friday that in theory the plan could
certainly be applied to any institution, but that in practice it
was more likely to be used in the failures of regional
institutions. Analysts also echoed that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Total Plan may include the largest banks, but the real
purpose is the small, secondary regional banks,'' said Brian
Waterhouse, financial analyst at HSBC Securities Japan Ltd. ``The
major 19 banks have the largest number of loans, but smaller banks
have a graver danger of going under.''
</P>
<P>
   One Japanese banker, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the process of devising the Total Plan and bridge bank system was
driven by Japanese politicians, who mainly have their regional
constituents in mind. The failure of a regional bank has a huge
impact on that region's economy, particularly on the ailing
companies that borrowed from that bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see greater instability,'' James Fiorillo,
banking analyst at ING Barings Japan, said of the Total Plan's
impact. ``It's not a straight and narrow road forward. It's going
to be bumpy.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has been particularly sensitive to the markets
recently, in light of the beating last month that certain bank
shares, such as those of the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank and
Nippon Credit Bank, have suffered. And it has criticized foreign
financial analysts in the past for publicly singling out the names
of weak institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
