<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9832 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAYINGHOME-AZR &LR;      07-03 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAYINGHOME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MOMS GRAPPLE WITH RETURNING TO JOB, STAYING HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EMBARGOED FOR USE SUNDAY JULY 5)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - When her daughter Shaelyn was born March 8, Cynthia
Ellershaw had every intention of returning to work when her 12
weeks of family medical leave was up.
</P>
<P>
   Not going back to work ``was something I never considered,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband had emigrated from England 12 months earlier
and in the interim purchased and furnished a north Phoenix home and
bought a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We arrived here with two suitcases and carry-ons and got
pretty far into debt,'' she said. ``We needed my check to get by.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the money, Ellershaw loved her job as a team leader with
a Scottsdale computer training firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best job I ever had,'' she said. ``The work was
very rewarding, there were very good opportunities, and the company
was very supportive of the work I did.''
</P>
<P>
   As the date when she planned to return to work approached,
however, Ellershaw found herself trying to justify staying at home
with Shaelyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't face the prospects of leaving my daughter,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her dilemma was complicated by her boss, who suggested she could
be up for a department manager job when she returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had been my goal since I joined the company, and it would
have meant a lot more money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellershaw's dilemma is not unique. Most women and their families
wrestle with their consciences, finances and egos when facing the
prospects of returning to work after having or adopting a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Some, particularly single parents, have no choice but to
continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   Others find work more rewarding than full-time parenthood and
willingly return.
</P>
<P>
   Still others find a compromise that works for them. The
important thing, according to Renee K. Frost, a certified marriage
and family therapist in Tempe, is to realize that there are gains
and losses in any choice and a family should be willing to live
with them,
</P>
<P>
   Ellershaw was able to find a way to spend her days with Shaelyn
and still contribute to the family finances. That required putting
her career on hold and taking a part-time job at a bank, processing
checks from midnight to 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely made the right decision,'' she said. ``I can
always go back to my career.''
</P>
<P>
   It was money that helped make up her mind. After considering the
cost of day care ($100 to $150 per week), the expense of an
additional car, work clothes, lunches and other expenses, Ellershaw
concluded there would be practically nothing left of her paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make sense to put in all that effort, be away from
Shaelyn and have nothing to show for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about day care and the guilt of having someone else
rear her daughter also helped her decide to work from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard stories about abuses and neglect and about high
turnover of staff,'' she said. ``This scared us a lot, even though
we knew there were good people out there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellershaw found support for her decision in an unlikely place _
the Internet. Before she made the decision to stay home, she
connected with parentplace.com, a Web-based support group for
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't been able to talk to other women in my situation and
all of a sudden there were women from all over the world trying to
find their way through the same thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone reaches the same decision. Some women, particularly
single parents, simply can't afford not to work.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, for them, employers are increasingly stepping up
with assistance in the form of flexible schedules, telecommuting
options and subsidized child care. Some are even setting up
in-house day-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Petersen, managing principal at Buck Consultants' Phoenix
office, said a recent survey, conducted by the employee benefits
consulting firm, indicated that about 10 percent of the country's
large employers are offering some form of day-care assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Circle K parent Tosco Marketing, for example, is building a
day-care center as part of its new corporate headquarteres under
construction in Tempe, and American Express offers child-care
referral services and encourages parents to telecommute and
job-share.
</P>
<P>
   PCS Health Systems in Scottsdale doesn't directly subsidize
day-care costs, but it does allow employees to pay for it with
pre-tax dollars. It also picks up the tab for the care of a sick
child and provides facilities where nursing mothers can express
milk during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Arlie Russell Hochschild, a sociologist at the University of
California at Berkeley, set out to write a book about such vanguard
corporate policies. She expected to find that workers were
increasingly taking advantage of the programs and staying home with
their children.
</P>
<P>
   What she found became fodder for a controversial book called
``The Time Bind: When Work Becomes Home and Home Becomes Work.''
Instead of embracing the family friendly benefits, Hochschild found
that fathers and mothers weren't taking advantage of them. Instead,
at all levels, from hourly workers to professional staff, they were
consistently choosing work over home.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Hochschild points out that the workaholic behavior
is a Catch-22. The more we work, the more rushed and unpleasant
home life becomes, she says. The more rushed our home life, the
more we escape into work where we can relax _ and get paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   And, although work has become more nurturing in one sense, it
also has become more demanding in others. The Human Resources
manual may outline flex time and paternity leave options,
Hochschild says. But the reality is that requesting any is
discouraged. Commitment is equated with long hours.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Kitterman, Tosco Marketing's vice president of safety,
considered staying home after her daughter was born last May. But
although her family could survive comfortably on just her husband's
income, Kitterman elected to return to work at the end of her
family medical leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed working,'' she said. ``I have been given a
lot of opportunities and a lot of responsibility, and I like that.
I like the challenge I get from working.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitterman has a nanny who comes to her home to care for her
daughter Abbey, and her husband, a consultant, is often home during
the day. The personal attention her daughter receives during the
day made it easier for Kitterman to make the decision to return to
work. But she acknowledges she struggles with feelings of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in my position goes through that,'' she said.
``You wonder if you made the right decision. I think I did. I think
I am a better parent working outside the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellershaw acknowledged she sometimes misses work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the responsibilities and the opportunities,'' she said.
``But there is nothing like staying at home and being a part of the
development of this human being you brought into the world.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
