<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-ELDERLY-HEALTHCARE-     07-03 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ELDERLY-HEALTHCARE-ART-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE REVAMPS SYSTEM OF PAYING NURSING HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 (ATTN: Ark., Pa., Md., Ga.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government took a big step this week to make the business of
caring for elderly patients less lucrative, a setback for
hospitals, some nursing homes and home-care services. But oddly,
under cost-reduction rules that took effect July 1, Medicare
patients are likely to spend more days, not fewer, in nursing homes
and beds for acute care in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping patients longer will mean more money for efficient
nursing homes, which will now be paid on a per diem rate.
</P>
<P>
   But the new system will be costly for some hospitals. It will be
harder for a hospital to increase revenues from Medicare by
shifting patients from acute care to skilled nursing units within
the hospital. Medicare will now pay a per diem fee, instead of
paying on the basis of nursing-care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare will also penalize hospitals that discharge certain
types of patients too quickly, as measured by national averages of
length of stay.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say the big nursing-home chains are
prepared and even eager for the change, which Congress enacted last
year in the Balanced Budget Act. It will phase in day rates over
four years, replacing the old cost-based system. ``It's an
opportunity to make a clean profit by delivering the product for
less, rather than `run your costs up and we will pay you more,'''
said Jean Swenson, a health-care analyst at BT Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But at least two big hospital companies, Vencor Inc. and Tenet
Healthcare, reduced their earnings estimates and said the Medicare
changes were partly responsible. Columbia/HCA Healthcare, the
biggest hospital chain, said it had adjusted estimates to take
account of the changes, ``but it clearly has cost them money,''
said Geoffrey Harris, a health-care analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, Medicare plans to wring about $16 billion
over five years from its payments for care at home, the place where
most older people insist they want to stay. Deep cuts for home care
last January are already compounding other major problems for the
biggest home-care companies, Apria Healthcare and Olsten Corp.
Shares of Apria, where the chief financial officer resigned last
month, plummeted by more than 50 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home-care industry is in a state of chaos; the companies
are losing money like crazy,'' said John Hindelong, a vice
president of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   He said the exception was Lincare Holdings, a tightly controlled
company that has prospered despite Medicare cuts for its specialty,
home treatments for breathing ailments.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimated savings of $9.5
billion over five years from the changes in skilled-nursing
payments. The office said Medicare payments for nursing care were
$12.2 billion in 1997. That was about 10 percent of the industry's
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The federal-state Medicaid program pays nearly half of
nursing-home bills but some states, flush with budget surpluses,
have loosened up on payments for Medicaid. And the Medicaid cuts in
last year's Balanced Budget Act will initially hurt hospitals more
than nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, for a change that is supposed to promote efficiency,
chains that formerly had high costs, like Beverly Enterprises, the
biggest nursing-home chain, will be rewarded, as the nursing-home
day rates, called prospective payments, are phased in over four
years. The new payments, which can be delayed to next January for
most publicly traded nursing chains, will initially be tied to a
company's costs in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing chains like Health Care and Retirement that had lower
costs in 1995 may not do as well, Hindelong said. However, Health
Care and Retirement, which is merging with Manor Care, another
efficient chain, gets most of its revenue from private,
nongovernment insurers. ``Eventually they will all have to get
their costs down,'' he said, ``and all the publicly traded
nursing-home companies will be fine.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hindelong recommends Beverly, based in Fort Smith, Ark. ``The
stock is cheap,'' he said, at only 14 times his estimate of next
year's earnings, compared with an average of 22 times estimated
1999 earnings for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1980s, Beverly has cut back to 600 nursing homes
from 1,200, reduced the proportion of low-paying Medicaid residents
and hired its own rehabilitation therapists instead of relying on
outside specialists, like Novacare Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The new payment system is a challenge for Novacare, an
independent provider of rehab services in nursing homes,
assisted-living centers and hospitals. Although there will be
higher per diem rates for Medicare patients who get certain types
of therapy, the institutions will try to spend as little as
possible on therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Novacare expects to reduce costs by repeating what it already
does to attract younger, managed-care patients in outpatient
clinics: assigning licensed therapists to supervise groups of
patients, rather than one on one.
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care economizing will spread to nursing homes, said Ms.
Swenson at BT Alex. Brown, as more Medicare participants join
health-maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends Novacare, based in King of Prussia, Pa., and
among the nursing chains, Genesis Health Ventures, based in Kennett
Square, Pa.; Integrated Health Services, based in Owings Mills,
Md.; and Centennial Health Care, a smaller company based in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Harris at Salomon Smith Barney said the cuts reflected ``a
fundamental philosophical shift'' in government policy.
``Historically,'' he said, ``Medicare said that seniors were
entitled to certain benefits. The costs were measured and increased
each year. But with the Balanced Budget Act, the government is
shifting to a defined-contribution mentality much like corporate
America _ looking at dollar amounts and saying if costs go up
beyond a certain limit, the consumer will pay the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate payer is the Medicare recipient,'' Harris said.
``As in corporate America, employees are increasingly bearing the
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
