<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-AR     07-03 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEXES MAKE FOR STIFF COMPETITION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla., Mass., N.J., Calif., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been one wild ride. Only an unmitigated bull could have
scooped up every dollar from the red-hot stock market during the
last five years as the Dow Jones industrial average flirted with
the 9,000 mark from the mid-3,000s.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, the theory of diversifying investments has not paid
off. Carefully balancing big stocks with smaller ones, or American
issues with international issues, was a waste of time. Investors
would have been better off sweeping their money into the Vanguard
Index 500 fund and going to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Although the five money managers who began managing hypothetical
retirement portfolios for The New York Times in July 1993 have all
made money, even the best of them could not approach the returns on
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. Moreover, only one manager
posted a gain for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The fund picks of the top-performing manager, Sheldon Jacobs,
who edits the No-Load Fund Investor in Irvington, N.Y., returned a
cumulative total of 126.98 percent from July 7, 1993, when the
contest began, through the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Harold R. Evensky, an investment adviser in Coral Gables, Fla.,
lagged behind the group with a return of 75.78 percent. By
contrast, the Vanguard S&AMP;P index fund rose 185.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But who possibly could have expected that? Eric M. Kobren,
president of Kobren Insight Group in Wellesley, Mass., conceded
that he certainly did not. Yet investors who as a result shifted
the bulk of their assets into an S&AMP;P index or large-capitalization
stock fund made a mistake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current valuation of the S&AMP;P 500 vs. other security
classes makes for a compelling argument in favor of
diversification,'' he said. ``I'm not suggesting that investors run
for the hills, but I certainly wouldn't abandon the diversified
approach in today's environment.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiment is echoed by the other four advisers. They are
sticking to their guns and in most cases even increasing their
portfolio allocations to the small stocks and international issues
that have been left behind during the last five years' stampede of
big American stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Five years, after all, seems much longer tracked quarter by
quarter than when viewed as part of a long-term financial plan,
Evensky said. And he noted that the dominant stock group changes
significantly depending on the five-year period examined, providing
an argument for diversification.
</P>
<P>
   For example, foreign stocks shone in the five years between June
1983 and June 1988, returning an annual average of 34.9 percent,
compared with 14.4 percent for the S&AMP;P, Evensky noted.
</P>
<P>
   Had he used November 1990 through November 1995 as his
benchmark, his portfolio would be concentrated in small stocks,
which trounced the S&AMP;P's 17.2 percent average annual return with a
return of 22.1 percent a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several managers drew a lesson from their last five years'
experience: use more index funds in various asset categories
instead of trying to select the single best manager in each
particular category.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term case for using index funds gets stronger all the
time, because it's getting tougher to find good active managers,''
Jacobs said. Also, index funds tend to hold stocks for longer
periods than other funds, leading to fewer realized capital gains
and therefore smaller tax bills for long-term investors.
</P>
<P>
   The managers cautioned investors to temper their expectations.
``The market cannot rise 20-plus percent year after year,'' Kobren
said.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the hypothetical portfolios is tracked each
quarter by Lipper Analytical Services Inc. of Summit, N.J. It
excludes sales charges, transaction costs and taxes, because most
retirement money is held in tax-deferred accounts. The five
managers can choose any fund open to new investors. From the
outset, they were asked to pick portfolios that would grow for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   In first place for the quarter was Jack A. Brill, a San Diego
money manager who picks ``socially responsible'' funds. Brill's
portfolio rose 1.39 percent in the second quarter, despite a 13.26
percent decline in the Parnassus fund, which accounted for 10
percent of his holdings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He plans to replace Parnassus with Calvert Capital Accumulation,
because Parnassus is very volatile, presumably because of its 50
percent position in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Brown, the Calvert manager, uses the
``growth-at-a-reasonable-price'' approach and has outperformed the
average mid-cap fund since assuming management in April 1997, Brill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brill is also replacing Citizens Global Equity with MMA Praxis
International to increase his overseas exposure. Europe and other
countries, he said, could outperform the American stock market over
the next three to five years. He gained more international exposure
by reducing Dreyfus Third Century to 10 percent of his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs came in second place in the quarter, although his
portfolio slipped 0.6 percent. He is getting rid of Fidelity Real
Estate because, he said, the market is fully priced. He is also
selling Yacktman fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has performed below the average growth and income fund for
five years now,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   He is shifting the entire proceeds into Vanguard Total Stock
Market, bringing it up to nearly one-third of the portfolio. ``The
S&AMP;P 500 index fund is a bet on large stocks,'' he said. By
contrast, he noted, about 30 percent of Total Stock Market is
invested in small- and mid-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Kobren, whose all-Fidelity portfolio dropped 1.37 percent, came
in third, as small-cap stocks and real estate issues lagged behind
the bigger stocks. Concerned that his exposure to real estate
investment trusts may be high, Kobren is selling half of his
position in Fidelity Real Estate and putting the proceeds into
Fidelity Spartan Government Income, a high-quality bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the beating that small stocks have taken in the last few
months, Kobren is sticking with Fidelity Small-Cap Stock. ``We are
confident that manager Paul Antico can uncover superior companies
and deliver the numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evensky, whose portfolio fell 2.58 percent, took fourth place
for the quarter. He is sticking with his funds going forward.
``Rapid changing of managers tends to reduce returns,'' he said.
``My portfolio is well diversified and run by world-class managers,
so no changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Dziubinski, who edits Morningstar Fund Investor, also
plans no changes to her portfolio, even though she came in last
with a quarterly loss of 4.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   She calculates that just over half of her portfolio is invested
in American stocks, about a third in foreign stocks and the balance
in a mix of cash, bonds and miscellaneous investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've placed a good chunk of change in poorer-performing areas
overseas that have a mean game of catch-up to play,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
