<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-KIDS-INFO-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN GROWS OVER ONLINE DATA-COLLECTION FROM CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By PAMELA MENDELS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a World Wide Web site for young investors developed by
Liberty Financial Cos., children can play a trivia game that tests
their knowledge about investing, learn how to open a savings
account with the guidance of a cartoon character named ``Murphy the
Magician,'' or participate in a contest where prizes include a
digital video camera.
</P>
<P>
   In order to enter the contest, however, they must complete a
survey asking their age and sex and whether they have ever received
savings bonds, stocks, mutual funds or gold coins as gifts.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the company says that the survey is intended to
help the operators of the Web site design appropriate content for
its visitors, and that the information is not saved, given out to
others or used for marketing. ``From our perspective, this site was
meant to be an educational site for the benefit of kids and parents
who want to teach about economics,'' said Porter Morgan, a senior
vice president for Liberty Financial, an asset management company
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But for Kathryn Montgomery, president of the Center for Media
Education, an electronic-media public interest group based in
Washington, the site is symptomatic of what she views as a big
problem: the ability of commercial Web sites to gather detailed
information from children without their parents' knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is happening, as one person said, under the
radar of parents,'' Ms. Montgomery said. ``They don't know what
questions are being asked of their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ms. Montgomery is worried that even if sites are not
currently exploiting the information they request, they could do so
in the future _ devising, for example, promotions aimed at a
youngster based on what site operators have figured out about his
or her tastes. ``What I see developing is a highly commercial
medium where collection of personal information from children could
become routine to create personalized advertising,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   These concerns have become a big topic in Washington and in the
technology industry. Last month, officials at the Federal Trade
Commission recommended legislation that would put curbs on the
online collection of information from children under the age of 13.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a coalition of about 50 companies and
organizations, including America Online, Microsoft and AT&AMP;T,
announced the formation late last month of the Online Privacy
Alliance, an industry group that aims to protect children's privacy
online.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this concern follows a recent Federal Trade Commission
study that found that almost half of all Web sites aimed at
children have made little effort to explain their
information-gathering practices to their young visitors, and that
most fail to notify parents when children are asked to give out
personal information.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was conducted in March, looked at 212 Web sites
selected from Yahooligans, a popular Web directory for children. It
found that 88 percent of the sites surveyed collected identifying
details like names or postal or e-mail addresses from children. At
the same time, only 23 percent advised children to seek their
parents' permission before giving out personal information. And
only 7 percent indicated that they would notify parents of their
information-gathering practices.
</P>
<P>
   To Mozelle Thompson, an FTC commissioner, the findings were
dismaying, and not just because of their implications for
children's privacy online. Thompson fears that these privacy
concerns will restrain the growth of electronic commerce. ``We
don't think that growth will be realized if consumers don't feel
comfortable and safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to say exactly how many commercial sites have
been set up to attract the estimated 10 million American children
online today. But Elizabeth Lascoutx, director of the Children's
Advertising Review Unit of the Council of Better Business Bureaus,
estimates there are thousands.
</P>
<P>
   They range from sites developed by cereal companies to those
posted by banks, broadcasters and toy makers, according to Regina
Joseph, a senior analyst for Jupiter Communications, a new media
market research company based in New York. Typically, Ms. Joseph
said, the purpose of such sites is to develop ``brand awareness''
while providing entertainment for children.
</P>
<P>
   These Web sites ask for identifying information and other data
in a variety of ways. For example, the trade commission report
says: ``Some sites require children to answer questions about their
interests in order to register or become eligible to win prizes. In
other cases a site may use `imaginary' characters to request more
information from children, have children sign a `guest book,'
solicit information to create home pages for children, invite
children to participate in chat and electronic pen pal programs,
require children to register with the site for updates and
information, and offer prizes and other incentives for completing
surveys and polls.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, online publishers insist, there are simple
explanations for the information gathering.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at a site run by Warner Brothers, the studio
division of Time Warner Inc., visitors can send electronic
postcards with characters from Looney Tunes or the recent animated
children's movie ``Quest for Camelot'' _ but only if they supply
their names and e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   But Arthur Sackler, vice president for law and public policy in
the Washington office of Time Warner _ one of the members of the
new Online Privacy Alliance _ said the information was requested
simply so that the recipient of the card knows who it comes from.
He said the names and addresses were not saved or used in any other
way.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he asserted, the site is aimed at teen-agers 15 and
older. But Sackler later said site operators would probably begin
inserting notices on electronic postcards that might attract
younger children, advising them that they should not give out
information without asking their parents, a practice that is used
at other Time Warner children's sites like Sports Illustrated for
Kids.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, site operators argue that a site that may appear
to be for children is, in fact, intended for older eyes. For
example, Scurvyboy, posted by the nonprofit citrus marketing
cooperative Sunkist Growers, offers an online hockey game and
features the adventures of a hapless secret agent who believes
space aliens want to steal the earth's supply of oranges. Ms.
Montgomery of the Center for Media Education criticized the site's
``smoothie contest,'' in which, for the chance to win a blender,
contestants fill out forms that ask two questions about eating
habits and request such information as a name and address.
</P>
<P>
   But Gee Wynands, a spokeswoman for Sunkist, which is based in
Van Nuys, Calif., said the criticism was unfair, because the site,
although listed in Yahooligans, is meant for 19- to 27-year-olds,
not younger children. ``They probably wouldn't even get it,'' Ms.
Wynands said.
</P>
<P>
   If such is the case, Ms. Montgomery said, information collectors
should make it clear that the site is intended for older children
or adults. ``At least disclose the target age group and let parents
judge if they think that's true,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies have developed stringent policies on gathering
information from children. For example, children under 18 who visit
Walt Disney Co.'s Web site and try to enter a sweepstakes promoting
a coming children's movie are told they must get their parents'
permission. The site also attempts to make sure children have
received their parent's go-ahead by alerting parents by e-mail when
their children have registered with the site.
</P>
<P>
   And if Mom and Dad do not want their children to enter the
contest, they can let the site know by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
