<SLUG> BC-PERKINS-JAZZ-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINETOP PERKINS JAZZ REVIEW: USING ONLY WHAT IS NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five days before his 85th birthday, the blues pianist
Pinetop Perkins appeared at Chicago Blues on Thursday night like a
wily sage who knows how to make silence eloquent. Perkins, who was
a mainstay of Muddy Waters' band, has the entire blues vocabulary
in his fingers, from boogie and shuffle bass lines to florid
barrelhouse trills and filigrees. He can splash chords around or
riffle up and down the keyboard, but without good reason, he
doesn't; he plays with a ruthless economy.
</P>
<P>
   For a solo during ``How Long Blues,'' Perkins dispensed nothing
more than one note, a pause, three rippling chords down, three
arpeggios up and a low plunked note. But every one of them was in
the exact spot to yield as much ornery bluesiness as possible.
</P>
<P>
   While Perkins doesn't have a striking voice, he used it just as
cunningly to sing about his Mississippi birthplace, chicken shacks,
mojo power and women. Some verses were half sung, half spoken, with
the words tucked in at the beginning of a phrase. But when Perkins
sang about lost love, he could raise his voice just slightly and
linger over a melodic turn, suddenly transforming a line from
offhandedness to desolation.
</P>
<P>
   George Kilby Jr. on guitar and his band, the Coolerators, who
have backed Perkins for a decade, kept the music lean and pushy.
Uptempo tunes kicked along; stop-time parts, like the ones in
``Caledonia,'' were absolutely exact. Two saxophonists played
sinewy riffs and broad-shouldered solos as Perkins goaded them with
just one chord per measure. And Kilby squeezed out blues lines and
traded licks with Perkins, whose lessons in pithiness have been
taken to heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
