</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARKIEWICZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIE THAT BONDS BASEBALL, TV IMPROVED BY ESPN CREATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The marriage of baseball and television technology has always
looked more like an arranged affair than a natural union of
compatible parties.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the altar you have the most traditional of
sports, a game that burrows ever deeper into its past to hold onto
the retro look _ with throw-back uniforms, asymmetrical ballparks
and lily-white front offices.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite, you have TV, steadfastly dragging the game and its
fans into the present with helmet-cams, miked-up coaches and
hitter's hot zones.
</P>
<P>
   Purist that I am, I prefer grass fields, neighborhood ballparks
and $4 box seats, but the realist in me has come to accept
retractable domes, luxury suites and $3 hot dogs as the costs of
progress.
</P>
<P>
   I've also come to believe that, at its best, the technology TV
offers baseball can educate fans, especially casual baseball
watchers, increasing both their appreciation and interest in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example is ESPN's Bat Track, which will be on
display again tomorrow night when the network airs the Rangers game
at The Ballpark against the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived by Hall of Fame second baseman-turned TV baseball
analyst Joe Morgan, Bat Track measures the bat swing speed of
selected hitters during televised games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bat speed'' has come to be a more commonly used term in recent
years. Broadcasters, writers and fans as well as scouts and coaches
now employ it when talking, for example, about a hitter's ability
or inability to catch up with a high, hard one.
</P>
<P>
   But how many casual fans really had any idea whether a fast
swing is always better than a slow swing, or which major-league
hitters have fast bats and which have slow ones?
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of Bat Track, Morgan has helped enlighten the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quicker the bat, the longer the hitter can wait to
recognize the pitch,'' Morgan explains. ``In doing so, he's going
to have a better chance to drive the ball. To be a good hitter, you
need either bat speed or strength; the great hitters have both.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bat speed is very much like pitch speed,'' Morgan adds. ``The
fastest pitchers are not necessarily the best pitchers. Similarly,
the hitters with the fastest bats aren't necessarily the best
hitters. Instead, the better hitters are the ones who make more
adjustments at the plate. For example, on an inside fastball, you
need to use all of your bat speed. On a changeup away, you need to
slow down your bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan notes that a Mark McGwire, like a Nolan Ryan throwing a
fastball, can overpower a pitcher with his bat speed and strength.
``But a hitter like \RSan Diego's\S Tony Gwynn makes adjustments;
he has several bat speeds.'' Gwynn's approach, Morgan notes, is
similar to that of Atlanta Braves pitcher Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of bat speeds taken by Bat Track shows just how
different swings can get different results. Ken Griffey Jr., for
instance, homered with a bat speed of 97 mph. But San Francisco's
Bill Mueller also homered, with a 77-mph cut. Meanwhile, Houston's
Jeff Bagwell fanned, even while employing a 91-mph rip.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Indians-Yankees game, Morgan pointed out that Manny
Ramirez took a 94-mph cut on a Hideki Irabu fastball _ his best
swing _ because he was sitting on a 3-1 count. He homered. In his
next at-bat, Ramirez took a slower swing, largely because he was
down in the count and not looking fastball. Because of his
strength, he homered again.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers may dismiss such technologically derived data, calling
it the stuff of ``seamheads'' or techno-geeks. But there's nothing
wrong with using technology if it contributes to the fan's greater
understanding of the game, especially at a time when baseball
interest is about as wide as an outfield but as deep as a
chalkline.
</P>
<P>
   Go to The Ballpark this weekend and you'll find the stands
jammed as usual. But see how many are avidly watching the game,
really paying attention and not just gnawing on turkey legs,
sucking down lemon chills and cheering the dot races.
</P>
<P>
   Providing casual fans more information might not deepen their
interest; they may have to play the game for that. But it can't
hurt either.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all TV technology has provided a clear benefit to
baseball. The only thing we learned from the ballyhooed hot
zone/cold zone hitting graphic was that batters like their pitching
belt high and over the middle of the plate, and that they don't
like it up and in or down and away.
</P>
<P>
   But the good stuff, like Bat Track, offers information that is
otherwise unavailable to fans and helpful to understanding the
nuances of the game. It shows that even an arranged marriage can
have a happy outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
