<HEADER>
A9851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAFIRE-EQUIPMENT-COX     07-03 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRE-EQUIPMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida fighting fire with best equipment
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- As wildfires continue to blaze across
Florida, firefighters are using everything they've got.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 fire engines were flown from California in a massive,
$18 million air-lift, said Florida Unified Command spokesman Steve
Parsons. And another 20 bulldozers were scheduled to arrive from
Texas on Friday, adding to more than 400 that depleted supplies
around the Southeast. So much equipment has arrived, in fact, that
workers are finding it impossible to keep a tally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the country's sky hook helicopters _ huge choppers
used to hoist air-conditioning units onto skyscrapers _ are now in
Florida lugging water.
</P>
<P>
   At least 100 aircraft are being used and 150 fire engines,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firefighting in Florida is not real conducive to large numbers
of crews as we do in the western United States. It's a lot swampier
and muckier,'' said Dick Mangan, a program leader for the Rocky
Mountain Research Station's Missoula Lab, the nation's leading fire
research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's an equipment operation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what an operation: A handful of converted bombers that drop
thousands of gallons of fire-retardant; the Superscooper, an
amphibious 1,400-gallon water bomber from North Carolina that skims
lakes and rivers for water to spew on fire; and ``water tenders,''
tanker trucks that hold massive amounts of water to resupply fire
engines in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters also have equipment to start back-burns and destroy
fuel: ping-pong balls filled with the chemical used in anti-freeze,
which they have not yet used, and hand-held drip torches. A flying
drip torche that attaches to helicopters is also available, Mangan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Special gear worn by firefighters protects them from fire and
cuts heat stress. Shirts with billowy sleeves and pants are made of
light-weight Nomex, a material manufactured by Dupont. The material
is fire-resistant so firefighters trapped in a fire can survive 15
to 20 minutes, Mangan said.
</P>
<P>
   Many firefighters also have shelters, grimly dubbed
`shake-and-bakes'. The small aluminum pup tents are packed in waist
packs that can be shaken out in 15 seconds, weigh under three
pounds and can fit two men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects 95 percent of radiant heat, so if you have 1,000
degrees of temperature, this thing would absorb only 50 degrees of
it,'' Mangan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of the country's 67 hotshot crews, 20-member teams
considered the best firefighters in the nation, have also arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the crews that are digging the lines and get as close
as you can get,'' said James Stone, spokesman for the National
Interagency Fire Center, the clearing house that routes all the
teams and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But even such advanced equipment does little good without the
cooperation of nature, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually it all comes down to two things. Number one, the
weather has got to change and when the weather changes, that allows
firefighters to get in close,'' said Greg Thayer, a fire
information officer for the Florida Unified Command. ``And three
things are required to burn anything. Fuel, oxygen and heat. If a
firefighter can take away one of those three things, then the fire
will go out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
