A9855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-B     07-03 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE ELIMINATES ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Thus was daring rewarded. L'audace,
l'audace, and all that. France's soccer team kept pushing and
risking and pushing some more before 77,000 at the Stade de France
Friday afternoon. Les Bleus pushed for 90 minutes, then 30 minutes
more.
</P>
<P>
   And then, when it came down to penalty kicks, their crossbar
pushed, too _ pushed Luigi DiBiagio's shot over and out, pushed
Italy out of the World Cup and France into a semifinal date here
Wednesday with either Germany or Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel utterly wiped out,'' coach Aime Jacquet declared, after
his squad had prevailed, 4-3, in the shootout after the match had
ended in a 0-0 draw. ``But in the end, the best team won.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third straight time that the Italians had been
eliminated in a shootout _ they lost to Argentina, 4-3 (after 1-1),
in the 1990 semifinals and to Brazil, 3-2 (after 0-0), in the 1994
final. ``It is a curse,'' shrugged coach Cesare Maldini, who
thought it might be the Azzurri's day after keeper Gianluca
Pagliuca had saved Bixente Lizarazu's bid on the second French
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's what happens to teams that deliberately play not
so much to win as not to lose. The Italians, who consider 0-0 a
perfect game, play a counterattacking style as a matter of national
tradition. They mark and tackle and thwart and grab and wait for
the error, the lapse, the loss of form or focus. Then they go for
the knockout.
</P>
<P>
   It works most of the time _ the Azzurri played six 1-0 or 0-0
matches in Cup qualifying and lost none and they beat Norway, 1-0,
to get here. It works until they have to take the long walk, one at
a time, to the penalty spot. ``In penalty kicks, it's about keeping
your nerve,'' said Jacquet.
</P>
<P>
   The French, who ousted Brazil in their last Cup shootout in
1986, were the cooler hands Friday. After keeper Fabien Barthez
brought them back even by blocking Demetrio Albertini, their last
three shooters all cashed in. When DiBiagio's ball slammed off the
bar dead center and sent soaring into space, Les Bleus linked arms
at midfield and jumped up and down in giddy disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   The French have waited a dozen years to get back in the Cup, and
they believe they'll never have a better chance to win it than they
do now as hosts, with tens of thousands of fans singing ``La
Marseillaise'' as a fight song. They knew they couldn't beat the
Italians by sitting back and waiting, so they went after them as
soon as Scottish referee Hugh Dallas blew the opening whistle.
</P>
<P>
   With playmaker Zinedine Zidane, back after a two-game
suspension, dashing and dishing all day, the French kept surging
upfield. They took 24 shots to Italy's seven. They got 13 corner
kicks to Italy's two. And yet it came to nothing, just as the
French had feared it might.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were 3-0-1 against the Azzurri with three
shutouts in their last four matches, Les Bleus were bracing for the
match as if it were a final. Seven of them play in Italy's Serie A,
and they know the Italian mindset and style by heart. ``Only one
thing matters to the Italians,'' French captain Didier Deschamps
had said before the match. ``And that's winning, no matter how.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the French set up housekeeping in the Italian end,
the Azzurri were on them like freestyle wrestlers, wrapping arms
around chests, putting knees into thighs, sliding feet between
legs. Of France's 24 shots, only seven were on goal. ``The French
tried to attack,'' said Maldini, ``but they were never all that
threatening. I don't think our goalkeeper had much to do.''
</P>
<P>
   France did have chances. Zidane put a ball wide in the fourth
minute. Youri Djorkaeff barely missed with Pagliuca down just
before the half, then watched Pagliuca block him point-blank with a
minute left in overtime. But most of the time, the Les Bleus were
high and wide. Most of the time, their corner kicks sailed long or
were headed away.
</P>
<P>
   Their nightmare was that after all the daring, all the risk, the
Italians would seize on 10 seconds of 120 minutes and tear out
their hearts. And it almost happened.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Baggio, the man who'd missed Italy's last penalty kick
in the Rose Bowl and given the Cup to Brazil, slipped into the area
a dozen minutes into overtime and launched a volley that missed the
upper far corner by inches, as Baggio covered his face in dismay.
The Azzurri never got another chance.
</P>
<P>
   So it came, again, to penalties. Zidane, the man of the match
for Les Bleus, drilled his to the lower left side. Baggio matched
him. Then, as the French watched in horror, Lizarazu was thwarted.
But Barthez, whose shaved head his mates rub for luck, denied
Albertini and it was even.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they made them after that _ David Trezeguet, then
Alessandro Costacurta, Thierry Henry, then Christian Vieri, Laurent
Blanc and then ... DiBiagio tried to roof his shot and the clang
was heard all the way to the Spanish Steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hardly seems fair to lose the World Cup in this way,'' said
DiBiagio, who lay on his back with his hands over his face as
Barthez came leaping and exulting off the line and all of France
leaped and exulted with him. ``And to feel in some way responsible
is a dreadful feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBiagio has plenty of company _ the Italians have missed six
penalties in their last three Cup shootouts. Eight years ago in
Naples, Aldo Serena was the man on his knees in torment at the end.
Four years ago in Pasadena, it was Baggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this is the third time for me and it leaves a
very bitter taste,'' said Baggio, who has been on the field for all
of them. ``Penalties are the worst way of all to lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
