<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9856 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GERMANY-CROATIA-B     07-03 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GERMANY-CROATIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER GERMAN TEAM DOESN'T LACK ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ The Germans have been rapidly growing older
during the World Cup finals. It has nothing to do with overexposure
to sun in their Cote D'Azur training camp, where they can find
refuge in their $450 per day hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But by adding Lothar Matthaus to the lineup, the average age of
the starting team has incresed to 30.6 years. This might not be a
promising sign for the future, but the Germans seem as dynamic as
any team in the quarterfinals, certainly more attack-minded than
Croatia, their opponent in Lyon tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Matthaus set a record for World Cup appearances when he replaced
Olaf Thon in the second half of the second match against Yugoslavia
in Lens. This might have seemed an act of desperation by coach
Hans-Hubert (Berti) Vogts, who had dropped Matthaus from the team
two years ago, knowing he had viable successors in 1996 European
Footballer of the Year Matthias Sammer, Jens Nowotny, and Thon.
This also illustrates the depth of talent in Germany, regardless of
age _ a former European player of the year is replaced by Matthaus,
world player of the year in 1990 and '91.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign that the move would pay off was demonstrated as
Germany visibly galvanized after scoring twice in the second half
to tie the Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   Matthaus plays the libero role, which was first interpreted by
Franz Beckenbauer in the 1970s and has been the linchpin of the
German philosophy since. The position requires experience,
leadership qualities, an ability to dictate the terms of the game,
and an innate sense of when to attack, when to defend.
</P>
<P>
   German liberos are usually athletic marvels, and Matthaus
exemplifies this, going strong into a World Cup record 25th game.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are his bionic teammates: goalkeeper Andreas Koepke
is 35; Jurgen Klinsmann 33; Thomas Helmer 33; Thomas Hassler, Ulf
Kirsten, Jurgen Kohler, and Thon 32; Stefan Reuter 31. The heir
apparent libero, Nowotny, is only 24, which might be why he was cut
from the team before the finals began.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a rematch of the 1996 European Championships
quarterfinal match in Manchester, won by Germany, 2-1. The Croats
felt cheated in that game because striker Davor Suker's goal was
negated by a questionable offside and Sammer scored the winner in
another controversial situation.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia might have protested more, but the Croats have strong
feelings of gratitude toward Germany, which was the first to
recognize their independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the surprise of the tournament,'' Suker said. ``But
this is not enough for us. Sure, Germany is the favorite, but the
favorites do not always win.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we, two years later, are more mature than we were at
Manchester.''
</P>
<P>
   The Croats are also missing two of their top players _ Sasho
Cvitanovic, dropped by coach Miro Blazevic after a training camp
dispute, and Alen Boksic, who is injured. With a population of 5
million, Croatia is not as capable as Germany of finding top-level
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   This contest could be decided by the strikers, Croatia's
``Sukerman'' against Germany's ``Super Sub.''
</P>
<P>
   Suker has scored 32 goals in 38 games for the national team and
110 goals in Spain for Seville and Real Madrid. Bierhoff has been
among the top scorers in Italy's Serie A with Udinese in recent
years, and will move to Milan this season, but was not considered a
starter on the Nationalmannschaft until this tournament, despite
scoring the winning goal in overtime in the Euro '96 final against
the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia is still becoming accustomed to having a national
identity. Meanwhile, Matthaus has been playing since the Tito Era.
His first World Cup was Spain '82. He marked Maradona in Germany's
championship game loss at Mexico '86, captained the team which won
Italia '90, then left the team soon after USA '94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost two finals and I won one,'' Matthaus told La
Gazzetta dello Sport. ``I would like to even the count.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
