<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY TO PROBE REFUGEE CASH FLOW TO ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The German Foreign Ministry has asked ``all relevant
authorities'' to investigate whether money donated by Kosovo
Albanian refugees in this country is being used in Kosovo to
purchase weapons for a separatist rebel movement there, the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Ministry spokesman Markus Ederer Friday said that Germany would
consider such a use of funds to be a violation of a UN resolution
banning weapon sales to either side in the Kosovo dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``If money collected here is going to the UCK (the Kosovo
Albanian acronym for the rebels) to purchase arms, then we have to
look into that,'' said Ederer.
</P>
<P>
   While Ederer would not say which arm of the German government
would carry out such a probe, it is likely to be the Ministry of
Interior.
</P>
<P>
   He also added that the German government has called on Kosovo
Albanian leaders to halt fund-raising because of suspicions that
money has been forcibly collected from Europe's large Kosovo
Albanian refugee community. ``We have no proof, but we have hints
that it is happening,'' Ederer said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Boston Globe reported that Kosovo Albanians in
Germany and Switzerland were donating hundreds of thousands of
dollars to funds established to aid Kosovo. Many of those
interviewed said they gave a percentage of their income to these
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   One fund, the ``Fatherland is Calling'' does give its money
directly to the Kosovo Liberation Army, according to its director,
Ibrahim Kelmendi. Kelmendi told the Globe that money he raises goes
to the rebel movement ``and I guess they use it to buy weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Donations have increased dramatically as fighting has
intensified in the Serbian province, he said. Kelmendi, who also
heads the Democratic Associaton of Albanians in Germany, said
fellow refugees ``had saved up a lot of money, and now they are
spending their savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other funds are overseen in Germany by exiled members of
the Kosovo government. Kosovo was stripped of its political
autonomy in 1991 by Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic, and many
political leaders have fled since then to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a spokesman for the exiled leaders, Rexher Bajrami,
denied that any money was going to the rebels. He said all of the
money is being used to support the educational system in Kosovo as
well as for medical and other humanitarian purposes. Bajrami added
that the government has recommended that Kosovo Albanians give an
estimated three percent of their income to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fund is recognized by the German revenue authority as a
nonprofit, and the money is being used to soothe the situation back
home,'' Bajrami said.
</P>
<P>
   But the exiled prime minister, Bujar Bukoshi, had earlier told
the Globe that the money being raised was ``to help Kosovo with all
means'' and would not comment on whether funds went to the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo government has called for peaceful protests, not
violence, to settle the question of Kosovo's future. Kosovo
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's population,
want independence from Serbia. While the international community
does not support its quest for independence, it has chastised
Serbia for its brutal crackdowns in Kosovo against the rebels that
left many civilian dead and over 60,000 ethnic Albanians uprooted
from their homes there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1844EDT &QL; 
