<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      07-03 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA IS ELATED OVER CLINTON'S 9-DAY VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 &HT;    
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The Chinese, from the top leaders to the man in the
street, were elated with the nine-day visit by an American
president who struck many here as vibrant and empathetic.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that President Clinton lectured China, gently but
firmly, about the merits of freedom, called the bloody 1989
crackdown on demonstrators wrong and praised the Dalai Lama, who is
usually portrayed here as a villain. He seemed to come as a
respectful friend.
</P>
<P>
   President Jiang Zemin's startling, self-confident decision to
allow Clinton to speak on live television only added to the sense
of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the view of most people here this signals a new acceptance
of China after 1989,'' said Zhang Xiaojin, an international
relations expert at the People's University.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, facing mounting complaints at home that it is
coddling the Chinese at the expense of American values and
interests, and the Chinese, who want American trade, investment,
technology and respect, had congruent interests in this state
visit. That was to improve China's image in the United States,
showing its diversity and social changes and growing freedoms in
the personal realm.
</P>
<P>
   In that, the visit appears to have been a success. And it was
President Jiang's insight to recognize that a major concession,
like the televising of his news conference with Clinton and
Clinton's Beijing University speech, was needed to make it so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This prevented Clinton from coming back with egg on his
face,'' said Roderick MacFarquhar, a China expert at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   The visit has certainly bolstered the status here of Jiang.
Equally important, it gives a boost to the many other pragmatic
officials, from Prime Minister Zhu Rongji on down who believe that
the success of their transition to an advanced, market-oriented
economy depends on better ties with the undisputed economic and
political superpower, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the paucity of diplomatic breakthroughs at the summit
meeting, the friendly, tactful demeanor of Clinton, and Jiang's
bold decision to loosen temporarily the usual tight controls on
political discourse, helped create a happy feeling about
Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   But elation is hard to follow, and the Chinese could be in for
morning-after dismay when the unresolved differences rear up again.
</P>
<P>
   These include America's huge and growing trade deficit with
China and its refusal to consider Chinese admission to the World
Trade Organization until painful changes are made to open markets.
American concerns over political and religious freedoms may have
been muffled this week, but China is not about to become a liberal
democracy, and concerns about weapons proliferation have not yet
been fully satisfied either.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its own economic cycle, its efforts to revamp the
vast state-run economic sector and the Asian financial crisis,
China may be in for a rough economic period in any case. Seeing no
rush of American trade and investment and high technology, some of
this week's cheering citizens here may become disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the old-guard Communist hard-liners in the government who
might lead an anti-American reaction seem to have been routed from
real influence over the last year by Jiang and the pragmatists.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials and experts, sounding quite like American
officials on the subject, say they hope that the good will and
low-profile technical ties forged by the reciprocal state visits
will help the two countries live through their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems are still here,'' said Xiong Zhiyong, dean of the
Foreign Affairs College in Beijing. ``But I think both sides now
understand each other better.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope, in Beijing as well as in the White House, is that an
overarching sense of partnership will enable these two giants to
avoid dangerous conflict _ a military confrontation over Taiwan
being the worst case _and to reap mutual economic benefits. The
American officials, rightly or wrongly, also believe that by
engaging China they will nudge Beijing to become more open and
democratic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chinese people, like Americans, are pondering the meaning of
President Jiang's decision to allow the televising of an extended
discussion of Tibet, human rights and the 1989 killings in and
around Tiananmen Square. It was done in the most tentative of ways:
there was no announcement beforehand, insuring a small
Saturday-noon audience, and Clinton's most direct words on 1989 and
the Dalai Lama and democracy were not reported in the official news
media.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how this limited but genuine public airing will
play out _ whether the government will feel emboldened to allow
more free debate at home, whether people's expectations of free
speech will change.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt about the short-term gains, for China as
well as for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost to China was relatively small compared to the
benefits,'' said Yasheng Huang, a Chinese-born political economist
at the Harvard Business School. ``The American public and media
were happy with the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kept the costs for China down, and avoided a more
defensive reaction, by holding back on some sensitive topics, said
MacFarquhar of Harvard. For example, he might have spoken about
Taiwan's heady democracy, or pointed to the student-led downfall of
President Suharto in Indonesia as a grim example to the Chinese
leaders, who brook no political opposition themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In his final-day remarks in Hong Kong, Clinton seemed to credit
China's leaders with a stronger commitment to radical political
change than they have ever revealed to their own countrymen. He
said Jiang and Zhu were ``the right leadership at the right time''
and are ``clearly committed to reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is an accurate assessment of these longtime
Communists whose reforms, so far, seem more designed to save the
party's rule than to destroy it, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, Clinton's American-style politicking may change a
new generation's expectations of its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton was widely admired for his directness, quick
wit and frankness,'' said Zhang, the People's University professor.
``Most importantly, he stood out here in his youth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
