<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BIDS FAREWELL WITH KUDOS FOR JIANG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton offered a glowing endorsement
Friday of President Jiang Zemin of China as a man of
``extraordinary intellect'' capable of guiding his country through
historic change. Clinton also predicted that democracy will one day
be a way of life in China.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference here as the last official act in
his fast-paced and controversial nine-day diplomatic mission,
Clinton said he has been witness to a ``remarkable transformation''
in the Chinese economy and lifestyle, one he said will continue
under Jiang's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,'' Clinton said, when asked by a reporter if democracy
could ever come to China. ``I believe there can be and I believe
there will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Jiang, with whom he dined twice last weekend, Clinton said:
``I have a very high regard for his abilities. After I met with him
the first time I felt very strongly that his chances of becoming
the leader of China for a sustained period were quite good because
he's a man of extraordinary intellect, very high energy, a lot of
vigor for his age, or indeed, for any age.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``He has a good imagination. He has vision, he
can visualize, he can imagine a future that is different from the
present.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's parting words displayed a significant admiration for
the leader of a communist regime that routinely suppresses public
opinion, arrests dissidents, and refuses to admit wrongdoing in the
massacre of thousands of protesters in Tiananmen Square nine years
ago. To that end, his friendliness toward Jiang may prove fodder
for those on Capitol Hill who oppose his policy of engagement of
China.
</P>
<P>
   With the news conference over and the last meeting finished, at
8:26 p.m. Friday, Clinton, his family and the exhausted US
delegation left on Air Force One for Washington from the new Hong
Kong International Airport, refueling at a military base in Alaska
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left, Clinton did caution that change may not come as
rapidly to China as some Americans might like. And to that end, he
stopped short of predicting democracy would come to China in his
lifetime, asking the rhetorical question, ``Do I think a woman will
be elected president of the United States? I do. Do I know when it
will happen? I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Clinton defended his decision not to
meet with political dissidents in Beijing last weekend as a
diplomatically prudent tactic that would aid his ultimate cause of
bringing more rights to the Chinese masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisions I made were based on my best judgment on how to
be most effective on expanding human rights,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he wanted to relay a public messages to the dissidents
whom he failed to meet, Clinton said: ``My message is the US is on
your side and we did our best. We think that it's going to take a
lot of discipline and a lot of effort, but we believe that this
strategy is the one most likely to advance the cause of free speech
and free association and free expression of religious conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual moment, Clinton came close to expressing regret
for his harsh criticism of former president George Bush's China
policy in the 1992 presidential campaign, a time when he accused
Bush of ``coddling dictators'' in the aftermath of the Tiananmen
Square massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter if he did ever have the occasion to regret
his campaign stance, Clinton said he believed the United States
needed to be ``clear and unambiguous in our condemnation'' of the
massacre. But he went on to cite Bush's ``genuine concern'' in
maintaining a relationship with China, and added, ``I think any
president would say that once you've served in this job you
understand a little bit more the nuances of all policies than you
do before you get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one question in the 40-minute news conference addressed any
of the myriad scandal issues being pursued in Washington by
Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr, and that one question
focused on Jiang's assertion last Saturday that China played no
role in trying to influence the 1996 US elections.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, reporters focused almost entirely on foreign policy,
spending most of their time on China but also asking questions on
Japan, Cuba, and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of Northern Ireland, Clinton said he has had ``good
long talks'' with Irish leaders over the last few days, as the
marching season begins, bringing with it the potential for further
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton referred to a series of arson attacks on Catholic
churches in Northern Ireland, saying, ``I feel personally horrible
about what has happened to the churches.'' He compared the arson to
church burnings in the United States two years ago and during the
civil rights movement, then added, ``I would just plead to whoever
was responsible for this for whatever reason, you need to take the
churches off the list, and you need to take violence off the
list.''
</P>
<P>
   On China, Clinton said the United States had a ``profound
interest in a partnership with the world's largest country.'' He
said the nation was well on its way to ``defining and honestly and
openly dealing with areas of differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he asked Jiang to cooperate with investigators
pursuing information on campaign fund-raising practices. Jiang had
said last week that he conducted his own investigation into whether
Chinese government officials funneled campaign contributions to
Clinton, and determined they did not.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Clinton returned to the theme of China's capable
leadership steering the country through historic change during a
time when cellular telephones and stock issues are becoming
emblematic of a more open, more market-oriented society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that leaders of vision and imagination and courage
will find a way to put China on the right side of history and keep
it there,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also said, ``There remain powerful forces resisting
change, as evidenced by continuing governmental restrictions on
free speech, assembly, and freedom of worship. One of the questions
I have tried to frame on this trip for the future is how do we deal
with these issues in a way most likely to promote progress. The
answer I think is clear: dealing directly, forcefully, but
respectfully with the Chinese about our values.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
