A9865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-CASTLES-BOS &LR;      07-03 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-CASTLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED A CASTLE? TRY GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEEBURG, Germany _ With its commanding lake view, immense stone
hall, and more bedrooms than the real estate sales force can
remember, Schloss Seeburg resembles a Walt Disney creation _ not to
mention an investor's dream at $99,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the castle roof is dotted with gaping holes. Pigeons live in
its hallways. Ten families are tenants in its outbuildings. The
town elders must approve all development plans. It is no surprise,
then, that industrial magnates are not rushing to invest the $10
million necessary to make this east German castle livable again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Seeburg goes under the auctioneer's gavel Saturday,
experts say it will find aa buyer. But chances are, he or she will
not be from the west, but from the Communists-turned-capitalists of
Germany's former east.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Germans seem to have the money now,'' says Sabine Pentrop
of the Treuhand Liegenschaftsgesellschaft, the agency charged with
selling former Communist assets. ``And they have no dreams. They
know this is no fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a fairy tale ending, though, to the violent saga of
east Germany's castles, which were seized first by the Nazis, then
by the Russians, and finally by the East German communists. Now,
some of these behemoths are returning to local ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Few would have predicted this in 1992, when 118 of east
Germany's most stately castles were put up for sale. Under the
terms of unification, they could not be returned to the families
who once owned them. Nor could the German government afford to keep
them, given their estimated $281 million annual upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   Many expected wealthy Americans, hungry for a piece of Europe,
would snap up the stately homes. That is why, in 1994, a marketing
campaign billed them as ``Fairy Tales For Sale.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood magnates did not materialize. Americans were put
off, among other things, by Germany's strict historic preservation
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one American has bought one,'' says Pentrop. ``Not even
Michael Jackson wanted to buy one of our castles.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a few wealthy west Germans came hunting. One aristocrat
bought back his family's castle, Schloss Kannenberg. An unlanded
aristocrat, Count von Rehbinder bought a castle that he is
transforming into a equestrian riding school.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the east Germans who have bought castles are
businessmen, combining new-found capital with socialist heritage,
have been the most successful in proposing ways for castles to be
developed that local communities would approve.
</P>
<P>
   These buyers are not looking to live in the castles or make them
Michelin-star hotels. Instead, they're talking about music
retreats, children's camps, and even business headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others proposed hotels, but we were providing jobs,'' says
Gisela Schroth, who bought Castle Koetteritzsch, east of Leipzig,
as the future headquarters of her family construction business.
``And we have the motivation to say we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Motivation is a requirement. Renovating these castles is no easy
task.
</P>
<P>
   At Schloss Seeburg, years of communist neglect have left their
mark. The driveway is choked with weeds. The walls still bear faded
posters from the FDJ, the Communist youth organization.
</P>
<P>
   A clock in the hallway is stopped at 12:00. The coal heating
doesn't work. The castle's rooms, turned into shabby dormitories,
reflects its days as a Nazi youth camp and then a training school
for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, nothing works,'' concedes Michael Kneb, an
assessor, standing in Seeburg's dusty main hallway. ``But this is
better than average. There are some that have no roofs.''
</P>
<P>
   Families today still picnic in the Seeburg's grounds, as they
more or less have since it was built in the eighth century. Not
surprisingly, locals are nervous about the new owners and what the
castle will become.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard the Columbian or Russian mafia were interested in
buying it,'' says Franz Graf, the 64-year-old caretaker. Graf's
family worked at Seeburg in pre-war days, his grandmother as a
gardener and his mother as a cook.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever buys Schloss Seeburg also becomes the landlord for the
10 families living in its outbuildings. When potential buyers react
with dismay to the news that the tenants cannot be evicted, auction
house representative Martina Stein tries to reassure them. It's
extra income,'' she says brightly.
</P>
<P>
   And these castles eat up money. Of the 79 castles which have
sold since 1992, buyers have invested a total of $29 million the
Treuhand estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Sven-Erik Hitzer, an east German travel agent who bought Schloss
Thuermsdorf near Dresden in 1997, estimates he will need $3 million
to renovate the 50-room castle, formerly used as a labor union
vacation camp. But he hopes to recoup the money by turning the
place into a historic rental property.
</P>
<P>
   It was that populist ideal that appealed to town elders, who
rejected a bid from another buyer to transform the castle into a
golf hotel. ``Somebody once calculated that 0.002 of all people
live in a castle,'' says Hitzer. ``But anybody can rent this castle
and feel like they are the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all easterners are thrilled that their neighbors are buying
local castles. Schroth grew up in the village of Sermuth, where
Castle Koetteritzsch is located, but was snubbed by some when she
became its landlord.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the older men came up to me, grabbed my pocket, and
said, ``Show me, where are your millions?'' recalls Schroth.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Castle Koetteritzsch is in anything but fairy tale
condition. But there is a Cinderella quality to Schroth's story.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, she played outside the castle walls, and dreamed of
living in its peaked tower. But that vision was not to be as she
grew up under communism. Castle Koetteritzsch was the headquarters
of a local agricultural association.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed after the Berlin Wall fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stood in the courtyard with a woman from the Treuhand,
discussing who would buy the castle,'' says Schroth. ``And she said
to me, ``What about you?''
</P>
<P>
   She gathered up the family earnings and argued she could make
the castle an expanded headquarters for the family construction
business, which employs 120 in Sermuth. Even though her bid was
less than a prospective owner from California, Schroth got the
castle.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she has opened a small pub on the grounds. Flower boxes
hang outside the renovated apartments in the former stables. More
renovations are underway on the main castle, for the business
headquarters and employee housing.
</P>
<P>
   And Castle Koetteritzch, once again, belongs to a local.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so special that we were able to do this,'' Schroth says,
whose family settled in Sermuth in the 1600s. ``We're keeping this
castle in the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
