<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIREFIGHTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTER PILOTS `TRYING TO STOP A HURRICANE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITUSVILLE, Fla. _ From the cockpit of his World War II-vintage
airplane, Andrew Brucker has seen more of Florida's smoky nightmare
than anyone else _ a familiarity has bred a reluctant respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Mother Nature is just having her way,'' said Brucker, who
has been dropping 2,000 gallons of red-stained fire retardant on
the ruinous wildfires several times a day since May 27. ``It's just
like trying to stop a hurricane. We can't do it. It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Brucker is a soldier in an army of firefighters who are using
water and chemicals, bulldozers and shovels, sweat and prayer to
combat walls of flame and towers of smoke that have turned parts of
the Sunshine State into a blackened moonscape under perpetually
ashen skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen fire behavior so severe that the fire's created its
own thunderstorms and lightning,'' said Brucker. ``That's the first
time I've ever seen anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Colorado native and an 18-year veteran of aerial firefighting,
Brucker was the first of what is now a team of pilots here,
arriving more than four weeks ago and working 14-hours shifts
almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   His red-and-white Douglas DC-4 aircraft, built in 1944 and used
during the Berlin Airlift, is pumped full of ammonium
polyphosphate, a commonly used agricultural fertilizer, that is
mixed with water stored in 5,000-gallon plastic water tanks on the
tarmac of the airport here.
</P>
<P>
   These chemical bombing runs of Brucker and his colleagues,
directed by US Forestry Service and Bureau of Land Management
officials, are designed to preserve the perimeter of fires that are
moving with terrifying speed in unpredictable directions.
</P>
<P>
   Guided by a smaller plane, Brucker flies at 150 miles per hour
and is just 150 feet above the ground when he pulls a lever to
release a surrealistic stream of red relief before returning to the
airport to repeat the routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing now is trying to keep individual houses from
burning down,'' the pilot said before his first run Friday. ``And
we can be somewhat successful. We can herd the fire around
particular sites sometimes. But as far as stopping these fires, the
only thing that's going to do that is rain. You just can't stop a
hurricane. When these fires are putting off the same energy as
low-yield nuclear bombs _ over a minute instead of a second _ that
power is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The work done by Brucker and his colleagues has been so
appreciated here _ where it was 100 degree Friday and so smoky some
pedestrians wore protective masks _ that their last runs on
Thursday night were hailed by 300 residents who stood on the end of
the runway and waved and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dangerous gesture because any aircraft aborting a
landing may have plowed into them. But Brucker said it put a human
face on a fire that is impersonal from treetop level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes on a human dimension when people's houses are burning
down,'' the gray-haired pilot said. ``We tend to depersonalize
things today. In the lexicon of disaster reports, it's not
somebody's house that's burning down, it's a `structure' that's
threatened. I kind of resent that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brucker, who has fought fires in Alaska's magnificent wilderness
and in the Snake River Canyon in Idaho, said that Florida's
wildfire of the century is providing a lesson on what happens when
man seeks to harness nature's sometimes untamable domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view my job more and more as not putting out forest fires
per se but protecting people's homes who have bumped up against the
forest,'' Brucker said. ``We call it the urban interface. We've put
out every fire ever started almost without fail, and we're seeing
the consequences of that policy. Forests don't get to go through
their natural burning-down process that they need to go through. I
can imagine how devastating I'd be if my house burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll tell you, there aren't enough airplanes in the world
to put these fires out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
