<HEADER>
A9874 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAFIRE-SCIENCE-COX     07-03 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRE-SCIENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pine needles prove to be perfect fuel for Florida wildfires
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- The answer to why Florida keeps burning
is below our feet and above our heads.
</P>
<P>
   Slash pines, with needles that decompose slowly, longleaf pines
and others pack flammable resin and have air between needles that
allow them to burn quick and hot. Some get so hot neighboring trees
``will just kind of explode. It will turn red and blow up into
flames,'' said Greg Thayer, fire information officer for the
Florida Unified Command.
</P>
<P>
   Below, brush is even more volatile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have been plotted moving at 30 to 40 mph,'' he said.
``Once it starts moving and has a high flame length, it will create
its own wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, what grows in central and southern Florida is perfect
fuel for wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   Typical Florida pine forests have an open canopy that allow
needles and scrub to dry quickly, making fire possible within a day
of rain, studies show. Hardwoods often stop fires, but when fires
get hot enough (upwards of 1,300 degrees), hardwood ignites as
well. Routine burning helps keep down the fuel, but most areas no
longer do controlled burns.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Jacksonville officials ``have been doing under-burning
for five to six years and they noticed when the fire moved through
there, it did not just pick up and run. It smoldered around and
didn't have ground fuel to carry it to the next tree,'' Thayer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eons ago, fires typically burned pine forests every two to three
years, usually ignited in June with heavy lightning when most
vegetation is dry and burns quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, roads, canals and firefighters quickly extinguish those.
</P>
<P>
   Studying wildfires, why they burn, how they burn, what their
smoke does to the environment and to our health has engaged
scientists around the world. Scientists from around the world are
gathering this month in Canada's Northwest Territory to study crown
fires, the most dangerous fires that light the tops of trees and
allow wildfires to move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   This year, U.S. scientists completed a 7-year study of the
effects of wildfire smoke on firefighters and surprisingly found it
caused no long-term health effects, said Dick Mangan, fire program
leader for the Missoula Technical and Development Center.
</P>
<P>
   While smoke depresses the immune system temporarily, they found
it caused only short-term problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your nose runs, eyes water and you hack and cough sometimes
for a couple of days,'' he said. ``In a real severe season of 90 to
100 days when they're out all the time, it can be a two to three
month period where they get the crud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
