<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-NEWHAZE-COX     07-03 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NEWHAZE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rehashes of ashes? No _ it's just dust
 &HT;    By Jodi Wetuski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The new haze hovering over parts of Texas is not
the smoky-brown variety that comes from south-of-the-border fires,
but one caused by dust particles that have floated all the way from
the Sahara Desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove to Austin and I thought, `Is it just me or is it
hazy?'' said Zoe Rascoe, air program manager for the Waco office of
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission. ``It's very
likely (Saharan dust) is what we're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Sahara, located in northern Africa, the wind whips up
dust storms every few days, said TNRCC meteorologist Bryan Lambeth.
In the winter, this dust sails over the Atlantic Ocean to Europe,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the summer, the same winds that bring hurricanes to the
Gulf Coast carry the dust to the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This occurs several times each summer, Lambeth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably always happened,'' he said. ``But it's much
easier to document now'' thanks to satellites and high-tech
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The first Saharan dust cloud of the summer swept through South
Texas on Sunday, Lambeth said. It peaked in North and Central Texas
on Tuesday, and it's fizzling out now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though this week's Saharan dust measurements have caused a
slight reduction in visibility, this particular cloud isn't the
worst one meteorologists have seen, Lambeth said. Last summer
produced more noticeable ``Saharan Dust Episodes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are likely paying more attention to this dust episode
because of a heightened public awareness of air quality issues,
brought on by the recent fires in Mexico and Central America,
Rascoe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican smoke haze has people pretty sensitive,'' Rascoe
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those fires, which have been brought under control in recent
weeks, burned for months. They churned out vast amounts of smoke,
prompting a few public health alerts across Texas for the elderly,
children and people with respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saharan dust isn't a big health hazard, Lambeth said.
It's mainly a concern for people with mold allergies, because mold
spores can hitch a ride with the dust particles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of dust traveling so many miles to Texas is amusing
to some TNRCC officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it's the first `Saharan Dust Episode' of the season,
but it's the first one of my life,'' said Rascoe, claiming she
wasn't aware of the phenomenon until this summer. ``I assumed (the
dust) was from West Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
