<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL KEEPS IT TOGETHER, DEFEATS DENMARK, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Brazil has demonstrated flair, style, and a
tendency to self-destruct during the World Cup finals. But the
Selecao gained credibility and enhanced its self-belief, and
finally got in the rhythm of (itals)jogo bonito(unitals) in
rallying to overcome Denmark, 3-2, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mastered the game and showed our qualities,'' said
Brazilian defender Cafu, who will be suspended for Wednesday's
semifinal at Marseilles against the winner of
Argentina-Netherlands. ``This is the spirit of our game _ we always
keep control of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Both coach Mario Zagallo and forward Bebeto redeemed themselves
after several days of intense criticism, as Zagallo made successful
adjustments and Bebeto scored the first Brazil goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a victory of willpower, a victory of a team that
knows how to win,'' Zagallo said. ``Brazil showed what the game
should be like in the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians reacted positively after surrendering an early
goal, eventually devising a defense to halt Michael Laudrup, and
opening room for Rivaldo to take over the midfield and score twice.
</P>
<P>
   The open play rewarded a festive crowd dominated by yellow-clad
Brazilians and augmented by red-clad Roligans, the Danes' opposite
of hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   The Laudrup brothers inspired the first goal, by Martin
Jorgensen, less than two minutes into the match. Peter Moller raced
past Junior Baiano on the left, nutmegging him on the way to the
edge of the penalty area, where he was fouled by Dunga. Michael
Laudrup quickly slipped the free kick to brother Brian, who went
toward the end line and drew the ball back to Jorgensen in front of
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Nigeria, which fell behind Denmark and continued to make
defensive tactical mistakes in a 4-1 second-round defeat, the
Brazilians retaliated in a cohesive, inspired manner. In other
words, they made certain the ball went to Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the first 10 minutes, Ronaldo struggled to elude the
marking of Glasgow Celtic defender Marc Rieper. Then, Ronaldo
retreated toward the center circle, took a pass from Dunga, and on
his first touch of the game went left, then cut the ball back with
his left foot. Bebeto stepped over the ball, touched it toward the
edge of the penalty area, and shot low just as Jan Heintze and
Thomas Helveg closed in.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo's first chance to go directly at the goal midway through
the half was halted from behind by Brian Laudrup, who could have
been cautioned, or even ejected. But referee Gamal Ghandour allowed
play to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians increased their intensity, pressing forward as
the Danes attempted to clear. Dunga stole from Helveg, laid off to
Ronaldo, who slipped the ball to Rivaldo on the left. Rivaldo, who
helped Barcelona win the Spanish championship last season, drew
goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel to the edge of the goal area, then
chipped over him into the far side of the goal for a 2-1 edge in
the 26th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Laudrup continued to threaten, setting up Moller for a
clear shot in the 35th minute. But Moller stumbled just inside the
penalty area and squandered the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark tied in the fourth minute of the second half as Brian
Laudrup roofed a missed bicycle kick clearance by Roberto Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Brazil responded. Dunga, who struggled to keep pace with
the Danes defensively, controlled the pace from defensive midfield.
He waited until Denmark had opened space in the midfield, then
found Rivaldo 50 yards from goal. As soon as Rivaldo faced the
goal, Schmeichel retreated and the Danish defenders allowed Rivaldo
to carry forward unhindered for another 15 yards. Schmeichel,
respecting Rivaldo's long-range shot, failed to cut the angle as
Rivaldo drilled a low drive into the right corner of the goal in
the 15th minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Rivaldo took over Leonardo's role and took
command of the midfield, once trapping a long pass on his chest,
then dribbling through three defenders into the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   But the Danes persisted, and Rieper barely missed off a
33d-minute corner and a header off the bar in the final minutes.
Zagallo added defensive reinforcements Emerson and Ze Roberto, but
even then the Brazilians continued to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team was fantastic, almost as good as the world
champions,'' Denmark coach Bo Johannson said. ``I didn't think my
players were that good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
