<HEADLINE>
(RESENDING TO CORRECT HEADLINE, SLUG)  
 TRUCKLIKE ASTRO IS ROUGH, TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) -The Chevrolet Astro is a box on wheels, a simple,
rugged device that has more in common with the Chevy van of the
'60s than it does with the popular front-drive minivans of today.
</P>
<P>
   As a rear-drive van with a truck frame, the Astro (and its
General Motors Corp. sibling, Safari) is also a survivor. It's the
last of its breed now that Ford Aerostar has gotten the ax. All the
other small vans are hybrid minivans, based on car chassis and
pulled by their front wheels, including Chevy's own Venture and
Ford's Windstar.
</P>
<P>
   Because Astro's handling and driveability are subpar compared
with the carlike minivan herd, some drivers brand it a throwback.
Indeed, the Astro seems to have missed the minivan revolution,
soldiering on with the clumsy handling, body sway and bounding ride
of an earlier generation of vans.
</P>
<P>
   But that's missing the point. The Astro is not trying to be a
car with cargo space, like the front-drivers, but a small truck
that can be used like a car.
</P>
<P>
   Astro is slightly bigger and significantly stronger than the
competition, with greater cargo capacity and enough towing muscle
to handle a 5,500-pound trailer, which would include many boats and
horse trailers. That's the beauty of the Astro and Safari, allowing
them to be used like full-size vans without the driver having to
shoulder such a big, unwieldy vehicle through traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there are those drivers who like the driving feel and
security of a truck, rather than the softer ride of a minivan.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful V-6, truck frame and rear-wheel drive provide the
extra towing and cargo utility, and many Astros serve as work
trucks and delivery vans. Our test Astro, an upscale LS version,
was equipped with optional all-wheel-drive, increasing its
usefulness on dirt roads and under snowy conditions, as well as
enhancing its maneuverability on slick surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the ride height and a certain level of roughness,
drivers and as many as seven passengers, depending on
configuration, should find the interior of the Astro as
accommodating as any minivan. The wheel wells intrude on foot space
up front, but cargo space behind the rear bench seat is superior to
the minis.
</P>
<P>
   The optional rear ``Dutch door'' tailgate is a mixed blessing.
Although it provides improved access for loading and unloading, it
can be a pain to open or close with your hands full. Also, Astro
and Safari fall short in the door wars, providing no second door on
the left side for rear passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The front-end styling changes lack the panache and individuality
of the old design.
</P>
<P>
   Cornering this high-profile truck can be dicey, requiring
moderation in speed and adding to the sense of driving a big van.
The steering is relatively quick, which seems odd considering the
limited handling capabilities. The brakes are effective, with
standard anti-lock technology.
</P>
<P>
   The driver sits high above the asphalt, requiring an extra
built-in step for climbing aboard, and some people may feel that
they're piloting a big cargo van rather than a lightweight truck.
The dashboard is high and the windshield seems small.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard is sensibly designed, with simple, accessible
gauges and switches in familiar Chevy style and configuration. The
upgraded stereo with CD, which included rear-seat controls, sounded
great. Seating is comfortable, though the bench seat in the back
has limited legroom, and there are plenty of nooks and cubbies for
stowage.
</P>
<P>
   The Astro and Safari have been around since the early days of
minivans, and although they are clumsy and rough riding, they do
provide an alternative for people who need extra space, cargo
capacity or towing strength. And in that respect, they pretty much
stand alone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chevrolet &QL; 
Astro LS &QL; 
- Vehicle type: Seven-passenger, three-door passenger van,
all-wheel drive. &QL; 
- Base price: $22,374. &QL; 
- Price as tested: $28,444. &QL; 
- Engine: 4.3-liter V-6, 190 horsepower at 4,400 rpm, 250
pounds-feet of torque at 2,800 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: Four-speed automatic. &QL; 
- Curb weight: 4,432 pounds. &QL; 
- Length: 189.8 inches. &QL; 
- EPA fuel economy: 15 city, 19 highway. &QL; 
- Highs: Versatility. Cargo, towing capacity. Interior space. &QL; 
- Lows: Awkward handling. Rough ride. Boxy styling. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
