<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENMAN FALLS TO SAMPRAS, DISAPPOINTING BRITONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Pete Sampras had more than just Tim Henman to overcome
in the Wimbledon semifinals. Over 16,000 fans jammed into Centre
Court Friday to root for their countryman against the defending
champion.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras ignored the English partisans to post a 6-3, 4-6,
7-5, 6-3 victory over Henman in what the world's No. 1 ranked
player termed a ``very intense'' match.
</P>
<P>
   The pivotal point came in the third set, when Sampras broke in
the 12th game to take it on his third set point, which came when
Henman belted a backhand volley into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised my level just a bit, hitting some good shots, and
that was the key to the match,'' said Sampras, in search of his
fifth Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of sets, we both had our moments, but in the
third set we both tightened up our tennis and it really came down
to me raising my level. That was the key and I knew that and I
think he knew that too.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was especially helpful to Henman in the second set.
``That's when the crowd had an opportunity to get behind me,'' said
the 12th-seeded Henman. ``They're the ones giving me a boost and I
think put him under a little added pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was more emotional than usual, arguing several times
with the umpire about what he thought were inconsistent calls by
Cyclops, the machine which determines whether serves are good or
not.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras, as usual, had his serve working with 16 aces to
Henman's seven. Henman, who had won just 50 percent of his second
serves, had 10 double faults to Sampras's seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a difference between us, it was probably our second
serves,'' said Sampras. ``His second serve probably let him down a
bit. I know Tim as a person and he'll work on that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decisive fourth set, Sampras notched the only service
break to go up, 3-1, and breezed from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was playing Tim and the crowd, so I was going to show
a little more emotion than usual and I did after that third set,''
said Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Henman said he didn't feel as though he let his country down by
not reaching the final. ``I've said all along that when I'm
winning, I'm not playing for the nation,'' he said, ``so when I
lose I'm not letting anyone down. When I'm on the court, it's about
myself. I win and I lose. It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Goran Ivanisevic defeated Richard Krajicek, 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 6-7
(5-7), 15-13, in the other semifinal, with the final set taking 77
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ninth straight time that Ivanisevic has defeated
Krajicek, the 1996 champion and ninth seed.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, Wimbledon runnerup in 1994 and 1992, had two match
points in the 10th game of the fourth set, but couldn't put
Krajicek away.
</P>
<P>
   Each had one break in the fifth set (Wimbledon plays out the
last set rather than going to a tiebreaker).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the 28th game, another break came, when Krajicek
netted the ball on a serve-and-volley backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic benefitted from serving before Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I was hoping was going to help me; it's easier to serve
first,'' Ivanisevic stated. ``I was enjoying the fifth set. I just
said, `OK, now you're going to be cool, you're not going to talk
too much, you're not going to talk at all, and just keep your mind
on what you have to do today, and you're going to win it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Invanisevic had been the forgotten player on the tour. But here
he is now, the No. 14 seed in the Wimbledon final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
