<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-VANGUARD-ART-3TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT VANGUARD, IT'S FULL SPEED AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ill., Mass., N.C., Ariz.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To hear John J. Brennan tell it, there's really nothing much
afoot at the Vanguard Group, the giant fund company he heads.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard definitely does not intend to join the rush to build a
financial services conglomerate, he said. Discount brokerage
services ``are never going to be a dominant part of what we are.''
Selling financial advice, he said, ``is not a core business.''
Overseas expansion? ``An experiment,'' Brennan responded. And
trouncing the competition ``is not a subject we talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are not what we do,'' Brennan, Vanguard's
chairman and chief executive, said in a recent interview at the
firm's rural corporate campus near Valley Forge, Pa. ``My job is to
keep people focused on what it is that made us successful in the
first place,'' namely, ``a high value, client-first philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Brennan is simply trying to lull the competition to
sleep. Despite his protestations, Vanguard is moving aggressively
to expand its fledgling efforts in overseas markets and in such
businesses as discount brokerage, annuities and financial planning.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, those efforts are likely to lessen
Vanguard's reliance on its popular stock index funds significantly
while challenging a flotilla of bigger competitors in a broad array
of fields.
</P>
<P>
   As for Vanguard's mutual fund business, which has $400 billion
under management, it is setting a blistering pace for its rivals.
So far in 1998, the company has taken nearly as much money into its
stock and bond funds as Fidelity Investments, Putnam Investments
and the American Funds combined.
</P>
<P>
   And since the beginning of the decade, Vanguard's market share
has grown at twice the rate of Fidelity's, to 8.5 percent at the
end of April, according to the Financial Research Corp., a data
gatherer in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Vanguard's growth has come from its stock-index funds.
Its most popular offering is the Index 500 portfolio, which by
simply seeking to match the stock market's performance has beaten
the returns of 9 out of every 10 American stock funds during the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months alone, that performance and the flood of
new cash flowing to the Index 500 fund have added $30 billion to
Vanguard's assets under management, which by itself is more money
than is managed by fund companies like Strong Funds, BancAmerica
Robertson Stephens or Gabelli Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   Yet index funds tell only part of the story. Three out of the
top five of Vanguard's biggest-selling stock funds last year were
actively managed portfolios. The company is grabbing a growing
portion of the market for 401(k) and similar retirement plans. And
in the second quarter, Vanguard surpassed the Franklin Templeton
Group as the largest manager of bond mutual funds, up from No. 5 at
the beginning of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Those who think Vanguard's hegemony is of the passing kind, like
that of so many other financial service giants, may well be
surprised. Because of its intense emphasis on keeping costs low,
``the advantages that Vanguard has are enduring,'' said Don
Phillips, president of Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``And who's in a better position to offer good bear market funds
_ bond or money market funds _ than Vanguard?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Vanguard turns greater attention to other parts of the
financial services business, investors are likely to benefit from
the same approach of low cost and convenience that Vanguard took to
mutual funds. At the very least, such moves will challenge
competitors to lower costs and improve service.
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives in brokerage, financial advice and international
activities that Vanguard is so aggressively pursuing are not
entirely new. But chances are that relatively few Vanguard
customers know about them. That is because Vanguard has taken a
determinedly low profile in all of its businesses outside of funds.
</P>
<P>
   The policy goes back to the insistence of Vanguard's founder,
John C. Bogle, that the company not tamper with the source of its
success.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the position taken by Bogle, then the company's
chairman, when Vanguard started its discount brokerage business in
1983. He promised the board he would not spend any money marketing
the service except to Vanguard shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vanguard will actively seek to have investors bring more of
their nonfund assets to Vanguard. By fall, it plans to offer
on-line trading of stocks and bonds, according to James H. Gately,
the managing director who oversees Vanguard's Individual Investor
Group. Vanguard will also expand the offerings of funds from other
companies in its Fund Access program, which is similar to the fund
supermarket programs offered by Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., Fidelity and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard also plans to step up the marketing of its financial
advisory services, particularly to retirement-plan investors.
Already, such services come in several forms. Investors can pay
$500 for one-time assessments of their portfolios or for estate
planning services. Or, for annual fees of 0.65 percent of assets or
less, investors can receive ongoing investment guidance from
Vanguard consultants. That compares with a typical financial
planner's fee of about 1 percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 percent of Vanguard's retirement-plan customers now
also have individual accounts with Vanguard, Gately said. Vanguard
hopes to increase that eventually to between one-third and
one-half.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, plenty of other firms offer discount brokerage,
financial planning and on-line trading services. What makes
Vanguard's moves so important is that it has already proved that
its low-cost approach can give it a major share of a highly
competitive business. That has been the history in the market for
retirement plans, in which Vanguard has become a top choice among
the corporate treasurers who oversee such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's share of the market for 401(k) retirement programs
has grown to 9.4 percent last year from 7.9 percent two years
earlier, according to Cerulli Associates, a Boston consulting firm.
That is little more than half of the percentage held by Fidelity,
whose share has grown even faster, to 18.9 percent last year from
15.8 percent two years earlier. But Vanguard remains solidly in
second place among all retirement-plan providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As 401(k) sponsors try to reduce costs over all, they have
taken up the battle cry of index management,'' with its lower
costs, said Karina Istvan, a consultant at Cerulli.
</P>
<P>
   And Vanguard's prices are, famously, among the lowest in the
industry. Since 1986, the average expense ratio for Vanguard's
funds has declined to its current level of 28 basis points _
equivalent to $2.80 for each $1,000 of investment _ from about 45
basis points. That compares with the industry's average expense
ratio of $12.40 for each $1,000 of investment.
</P>
<P>
   What allows Vanguard to keep costs so low, and gives it a
competitive advantage that few rivals can match, is its unusual
corporate structure. Unlike any other major mutual fund company,
the Vanguard Group is mutually owned, meaning that it is owned by
the shareholders of the funds it manages.
</P>
<P>
   While companies like Fidelity seek to profit from providing
their services to funds, the Vanguard Group is committed to
providing its services to the Vanguard funds at cost. That gives it
a powerful edge, especially since it seems unlikely that any other
profit-seeking rival would want to follow its lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the structure is far more flexible than it might seem. The
company can spend as it sees fit because its board decides what
``cost'' is. If, for instance, Vanguard's board were to approve the
offering of 24-hour toll-free phone service to shareholders _
something it has opposed doing in the past _ the cost would be
incorporated into the funds' expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Big capital projects, which require large sums of money,
generally require extraordinary financing measures. In 1992, for
example, when Vanguard decided to build its own office complex on
200 acres of land it had bought in Malvern, Pa., rather than
continuing to rent space, the company asked shareholders of its
funds to approve the expense. At the time, Vanguard estimated that
the move would save investors $6 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual system of providing services at cost, however, also
raises a challenging question. Will the company have access to the
capital it will need to grow?
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard answers yes. ``We've never felt capital-constrained,''
said F. William McNabb III, a managing director who oversees
Vanguard's Institutional Investor Group. If the company increased
its 28 basis-point average expense ratio to just 33, ``that would
provide roughly $200 million a year in incremental money to spend
on service and technology,'' McNabb said.
</P>
<P>
   The parsimony in the funds' expenses is completely in keeping
with Vanguard's philosophy and culture, forged over the company's
23 years by Brennan's mentor, Bogle, who remained the company's
chairman until his retirement early this year.
</P>
<P>
   While Bogle served as the public face of Vanguard, his
anti-establishment rhetoric often making him the fund industry's
most vehement critic, Brennan easily slipped into the role of
detail man. He joined Vanguard in 1982 from S.C. Johnson &AMP; Son, the
maker of household products like Windex, Raid and Drano, where he
was a planning associate.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning as an assistant to Bogle, he took on the chief
financial officer's role in 1985, rising to president in 1989 and
chief executive in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, when he was named chairman, the transition from
Bogle's command was completed. But Brennan is only beginning to
emerge in investors' minds from the shadow of Bogle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a profile of huge importance within the mutual fund
industry, and we have a great depth of talent to maintain and
enhance that profile,'' Brennan said. ``Am I and will I be the
demonstrative leader of the company? Absolutely. But we're in no
rush to run out and start putting people's faces in ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his hair is fully gray, Brennan's still-boyish looks,
even at 43, bring to mind a collegiate student-body president more
than the chairman of one of the country's biggest
financial-services companies. He is the picture of probity, in a
white button-down shirt (no cufflinks, of course) and tasseled
loafers (an indulgence, perhaps).
</P>
<P>
   Fund industry insiders have long known Brennan as a steel-willed
competitor. He runs as many as 10 miles a day, more when he's
training for one of the few marathons he runs each year. Obsessed
with the details of performance, he checks statistics each day on
how quickly Vanguard's telephone representatives are able to
respond to callers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And his interest in the minutiae of the business extends down to
interactions with employees. Few events are as hoped for, or as
feared, as the arrival of one of Brennan's handwritten notes,
penned in his trademark green ink and commenting on some aspect of
the business.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping those employees satisfied will be an increasingly
difficult task for Brennan as Vanguard grows. Exporting the esprit
de corps of the Pennsylvania headquarters to new employees in
Charlotte, N.C., and in Phoenix, where Vanguard recently opened
large service centers, or abroad makes the job even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Vanguard's management structure is very flat for a
company its size, with 8,000 employees overseen by 10 managing
directors and just one intermediate level of management. That might
give the average employee little opportunity for upward movement.
</P>
<P>
   This situation appears to have been a factor in a recent rash of
defections in the fixed-income department. Several senior traders
and at least one upper-level portfolio manager left for rival
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Ian A. McKinnon, the managing director for the fixed-income
division, said he believed that the competition for talent in the
fund industry had led to some of the departures in the last year.
But he acknowledged that in a company with few layers of
organization, advancement can be slow in coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our portfolio management staff has been in place for a long
time,'' McKinnon said. ``People in the next level down in the
organization get impatient. Some of those people availed themselves
of the chance to manage money elsewhere. If someone is offering an
opportunity like that, a reasonably ambitious person is going to
give it consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   With Vanguard branching out, more opportunities might emerge
within the company, too. For instance, Vanguard is moving to use
its growing expertise in retirement plans to develop overseas
business, first in Australia, then in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're very optimistic about the global expansion
opportunities at Vanguard,'' said Jeremy G. Duffield, who is
overseeing the company's Australian effort. And as the world's
fifth-largest market for corporate- and government-sponsored
pension plans, Australia provides plenty of opportunity for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard will not be operating its overseas businesses in
entirely the same fashion as it does its United States fund group,
said Michael S. Miller, a managing director who oversees planning
and development. They will be priced to earn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do overseas we have got to do on a for-profit
basis, showing a return to our U.S. shareholders,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   What could tie an anchor to Vanguard's ambitious plans? A major
downturn in the American stock market. Some industry experts
surmise that such an event, after an extended period of fervor for
the Index 500 fund among investors, could severely test Vanguard's
long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vanguard Index 500 fund has become a proxy for the
Vanguard Group in the minds of many investors, much as the Magellan
fund did for Fidelity,'' said Burton J. Greenwald, a fund industry
consultant in Philadelphia. ``When the Magellan fund
underperformed, the perception that something was amiss at Fidelity
clouded all of their funds, despite the fact that many of the
Fidelity funds continued to furnish superior results. Vanguard is
susceptible to the same risk if the market falters.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, those worries have not slowed Vanguard's growth a bit.
The company continues to exceed its peers significantly in
gathering assets, raising the inevitable question of whether, or
when, it will push ahead of Fidelity to become the largest American
fund company.
</P>
<P>
   On that score, Brennan firmly declares his indifference. ``I
would not be surprised to see two firms merge, leaving us further
down the list from No. 2,'' he said. ``As long as we do the right
thing for our clients, it isn't a goal for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
