<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH FINDS 150-YEAR-OLD TIME CAPSULE, PONDERS OWN FUTURE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you were to put together a package for your
descendants, with information that would describe your life and
times for people a century from now, what would you put in it?
</P>
<P>
   That question has lately engaged the Plymouth Church of the
Pilgrims, an independent, congregational church that is a Brooklyn
Heights landmark, whose pulpit was originally occupied by the great
anti-slavery crusader, the Rev. Henry Ward Beecher.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as Plymouth Church was celebrating its
sesquicentennial, workers discovered a lead box placed inside a
wall by the church's mid-19th century founders. Broken open, the
box revealed rather impersonal contents, mainly newspapers and
pamphlets from May 1849, when the present building was going up.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the idea of creating a new time capsule, one that
would give a broad range of information about the current church
and its members, has given the congregation an unusual opportunity
to think about its identity and its hopes for the future, said
Frank Decker, president of the church's council.
</P>
<P>
   This has come at a time when the congregation's leaders have
been wrestling, in study sessions and discussions, with the larger
question of what role a Protestant church can and should play, for
its members and for the larger society.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the church's offices, at 75 Hicks St., Decker
and the Rev. Sharon Blackburn, the church's senior minister, talked
about the challenges facing a church like Plymouth, in a culture
that is at once more secular and more religiously diverse than ever
before. The once-dominant position of Protestant churches has been
eroded, and the membership of many individual congregations,
including Plymouth, has gradually shrunk,
</P>
<P>
   In the church's current annual report, a copy of which will be
placed in the new time capsule, Ms. Blackburn wrote that the church
is ``experiencing and now living through our most major spiritual
challenge in some large number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said in the interview, ``We're beginning to look ahead,
we're beginning to see what we might be able to offer.'' Later, she
cited the results of a demographic study of local neighborhoods,
showing a high concentration of people 25 to 40 years old. ``This
is the group that wants a very strong Christian education program
for their children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One might optimistically argue that Plymouth Church has faced
major spiritual challenges before, certainly if one looks back to
its early days as an institution dedicated, from a Christian
standpoint, to the destruction of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   The church's founders were largely New Englanders who had
settled in Brooklyn (as were the people who started the nearby
Church of the Pilgrims, with which Plymouth merged in 1934). In
hiring Beecher, they gained a preacher whose convictions and pulpit
skills gave him national stature. The church became a major stop on
the Underground Railroad. When Abraham Lincoln visited New York in
February 1860 to give what became a famous address at Cooper Union
in Manhattan, he crossed the East River to hear Beecher. (A small
plaque marks the pew where he sat.)
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of its past are also appreciated at the church.
Ms. Blackburn took out a copy of the church's bylaws, which
describe Plymouth's purpose as combining Christian nurture and
community with a certain social action. The church, the bylaws
state, is dedicated to bringing together Christ's followers in
worship and to pledging its members ``will work and pray for the
transformation of this world into the Kingdom of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This church,'' Ms. Blackburn said, ``has always had a strong
biblical faith, and yet that faith has been able to speak to
contemporary issues in such a way that it would rally people.''
These days, she said, that would place the church in the
theological middle, far from fundamentalism, but not on the left,
either.
</P>
<P>
   In their study of what Plymouth Church should be about, its
congregational leaders came up with six purposes, Decker said,
among them an emphasis on worship and education within the church
and on love of one's neighbors, within and outside the church
walls. ``You can't just live on the laurels of the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blackburn said that sentiment was widely felt as the church
marked its 150th anniversary last year. ``While it was a wonderful
focal point, we decided the past wasn't enough,'' she said. ``We
needed to make our history.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one item from the celebrations will go in the time
capsule, a compact disc recording of a concert in the sanctuary in
May 1997, to be included with the hope that the technology to play
it will still exist a century from now.
</P>
<P>
   Another item to go in will be a sermon outlining a vision for
the church's future, written by Ms. Blackburn, in which she
described a hope that the church would emphasize its essential
Christian beliefs as the basis for all it did. She said she
addressed the sermon ``to our grandchildren's children,'' and she
closed it with a blessing, signed in the name of the current
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
