<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEACHER PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nancy Cohen teaches American history to eighth graders. The
typical 13-year-old's barometer for injustice being what it is, her
students are especially receptive to the lessons of the past.
</P>
<P>
   In the time between September and June, her classes used to
cover the period between colonization and westward expansion. Her
students simulated the Constitutional Convention in their classroom
and recreated Civil War battles in schoolyard games of capture the
flag.
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, after new statewide curriculum standards mandated
that she make it through Reconstruction, Nancy Cohen found herself
teaching more of a survey course. ``It's as though they put us on a
treadmill and turned up the speed,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the two weeks since school in Newton, Mass. ended, she has
been listening with morbid fascination to the public pounding she
and her teaching colleagues are taking from parents and politicians
alike. News that only 41 percent of would-be teachers passed a
basic skills test triggered much of the outcry but Nancy Cohen,
ever the history teacher, thinks there is more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long has it been since these people have been in a
classroom?'' asks the 18-year teaching veteran. ``Do they have any
idea the number of balls we are being asked to juggle?''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just the pressure to cover more material in less time.
There is also the matter of the MCAS, those standarized tests
introduced last spring for fourth, eighth and tenth graders. Nancy
Cohen spent the year teaching American history only to have her
students tested on the ancient civilizations they had studied in
grade six. ``Now I know that if I want my students to test well I
have to build in at least one week every year to review what they
learned in the previous two years,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The erosion of teaching time is only one problem. The very
nature of the classroom has changed in fundamental ways since Board
of Education Chairman John Silber and Acting-Gov. Paul Cellucci
were toting bookbags.
</P>
<P>
   Were Silber and Cellucci to drop by Nancy Cohen's class in
September, her 24 students would hardly notice the presence of
additional adults. There could be three or four aides with her in
the classroom: an aide for the noncommunicative, wheelchair-bound
cerebral palsy student; an aide for the boy in the BRIDGE program
for students with behavioral problems; an interpreter for the deaf
students.
</P>
<P>
   This does not include the special education teachers with whom
Nancy Cohen will confer regularly about several students in her
class who will have IEPs (Individual Education Plans) or GEAPS
(General Education Accomodation Plans.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The day when you could give one homework assignment and grade
them all the same way is over. A student with one kind of learning
disability may have an education plan that requires me not to grade
his spelling; another plan might require that a child be given more
time to complete an assignment; an exceptionally bright student
might need extra work to supplement the textbook. I have a
classroom full of individuals. The state tells me I can't judge
them all by the same standard, but then turns around and gives them
all the same standardized test. Does this make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. But the debate about education reform, like the
one about welfare reform before it, is less about good sense than
simplistic solutions. No one, least of all teachers like Nancy
Cohen, opposes building accountability into the profession. ``I was
as horrified as anyone by how many candidates flunked the
competency test,'' she says. But how will Silber and Cellucci
measure a teacher's ability to engage students, to excite them
about learning? How will they attract the brightest students to a
career held in such low esteem that a fair number of parents assume
they could do a better job than their child's teacher? And how
accountable will they hold themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, got my masters degree in education from Boston
University when John Silber was president of the university. It was
a Mickey Mouse proram, at best. Whose responsibility is it to make
schools of education more challenging and more accountable? Didn't
John Silber hand out some of the degrees he is so quick to
disparage?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
