<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCK-CD-REVIEWS-NYT &LR;      07-03 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-CD-REVIEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK CDS: GO, GO BOY POWER _ SMELLS LIKE TEAM SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The base runners filling Yankee Stadium aren't the
only boys exuding grace and sweat this summer, and the World Cup
isn't the only game that has crowds chanting in the stands. Rock
'n' roll, the athletic activity favored by outsiders who never
wanted to be jocks, is often at its finest when played as a team
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, three bands that exemplify this spirit _ Rocket From
the Crypt, Girls Against Boys and Rancid _ are touring in support
of new bids for the jukebox crown. Those who like to watch women
win must wait until late summer, when Liz Phair, Hole, Polly Jean
Harvey and Lauryn Hill stage their own musical Olympics. For now,
though, it's the guys' turn to flex some muscle and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Girls Against Boys
</P>
<P>
   New York has not been home to many championship rock bands of
late, but this quartet of transplants from Washington give all the
signs of being contenders. ``Freakonica'' (DGC), the band's major
label debut, finds G.V.S.B. (the group's hip nickname) in
competitive shape, but its faults make one wonder if this club will
be like last season's Knicks, rich in skills but lacking focus.
</P>
<P>
   The band certainly owns a blueprint for success. After starting
life as a hardcore punk band, a past evident in Alexis Fleisig's
pugnacious drumming, G.V.S.B. stretched to accommodate the dub
reggae fascinations of the bassist Johnny Temple and the disco
fantasies of Eli Janney on keyboards, samplers and second bass.
Scott McCloud, the guitarist and front man, penetrated this whirl
of influences with his lascivious growl. The result was music about
the pleasures of electrified rhythm, stepping lightly from the rock
club to the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Freakonica,'' the elements still churn together, but the
blend gets a little too smooth. The insistent bass line of ``Park
Avenue'' sets the right mood, while the delightfully mean-spirited
``Psycho-Future'' and the frenetic ``Pleasurized'' achieve
satisfying intensity. Often, though, the musicians' thrilling
connections are compromised by Nick Launay's production, which
slicks up McCloud's voice and overprocesses rough spots that the
band could work through on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Freakonica'' is an indication that G.V.S.B. will grow
only stronger with time. Live, they're already there, as they'll
prove at the Bowery Ballroom on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket From the Crypt
</P>
<P>
   This San Diego-based sextet trades in a different kind of
masculine bravado from G.V.S.B.'s sexy prowl. Led by the suave yet
goofy singer John ``Speedo'' Reis, ``RFTC'' (Interscope) delves
into rock's rowdy history to turn punk clubs into sock hops.
</P>
<P>
   Speedo and his gang love garage rock, but on ``RFTC'' they turn
toward slightly older forms of boisterousness. Speedo models his
shtick after the jump-jazz king Louis Jordan, singing about love
and doglike desire in a deep moan that prompts hearty choruses from
his band. The call-and-response of ``Lipstick'' and ``Let's Get
Busy'' conjure scenes of beefy guys whistling after women in the
street; Holly Golightly, guest vocalist on the album's first track,
``Eye on You,'' proves that the ladies can talk back.
</P>
<P>
   The camaraderie felt in the vocals is reinforced by the music,
an exuberant mix of aggressive rock, swing horns and ska rhythms.
Comical horns and speedy drumming keep the band's mood meter on
high. Rocket doesn't hesitate to celebrate the obvious, as in
``Break It Up,'' which borrows from the sports arena anthem by Gary
Glitter, ``Rock and Roll Part 2.''
</P>
<P>
   But saying no to subtlety is part of this band's charm. Fans
claim its live show is rampantly entertaining; catch it at
Summerstage on Saturday, when Rocket opens for Question Mark and
the Mysterians.
</P>
<P>
   Rancid
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a team isn't just a team: it's a family. This
well-loved California punk band (headed here with the Warped Tour
in August) believes in that communal ideal. Upholding the socially
conscious, musically uncompromising agenda set down by 1970s bands
like the Clash, Rancid makes invigorating rock meant to inspire
listeners to be as radical in daily life as they are in the dance
hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Won't Wait''(Epitaph), the follow-up to 1995's ``... And
Out Come the Wolves,'' makes this goal more explicit than ever.
Songs address the war in the Balkans, decry inhumane labor
conditions and even invoke those old favorites of the left, the
Sandinistas. Musical reports from the spots where bohemia meets the
down and out, from the Lower East Side to Echo Park, bear the stamp
of personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   This would all add up to boring agitprop if not for Rancid's
fractured humanity. The vocalists, Tim Armstrong and Lars
Fredriksen, blurt and growl as if they're in the midst of losing a
fistfight, but righteous anger and hope turn their garbled
utterances into testaments. Behind them, the band rages and rolls,
its punky reggae style (old enough to be a form of classic rock)
sounding as fresh as if it had just discovered it.
</P>
<P>
   Rancid exists to celebrate the bonds music makes, and it
welcomes many extended family members here, including the reggae
artist Buju Banton, members of the ska band the Specials and Roger
Mirel, of the hardcore group Agnostic Front. For Rancid, team
spirit promises more than just personal achievement. The band's
exaltation of rock as symbolic politics _ able to change a few
lives, if not the world _ elevates the stakes of its game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
