<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-SMALLBIZ04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small businesses in the South saw slowest growth rate
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Southern small businesses_ considered the leader
among small businesses _ had the slowest growth rate in the nation
during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   One reason: the tight labor market, according to a national
quarterly survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the advantages the South had always had was that labor
was pretty cheap,'' said Roger Harris, president of Padgett
Business Services, an Athens-based accounting tax firm that
specializes in small businesses and conducts the quarterly surveys.
``Now, it's catching up. To find good people, it costs more.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the nation rode a wave of growth between
January and March (10.4 percent increase in operating income),
small business owners in the South reported an 8.6 percent drop in
operating income.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not losing money, their rate of growth is not as
strong as it has been,'' Harris said. He cautioned against making a
snap judgment about the performance until second quarter results
are released in early August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could turn around the next quarter. I don't want to be too
alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey polled 3,865 small businesses, most in the retail and
service industries. The companies employ fewer than 20 workers.
Padgett began the survey, which looks at business patterns by
region, in 1992. Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   Total sales were up in all four regions. With the exception of
the South, operating income was up as well.
</P>
<P>
   Wages continued to increase in all four regions, with the West
recording the largest increase at 17.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite positive national results in the first quarter, small
business owners predict slow stagnant second quarter sales and slow
job growth for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very disturbing,'' said Dan Sautner, Padgett chairman.
``Given the second quarter always has been the strongest for small
businesses, these predictions, if accurate, could turn 1998 into an
exceptionally challenging year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
