</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL ESCAPES WITH 3-2 WIN OVER DENMARK  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Brazil escaped with a riveting 3-2 win over
Denmark Friday night in a World Cup quarterfinal match that was as
much about redemption as victory.
</P>
<P>
   For Brazil, the thrill of victory is routinely compromised by
the agony of criticism from fans and reporters. Only beautiful
domination is acceptable. Anything less might as well be defeat.
Even its 1994 World Cup title was dismissed by many as an
unfortunate return to the soccer of defense and individualism.
</P>
<P>
   No two players had been reprimanded more in this World Cup than
the forward Bebeto and the midfielder Rivaldo. Both were being
blamed for the subdued scoring of Ronaldo, considered the world's
greatest player, who has now delivered only three goals in five
matches. Bebeto was supposedly too old and slow at age 34. Rivaldo
was thought to be greedy, holding the ball too long as Ronaldo's
accurate feet waited impatiently.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, it was Rivaldo and Bebeto who delivered all of
Brazil's goals and who drew cheers instead of boos. Bebeto scored
once and Rivaldo twice as Brazil attacked from all angles, but
Denmark was fearless and it very nearly took the game away
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil now advances to the semifinals against either Argentina
or the Netherlands, but it has yet to fulfill its vast potential as
it seeks an unprecedented fifth World Cup title. Brazil made two
stark defensive mistakes Friday night and grew lucky near the end
when the Denmark defender Marc Rieper fired wide and hit the
crossbar from inside the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denmark dignified this game,'' said Marion Zagallo, the
Brazilian coach. ``We won, but Denmark also could have won. It was
a victory of power and will.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunga, Brazil's crusty old captain, suffocated the Denmark
attack repeatedly in midfield and contributed directly to two
goals. So did Ronaldo in the role of playmaker and decoy. He had
been the subject of a national convulsion this week after Brazil's
team doctor reported that he was as much as 4 1/2-pounds
overweight. The doctor later changed directions as deftly as
Ronaldo in the open field, saying the star striker was at his ideal
weight.
</P>
<P>
   And the tendinitis in Ronaldo's left knee that caused him to
miss a practice did not cause him to miss a minute of Friday
night's quarterfinal or disrupt his underappreciated ability to
pass the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But Denmark was direct and daring, and it caught Brazil
off-guard in the second minute by hurrying a free kick just outside
the penalty area. Brian Laudrup dribbled around the Brazilian wall
and laid a pass off to Martin Jorgensen, who finished the clever
set piece to put Denmark ahead 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not afraid,'' said Bo Johansson, the Denmark coach.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Denmark lacked the speed of Brazil's Cafu and Roberto Carlos
on the flanks and the constrictive defense of Dunga and Cesar
Sampaio in midfield. Brazil equalized in the 11th minute when
Bebeto slipped behind the Danish defenders, took an exquisite pass
from Ronaldo and delivered a low blast from 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand,'' Bebeto had complained before the
game. ``The others make bad passes, but the fault is always mine.''
</P>
<P>
   He had argued with Dunga during the Morocco game in the first
round and had accused Ronaldo of hogging the ball during the 1996
Summer Olympics. But he was not a sympathetic figure to Brazil's
fans, who preferred the injured Romario or the substitutes Denilson
and Edmundo.
</P>
<P>
   Bebeto was booed unfailingly when he was replaced in the second
half of Brazil's first four games. But Friday night, he pounded his
chest after scoring, as if to show that he still had the heart of a
champion. And he left to a chorus of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo, too, thawed frozen opinions. In the 27th minute, Dunga
stole a pass, Ronaldo fed Rivaldo like a point guard on the left
wing and Rivaldo deftly finished the counterattack. But the 2-1
lead was tenuous. Five minutes into the second half, Roberto Carlos
failed to clear a header, whiffing on a needless scissors kick, and
Michael Laudrup pounced on the loose ball for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the 60th minute, Rivaldo drilled the winning shot from 22
yards, appearing to surprise the Danish goalie Peter Schmeichel.
The Great Dane, as he is known, is considered the world's best
goalkeeper, but Schmeichel dropped to the ground too quickly Friday
night and was curiously vulnerable. Still, Denmark kept attacking
and missed twice at the end by an excruciatingly small margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hard match, honest, open,'' Zagallo said, ``the
way football should be played in the World Cup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
