<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-     07-03 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ They were called dinosaurs and fossils. Their coach, Berti
Vogts, was called the zoo keeper.
</P>
<P>
   But the Germans seem to have proved yet again that when you play
an ageless style of soccer _ tight on the defensive line, strong in
the air, opportunistic around the goal _ individual ages hardly
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are never going to play like the Brazilians, so there is no
point in trying,'' Vogts said. ``We must put faith in our
traditional values and our system. Then, we can beat anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans have.
</P>
<P>
   The success of this veteran German side in the World Cup should
come as no surprise to anyone. Yet for some it did, not because of
what World Cup history said but because of what these players'
birth certificates said.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, or West Germany, is the only nation that has managed to
qualify for at least the World Cup quarterfinals in 12 consecutive
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1934, when Germany last did not make the quarterfinals,
the Germans have been known to play the same, familiar game _ using
tall, fast players, perfectly executing the attack and refusing to
give any opponent the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is how we win,'' Vogts said. ``You don't want to change
how you win.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that seems to have changed for Germany is its
age.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team whose starting goalkeeper is 36, is held down at
midfield by a 37-year-old and whose top goal-scorers are 35 and 31.
</P>
<P>
   In an elimination game against Mexico, in which Germany came
back from a late 1-0 deficit to win on goals by Juergen Klinsmann,
35, and Oliver Bierhoff, 31, the average age of Germany's starters
was nearly 33.
</P>
<P>
   Only five players on the roster are under 30. Only three of
those 20-somethings see regular playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of experience on this team, and you cannot
underestimate experience in the World Cup,'' Klinsmann said. ``We
know how to fight to the last minute. We don't want to go home
early, and we know what it is to play these kinds of important
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, numerous players on this 1998 German side were on the
team that raised the Cup at Italia '90.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsmann and midfield general Lothar Matthaus, 37, started on
that 1990 team. Keeper Andreas Kopke, 36, was on that team, too.
And Vogts was an assistant coach to ``Kaiser'' Franz Beckenbauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an experienced team, you're able to overcome
some of the internal problems that every team has,'' said Vogts,
alluding to the longtime feud between Klinsmann and Matthaus that
some blamed for Germany's 1994 quarterfinal exit. ``This team is
much different than 1994's. The mentality of this team is totally
different, when in 1994 the players were only thinking of playing
time and playing against Italy in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the Bulgarians would be a pushover, and we were beaten
by them. This team is much better together than that one. We won't
look ahead of the job we have in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Today in Lyon, this German team faces another squad that many
consider a pushover, Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   But experience tells these dinosaurs different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remember the feeling of winning the Cup in 1990, and we
want that feeling again,'' Klinsmann said. ``We also remember the
feeling of losing to Bulgaria four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we will never get to the championship if we don't win
this game. Croatia has very strong players who play for great
(European) clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to have to come from behind again like we had to
do against Mexico. We have to raise our game from the start and
beat them. We have to play our kind of soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worked for decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
