<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PEONY-ART-2TAKE     07-03 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR `PEONY PAVILION' DIRECTOR, A LONG 2 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chen Shi-Zheng, you might have thought, had already
paid dues enough for a lifetime. Now he has paid again.
</P>
<P>
   Chen is the director of the magnificent production of the
Chinese opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' by the Shanghai Kunqu Opera
Company that was to have opened the Lincoln Center Festival next
Tuesday evening and formed its flagship. But after two years of
painstaking preparation and eight months of intensive rehearsal,
the project ran aground at the last minute on the stony will of Ma
Bomin, the director of the Shanghai Municipal Bureau of Culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the longest two weeks of my life,'' the
35-year-old Chen said Friday morning at his apartment near
Washington Square Park, looking drained but typically resilient. He
had returned a mere eight hours before from eight months in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   His original plan for Friday had been to meet the arriving
members of the company at the airport and, with the younger ones,
begin a weekend of shopping and sightseeing. ``I had promised to
take them to the Empire State Building, the South Street Seaport,
the fireworks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after a chaotic two weeks in which the sets and costumes for
the production were detained for a time at the Shanghai
International Airport and the players were sent back into rehearsal
for the benefit of the bureau's censors, the company was not
allowed to leave China. So instead, Chen was spending the day
fielding phone calls from around the world relaying conflicting
rumors: that some late miracle might still be possible; that the
company had just been packed off on a two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   After a preview in Shanghai, the production, running some 20
hours over six evenings, was damned for ``pornography,''
``superstition'' and ``feudalism.'' No matter that the
``pornography,'' chiefly the description of a subsidiary character,
Sister Stone, and the physical condition that enforced her
virginity, came right out of the 1598 text of the work by Tang
Xianzu, deemed one of the great masterpieces of Chinese literature.
Indeed, Chen had already compressed the offending discussion
considerably to keep talk of private parts out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The other two charges related chiefly to a funeral procession
for Du Liniang, the young heroine who pines away for lack of love,
in which dolls were burned in line with ancient Chinese folk custom
and much surviving practice. ``Feudal,'' it seems, is an
all-purpose condemnation applied to any part of pre-communist China
to which the pronouncing body happens to take exception. ``It's a
very heavy-handed word,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was also cited for transgressions of the style of Kunqu,
the most venerable and refined of the 360-odd types of Chinese
opera. What he actually violated, in his efforts to return to the
spirit of a 17th-century performance (if in fact the work had ever
been performed complete), was tradition as it now stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They criticized me for not using a proscenium stage and
brightly colored lights,'' Chen said. ``But there were no
proscenium theaters and brightly colored lights in the 17th
century. I made it clear from the very outset that I wanted to take
`The Peony Pavilion' as the subject and Kunqu as the vocabulary,
the expression. But they wanted to reverse that.''
</P>
<P>
   The production is to travel to Paris, for the Festival d'Automne
in November, then to Sydney, Australia, and Hong Kong. Lincoln
Center plans to forward the sets and costumes to Paris, said Nigel
Redden, the festival director, but it is far from clear whether the
company will be allowed to travel then or what the production might
be like, with or without Chen's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The entire incident carries deeply unsettling resonance in
Shanghai, Chen said. It was there, in 1966, that Jiang Qing, Mao's
wife, with her criticism of a theatrical production, set off the
momentous Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Momentous, certainly, for Chen, who was born in Changsha, in the
southern province of Hunan, in 1963. When he was 4, his mother, a
schoolteacher, was killed in front of their home by a stray bullet
fired during a rowdy, jingoistic parade. The bullet narrowly missed
the boy's head, he said, and the bloody scene constitutes his first
memory.
</P>
<P>
   His elder sister was there, too. She, like their father, a
public-health official, was sent to the country for
``re-education.'' The boy, spared because of his tender age, was
left to live with various relatives. He has never again seen his
father who, though still alive, was left brutalized and infirm.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people died,'' Chen said. ``The southwestern provinces
were the most violent area. Everybody was taking the opportunity to
kill his enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen, in fact, developed his love of Chinese opera attending any
number of funerals. Opera performances were banned, but mourning
was permitted. In southern China, death was celebrated in Taoist
fashion, for three days and three nights. Among other activities,
opera masters performed songs around the coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened a whole new world to me,'' Chen said. ``It taught me
traditional music, and it introduced me to the idea of
impersonating someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Hunan School of the Arts reopened at the end of the
revolution in 1976, Chen enrolled in the opera program, and was
among the first graduates. He thus learned Huaga opera, indigenous
to Hunan. He then went to Beijing and worked in Peking opera.
</P>
<P>
   One of the criticisms recently leveled against Chen is that he
was not a specialist in the rarefied style of Kunqu when he took up
``The Peony Pavilion.'' But he is experienced in several styles,
and he surrounded himself with Kunqu experts and immersed himself
in study with an enthusiasm, not to say ferocity, that can well be
imagined by anyone who saw him at work in Shanghai. In effect, he
produced as well as directed the production and turned a $500,000
budget into an incomparably beautiful silk purse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Already in Beijing, Chen was restless with the conventions of
Chinese opera and avid to find more expressive modes. He studied
Western opera, made commercials and sang pop music. He also met
Heather Steliga, an American poet, and married her in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Their move to New York in that year began as a visit to Ms.
Steliga's parents in Boston. On learning of the massacre in
Tiananmen Square, they decided not to return to China.
</P>
<P>
   Chen earned a master's degree in performance studies from New
York University, where he now teaches. He has returned periodically
to work in China, as he did two years ago, directing a production
of Euripides' ``Bacchae'' with the China National Beijing Opera
Company. Though typically controversial, it met with acclaim in
Beijing and Hong Kong and is still touring around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He has no idea what opportunities may arise in China now or how
he will feel about them. For the moment he is grateful to have got
out of the country without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said he told reporters: ``Make me a scapegoat. Call me a
pornographer. I can take that. Just don't call me
anti-revolutionary.'' For that last offense, which used to be
capital, he might still have been in China despite his American
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, he can at least celebrate Independence Day in style.
``Suddenly I feel I can breathe again,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
