<SLUG> BC-BRAGG-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLY BRAGG: SONGS MADE FOR YOU AND ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Billy Bragg doesn't want Woody Guthrie to be
remembered as a humorless, two-dimensional agitprop songwriter. He
wants to avoid that same fate himself; Bragg, too, writes songs
with direct political messages as well as songs on more personal
topics.
</P>
<P>
   After being invited by Guthrie's heirs to dig through an archive
of 2,500 Guthrie lyrics whose melodies were never recorded, and to
write new tunes for them, Bragg has become more of a Guthrie fan
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   His new album, ``Mermaid Avenue'' (Elektra), is a collaboration
with the country-rock band Wilco, which backs him up and plays its
own Guthrie finds.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bottom Line on Thursday night, amid a droll line of
between-song patter, Bragg praised Guthrie as a both a punk
forebear and a lyricist who ``mixes the personal with the
political.'' He chose Guthrie lyrics that can be whimsical and
rude, affectionate and pensive, connecting them back to Elizabethan
ballads and forward to Guthrie's rock heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg began his set alone with his electric guitar, then was
joined by Ian McLagan on keyboards. From his own material, he chose
songs about love's complications and about the death of his father.
His voice, which was once an untamed cockney bray, has grown more
controlled and gentle; he comes across as a regular guy trying to
muddle through.
</P>
<P>
   Then his band joined him, and the music started to romp. ``She
Came Along to Me,'' about women and equality, chugged like an Elvis
Costello song; ``Walt Whitman's Niece,'' about womanizing and
poetry, was oompahing country-rock. ``I Guess I Planted,'' a
reflection on unions and solidarity, rolled along like a shuffle by
the Band. ``My Flying Saucer,'' one of an additional 25 Guthrie
settings that don't appear on the album, used an
Appalachian-sounding melody above double-time garage-rock. For
``California Stars,'' Bragg's band changed Wilco's wistful ballad
into a New Orleans mambo, as Bragg sang ``This Land Is Your Land''
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie's own talking blues and children's songs contradict any
notion that he was a dull propagandist. But Bragg and Wilco have
rediscovered a Guthrie who speaks to them: a lover, a joker and a
questioner as well as a protest singer. Bragg, who was already on a
similar path, now has one more model.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
