<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAFTA-ENVIRON-NYT &LR;      07-03 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-ENVIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION PROBLEMS FESTER SOUTH OF THE BORDER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ Every day Ciudad Juarez, the Mexican city
across the Rio Grande from El Paso, produces 75 million gallons of
raw sewage, much of which flows through irrigation ditches into the
river, the prime source of water for nearly every community in both
Mexico and the United States between here and the Gulf of Mexico.
Juarez has no sewage treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   In Tijuana, Mexico, near San Diego, a sewage treatment system is
in the planning stage, but for now the city continues to discharge
sewage into the Pacific, periodically requiring American health
officials to close beaches in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Free Trade Agreement was supposed to provide
the border area with billions of dollars to address air and water
pollution _ and, in fact, both Juarez and Tijuana recently had
financing for sewage treatment systems approved by the bank set up
under what were known as NAFTA's side accords.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly five years after NAFTA was ratified, not a single
environmental project financed by the bank is in operation. To the
more than 10 million people living along the border between the
United States and Mexico, the money promised for the region's
serious environmental problems is too long and too little in the
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened so far does not at all meet the great promises
that were made,'' said Beatriz Vera, a program officer with the
Paso del Norte Health Foundation, which works to improve health
conditions in El Paso, Juarez and southeastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that environmental conditions along the border
are making people sick. On the Texas side, rates of hepatitis,
diarrheal diseases and gastroenteritis _ all commonly linked to
water and sanitation problems _ are two to six times the state
average. And conditions are worse on the Mexican side.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say pollution problems along the border are
especially daunting because the solution often lies on the other
side, in Mexico. That is true for water pollution in the Rio
Grande, stretches of which remain a dumping ground for human and
industrial wastes, and for air pollution like the gray haze that
periodically engulfs the remote Big Bend National Park in Texas,
giving it the smoggiest air of any national park in the West.
</P>
<P>
   American officials trace much of the haze to a mammoth complex
of coal-fired electricity plants in northern Mexico, about 125
miles upwind of Big Bend, but they have been unable to negotiate an
agreement with Mexico to build scrubbers that would cut the plants'
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico remains strapped for money, and many elected officials on
the American side are urging that the United States give it much
more assistance to develop solutions that could help people on both
sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look upon the border as an economic and political dividing
label,'' said State Rep. Andrew Nichols, a Democrat from Tucson,
Ariz., who also is director of the rural health office of the
University of Arizona College of Medicine. ``But disease knows no
border. If we worked more collaboratively with the Mexican
government, if we took that broader perspective, we'd be helping
our own people. It's not just generosity, it's self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But spending American money on projects like sewage treatment
plants in another country is a sticky diplomatic and political
issue. ``It's very hard to convince Congress we need money to deal
with problems that seem to be in Mexico,'' said Doug Farquhar, an
expert on environmental health issues for the National Conference
of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, NAFTA provided for a binational agency, the
Border Environment Cooperation Commission in Juarez, to certify
cleanup projects, and a $450 million commitment from both nations
for a bank to finance the work. President Clinton and other
proponents of the free-trade pact said the bank, the North American
Development Bank, could use its lending authority to leverage up to
$8 billion for the projects.
</P>
<P>
   But the devaluation of the peso in 1994 forced many Mexican
communities to curtail plans for landfills and sewage treatment
plants, even with low-interest loans available. In other cases,
Mexican officials have disagreed over what technological steps are
needed to fix the problems.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has certified 21 environmental projects costing
$473 million, including the sewage treatment plants in Tijuana and
Juarez. But the bank has provided only a fraction of the money so
far, and no project is operating yet.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts contend that NAFTA's environmental side accords
were flawed from the start because they did not provided a specific
way for Mexican or American cities to identify tax revenue from new
commercial activity generated by the pact's removal of trade
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still no system in place by which the growth,
especially on the Mexican side, can begin to pay for itself,'' said
Mary Kelly, director of the Texas Center for Policy Studies, an
environmental research group that has conducted extensive studies
of the border's environment.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the problems originate south of the border. Mexican
officials express outrage over Texas' plans for a low-level
radioactive waste dump in Sierra Blanca, a town 80 miles east of
here near the border, and anger over that issue has hampered
negotiations on air pollution in Big Bend and on other cross-border
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the border's environmental problem is simply the
population growth on both sides. It is most striking in Mexico;
Juarez, for example, which had 250,000 people in 1960, now has five
times that number. The overall border population has more than
doubled, to more than 10 million, and is expected to double again
in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they express frustration over the belated progress, some
experts here see signs of hope in the fact that the development
bank is approving loans, such as the $31.2 million for the first
two waste water treatment plants in Juarez's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slow, but this is much more than a technical problem,''
said Jim VanDerslice, a professor of environmental sciences at the
University of Texas-Houston School of Public Health at El Paso.
``It's politics, it's people, it's organizations. When you're
working binationally, it's just difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in charge of cleanup plans say they are working as
fast as they can. ``A lot of people would say it's slower than
expected,'' said Angeles Villarreal, a spokeswoman for the
cooperation commission. ``But once you are working on these
problems, you realize that it takes a while. These are complicated
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
