u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-FYODOROV-925(2     07-03 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FYODOROV-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASH, WEALTHY BUSINESSMAN MAKING WAVES AS RUSSIA'S HEAD TAX
COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Wearing black ski masks, a phalanx of gun-toting
Russian tax police officers swept into a dingy warehouse this week
and confiscated thousands of shiny bottles of vodka complete with
phony alcohol tax markings.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cheating owner managed to escape, but Boris Fyodorov
said he was not discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to use our powers to the fullest,'' Russia's new
tax chief said. ``They clearly weren't being used before.''
</P>
<P>
   Brash, wealthy and supremely self-confident, Fyodorov has is the
head of the State Tax Service, the most difficult task in Russia.
In a country where tax avoidance is a national pastime, tax
collectors have come and gone with little to show for their efforts
but a ballooning government budget deficit. Yet if anyone can
change the system it just might be Fyodorov, the economic reformer
turned wealthy investment banker who is a veteran of Russia's
rough-and-tumble politics. He is a rare official who delights in
stepping on a few toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in the government twice, and by the time I leave a
lot of people feel pain,'' he boasted in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Only a month in office, Fyodorov has been trying to dole out
more pain. He took on Gazprom, Russia's most powerful company and
one of the nation's biggest tax delinquents. He ordered his agents
to draw up a list of Russia's 1,000 wealthiest citizens, put
himself on the list, and decreed that every one of them would be
audited. And in an effort to scare tax deadbeats, he has begun a
series of highly publicized raids, like the one on the vodka
warehouse. In one instance, his inspectors went door-to-door in one
of Moscow's fanciest apartment buildings looking for people who
were secretly subletting their apartments and not reporting the
extra income.
</P>
<P>
   He has put his stamp on the Yeltsin government's plans to
overhaul the tax laws. Fyodorov wants lower corporate tax rates to
stimulate economic growth and encourage companies to pay their
taxes. He has also pushed for a flat tax on personal income.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia trying to contain a budget deficit and struggling to
prop up its currency, collecting taxes has never been more
critical. Any sign that Russia is serious about collecting revenue
would likely calm the stock and bond markets and, most important,
impress the International Monetary Fund, which is negotiating the
terms of a new multi-billion dollar loan for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Russians to pay their taxes, however, is not just a
matter of armed raids, publishing lists and ordering audits.
Success for Fyodorov will require nothing less than an act of
religious conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1 million Russians filed tax returns in 1997, a tiny
fraction for a nation with 147 million people. There are plenty of
skeptics who think the Fyodorov will fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can carry out kinds of checks and investigations and
change the head of the tax service 35 times,'' Grigory Tomchin, the
head of a trade association of privatized enterprises, told the
Russian press. ``The situation will not change. It won't be
possible to do anything until the debts of enterprises are
restructured.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov is a 40-year-old lone wolf who recently told associates
that if he were an American citizen he would be a conservative
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   An ardent free marketeer, he was picked in 1993 to be finance
minister by President Boris Yeltsin and earned a reputation for
taking off the gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Russian government, no one respects you if you are
weak,'' he once told a Russian interviewer. ``You need to punch
them in the muzzle, and then they understand everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov, threw plenty of punches. He clashed with Viktor
Gerashchenko, the chairman of the central bank whose loose money
policies helped lead Russia into debilitating round of soaring
inflation. Fyodorov resigned in 1994 and later wrote a dictionary
of economic terms in which he referred to Gerashchenko as the worst
banker in the world.
</P>
<P>
   He assailed then-Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as a
do-nothing politician. He even staged debates between himself and a
card-board cutout of the stolid Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov's feistiness has been strengthened by his financial
independence. He is wealthy and accomplished enough in the world of
business that he could walk away from the job tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   After the breakup of the Soviet Union, he did a stint at the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development and at the World
Bank. His income was tax-free, under Russian law, and Fyodorov
bought Russian treasury bills at sky-high interest rates, according
to a business partner, Charles Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov and Ryan later founded the United Financial Group, one
of Russia's leading investment banks. That has given him an
appreciation of how Russia's byzantine tax system hampers business
and earned him the respect of Russia's financial oligarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other top Kremlin aides, Fyodorov has refused to
publicize his assets or income but he insists that he pays his
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia was hit this year by a financial crisis that has
sent stock and currency markets into a swoon, Fyodorov sent a
strongly worded letter to Yeltsin criticizing the government's
inaction. Yeltsin tapped him to take over the State Tax Service and
be the government's junkyard dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me the job nobody really wants,'' he said
cheerfully.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to see why. Russian disdain for authority and an
archaic and burdensome tax code had turned the country into a
nation of tax deadbeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``For decades, there was no culture of paying taxes,'' observed
Mikhail Berger, an economic specialist and editor of the newspaper
Segodnya.
</P>
<P>
   During Soviet times, the communist government deducted a small
sum from people's paychecks. But people barely noticed it and
hardly any one ever had to fill out tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of a new Russia brought new problems.
Well-connected, profitable companies thumb their noses at the
government, while hard-pressed companies stay alive from barter
insisting they lack the means to pay what they owe. Millions of
ordinary Russians have embraced the underground economy, convinced
their taxes line the pockets of a powerful elite.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov's predecessor, Alexander Pochinok, did little to
instill a sense of discipline in his agency or among a contemptuous
public. As tax collection faltered in May, Pochinok was with his
family on a expensive cruise to Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   He returned just in time to be fired, leaving behind an army of
185,000 of demoralized and poorly paid inspectors and bureaucrats.
A tax inspector outside of Moscow typically earns less than $100 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov has sought to expand his authority and demonstrate that
no one is beyond the reach of tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the government has blocked access to export pipelines
for four oil companies that have not paid their taxes. It has
threatened to freeze the accounts of United Energy Systems, the
electrical monopoly run by reformer Anatoly Chubais, to force it to
begin paying up.
</P>
<P>
   But Gazprom, the nation's biggest and most politically potent
company, has emerged as the critical public test. The company,
whose gleaming, 34-story tower, complete with tennis courts and
gardens is a Moscow landmark, paid only one third of its taxes last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going after the big culprits to show that we can get
tough with them,'' Fyodorov said. ``Gazprom will feel it for sure.
Obviously, they have been playing games. When they want to buy a
bank or launch an investment program they have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   After Fyodorov issued orders for the tax police to confiscate
dachas, private planes and vacation homes, Gazprom said it would
reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with furious protests by Gazprom and their allies in
the Communist-dominated parliament, the Yeltsin government gave
some ground on Friday and decided to give the company until Aug. 1
to pay up or face confiscation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a committee is being established to assess the
Gazprom's claim that the money the government owes it and its tax
debt should cancel out. Fyodorov has made clear that he believes it
is Gazprom that owes the state.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he should succeed where so many others have failed,
Fyodorov had a characteristically blunt response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everyone who was in the job before me, and they could
not have done it,'' he said. ``I would like to prove that it is
possible to achieve something in Russia. That would be something to
talk to my grandchildren about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
