<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTING ANGUISH OVER '88 AIR DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE HORMUZ II, in the Persian Gulf _ Friday was a day to
demonize America.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago Friday, just before the end of Iran's long war
with Iraq, a U.S. naval cruiser shot down an Iran Air civilian
airliner as it flew over the Persian Gulf, killing all 290 people
on board.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan expressed ``deep regret'' for what he
called a ``terrible human tragedy'' and the United States
eventually compensated the families of the victims as well as the
Iranian government for the loss of its plane.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Iranians, the shootdown still represents one of the
most heinous entries on the list of U.S. ``crimes'' against their
country in the last 50 years _ one that became even more monstrous
in their eyes when two years later the U.S. Navy decorated two of
the vessel's commanders instead of punishing them immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian authorities invited relatives of the victims and members
of the news media to mark the anniversary, flying them to the port
of Bandar Abbas in a chartered Iran Air Boeing 707 and ferrying
them to the point 25 miles into the Persian Gulf where the plane
hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an act of state terrorism,'' Mahdi Chamran, the
deputy cultural events director for Iran's armed forces, said in a
speech as the slow-moving German-made ferry steamed to its
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an accident,'' he said. ``If it had been an
accident they would have treated the commanders differently. They
wouldn't have given medals to people who had caused such an
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamran said no amount of money would ever compensate the
victims' families for their loss. He called on the Clinton
administration to apologize. ``If the United States wants to break
down the wall of mistrust, it is important that the families
receive an official apology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The day was marked by both spectacle and sadness. At the airport
at Bandar Abbas, visitors saw a display of color photographs of the
bodies of some of the 57 children who died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Children were dressed in green-and-white-striped T-shirts
specially printed for the occasion showing the number of men, women
and children killed by an exploding plane atop a blackened Statue
of Liberty. The father of a 5-year-old boy dressed his son in
camouflage fatigues and draped a banner across his chest that read
in English, ``Down With U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ferry reached its destination near the tiny island of
Hengham near the Strait of Hormuz, small pleasure speedboats that
the Iranians had transformed into military vessels circled the
ferry.
</P>
<P>
   As a white-uniformed navy band played in the sauna-like summer
heat, weeping women and other passengers threw armfuls of red,
white and coral gladiolas over the side of the boat. Two U.S.-made
Sikorsky helicopters flew overhead, dropping flowers into the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still waiting for my father,'' said Farideh Ameri, a
13-year-old girl swathed in black, whose father, an Iran Air
official, was among those killed. ``Whenever I look at the sea I am
reminded that my father isn't coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she could ever forgive the United States for the
shootdown, she said: ``Never. Nothing replaces my father.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohsen Rezaian, whose son was one of the plane's pilots, said he
had nothing to tell the American people. ``What can I say?'' he
asked. ``My son is gone. What do you want me to say?''
</P>
<P>
   But then, perhaps in an effort not to offend an American
visitor, he noted that his other son was living in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The shootdown alternately angers and mystifies the Iranians. How
could the USS Vincennes, with all its sophisticated gadgetry,
mistake a regularly-scheduled passenger plane heading across the
Persian Gulf from Bandar Abbas to Dubai for a military plane poised
to attack?
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon investigation concluded that the mistakes were not
technological but human, caused by ``the fog of war and those human
elements which affect each individual differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Central Command, which is responsible for Persian
Gulf operations, recommended that Lt. Cmdr. Scott Lustig, the
Vincennes' anti-air warfare officer, receive a mild reprimand, the
recommendation was overruled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 Lustig was granted two Navy commendation medals for his
service on the Vincennes. The ship's commander, Will C. Rogers III,
was given the Legion of Merit for ``exceptionally meritorious
conduct'' during the period of his command.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the United States paid families of the victims
$300,000 for each wage earner and $150,000 for each non-wage earner
who had died. The Iranian government was paid $40 million for the
loss of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians were clearly torn Friday between their
determination to shine the spotlight on the tragedy and their
desire to follow the lead of President Mohammad Khatami and soften
their tone toward the United States. Khatami has made clear that he
has no use for the burning of the U.S. flag or the slogan ``Death
to America!'' and in the last few months there have been no
flag-burnings and markedly less anti-American sloganeering.
</P>
<P>
   But after a speech filled with fury, Gorbani Husseini, an
official with the Foundation to Preserve the Values of Sacred
Defense, which was the host at Friday's event, beckoned the
passengers to chant with him, ``Mag bar Amrika!'' _ ``Death to
America!'' They did, but only three times. And when he led them in
chanting the slogan in English, he watered it down to ``Down With
America.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked by a reporter why Iranians were still chanting
``Death to America!'' when Khatami had said he did not like it,
Ahmed Reza Kazemi, the general manager of the state-owned Iran Air,
said, ``What President Khatami has said is the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chamran, the armed forces cultural aide, begged to differ.
``There is no law preventing slogans against America,'' he said.
``President Khatami hasn't issued an edict banning them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, countered Kazemi, ``this year, culturally the activities
were very contained compared to last year. The reaction of the
people toward the United States was very mild.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, toward the end of the ceremony, a group of young women
who discovered that an American journalist was on board asked for
autographs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
