u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-03 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PROGRESS REPORTED IN TALKS TO END GM STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Negotiators from the United Auto Workers union
and General Motors Corp. have begun a push to resolve strikes in
Flint that have crippled the giant automaker's operations across
North America, but the two sides have yet to settle GM's demands
for improved productivity here.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood Jewell, the often-combative chairman of the bargaining
committee for the local UAW unit that began the strikes on June 5,
said in an interview here that the tone of the talks had definitely
improved and that negotiations would continue over the holiday
weekend. After weeks of criticizing GM publicly, and even canceling
talks temporarily over a perceived slight to striking workers by a
GM negotiator, Jewell refrained from attacking the company Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ternes, a GM spokesman, said that Friday's talks were
``slow but somewhat constructive,'' and represented an improvement.
``It has been much less than that in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials from GM and the union's national leadership have
also begun quiet negotiations this week, separate from the talks at
the factory here. The UAW has begun treating the current strikes as
local disputes, after initially seeking to turn them into a
showdown over GM's long-term strategy of reducing employment in the
United States through attrition to help cut costs and become more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell said no issues had actually been settled yet at the
factory here. ``We didn't resolve anything, but we had some good
discussions,'' he said in an interview late Friday morning at the
factory gate, as union negotiators left the talks for a lunch
break.
</P>
<P>
   In more than a dozen factory-level strikes against GM over the
last five years, a ritual has developed in which all issues remain
open until the final hours of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   These strikes typically begin, as this one did, with workers and
local union officials publicly vilifying the world's largest
automaker, while GM executives accuse union members of failing to
work hard enough. Serious negotiations begin when both sides cease
their public criticisms and instead make a series of proposals,
sometimes over the course of a week or more. Once each side has
laid out the relative importance of each of its many grievances,
round-the-clock talks start and a final bargain is usually struck
in a couple of days in which a few items are chosen from each
side's list of proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hackworth, GM's group vice president for North American
car operations, said in an interview before the latest round of
negotiations that the current strikes could be settled in as little
as four hours once both sides devoted themselves to the task.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, both sides would like to reach an agreement by next
Thursday or Friday, which would allow time for union members to
ratify a pact next weekend and allow production to resume here on
July 13, at the end of GM's regularly scheduled two-week summer
vacation. GM has shuttered 26 of its 29 assembly plants in North
America, and it could take two or three weeks to reopen them after
production of auto parts resumes here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 9,200 workers on strike at two parts
factories in Flint, GM has temporarily laid off 162,700 workers
across North America and outside parts suppliers have also laid off
thousands of workers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jewell's remarks Friday were the first instance of a senior
union official hinting at progress toward a settlement. UAW leaders
excoriated GM during a union convention in Las Vegas a week ago.
Stephen Yokich, the UAW's president, even suggested there that GM
was run by an unseen ``madman.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators here have not yet reached the stage of talking
through the night. Bargainers recessed at 5:15 p.m. Friday and
planned to resume at 9 a.m. Saturday, Ternes said.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators still face many tough issues here. There are
actually three sets of negotiations going on: one at each of the
two factories, and another round between national GM and UAW
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing dispute involves the walkout that began June 5
at Jewell's factory, which stamps and welds sheets of steel to make
hoods, fenders and engine mountings for most GM vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants GM to complete a promised $300 million
investment program at the factory and wants a variety of health and
safety changes, like the elimination of a machine lubricant that is
irritating the skin of some workers. GM wants the union to make
numerous changes in work rules, including the elimination of
production standards that allow workers to go home early and still
collect a full day's pay if they have made a certain number of auto
parts.
</P>
<P>
   To increase the pressure on GM, the union's national leadership
also allowed nearly 6,000 workers to go on strike June 11 at a
speedometer and spark-plug factory near the stamping factory. GM
has cut the work force there in half over the last decade while
buying more parts from outside suppliers, including some in Mexico,
and the union wants GM to slow the rate at which it is eliminating
jobs at that factory through attrition. But GM in particular has
given less importance to that strike, viewing it as a sideshow to
be resolved after the main dispute at the stamping factory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
