<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9939 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-H     07-03 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
PARIS _ This time, it wasn't the Baggio, as in Roberto, the once
and fallen star, who broke Italian hearts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Di Biagio. As in Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   With the world's World Series at his feet and an ominously
familiar scene buzzing around him, Italian midfielder Luigi Di
Biagio fell victim to a moment that is sure to live in World Cup
infamy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I failed, and I'm sorry,'' Di Biagio said. ``I am so sorry,
very sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an Italian calamity, for sure, on the way to a 4-3
penalty-shootout loss to France at Stade de France on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was a single, frozen scene that seemed impossible to believe
but all too familiar for the Italians.
</P>
<P>
   It was a miss, reminiscent of Bill Buckner's infamous World
Series gaffe of 1986. But instead of letting the ball and this
monumental World Cup game roll through his legs, Di Biagio couldn't
get the ball by French goalkeeper Fabien Barthez with the final
penalty-shot attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought it was going in,'' Italian coach Cesare
Maldini said. ``I can't blame him for what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Di Biagio sent the ball high, hitting the crossbar and sending
Paris into a flag-waving, horn-blowing frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   It also sent Italy home from the World Cup with a penalty-shot
loss for the third consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pity, considering how hard we played,'' Maldini said.
``For this to happen to us three times, it's very sad. It's a
curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Roberto Baggio's misfire in the World Cup final
against Brazil left Italy short of reaching the game's ultimate
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before that, it was another penalty-shot loss to
Argentina that sent Italy home after getting to the World Cup
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played very well, but we didn't get the result we
wanted,'' Maldini said. ``This team gave its all, down to the last
drop of sweat. Including Di Biagio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did his job. It's always easy to criticize afterward. But
we don't fault him at all, absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Di Biagio was practically inconsolable after missing the
critical shot, dropping straight back to the ground as the ball
bounced away, as if it was he who hit the crossbar, not the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As Di Biagio lay motionless on the ground, 80,000 fans and the
French team began celebrating reaching the semifinals and a date
with the winner of today's Germany-Croatia match.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian team surrounded Di Biagio, literally having to help
him off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all feel very disappointed,'' Italy forward Christian Vieri
said. ``No one feels more disappointed than (Di Biagio). It was
just something that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Italians, the loss seemed all the more painful and
unlikely, because until Di Biagio's miss, Italy was playing its
grimace-and-bear-it game to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly wary of France's electric scoring combination of
Zinedine Zidane and Youri Djorkaeff, Italy sent five men back to
protect goalkeeper Gianluca Pagliuca and placed three just behind
the midfield line.
</P>
<P>
   It was like an Azzurri wall.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a beautiful, high-flying strategy by any stretch of
the imagination, but it proved to strangle the zip out of Zidane
and Djorkaeff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make any mistakes,'' Maldini said. ``We had to
counterattack. We were never really in danger. We were faultless in
our defense. I had my strategy, and I stuck to my guns.''
</P>
<P>
   And it worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians hammered at the ball every time Zidane and
Djorkaeff touched it, eventually accounting for 24 fouls in the
process. Italy counterattacked only when there were clear
opportunities, and there were few.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 45 minutes, France earned some decent shots at
the goal, but beginning in the second half Italy clearly was
wearing on France.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played an overtime game against Paraguay (in the round of
16), and maybe it caught up to us,'' Zidane said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of regulation, Italy was beginning to create more
opportunities on the counterattack, particularly after Baggio
entered the game in the 67th minute. In overtime, Italy had a
chance to win when Baggio squeezed through France's defense and
barely missed a crossing chip shot to the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you play against a team like Italy, you can't afford
to let up,'' France coach Aime Jacquet said. ``For about
three-fourths of the game, we stayed focused and had full mastery
of the game. But as it went on, the Italians came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected them to come out and play that kind of match. We
tried to come up with some ways of countering their strategy, but
it was difficult. Things started getting more difficult for us, and
it was 50-50 who would win. It was up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   It was up to the shootout penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first eight of the 10 penalty-kick shooters, each
goalkeeper made one save _ Italy's Pagliuca against France's
Bixente Lizarazu and France's Barthez on Demetrio Albertini.
</P>
<P>
   France's Laurent Blanc, the hero of the Paraguay win, then
stepped up as the final shooter for his team. He nailed it high and
strong past Pagliuca.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Di Biagio. He charged and kicked, but the ball
ricocheted off the iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're into penalty kicks, it's a matter of keeping your
nerves,'' Jacquet said. ``Our players were able to do that through
120 minutes of a difficult game and the pressure of the penalty
kicks. We've worked for years to make this our World Cup, and now
we're living it to the hilt.''
</P>
<P>
   And Di Biagio is living the familiar Italian nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a lottery when you get to penalty kicks,'' Maldini
said. ``Argentina in '90, then Brazil in the USA and now France. We
haven't won one of these. It's been bad luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
