<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9940 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REEVES-COL-TEX     07-03 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKS DOES RIGHT BY STARS; HELP FOR RANGERS SHOULD BE NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ General manager Bob Gainey beamed from behind a
bow tie, and Brett Hull wore the look of a happy and wealthy man
early yesterday afternoon at the Dr Pepper StarCenter, but the guy
who clearly felt like a billion bucks _ and not one penny less _
was Stars-Rangers owner Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks continued to back up his promise to build the Stars into a
Stanley Cup winner, and when he sent Hull _ the biggest free-agent
catch in the NHL ocean this year until he signed a three-year, $17
million deal with Dallas yesterday _ to The Ballpark in Arlington
to throw out the first pitch before last night's game with the
Mariners, he might have also been sending a message to Rangers fans
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bank on it: The next superstar this mover and shaker sends to
the Rangers' mound will stick around for more than one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   And that day won't be too long in coming.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, the day and the champagne celebration
belong to the Stars. Next June, when they're chugging their ale out
of Lord Stanley's Cup, they'll look back on July 3, 1998, as the
day the last piece was put into place.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, after an abbreviated run in the playoffs, Hicks and
the Stars determined that the team had to upgrade its goaltending
to make it to the next level and promptly signed free agent Ed
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after reaching the Western Conference finals against
eventual champion Detroit with center Joe Nieuwendyk on the shelf,
it was obvious that the Stars needed a tweak or two offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we went out and got the best goal scorer we could get,''
Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to like his style, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   Word that the Stars were calling a news conference to announce
the signing of the 33-year-old Hull, son of NHL legend Bobby Hull,
sent a shock wave reverberating throughout the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey and the Stars, who had let it be known publicly that they
were interested in free-agent wingers Wendel Clark or Geoff
Courtnall, identified Hull as their No. 1 priority several weeks
ago, then successfully ran a smokescreen on both the media and
other NHL teams, most specifically the Chicago Blackhawks, who had
also targeted Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, the Blackhawks signed center Doug Gilmour yesterday
after learning that Hull was off the market. It's called romance on
the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hull himself was caught off guard when the Stars phoned
Wednesday, the first day free agents could begin negotiating with
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he was pleasantly surprised,'' Hicks said. ``We
weren't even on his radar screen. It didn't take him long to make
up his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   About as long as it took for Hull to pack his bags and head for
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stars were just a perfect fit for me,'' Hull said. ``When
Dallas came into the picture, it brought a whole new light on
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull has the potential to bring a whole new light to the Stars'
offense as well. Although he scored just 27 goals in 66 games last
season, when he was paired with strong offensive teammates Brendan
Shanahan and Adam Oates in the early '90s, Hull responded with
consecutive 72-, 86- and 70-goal seasons. Four times he has scored
more than 100 points in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, however, demands a defense-first
philosophy from his players. Can Hull adapt?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever coach Hitchcock wants me to do, I will,'' Hull said,
``but I've spent a lot of years in this league scoring goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, for one, is already envisioning a line of Hull, Mike
Modano and Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a formidable line,'' Hicks said. ``If I was
Detroit, I'd be nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the surprise in the Hull signing is that in so many ways
he doesn't appear to be a Gainey-Hitchcock kind of player. Until
the last few years he was considered to be strictly an offensive
player, and there were reports that he could be disruptive in the
locker room. Gainey generally likes players built in his own image:
quiet and quieter.
</P>
<P>
   That's obviously not the outgoing Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who say that don't know what they're talking about,''
Hull said of the rumors. ``I spent 11 great years in St. Louis, and
I wouldn't have been there that long if I'd been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time we heard from Hull, in fact, was after the Red
Wings had eliminated the Blues in the second round of the playoffs,
and he predicted the Stars would have little chance of upsetting
the defending Stanley Cup champions in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out he was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that because I know how good \Rthe Wings\S are, and I
also know how to beat them,'' he said. ``Hopefully, now we can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   We, as in Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hang in there Rangers fans. Your day is coming, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could use another pitcher,'' Hicks conceded, ``but nobody
much is really available until after the All-Star break.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what. That's next week. Something tells me Hicks already
knows that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
