<HEADER>
A9943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-ART-N     07-03 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINANT MEXICAN PARTY TRIES OUT CRITIC'S ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map, incorrectly slugged JUAREZ-DRUGS, is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUAREZ, Mexico _ This border city that is one of Mexico's main
drug corridors suffers extraordinary homicide rates, and one
candidate for governor of Chihuahua, Patricio Martinez Garcia, has
repeatedly lambasted the state and city governments for failing to
suppress crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder is out of control, so what should we do, throw rose
petals and say our opponents have run a great government?''
Martinez said in an interview. ``They offered better security and
haven't delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's posturing as an opposition candidate sometimes seems
jarring, since he is a federal congressman from the PRI, the party
that has controlled the presidency and nearly everything else in
Mexico for most of seven decades. But Chihuahua's is one of six
Mexican statehouses controlled by the National Action Party, or
PAN, making this state bordering Texas a place where the opposition
has become government, and the PRI is opposition.
</P>
<P>
   These and other topsy-turvy realities of Mexico's creeping,
15-year transition from one-party rule have charged the governor's
election here on Sunday with tremendous symbolism. PRI leaders, who
last year lost control of the Congress and Mexico City's municipal
government, are aching to demonstrate that they can recover terrain
lost to a rising opposition tide.
</P>
<P>
   And Ramon Galindo, the PAN candidate here, has been warning that
a PRI victory would damage Mexico's chances to elect a non-PRI
president for the first time in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Chihuahuans understand what's at play,'' said Galindo,
who stepped down as mayor of Juarez to run for governor. ``This
isn't just any other election. The battle for Chihuahua is the
battle for Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chihuahua has drawn the most national attention,
governors' races are also scheduled for Sunday in two other
northern states.
</P>
<P>
   In Zacatecas, Mexico's main leftist party, the Party of the
Democratic Revolution, or PRD, has nominated a former congressman
who bolted from the PRI after being passed over for the nomination.
He is running strong, fueling PRD hopes that a victory will prove
that the party's stunning triumph in last year's Mexico City
mayoral elections was not a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   In Durango, a PRI candidate is running far ahead of three
rivals, including one from a tiny leftist party once funded by the
brother of former president Carlos Salinas to splinter the
opposition. That tactic appears to have worked; polls show that the
three opposition candidates combined may garner 52 percent of the
vote, but the PRI is likely to win with about 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In these places, as in all of Mexico's 32 states, governors are
elected for a single six-year term, and are not eligible for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's balloting opens a 12-month electoral season in which
half the states will choose new governors, allowing Mexico's three
main parties to measure forces for the presidential race, which has
already attracted several declared candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These elections will be an exercise in changing the balance of
power between the parties and in building new majorities,'' Mariano
Palacios, the PRI's national party president, said in an interview.
``So what happens in the states will be a major factor in what
happens in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 16 elections are scheduled before December. Rafael
Gimenez, a poll-taker for the Mexico City newspaper Reforma, said
that the PAN and PRD have fair chances in 5 of the 10 races. The
PRI will win the rest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The closely disputed states include Aguascalientes, where the
PAN's candidate enjoys a slim lead, and Oaxaca, where a popular PRD
senator is running a strong race, Gimenez said.
</P>
<P>
   In oil-rich Veracruz on the Gulf Coast, the most populous state
to vote this year, the PRI candidate is Miguel Aleman Velasco, the
son of a former president. He is leading rivals by an overwhelming
margin, Gimenez said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of these campaigns will center on local issues,
the PRI's fortunes will also partly depend on voter perceptions of
President Ernesto Zedillo's economic stewardship. Market analysts
say Mexico's recovery has become a boom, but many working people
complain they have not felt it. Zedillo's approval ratings, which
have been high, have been slipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the classic George Bush recovery,'' said Federico
Estevez, a political scientist. ``Zedillo claims things are great,
and people say, `What's he talking about?'''
</P>
<P>
   Many campaigns will also focus on public security, and here the
opposition is on the defensive. The PRD controls Mexico City, and
has so far been unable to suppress lawlessness there. The PAN is
even more vulnerable because it governs Tijuana, Guadalajara and
Juarez, the three cities in which narcotics violence has been
deadliest.
</P>
<P>
   Chihuahua's outgoing PAN governor, Francisco Barrio, won
election in 1992 partly because under PRI governance, traffickers
overran Chihuahua, thoroughly infiltrating the police. Barrio's
1992 campaign slogan was ``Insecurity equals bad government.''
</P>
<P>
   Even many PRI leaders acknowledge that Barrio has made
government more efficient and responsive _ except on narcotics,
which has provoked hundreds of drug executions, and other crimes.
Hundreds of Chihuahuans have disappeared after detention by
security forces working for traffickers during Barrio's tenure, and
nearly 150 Juarez women have been murdered, many of them raped.
Galindo, PAN's candidate for governor here, blamed the
PRI-controlled federal government, noting that enforcing drug laws
is a federal responsibility and that most tax revenues go to Mexico
City, leaving Chihuahua little to spend on law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the PRI has exploited Chihuahua's record of violent
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, PRI legislators who control the Chihuahua congress
called Barrio's attorney general to a public hearing to berate him
over his failures against crime. This week Martinez closed his
Juarez campaign with a rally outside a restaurant closed since
August, when narcotics gunmen executed six diners as they sat at
their tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody that's been in government can use the public security
issue to their advantage; it's a great handicap,'' Barrio said in
an interview earlier this year. ``We can take credit for many
advances, but not for improving public security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
