<HEADER>
A9948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAFIRE-TOURISTS-COX     07-03 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRE-TOURISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR fans crank engines, exit Daytona
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- The past two days have not been good for
Patrick Holley as race fans in droves checked out of his Days Inn
and Tropical Seas motels. This was no forced evacuation, only an
economical one, the result of fires and smoke that have battered
this part of eastern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, NASCAR fans, being the hardy lot they are, didn't
budge from their rooms and campers until they got the word that the
Pepsi 400 race scheduled for today had been postponed until
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   The race-crowd exodus was hurting other businesses, too.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Allison, who sells hot dogs, soft drinks and french fries
from his beach wagon, complained emphatically, ``Ain't nobody
coming to the beach with all this smoke and stuff. This race just
killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Holley, gave it all a more positive spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to what the people of this area have endured these
last few weeks, a race cancellation is a minor inconvenience,''
Holley said. ``Economically, it will cost us tens of thousands of
dollars. Everybody came in Wednesday, paid up front, and left
Thursday with refunds. I can't blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many rooms suddenly vacant, Holley turned 30 rooms over
to charity, offering them for use by the local Economic Opportunity
Council, then he sent food and drinking water to firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live here, too,'' said Holley, whose home was spared by the
work of firefighters earlier in the week. ``The fans will be back
in October. They probably are the most loyal fans in all of
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the July Fourth holiday and the novelty of the night
race, Daytona merchants had been bracing for the biggest weekend of
the summer. Now, they're bracing for losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't begin to tell you what the dollar amount will be,
but it will be significant,'' said Lynne Fagan, president of Ramada
Inn Speedway. ``In terms of the entire season, we probably will not
recover. But, the fans will come back. They always do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The fans held their ground and hoped for the best until
the call came from NASCAR at 10 a.m. Thursday. Only then, with no
race to be run and smoke being an everyday headache, home sounded
like a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Clark thought so, too. He wished Thursday the nightmare was
gone and he was awake back home in Key Largo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent about $2,000 on this weekend, went all out,'' Clark
said of his camp site in the speedway infield. ``I bought an air
conditioner, a generator and a golfing canopy to cover our eating
area. Now, we can't even use them.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the hardy fans they are, race fans will endure most any
setback _rain, snow and tornadoes. This is the first time, however,
they've been ``fired'' out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent 12 days last year waiting to see the Winston 500 at
Talladega,'' said Ken Roam of Birmingham, while filling out a
reservation form at the Daytona Beach Hilton for the October race.
``Some people spend money on golf. I spend mine on racing, about 15
times a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Robinson has been coming here from Louisiana for 10 years to
attend the Pepsi 400. But he's relatively certain he can't make it
back for the Oct. 17 race. It's his wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has put up with a lot the 19 years we've been married,
but she told me today that if I wanted to be married 20 years, I
better have a better plan,'' Robinson said, laughing. ``I think
she's got a cruise in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The most dedicated fans award maybe should go to Randy Faulk and
three friends. They drove 22 hours straight from Green Bay, Wis.,
arriving at Daytona Beach at 10 p.m. Wednesday. About 12 hours
later, they were snapping pictures in a half-empty parking lot and
wondering ``where to now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty bummed out,'' said 23-year-old Faulk. ``We'll just have
to find something else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
