<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JDDREW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drew gets $7 million deal with Cardinals
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The long and painful holdout for J.D. Drew has ended.
His well-documented career in the independent Northern League is in
the books.
</P>
<P>
   Drew finally signed with a major-league baseball team, receiving
a four-year, $7 million deal Friday from the St. Louis Cardinals.
The signing ended what has been a bitter battle among Drew, the
Philadelphia Phillies and major league baseball. It came with a $3
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, who will join the Cardinals' Class AA team in Arkansas,
said his year-long holdout was about principle, not money, but his
stance has left him unpopular with fans and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do it all again, I would,'' said Drew, who lives
in the South Georgia town of Hahira. ``I said all along it was
about being comfortable, and I'm comfortable with St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew, who played at Florida State, originally was selected by
the Phillies as the second overall choice in the June, 1997 draft.
But he demanded an $11 million signing bonus and was offered a
four-year package for a guaranteed $3 million that could grow to $6
million with incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Drew declined the deal and began playing with the St. Paul
Saints in the Northern League. His effort to have his amateur
status revoked _ he wanted free-agent status _ was turned down by
an arbitrator, so Drew went back into the draft for 1998. He was
the fifth-overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are thrilled about the signing, but likely will be
criticized by other clubs for giving Drew such a large deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel J.D. is definitely one of the top players drafted in
the last 10, 15 years,'' Cardinals general manager Walt Jocketty
said. ``There's no guarantee when he'll play up here. He's going to
have to work his way up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
