<HEADER>
A9952 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$A     07-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Raging Bulls and an Angry Steer
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investors increased their stock mutual fund purchases in
June, a month when the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose to
record highs, and also put more money in bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $21.1 billion entered stock mutual funds in June,
up from $18.7 billion in May, according to Trim Tabs Financial
Services Inc. And according to the Investment Company Institute,
the industry's trade group, about $9.81 billion was invested in
taxable-bond, municipal-bond and so-called hybrid funds in May, up
from $5.24 billion in April.
</P>
<P>
   But while the bulls were having a good time, neither Paul
Turcato nor his steer was staying on top of things at the Ponoka
Stampede rodeo in Edmonton, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   Confidence Is Not High ...
</P>
<P>
   The United States' manufacturers have slowed production to the
lowest rate of growth since 1995, the clearest impact so far of the
Asian crisis on the American economy. The National Association of
Purchasing Management reported that manufacturing activity weakened
in June for a majority of the companies that it surveys each month.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 22 months that a majority had reported
weakening instead of strengthening in their businesses.
Manufacturing employment has fallen in recent months, and
industrial production has slowed to an annual growth rate of less
than 2 percent, down from 6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Production is slowing in large part because stockpiles of unsold
goods have surged, but also because companies are becoming worried
that the economic boom cannot continue at the fervent pace of the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the index of leading economic indicators was flat in
May, a sign that growth will moderate in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ... Except Among Consumers
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence in the economy rose in June to a 29-year
high, as Americans remained optimistic that the strong labor market
and healthy economic growth would continue in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board, a private research group, reported that
its index of consumer confidence rose to 137.6 in June from a
revised 136.3 in May, a larger rise than Wall Street analysts had
expected. That confidence was also reflected in sales of new homes,
which rose in May to a record level.
</P>
<P>
   And the Federal Reserve Board helped matters down the road by
leaving interest rates unchanged. New single-family home sales rose
0.3 percent in May to an annual rate of 890,000 units, the Commerce
Department said, breaking the previous record set in April.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the percentage of homeowners who were late on
their mortgage payments also rose in the first quarter, according
to the Mortgage Bankers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL MOTORS
</P>
<P>
   Stop-and-Go Manufacturing
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. said June car and truck sales were the
highest for any month in nine years but that July sales would
plummet because of two strikes that have shut down most of the
automaker's North American assembly plants and idled almost 172,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Most other carmakers also reported higher sales. A GM official
said sales would drop 30 percent to 40 percent this month compared
with sales from the month a year earlier because of the strikes.
That would push GM's market share to a record low of 25 percent and
put GM behind Ford Motor Co. as the largest volume vehicle
manufacturer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Already, analysts say the strikes at two plants in Flint, Mich.,
have cost GM $1.18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Cleaner Air, Costlier Cars
</P>
<P>
   People in Europe's car-filled cities are likely to start
breathing a little easier in the next few years because of tough
new anti-pollution rules announced in Brussels, Belgium, by the
15-member European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, which ban the use of leaded gasoline, require many
car engines and all fuels to become cleaner by 2000. Even tougher
standards will go into effect in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   With the changes, governments hope to cut as much as 70 percent
of the pollutants in emissions from cars, which regularly foul the
air in some of Europe's most beautiful city centers. The changes
are expected to raise the prices of cars between $300 and $600 in
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Carmakers will need to invest some $65 billion to meet the new
standards, according to European Union officials. The oil industry
estimates it will cost $35 billion to put the program into effect.
And surprise, surprise, most of the higher costs are expected to be
passed on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Bailing Out the Banks
</P>
<P>
   The government outlined a long-awaited ``Total Plan'' to clear
away bad debts, estimated around $600 billion. The plan seems to be
modeled on the United States' bailout of savings and loans in the
1980s and is intended to gradually shut down banks weakened by bad
loans while keeping credit flowing to healthy corporate borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, insolvent banks will be managed by a new
watchdog agency while a merger partner is sought. Bridge loans will
be provided to corporate customers dependent on financing from the
troubled banks. When no suitor can be found, the banks will be
taken over by a state-funded holding company and then sold off or
liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   Bad loans will be handed over to special institutions and good
loans are to be transferred to healthy private banks. The process
is to be completed within a maximum of five years and funded by
taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Balance of Payments, Indeed
</P>
<P>
   Russia's legendarily ineffectual tax men stared down the
nation's biggest and most powerful corporation last week,
threatening to seize control of the company _ and its executives'
dachas, yachts and other perks _ unless it paid billions of dollars
in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   To most everyone's amazement, the company, Gazprom, gave in and
agreed to turn over 4.2 billion rubles ($675 million) in unpaid
taxes by Monday and to start paying the government about 4 billion
rubles a month.
</P>
<P>
   Had President Boris Yeltsin grown a backbone in dealing with the
oligarchs who control the economy here _ or had he staged a deft
act of political theater?
</P>
<P>
   For the agreement does not merely force Gazprom, the world's
largest petroleum company and Russia's biggest tax delinquent, to
make good on its back taxes; it also requires the government to pay
Gazprom billions of rubles for oil and gas that government agencies
and state companies purchased but never paid for. By many
estimates, the two sums amount to a wash.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   Mean and Green
</P>
<P>
   Fore! New golf courses are opening in the United States at the
rate of more than one a day, according to the current issue of
Audubon magazine, and the more than 16,000 of them take up an area
three times the size of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   A major cost of golf courses _ both environmentally and bottom
line _ involves the heavy use of pesticides and herbicides to keep
those greens green. But some courses have found that sound ecology
pays twice: The Old Westbury Golf and Country Club on Long Island,
for example, spent $150,000 on chemicals in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Today, largely thanks to organic fertilizers, it has cut that
budget item to $8,000 a year and is much more user-friendly for
both the birdies and those who covet them.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   Big Pricey Cities
</P>
<P>
   Business executives living abroad may have become used to the
astronomical prices they pay in Tokyo and Hong Kong, and maybe even
in Beijing and Shanghai. But companies doing business in China for
the first time might do a double take when their employees file
their first expense statements from Dalian, the globe's
ninth-most-expensive city for overseas workers _ and notably more
costly than New York, ranked No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   According to Corporate Resources Group, a consulting firm based
in Geneva, Asia still has seven of the world's 10 most expensive
cities for foreign workers. For big savings on expenses, try
Harare, Zimbabwe, which ranked at the bottom of the list.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Burger Flippers, Take Note
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy is showing signs of cooling. In June,
unemployment edged up to 4.5 percent and job growth slowed. There
were other signs of moderation, too.
</P>
<P>
   Total hours worked were virtually flat in June, a clear
indication that the nation's output of goods and services is
growing much more slowly than in recent quarters. And hourly pay
rose by a mere penny, suggesting that wage inflation, while higher
than a year ago, was not accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown, however, is from an exceptionally torrid pace. As
recently as a year ago, joblessness stood at 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
