<HEADER>
A9956 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AMUSEMENT-PARK-ART     07-03 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AMUSEMENT-PARK-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL FUN PARK, REPOSITORY OF MEMORIES, IS FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the pulsating sunlight, children churn round and
round on a groaning Jolly Caterpillar, while others vigilantly man
the guns on the rocket ship, caring not a whit that the paint is
faded and the upholstery torn. Their parents watch dreamily,
remembering how they once rode the same rides in the same little
kiddie land.
</P>
<P>
   South Beach Amusement Park is the heart of the Staten Island
summer, an acre of Americana almost in the shadow of the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge. It is the final remnant of a continuous
string of amusement parks _ replete with Ferris wheels, sideshows
and tens of thousands of weekend visitors _ that once rivaled Coney
Island. But city and private development plans, television,
airplane vacations, Disney and change itself killed the South Beach
fun land. Except for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a landmark; it's been here forever,'' said Joanne
Barile, 33, who had brought her four children. ``I was on all these
rides.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the little park that stayed is for sale. The price is
$550,000, including 16 rides _ a carousel, a little roller coaster,
a Tilt-a-Whirl and you can probably guess the rest. It also comes
with a food concessionaire who pays $16,000 a year. The offer does
not include the land, but the owner, Marshall Lepre, would throw
that in, too, if a buyer asked.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes, but offers no assurance, that 326 Sand Lane will
remain an amusement park. Several people have visited since he
began advertising the park in newspapers several weeks ago. One
possibility is apparent: A town house development, a ubiquitous
feature of Staten Island, is rising across the street.
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Association of Amusement Parks
and Attractions, Lepre's decision to sell is an increasingly common
one among the families who have long owned such little parks.
``We're seeing some consolidation for the first time,'' said Susan
Mosedale, a vice president of the association.
</P>
<P>
   Lepre, 35, who began by selling cotton candy and popcorn from
his father's stand, said he would like to go into catering. He can
no longer work the long weeks, not least because he has a
5-year-old son and because his wife, a registered nurse, is sick of
the schedule. His father died in 1985 at 54 and his mother,
Maureen, who loved the park dearly and is famous for her lasagne
and for giving away tickets, died seven months ago at age 61. One
of the things Lepre, whose T-shirt says ``No. 1 Dad,'' is thinking
these days is that life is short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard right now,'' he said. ``There are lots of memories
here. Some of them are overwhelming.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most of the time, he stands behind the counter, in front of a
poster sent by a day care center. It has children's handprints in
different colors and an inscription: ``Thanks for being so kind to
our children.''
</P>
<P>
   A sign gives the prices: $1.25 a ride, 20 tickets for $20 and 40
for $35. Any unused ones can be used in the future, even in a
future season. There is no admission or parking fee. Birthday party
packages draw 350 parties of at least 10 a year. Groups of
disadvantaged children are often admitted free.
</P>
<P>
   The scene could seem depressing, were it not for the squeals of
the children and the low prices. The pavement is cracked, the
fluttering triangular pennants sun-bleached. There are no trees or
other shade. Some of the rides are rusted. Weeds taller than an
adult surround two sides of the park, and a half-block down the
street is a rather shabby strip club. The blaring radio music is
'60s and '70s rock, and, yes, Cat Stevens is still Cat Stevens on
this frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Several rides are restricted to passengers over 42 inches tall.
A sign on the Tilt-a-Whirl warns: ``Do not ride it if you have a
medical condition. For example, heart, back, neck or head, or if
you think you're pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are not charmed. John O'Day, 65, who calls himself Smiling
Jack, scrunched on a bright yellow bench and allowed as how the old
days, before the city condemned most of the park in the mid-1950s,
were golden. He remembered grabbing the brass ring on a great big
carousel, nickel mugs of root beer and 15-cent hot dogs. He said
Staten Island was special then, but now it is just another
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pale imitation,'' he growled. ``It stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Others seem happy just to be in a pleasant place, though many
acknowledged it seemed so much bigger through the eyes of a child.
A mother cheers when her son shouts ``Hi-yo Silver!'' as he rides
the carousel. Another delicately splashes water on her toddler
daughter as she glides along in the boar ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy's face glows when he's on there riding,'' said Denise
Payne, 32, as she watched her boy ride the Jack Rabbit roller
coaster. She said her husband came here as a boy, just like her,
although they did not know each other then.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my place,'' she said. ``My mother took me with my
brothers and sisters _ you know, everybody. Nothing bad has ever
happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1919, there were 1,500 amusement parks in the United States.
Now there are less than half that many. Some of the little ones,
including bustling Nellie Bly Amusement Park over in Gravesend,
Brooklyn, are doing well by offering more for less. But others are
falling by the wayside, and the future of South Beach Amusement
Park is anything but certain.
</P>
<P>
   Many are hoping it will manage to stay open. John Connolly, 38,
a New York City firefighter, had brought his triplets to celebrate
their sixth birthday, along with his two older children. The
triplets' faces were smeared with the ice cream cake that comes
with the birthday packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live on Staten Island, this is a place you can go and
treat the kids to a good day,'' he said. ``Just to see the smiles
on their faces, you can't put a price tag on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
