</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRE-BORDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytona Beach sees tourism being choked off
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla._It's supposed to be the biggest weekend of
the summer, a four-day spending spree when hard-partying stock car
racing fans jam this beach town's hotels, restaurants and gift
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Florida wildfire crisis that postponed the Pepsi
400, this July Fourth has turned into a disaster-tinged dud, so
much so that hoteliers seemed almost grateful when an unexpected
wave of would-be lodgers arrived _ evacuees from next-door Flagler
County looking for shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of cars streamed south into Volusia County, with many
people stopping to rent the rooms just vacated by disappointed race
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, evacuees worried about their homes burning down
weren't going to spend the kinds of cash that revved-up racing fans
would. And some hoteliers _ in a spirit of charity _ were giving
reduced rates to evacuees, sometimes not even charging at all if
the people were in tough financial shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking a big financial hit,'' said Sammy Mistry, who
owns the Cardinal Motel. ``But we had a plumber from Flagler come
in last night at 3 a.m. with his five kids and his dog, and we
couldn't turn him away. His house may have burned down.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Thunderbird Beach Motel, what looked to be a fully-booked
weekend evaporated Thursday morning when Daytona International
Speedway officials canceled the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bust,'' said manager Judy Foster. ``We had to drop our
rates from $150 a night with a three-night minimum to $45 and $55 a
night. And last night I still only had 43 rooms full out of 97
available. A bunch of those were evacuees.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Foster's race fan customers were rolling over their
reservations to the Oct. 17 date when the Pepsi 400 has been
rescheduled. Others, though, had already taken long-planned
vacations and couldn't get more time off. Foster was refunding
their deposits fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't keep their money,'' she said. ``That just wouldn't
be right. You treat them right now and they'll treat you right
later. They'll be back when all this smoke and ash clears . . .''
</P>
<P>
   At The Corner, a T-shirt shop and body-piercing parlor, manager
Chris Saliba said he figured the July Fourth weekend would mean at
least $5,000 a day in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we can do $1,000 now,'' he said. ``All that's
coming in are locals. I'm not going to charge them high prices when
they're living with this disaster. ``
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach has suffered from smoke from the fires for much of
the past two weeks. Often the beach is blanketed with thick smoke
at daybreak, then clears for several hours at midday when the sea
breeze kicks in, only to descend under the haze again at dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Some hoteliers reported business dropping off a week ago. News
reports about the fires were prompting some people with
reservations to call ahead. Others arrived but checked out after
one night once they found themselves gasping for breath on the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Many merchants were counting on the busy holiday weekend to turn
things around. Now they don't know when things will get better,
especially since news coverage has made it seem like half the
county is on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, about half the county is on fire, but so far, the
flames have been contained in the western rural areas, away from
the populated coast.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Ben, a clerk at the Rusty Cat Gift Shop, said business has
been off for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off about 70 percent,'' she said. ``The store would
normally be full, and now there's no one in here. It's been slow
for the last two weeks. This weekend is supposed to be the real
start of summer, and it just isn't happening.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the lost business, though, none of the merchants seemed
critical of race officials for postponing the event. With fires
burning in a long, smoky line across the western horizon, they
agreed it was no time for a hard-partying crowd of 250,000 race
fans to be coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't bring a party to a town that's been devastated,''
Saliba said. ``That would just be a slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
