</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENSOPEN-LOPEZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White flag day: Lopez fails to make cut at U.S. Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ After four second-place finishes at the U.S.
Women's Open, Nancy Lopez was prepared to once again leave town
unfulfilled. But nothing could have mentally braced her for this.
</P>
<P>
   Missing the cut? Sadly, Lopez made that all but official by the
end of her front nine Friday. The wheels not only came off. They
rolled off the course property and halfway down I-43.
</P>
<P>
   In 22 U.S. Opens, Lopez had never failed to break 80. Friday the
elegant icon from Albany shot an 83 for a two-day total of 18-over
par 160, missed the cut and stood before the media admittedly
shell-shock. During an eight-hole stretch in the middle of the
round, she went 11-over par with three double-bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really would have liked to have just gone like those pigs
who buried themselves where the fires are in Florida,'' Lopez said.
``I felt like just burying myself in the dirt. I just wanted to
hide and go away for a little while. ... Golf is so humbling, and
you just don't want to play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there was no place to hide and nothing to do but
deflect the pain. Lopez started the round with tragedy, hitting a
fan, Cecelia Logan, 49, of Jamison, Pa., in the face with a ball on
the first hole. She was treated and released at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, Lopez could barely find a green. Over two
days, she found the putting surface in regulation only 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been surreal, really,'' said husband Ray Knight.
``It's the weirdest round I've ever watched her play.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming to the 18th green, after Lopez found the water with her
second shot, the threesome of Lopez (83), Meg Mallon (76) and Jane
Geddes (79) recognized the demanding Blackwolf Run Golf Course as
the true champion. At Geddes' suggestion from back on the 10th
hole, when Lopez had just moved to 9-over for the day, the three
players put towels on their putters and waved them in surrender for
the final walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was pretty appropriate,'' Mallon said. ``The
course definitely won.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this time Lopez had moved into weekend position on
rounds of 69-68 and stood one stroke off Alison Nicholas' lead.
Eventually, Lopez would lose by a stroke, missing a 10-foot putt on
the 72nd hole. What transpired Friday was in no way comparable.
This was the greatest player in modern women's golf playing like an
amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a whole different kind of disappointment,'' she
said. ``It's just hard to feel like you have to smile when you
don't really feel like smiling. That kind of frustrates you. But
it's not like last year.''
</P>
<P>
   When many players would have blurted out a few words afterward
and bolted, Nancy Lopez was being, well, Nancy Lopez. She spoke to
reporters for a half-hour and then signed autographs for nearly as
long.
</P>
<P>
   When her voice choked in front of the microphones, she said,
``You know, I'm a crybaby. I'm all right. I just have to get over
it. I wear everything on my heart ... always.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching quickly for another goal, Lopez said she would be
playing the next four LPGA events and trying to make the Solheim
Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I didn't play well here,'' she said, ``I think next
week's going to feel like pitch-and-putt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
