<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVANISEVIC DEFEATS KRAJICEK IN `LONG MARCH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Chairman Mao, the ``Long March'' guy, would have loved
what Goran Ivanisevic and Richard Krajicek committed in the name of
tennis Friday at the Big W. As a sporting version of the Chinese
water torture, it will live in infamy for all those who believed
the tiebreaker had liberated their favorite game from such
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the USA. Only at the US Open among the four majors does
the tiebreaker conclude all sets that arrive at 6-6. All sets, like
all men and women, are created equal in America. It is comforting.
Not so at Wimbledon, where the archaic deuce scheme _ you've got to
be two games ahead to win _ prevails in the ultimate set: fifth for
guys, third for dolls.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Krajicek, champion two years ago (the only
victimizer of Pete Sampras in Pete's last 39 capers on the old,
balding sod), and Ivanisevic came in for the longest fifth set
trudge in Wimbledon history. One tiebreaking game could have
settled it well before. But no, tradition dictated that they
soldier on and on, for 16 more games before Krajicek _ wondering if
he would miss Christmas at home _ became despondent and forgot
where to serve the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Frying Dutchman, using his gut-strung skillet heatedly,
already had 43 aces. However, after 72 games and 3 hours 20
minutes, Krajicek abruptly couldn't put a first serve in the proper
space. He lost the game and the hyperextended semifinal by an army
serial number score: 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 6-7, 15-13. His long march had
been to oblivion for this year. Ivanisevic's was to a final with
Sampras that nobody, including himself, could have envisioned when
he showed up at the front gate with a 16-14 record (nine first
round losses), a No. 25 ranking and looking like Rasputin: bearded
and wild-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   When Chairman Mao Zedong marched the Red Army that very long way
to remote Shaanxi Province in 1934, they had plenty of time after
arrival for tennis and such interminable sets. It was three decades
before the tiebreaker became a sport-saving gleam in the eye of its
papa, Jimmy Van Alen of Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, according to Mao's biographer, Edgar Snow, the Chairman was
an enthusiastic player in camp while the Commies hid out, preparing
to take over China. Alas, his career ended when a goat ate the net.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic was nearly the goat who choked on a net cord. He had
worked his way to double-match point with serve at 5-4, 40-15 in
the fourth set _ only to bungle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem. It's over. You could win a lot of money betting
I'd lose serve with two match points.'' He hadn't lost it _ yet.
Zing! Goran fired an apparent goodbye ace, and Richard began the
long walk to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly,'' Krajicek says, ``as I think it's over ... it's
still going on. I didn't hear the ball tick the net, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   But, according to an electronic net judging device, it was a
let, to be replayed. Reprieved, Krajicek cracked the momentarily
rejoicing Ivanisevic's serve and forced that slow-boat-to-China,
79-minute fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   Stroking his billygoat beard, Goran looked and felt distraught.
He should have been in the shower long before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strange for me not to lose my temper, but I didn't. I
prove I kept my mind when I break him right back after he breaks
me'' _ to 3-3. ``No more breaks until the end. In the fifth I never
saw somebody serve like Richard. Even when I guessed right _ boom!
_ I couldn't reach it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aces fell like dandruff in a shampoo commercial _ 24 for
Krajicek, 15 for Ivanisevic in the home stretch alone. They totaled
71 for the matinee in which points were shorter than Michael
Jordan's coiffure.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek says he would have preferred a tie-breaker to decide
it, saving 15 games. Ivanisevic likes it the way it is, even though
``my (butt) was sore as hell, and I worried about cramping.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras sides with Ivanisevic until somebody reminds him that he
wouldn't have won the US Open in 1996 if this system were in effect
at Flushing. Swooning, vomiting, he barely wobbled past Alex
Corretja in the fifth-set breaker of their quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it should be the players' option,'' Pete laughs. ``If
I'm throwing up, we play a breaker. Otherwise, play it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some like it hot in a tiebreaking, risky roulette climax; others
like it as long as it can go. Regardless, the fifth was tense,
nerve-pinching as games mounted and the adversaries dueled in
staccato bursts.
</P>
<P>
   Two double faults troubled Goran before he held to 9-8, and
another as he got through deuce to 11-10. A pair of one-armed
bandits, they kept hitting jackpots at each other. Elizabeth Taylor
had a couple of marriages briefer than their fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Triskaidekaphobes in the Centre Court gathering of 13,120 would
have predicted disaster at 13-13. Having no fear of that number,
Goran got to 14. Richard couldn't, bowing out on the Croat
Croaker's backhand passer, and his own wayward volley.
</P>
<P>
   Tiebreaker sire Van Alen used to call such overgrown sets
``urological torture for players, fans and court officials.
Lingering death.''
</P>
<P>
   Sighs of relief greeted the 28th game conclusion where 13 would
have sufficed. But Chairman Mao, who encouraged his marchers with,
``A journey of 1,000 miles begins with the first step,'' might have
hailed it as worthy discipline for these two young capitalists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
