<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-HNS     07-03 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
WIMBLEDON, England _ The Pete Sampras era at Wimbledon began after
a loss to Goran Ivanisevic. That defeat in the 1992 semifinals
opened the door for Andre Agassi, not Sampras, to become the first
player of this latest golden generation of American players to
break through on Centre Court.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ironic, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Today, Agassi is an afterthought, destined to be remembered as a
flukish champion, certainly on Wimbledon's lawns. But Sampras is
one title short of making big-time history. With another victory
Sunday _ against, as fate would have it, Ivanisevic _ he would put
himself in very special company.
</P>
<P>
   In the modern era, only Bjorn Borg has won Wimbledon five times.
Of the Open Era players, only Borg has won 11 Grand Slams. Now,
having stopped Englishman Tim Henman's milestone sprint through the
draw 6-3, 4-6, 7-5, 6-3 in the semifinals Friday, the 26-year-old
Sampras is three sets from pulling even with Borg on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Which also would leave him one Slam championship short of tying
Roy Emerson's all-time record of 12 _ many of them coming in the
mid-1960s when rivals such as Rod Laver, who also claimed 11
majors, had become barnstorming professionals and were thus banned
from tournaments like Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   But after beating Henman, Sampras didn't sound like a man making
a date with destiny. He had left everything on the worn grass,
although he hardly had been through an ordeal like Ivanisevic's
earlier five-set battle with Richard Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fried, to tell you the truth,'' Sampras said. ``It was
very difficult out there. Not only was I battling Tim, the crowd
was pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman, 23, was the first native son to reach a Wimbledon
semifinal since Roger Taylor in 1973. Had he won, and the
boisterous Centre Court audience did everything under its power to
pull him through, he would have been the first British finalist
since Bunny Austin lost to the Grand Slam-bound Don Budge exactly
60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With England's World Cup soccer fortunes having cratered during
the week, there was an air of desperation about Henman's fanciful
bid to upset the No. 1-ranked and top-seeded Sampras, who has been
having a mediocre year by his august standards.
</P>
<P>
   Henman rose to the occasion as best he could in his first Slam
semifinal, but he said he wouldn't accept the outcome as any kind
of moral triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the score is irrelevant,'' he argued. ``It's about
winning and losing. I lost today. That's the bottom line of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, the underachieving Croat who never has won a major,
earned the right to try to change his fortunes and thwart Sampras'
aspirations by hanging on in a grueling 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 6-7 (5-7),
15-13 saga against the 6-foot-5 Dutchman Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   The year he claimed his title, Krajicek had knocked Sampras out
in a rain-plagued quarterfinal that took two days to complete. That
was Sampras' lone loss since the one to Ivanisevic, which Sampras
avenged convincingly in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, he might have preferred to settle his account with
Krajicek as well, but he insisted he is content to take his chances
against Ivanisevic, whose spirit, as well as his serve, he broke in
a straight-sets final that went 7-6, 7-6, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek had suggested last week that Sampras had become just
another player, perhaps no better than 10th-best on the tour in
1998. But if that got under Sampras' skin, he declined to show it
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not personal, you know,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras would be put to a test by Henman and his rabid
army of supporters, he never gave a strong indication he might let
the match slip away. With his serve reaching 136 mph at various
times, he rebounded impressively in the third set after dropping
the second and then staved off Henman's final serious threat to
cloud the outcome when he saved a break point in the first game of
the fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come through there,'' he said, ``that was a big moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Sampras would convert five of his eight break points,
Henman only two of six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's relentless the way he plays,'' Henman said. ``I
think that's why he's so difficult to beat. There's no letup.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who hadn't lost a set at Wimbledon until Henman took
the second, appears to be back to being the Sampras who has headed
the ATP rankings each of the last five years. He has, by his own
admission, had a subpar '98, succumbing in the quarterfinals of the
Australian Open _ a defeat that briefly cost him his No. 1 ranking
to Marcelo Rios _ and the second round of the French Open, the one
major in which he remains a minor player.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivanisevic-Krajicek semifinal had interminably delayed the
start of the much-anticipated Henman-Sampras showdown, dragging on
for 3 hours, 22 minutes after Krajicek, an ace-negating net cord
away from defeat in the 10th game of the fourth set, rallied to
produce one of the longest and most memorable Wimbledon battles in
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was already walking to the net,'' Krajicek admitted. ``I
didn't hear the net cord. I thought it was over. I was going up to
shake his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, though, Krajicek had squared the match, and
then it was Ivanisevic's turn to anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `My God,' but I also say, `OK, you cannot get it back,
so you just have to try to win this set,''' Ivanisevic said. ``A
fifth set, it's always roulette.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour's two biggest servers needed 77 minutes to complete
that final set, since Wimbledon is the only Slam that doesn't
employ the tiebreaker at 6-all in the fifth. They played on for
another 15 games with barely a break in stride before Ivanisevic
put Krajicek in a 15-40 bind and then finished him off with a
jammed forehand return that Krajicek volleyed into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, seeded ninth, had fired 23 aces in the set and 42
overall, compared to the 14th-seeded Ivanisevic's 15 and 28.
Although the bedeviling lefthander from Split was the tournament
leader going in with 133 aces in his five previous wins, he was
definitely outslugged by Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just `boom!' and I couldn't even react,'' Ivanisevic
said. ``Even when I picked the right side, I couldn't reach it. I
never saw anybody serving like that in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, requested to make a prediction about Sunday's outcome,
was outspoken as usual. But he has definitely changed his tune
regarding Sampras, who has beaten Ivanisevic in eight of their last
nine meetings, the latest victory coming in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if Goran plays Pete,'' the Dutchman said, ``he's not
going to win. There were a few holes in his game today. I mean,
he's playing good, but I don't think Pete would let him get away
with what he got away with against me. I think he has to hope he
plays Henman.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of England was hoping that as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
