<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9968 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-DOMESTIC-ART-     07-03 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-DOMESTIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FUNDS FAIL TO MATCH INDEXES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the stock market hot as a firecracker, pushing the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index to record highs, why aren't mutual fund
holders cheering? Because it is no fun to have few or no gains in
one's fund holdings while the indexes race ever higher.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to own a fund that underperforms the market
averages by a few percentage points but still winds up with a gain
in net asset value. At least these shareholders are making money.
</P>
<P>
   But many domestic stock mutual funds this quarter were flat or
slightly down while the major indexes moved up. The average U.S.
diversified stock fund listed in the tables in The New York Times
rose 0.05 percent. The 251 specialized funds lost an average 1.41
percent, while the 655 international funds lost the most: an
average 3.96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast these returns with what the various broad-based indexes
did for the period. The most common benchmark for American stock
funds, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, returned 3.3 percent
during the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index returned 3.2 percent and the Dow
Jones industrial average returned 2.1 percent. Morgan Stanley
Capital International's all-encompassing index of foreign stocks
lost 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only stock funds that outperformed the S&AMP;P during the
quarter were large-capitalization growth funds, up an average 5.24
percent. Large-cap growth and value funds were up just 2.12 percent
and mid-cap growth stock funds eked out gains of only 0.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So when shareholders open their latest fund statements, many
will be wondering what is behind the mediocre performance turned in
by most mutual fund managers this last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it can be attributed to the expenses levied on fund
holders; management fees, sales charges and advertising costs can
really add up, taking 1 percent or more off a fund's performance.
</P>
<P>
   But a more significant driver may be the serious bloodletting
going on in secondary and third-ranked stocks that are not included
in the major indexes. Through June 2, for example, 43 percent of
all Nasdaq stocks were down 30 percent or more; almost two-thirds
had lost 20 percent or more of their value.
</P>
<P>
   According to John L. Manley Jr., equity strategist at Salomon
Smith Barney, only once in the last eight years has greater damage
been done to these stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The positive performance by the major indexes has obscured the
pain. But the further fund managers strayed from the most heavily
weighted stocks in the S&AMP;P 500, the more likely their performances
lagged behind the market's. Small-cap growth funds lost 3.49
percent during the second quarter; small-cap value funds fell 4.86
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason funds may be underperforming the indexes is
related to the weak market for initial public offerings. Access to
hot issues has often helped fuel rocketing fund performance, but
the performance of initial public offerings in the second quarter
was well below the gains made by new issues during the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   According to Securities Data Co., the average gain on new issues
was almost 17 percent in the first quarter. In the second quarter,
the average gain was 9.3 percent. Not bad, but not exactly the push
needed to propel stock fund performance into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fundamentals of various industries also affected
performance. Among the eight sector-fund groups followed by
Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago, four showed
gains and four showed losses. The biggest losers were those
investing in gold and other precious metals, which lost almost 18
percent during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Falling oil prices depressed natural resources funds, which lost
almost 9 percent. Winners included communications company funds,
which rose 1.93 percent, and financial services funds, which gained
1.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market does not deserve all the blame. Some of the
poor performances of many funds may also have their roots in a
subtle shift in the goals of the fund companies. In the 1980s,
mutual fund giants like Fidelity, Vanguard and Putnam once went
after individual customers, with impressive performance as the
lure.
</P>
<P>
   But now, many appear to be more interested in not lagging behind
the market averages to an embarrassing degree. This more defensive
posture has much to do with how funds appeal to today's investors,
because the biggest growth area in the business is in managing
blocks of 401(k) retirement money.
</P>
<P>
   Since retirement money is at issue, 401(k) customers are viewed
as more risk-averse than investors who buy and sell using
discretionary money. Therefore, many funds are focusing on making
sure that performance does not fall way behind the appropriate
benchmark, instead of following the more risky strategy of seeking
to outperform the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These funds know that they are selling to a risk-averse market
and don't want to stick their necks out,'' said Alan Dworsky,
principal at the money management firm Mt. Auburn Management in
Boston, who runs some $600 million in institutional money. ``They
believe they have more to lose by significantly underperforming the
market than they have to gain'' by top returns.
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky, who was a fund manager at Putnam Investments for 17
years before starting his firm in 1984, also noted that the larger
the fund organization, the more likely that the investment
decisions would be dominated by committees, which usually gravitate
toward well-known stocks. This minimizes risk, but it also hurts
their funds' chances of doing much better than their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, conservative funds investing in both corporate
bonds and municipal issues did fairly well in the quarter.
Corporate bond funds, which include those investing in high-yield
bonds, rose 1.24 percent. Municipal bond funds advanced 1.33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of course, fund managers may be in a more defensive posture
these days because so many of them have underperformed the broad
market indexes for years. Only one group of money managers has seen
its funds outperform their benchmark for the last five years: the
small-cap managers.
</P>
<P>
   But this may be because growth stocks have been the place to be
recently, and the Russell 2000 index is relatively easy to beat
because it is underweighted in such recent high-performance areas
as technology and health care. In addition, small-cap fund managers
have been expanding their horizons to include larger-cap issues,
which has probably helped their returns as well.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, this underperformance feeds on itself, making
managers less secure in their stock-picking and more likely to
follow the crowd. It also has sent investors fleeing to funds that
mirror the indexes, offered by Vanguard, Fidelity and others.
</P>
<P>
   Index funds now have $195 billion invested in them, up from
$56.7 billion in 1995. Although index funds account for only 6
percent of the $2 trillion investors have put to work in stock
funds domestically, that percentage is double what it was three
years ago. Morningstar reported that the best-selling fund so far
this year was the Vanguard Index 500 fund.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the money in the so-called closet index funds,
those run by managers interested in mirroring the S&AMP;P's returns but
not willing to own all the stocks in the S&AMP;P 500. These funds,
which own big-cap stocks, are also exceedingly popular among
investors.
</P>
<P>
   According to AMG Data Services, of the roughly $4 billion
investors are currently delivering to fund companies each week,
half goes into index funds or funds that invest in the same
big-capitalization stocks that populate the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   To give fund managers some credit, the disparity between their
performance and the index seems to be narrowing, probably as a
result of a slowing in the averages' bull runs through much of the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12 months ended May 31, for example, the S&AMP;P returned
30.67 percent. During that time, the average large-cap stock fund
with a growth and value blend, the best proxy for the S&AMP;P, returned
only 26.77 percent. That's a difference of almost 4 percentage
points, well above the 1 percent to 2 percent disparity during the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The love affair with big stocks continued during the second
quarter in another measure: every week, investors put more money
into big-cap and index stock funds than they removed, according to
AMG Data Services. Contrast this with the up-and-down investor
interest in small-cap stock funds: in only six of the last 12 weeks
did investors put more money into small caps than they took out.
The rest of the time, investors in small-cap stock funds were net
sellers of these shares.
</P>
<P>
   Will the second quarter's dismal performance lead investors to
dump their funds? Probably not. Investors are famously unfocused on
their fund holdings. Committed to stocks for the long run, most
seem able to take a lot of pain without running for the door.
Losses of 1 percent to 2 percent of assets is not likely to be
enough to raise the ire of investors.
</P>
<P>
   But investors who find their funds lagging behind the market by
more than 2 percentage points should rethink their holdings,
especially in funds that charge fees and loads of more than 1
percent for the privilege of losing money. The Parnassus fund, for
example, which lost roughly 13.3 percent of net asset value during
the most recent quarter, charges a 3.5 percent front-end load.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer Micro Cap B shares lost 9.7 percent in the most recent
quarter. The fund sports an expense ratio of 2.4 percent, a
descending back-end load starting at 4 percent if you sell within
two years of buying the fund, and a 1 percent 12b-1 fee.
</P>
<P>
   As long as fund managers continue to get beaten by stock indexes
in the performance game, investor ardor for index funds and those
that mimic their performance will continue. Indeed, there is a
feedback effect created by the rise of index funds and shadow
indexers.
</P>
<P>
   As the money pours into big-capitalization stock funds, the need
for liquidity in the stocks they buy rises as well. Funds with $2
million to $3 million to put in each stock holding cannot buy
shares in companies that are illiquid without moving these stocks'
prices.
</P>
<P>
   So these fund managers cannot buy anything but the tried and
true, very liquid stocks that dominate the S&AMP;P 500. This drives
those stocks' already high prices even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Will active managers ever again be able to beat the market
averages? Perhaps. But investors might not want to wish for such an
event. When asked under what circumstances mutual fund managers
might be able to outdo the market averages, Amy Arnott, editor of
the Morningstar survey said, ``It would be easier for active
managers to look a little better if the indexes were to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Indexes fall? Maybe middling investment performance by mutual
funds isn't so bad after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
