</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDE POLITICAL AND PHILOSOPHIC GAPS SEPARATE PARTIES PLANS ON
HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Democrats and Republicans want to compromise
their differences on legislation to define patients' rights, they
will have to bridge a broad conceptual and political gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats would establish far more protections for
consumers. But to do so, they would create vast new authority for
the federal government to regulate the operation of health
maintenance organizations and insurance companies. The government
would, for example, set standards for the quality of care,
including coverage of prescription drugs and the length of hospital
stays for mastectomy patients.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, too, follow their traditions. They say they trust
the market, abhor big government and want to avoid litigation. They
offer several proposals that have no parallel in the Democratic
bill. The Republicans would expand the use of medical savings
accounts, limit damage awards in medical malpractice suits and help
small businesses band together to buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such differences, the Democratic bill, which is strongly
supported by President Clinton, and the Republican proposal, which
is still being translated into legislation, have a common core.
</P>
<P>
   Both would require coverage of emergency care whenever ``a
prudent lay person'' would consider it necessary. Both assure women
that they can go directly to obstetricians and gynecologists
without getting prior authorization or a referral. Both ban ``gag
rules,'' restricting what doctors can tell patients about treatment
options. Both require health plans to disclose certain information,
so consumers can compare costs, benefits and performance.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills would also establish procedures for patients to
appeal the denial of health services or payment by seeking review
from an independent panel of medical experts. Both require health
plans to keep medical records confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Both also say many consumers could, for an extra charge, buy
coverage that would allow them to use any doctor. Such patients
would not be confined to a list of physicians approved by their
health plan.
</P>
<P>
   But each bill also includes many provisions not found in the
other. For example, the Democratic bill would make it easier for
people to sue HMOs and employer-sponsored health plans, under state
law, for personal injury or wrongful death caused by the improper
denial of benefits. Patients could seek reimbursement for lost
wages, compensation for pain and suffering and punitive damages in
some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican proposal, patients could obtain a more
limited type of relief in disputes over the denial of benefits.
They could go to court to recover the amount of the original claim,
plus lawyers' fees and court costs, and they could seek a court
order requiring their health plans to provide a particular benefit
or service. Health plans would have an incentive to provide
promised benefits in a timely way because they would be subject to
a penalty, perhaps $250, for each day they improperly withheld
care.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and advocates for consumer groups prefer the Democratic
approach. ``HMOs should be held liable if they make medical
decisions, just as physicians are,'' said James H. Stacey, a
spokesman for the American Medical Association. But insurers and
HMOs adamantly oppose any expansion of their liability, saying it
would raise costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill would establish new protections for doctors,
nurses and other health care workers who report evidence of
substandard care to the government authorities. Labor unions that
represent hospital and nursing home employees have sought such
protections for whistle-blowers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the Democratic proposals would dismantle the
fundamental structure of managed care while their own proposals
would build confidence in it by guaranteeing adequate recourse for
patients who have disputes with their health plans. Conversely,
Democrats say the Republican demands for medical savings accounts
and limits on malpractice suits are ``poison pills'' that would
kill legislation to regulate managed care.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Democratic bill appears to be far more prescriptive, but it
is impossible to be sure because details of the Republican bill are
not yet available.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a summary of Democratic proposals not found in the
blueprint devised by House Republicans:
</P>
<P>
   _ A health plan must have ``a sufficient number, distribution
and variety'' of doctors to serve all its patients in a timely way.
</P>
<P>
   _ If an HMO does not have an ``appropriate specialist'' to treat
a patient with a serious or complex medical condition, it must
refer the patient to a specialist outside its network, at no extra
cost to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   _ If an HMO terminates a doctor's contract, it must continue
coverage for patients receiving ``a course of treatment'' from that
doctor, including pregnant women and people with terminal
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   _ A health plan must cover at least 48 hours of hospital care
for a mastectomy, and it must cover reconstructive breast surgery
after the operation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health plans and insurance companies must help pay the routine
costs of care for people in clinical trials and research studies if
they have serious illnesses for which no standard treatment is
effective.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a health plan or an insurance policy provides any coverage
of prescription drugs, and if it establishes a list of approved
medications, it must also pay for other drugs when they are
``medically indicated.'' Moreover, if a new drug has been approved
by the Food and Drug Administration, insurers may not refuse to
cover it by contending that its use is ``investigational.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In delivering health care services, an HMO may not
discriminate against patients on the basis of race, religion, sex,
age, mental or physical disability, sexual orientation or genetic
information. This provision does not require insurers to offer
coverage to everyone who applies, nor does it affect the premiums
that may be charged.
</P>
<P>
   _ An HMO or an insurance company may not arbitrarily interfere
with or alter a doctor's decision about the ``manner or setting''
in which services are provided, if they are medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Democratic bill, private health plans and insurers
would have to collect a wide range of data on the use of services,
the quality of care, mortality rates, customer satisfaction, the
number of grievances and the demographic characteristics of
patients. The government would prescribe a standard format, and the
secretary of health and human services would have access to all the
data collected.
</P>
</TEXT>
