<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTONA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytona and Pepsi 400 feels the heat
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The wildfires have transformed this city
and the baby powder and underwear in the middle of a sports bar are
among the many starkclues.
</P>
<P>
   The ash on cars and the masks on faces is more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepsi 400, the city's strongest summer lure and a $100
million economic infusion, was postponed Thursday as the fires
pressed closer and closer to Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of a bustling weekend, businesses tried to make due
in a city that, at times, looked like it was at the foot of a
volcano rather than the edge of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just kills us, but what can you do?'' said Armando
Deloera, general manager of Rio Bravo's Cantina, next to the
speedway. ``I really don't think anyone is worried about business.
We're just trying to feed as many firefighters and help as many
people as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant owners are still serving up huge amounts of food.
Bartenders keep serving drinks to customers lined up five-deep. And
Hooters waitresses still attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of catering to 150,000 or so race fans, businesses
are serving hundreds of firefighters who have battled the fires for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters sent its waitresses to fire stations delivering chicken
wings, while other restaurants converted to relief stations.
</P>
<P>
   Houligan's Sports Pub, about five miles from the front lines of
Volusia County's fires, has become the favorite spot for
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of cases of Gatorade and water, ice, food, underwear,
baby powder, eye drops and dozens of socks sit where beer bottles
and happy hour food usually are seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle sits Houligan's owner Walter Curtis. Curtis
jokingly acknowledges he didn't have much choice but to become a
Good Samaritan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cops came in Wednesday night and kicked everybody out,''
Curtis said. ``They evacuated the whole area, so what the hell else
was I going to do? I had an empty restaurant and a lot of people
who needed help, so it made sense. But, yeah, it kills a HUGE
weekend for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many people who have pitched in to help, one tourist
stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Loomis of Columbus, Ga. came to Ormond Beach four days ago
for a family reunion. Instead, he's become a reluctant celebrity, a
volunteer who organized a massive relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters in two towns talk about him as they take breaks
from the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm just one of those do-gooders saving the day,''
Loomis said. ``It keeps me off the street and out of trouble, I
suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Others handled their ruined vacations differently. Greg and Dana
Cline of Columbia, Mo. arrived Monday with their two young sons,
hoping to see their first race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we knew it was like this, we never would have come,'' Dana
Cline said. ``It's been difficult, but we are going to go back to
safe homes, so it puts things in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to get rid of our tickets, because we're not
coming back,'' Greg said.
</P>
<P>
   That should be no problem. Several men lined Speedway Boulevard
Friday carrying ``I need tickets'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   It's seems scalpers survive any natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
