u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-330&AMP;ADD-     07-03 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN OFFICIALS SAY PACT ON KOSOVO SEEMS UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Key U.S. and French officials vowed Friday to keep
pushing for a diplomatic solution to head off a wider war in
Kosovo, but agreed that chances for success in the violence-torn
Serbian province were uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is intensifying its effort, but this issue
is going to be decided on the ground in Kosovo,'' said Richard
Holbrooke, nominated by President Clinton to be the U.S. delegate
to the United Nations and a special envoy to the Balkans.
Meanwhile, fighting between Serbian government forces and
secessionist ethnic Albanian rebels continued.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke spoke Friday before leaving Paris for Belgrade for
another round of talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
and the political leader of the Kosovo Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova,
whom U.S. and European diplomats regard as the key Albanian player
in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Paris, Holbrooke said Western efforts to
press Milosevic into ordering heavily armed Serbian forces in the
province to stop attacking Albanian rebels were clouded by
uncertainty about who spoke for the Kosovo Liberation Army, which
has seized about 40 percent of the territory in the last couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal for the province, which enjoyed wide powers of
self-government within Serbia until Milosevic abolished autonomy in
1989, is independence, which no Western country supports.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said he told that to rebel commanders he met near the
provincial capital of Pristina last week, and the principal U.S.
troubleshooter in the Balkans, Robert Gelbard, had a separate
meeting a week ago with two exile leaders claiming to speak for the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting did not establish that the people with whom he met
had authority or influence over the men with guns,'' Holbrooke said
Friday. ``How do you negotiate a cease-fire and a withdrawal of
forces when you don't know you are in contact with the people in
control?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, who conferred with
Holbrooke for an hour Thursday on Western strategy for keeping the
fighting from spreading into Albania and Macedonia, said Friday,
``A catastrophe scenario is quite possible despite all our
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vedrine said the threat of NATO air strikes against Serbia
had kept Milosevic from ordering a full-scale Serbian military
assault to retake rebel-held areas.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials estimate that Serbia, which with Montenegro
makes up what remains of Yugoslavia, has 30,000 troops, 25,000
heavily armed police officers, dozens of anti-aircraft missile
batteries and heavy artillery and armor in the province, where at
least 90 percent of the population of about 2 million is ethnic
Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we will resolve the dilemma,'' Vedrine said
at a breakfast with U.S. and British reporters. ``If Milosevic
orders a big operation, we cannot remain inactive.''
</P>
<P>
   France, a NATO ally, supported contingency planning ordered last
month by allied defense ministers to prepare for the use of
military force if necessary to stop the fighting in Kosovo, Vedrine
said. But the French believe that any action by the allies should
first be approved by the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China, both permanent members of the Security Council
with the power to veto decisions there, are both opposed to outside
military intervention in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine could not say Friday what France would do if Serbia
unleashed a full-scale attack and the Russians vetoed a Security
Council resolution authorizing NATO to act. United States officials
have said that United Nations authorization would be desirable, but
they do not think it is indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has worked with the United States, Britain, France, Italy
and Germany in the so-called contact group of nations monitoring
the cease-fire that Holbrooke brokered in Bosnia in 1995, and has
urged Milosevic to pull back in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to use force, and we may, and if we went in without
United Nations authority, we would not be in a position to insist
that Russia, China, Nigeria, or other countries cannot use force
without United Nations authorization,'' Vedrine said. But he added
that he did not think that Russia or China had said their last
words yet on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine and other French officials said they had pushed allied
military planners in Brussels to come up with as wide a range of
military options as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the only option was to bomb strategic Serbian military and
communications sites throughout the country, the next day the
Kosovo Liberation Army could declare Kosovo a sovereign republic,
Albania could join in supporting it, and the war could spread to
Macedonia and beyond,'' Vedrine said. ``The use of force could
provoke exactly the opposite of the desired result.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no simple military option we haven't taken simply
because we were afraid to do so,'' Vedrine insisted.
</P>
</TEXT>
