<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BIRDHUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIANT FRANCE WILL LET BIRD HUNTERS BLAST AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bashing those meddling European bureaucrats in Brussels,
Belgium, long a favorite pastime in Britain, is now in season in
France, where President Jacques Chirac signed into law Thursday a
measure defying a Europe-wide regulation that bans the hunting of
migratory birds during the nesting period.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Margaret Thatcher when she was Britain's prime minister,
Chirac took little apparent pleasure in defying Brussels, where the
bureaucracy has already threatened legal action that could end in a
European Court of Justice fine against France of about $114,000 for
every day it violates the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president desires coordination between the government and
the European Commission to find a solution to this affair,'' his
office said after announcing that Chirac had signed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Passed by the French Legislature last month over only cursory
resistance by the Socialist-led government, the law allows hunters
to fire away at waterfowl up to a month beyond the end of the
season next Jan. 31, as prescribed since 1979 in a Europe-wide
directive.
</P>
<P>
   That directive was approved by French elected officials at the
time, according to Environment Minister Dominique Voynet, a member
of the Greens party who described herself as furious and insulted
by the behavior of her legislative colleagues when they raised
their guns in Parliament last month.
</P>
<P>
   The directive, adopted unanimously, was intended to protect
birds during the reproductive cycle. International lawyers say
European law supersedes any national legislation that contradicts
it, supposedly binding all 15 member states of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   France is usually a pillar of that union, except occasionally
when disgruntled farmers and other rural denizens rise up against
regulations that tell them how much grain they can grow and how big
tomatoes and cucumbers should be.
</P>
<P>
   The French heartland has become increasingly insurgent about the
hunting rules, and earlier this year 800,000 French hunters signed
a petition to the European Parliament, asking for a modification of
the regulations. A million petitioners from other countries joined
in the protest, and Alessandro Fontana, a member of the European
Parliament's commission on petitions, told the daily Le Figaro last
month that the directive might be changed next fall if French
hunters would just be patient and go through European channels.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing an easy target, French legislators of every party except
Mrs. Voynet's Greens vowed to defy Brussels and let French hunters
keep blasting.
</P>
<P>
   France has two months to settle the conflict out of court with
the European Commission, which can otherwise go to the European
Court of Justice in Luxembourg and ask it to find France in
violation of its treaty obligations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
