<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUMP, MIZE, URESTI, WAITE HAVE OUTSTANDING DAY AT GHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ As Stewart Cink surveyed the scoreboard after
Friday's second round of the Greater Hartford Open at the TPC at
River Highlands, he compared this year to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's night-and-day difference,'' said Cink. The rain and wind
came early and now the course is soft and the winds died down.
These are perfect scoring conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the field was stacked with a host of big names, the
players who showed up ripped the place apart in Friday's sunny and
soft conditions. Scott Gump showed the way by equaling Billy
Andrade's course record with a 62. Larry Mize checked in a 63 and
Omar Uresti and Grant Waite had 64s. There were 77 rounds in the
60s and 76 players bettered par 70. The cut was 139, matching the
low numbers of the year (Hawaii, Byron Nelson). Translated, you had
to have broken par for the first two rounds to play today's third
round here in the suburbs of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Gump wound up leading with minus-10 figures of 62_130 to take a
one-shot lead over Omar Uristi (64) and Mize. Waite, Cink (65) and
Doug Tewell (66) trailed at 132. Pete Morgan, the Cape Cod native
son who was a Monday qualifier and led after the first round with a
64, hung on to easily make the cut with 71_135. Casey Martin,
playing in his first PGA Tour event after getting an injunction to
ride in a cart, took an 8 on the 13th hole and missed the cut with
73_144.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who made the cut at the US Open at San Francisco's
Olympic Club and finished tied for 23d, plans to play Quad Cities
next week but is undecided beyond that. ``I played poorly,'' said
Martin. ``I wish I wouldn't have played like I did. It was fun. The
people are great. They went out of their way to treat me well and
encourage me. I didn't hit it well at all. It's pretty much what I
expected. It's hard, but if you uplay well you can score. I'm not
sure what I'll take out of here. Give me time on that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gump, who has played in 18 PGA Tour events this year but whose
best finish was a tie for 19th in the BellSouth Classic, started on
the 10th tee and birdied the 12th (9-iron, 15 feet), 13th (wedge, 3
feet), 15th (sand wedge, 15 feet), 17th (7-iron, 20 feet), and
18th, when he watched a 210-yard 4-wood out of a fairway bunker
bounce out of trouble to four feet of the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a bonus,'' said Gump. ``It just hit left of the
bunker, rolled up to four feet. I wasn't planning on that one.''
</P>
<P>
   After that he birdied the 2d (7-iron, 20 feet), 3d (pitching
wedge, 4 feet) and 8th (5-iron, 8 feet) to shoot his 62 and match
Andrade's score in the third round three years ago. ``I just wanted
to keep it going,'' said Gump. ``It was fun. I knew if I was seven
under after 11, I had a chance to shoot 59. You don't get those
opportunities too often. That was in my mind. You never know. I may
get lucky, make a couple of putts, and boom.'' He was happy to take
his 62 and the lead and get into the Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Uresti, who led Bay Hill going into the final round a year ago,
was actually in minus-11 figures before bogeys on the 15th and 16th
holes brought him down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little wait on the 15th tee,'' said Uresti. ``I
started thinking about everything and was getting anxious and a
little nervous. I just got a little quick with my tee shot and hit
into the right rough. I got a little quick on the next hole with a
7-iron, ended on the right front of the green and didn't hit my
first putt hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mize, whose most famous moment came when he holed out a shot on
the second hole to beat Greg Norman in the Masters 11 years ago,
had front and back nines of 31-32. ``It was a great day to play
golf,'' he said. ``I'm happy with it. I haven't really gotten
myself in this poisition, so that's what exciting about it. You
can't win a golf tournament until you get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who grew up in Harwich, made his first cut in his fourth
PGA Tour event at age 35. Even though his 64 led the tournament
after the first round, he said he felt Friday's round, which
included one birdie and two bogeys, was solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm happier with this round,'' said Morgan. ``I think
the pressure's off now.'' He had trouble sleeping Thursday night.
``I never thought about it until somebody brought it up in the
pressroom. Now I just want to do the best I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
