<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDRICKSON DELIVERS ON CUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy defender Ezra Hendrickson
could have just as easily chosen cricket instead of soccer as his
sport of choice. While he grew up on the tiny island of St. Vincent
&AMP; The Grenedines in the West Indies, cricket was the more popular.
But Hendrickson stuck with soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone played cricket; it was all over the place,''
Hendrickson said. ``And I was a pretty good batsman too, but in
grammar school I chose soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson's parents separated when he was 13 and he moved with
his father to Indiana. The only cricket anyone heard of there, they
stepped on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basketball and basketball,'' Hendrickson said of
Kokomo, Ind. ``And it was cold, very cold.''
</P>
<P>
   His MLS career was almost over before it began. Hendrickson
wasn't selected in the inaugural MLS draft in 1996. He went to the
A-League, where he was named defensive player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, New York/New Jersey of MLS made him a first-round draft
pick, but Hendrickson only started four games and was put on
waivers last August. Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano quickly picked
him up.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 games with the Galaxy this season, Hendrickson has earned
the reputation as the best attacking defender in MLS. He has netted
five goals with six assists since he became a regular starter March
28 for the injured Paul Caligiuri.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a season of redemption for Hendrickson. Throughout
his career, coaches have dwelled upon his awkward running style and
lanky 6-foot-3 frame and have failed to appreciate the soccer
player underneath. But given a chance, he's delivered at every
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely have a different look of what a soccer player
should look like, but I never pay much attention to that,''
Hendrickson said. ``Coaches can say what they want, but if you can
play the game, that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, known for his ability to spot talent, took criticism
when he picked Hendrickson off waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see how he can be dismissed at first sight,'' Zambrano
said. ``And I had my doubts and share of critics when I picked him,
but I said to myself, `In time, this guy will come around.' You
know, he doesn't look like a player or run like a player, but he is
a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson's deceptive quickness allows him to attack up the
flanks, where he has scored more MLS points (16) than any defender
in the league. He also has incredible stamina to hurry back on
defense. He's had such an impact that Zambrano will have a big
decision to make with Caligiuri coming off the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson's minor ligament strain in his right foot allowed
Caligiuri to start last Saturday against San Jose, where Caligiuri
scored a goal in a 2-1 victory. But once Hendrickson's healthy
again, he says he's going to continue to make Zambrano's decision a
tough one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said when I was on the bench, that when I got my
chance, I was going to make it hard for Octavio to put me back
there,'' Hendrickson said. ``I think I've done that and I'm going
to continue to make it a hard choice for him to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, not sure who will be the regular starter when both are
healthy, says he will weigh his options and do what's best for the
team. He could start both. Zambrano does agree, however, that
Hendrickson should be given a spot in the MLS All-Star game, Aug.
2, in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' he said. `C'mon, show me a defender that
has done what he has done? I'm surprised he hasn't gotten player of
the week yet because he's had marvelous matches back to back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
