<HEADLINE>
HOW FLORIDA'S WILDFIRES DEVELOPED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also FLA-FIRES, as well as extensive coverage of the
Florida wild fires from Cox) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida's troubles with weather and wildfires in June and July
actually began last winter.
</P>
<P>
   While El Nino was grabbing center stage as a prime culprit in
producing tornadoes in Florida in February, the winter there _ as
in the rest of the country _ shaped up less obviously and more
quietly as unusually wet and warm, a condition that also was
probably due to El Nino. Bushes and grass grew faster than usual
and became thicker, meteorologists say, producing abundant fuel for
any fires that might start.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late spring and early summer, the moisture tailed off
but the warmth remained. Aloft, two on-again, off-again climatic
features joined forces to dry out the state. First the jet stream,
the high-altitude, west-to-east river of strong wind that marks the
boundary between masses of cold polar air and warm tropical ones,
was stronger than normal in the spring. And its path was farther
south than usual.
</P>
<P>
   This had the effect of suppressing rainfall in northern and
central Florida. In the spring, the sun heats Florida's land mass
more than the surrounding water. This creates a pattern of
relatively low-level air circulation in which the heated earth
causes air to rise over the land and sink over the water. With lots
of moisture in the air, this pattern creates thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   This year that arrangement was thrown off kilter by the strong
jet-stream winds that ordinarily would not be present, said Fred
Gadomski, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University. The
result was a suppression of storms and rain.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a persistent high-pressure system, as
sometimes happens in the atmosphere, lodged stubbornly in position
over Florida and the Gulf of Mexico. This also suppressed the
formation of storms.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these large-scale circulation patterns were influenced
by the aftereffects of El Nino is unclear. Even though the big pool
of warm water in the eastern South Pacific that defines El Nino has
disappeared, Gadomski said, it takes time for the climate system to
respond. So it is a ``reasonable hypothesis'' that the lingering
effects of El Nino could have had something to do with the unusual
circulation pattern, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, northern and central Florida have had only a
fraction of their normal precipitation this spring and early
summer. The abnormally lush growth of vegetation dried out,
providing abundant tinder. Any spark _ a match, a campfire, a
deliberately set blaze, a relatively rare lightning strike _ might
have set it afire.
</P>
<P>
   With less moisture on the land, less of the sun's energy has
been devoted to evaporating moisture, and more has gone into
heating the earth. Result: record high temperatures, which
intensify the drought even further. In June, Melbourne, Fla., had
more than 20 days with temperatures higher than 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability of this occurring is less than one in 1,000,''
said David Easterling, a climate scientist at the National Climatic
Data Center, a federal installation in Asheville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that something new is going on? Computer models
suggest that as the earth's atmosphere warms, as it has been for
about a century, its water cycle should become more intense: Heavy
rainstorms become more common, while at the other end of the
continuum droughts become worse.
</P>
<P>
   The center has gathered evidence that heavy rains are indeed
becoming more common. But ``on the dry end, there is none that I
know of,'' said Robert Quayle of the climatic data center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES-BOS &LR;      07-03 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA WILDFIRES WORSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER   AND BRAD LISTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM COAST, Fla. _ Fed by bountiful, bone-dry brush, Florida's
worst wildfires this century continued a merciless march through
this state Friday, forcing 30,000 people from one coastal county
into frantic flight down Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that the fingers of several blazes in coastal Flagler
County could unite into a powerful _ and potentially deadly _ fist
of fire, state emergency managers ordered a countywide evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   That brought to 70,000 the number of Floridians who have been
chased from their homes during a two-day assault on the wind-blown
east coast from Jacksonville to Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish we knew when this was going to be over,'' said Richard
Wieser, a Flagler County emergency management spokesman. ``Nature's
course is that this fire will continue to build.''
</P>
<P>
   As they snaked their way along jammed evacuation routes, many
residents got their first hard look at what the wildfires had
wrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never looked like this on television,'' said Maria
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who fled the flames described a chaotic scene as
thousands of people loaded vehicles with possessions ranging from
furniture and computers to clothing and books. One man stuffed a
deer head into his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation was complete chaos,'' said Palm Beach resident
Jeff Bardy, who left his home Friday morning. ``People were getting
no information or bad information. People were panicking and there
was nobody on the scene with any information. You've got to know
when it's time to get out, and it was time to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Portions of Interstate 95, the main north-south highway on the
Atlantic Coast, remained closed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But by last night, officials said they were hoping an unexpected
sea breeze would prevent diverse fires in Flagler County from
converging.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Governor Lawton Chiles said: ``It doesn't look like we're
going to get any relief any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tallahassee, the state capital, Federal Emergency Management
Agency Director James Lee Witt implored residents to heed
evacuation orders _ some shouted from police bullhorns _ to prevent
the fire from growing from a multimillion-dollar catastrophe into a
killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do everything we can to help you rebuild,'' said Witt,
who announced millions more in federal disaster aid. ``The most
important thing is not to get killed or injured. We can help
rebuild, but we can't help replace a life.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene in central Florida, north of the Kennedy Space Center
and east of Disney World, where Mickey Mouse's parade was
unaffected, was nothing less than surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Gray smoke blocked out the sun. Ashes drifted slowly from the
skies. Screaming sirens drowned out sidewalk conversation.
Temperatures hovered near 100 degrees Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night it looks like hell,'' said Jerry Kiser, 51, who has
been forced from a home he believes has survived the flames.
``During the day, it sounds like a war zone. It's just terrifying
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Smith said he grabbed his little boy's fire truck, his
infant daughter's toy carousel, and some clothes when the call came
for his family of five to evacuate their mobile home in Mims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we've got is back there. We lose that stuff and we
lose everything. There's no way we can afford to replace it,'' said
Smith, who has been sleeping on the cot of a Red Cross shelter.
``We moved here five months ago from Missouri and we're going back.
We kind of lost hope when all this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 4,000 firefighters battling the 1,900 blazes, which have
blackened more than 500 square miles and destroyed more than 150
homes since late May, hope for rain and relief is what cushions a
grueling regimen at the fire line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of flames. A lot of smoke. Visibility is real
poor. The heat's bad. You get tired real quick,'' said Andrew
Schulte, a 21-year-old firefighter from Micco, who has been working
18-hour-a-day shifts. ``The fire's going every place. We've been
working for days and days and days, and we can't stop it. We think
we got a hold on it and it goes someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Banfield, 38, a Palm Bay firefighter, sat exhausted in the
cab of his pumper truck Friday afternoon, dripping sweat and
visibly exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting a losing battle here. We can't seem to beat
it,'' he said. ``But this state is my home. And I'm going to defend
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Schulte and Banfield prepared to take another shift, federal
officials nearby were plotting how to dampen the fire's power by
air, directing a fleet of helicopter and fixed-wing aircraft,
imploring the pilots under their command to make safety their
watchword.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to play catch up on the old fires, and the new
ones keep starting up and we just don't have the resources,'' said
Ryan Curl of the federal Bureau of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to extinguish these fires, we're going to need a
major rain event,'' he said. ``The brush is so dry and so plentiful
that within a few hours after we get to them, they're right back to
where they were when we started _ and at full intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   By early last night, a steady rainfall began in evacuated
Flagler County _ welcome relief where four fires were raging and
officials were hoping the rain would prevent them from becoming a
wall of flames.
</P>
<P>
   But even the rainfall that residents have been praying for for
days is not without its danger. Meteorologists said lightning
strikes were possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we have a thunderstorm, it's like little fingers
walking across the carpet,'' said Mary Verry of the US Forest
Service. ``You can just see the fires just flaring up all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In Flagler County, the evacuation order sparked anger and
bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Don Pell, 70, said he was forced to evacuate Thursday night only
to return to his home Friday as fire crews were pulling away. His
home and the home behind it were still standing, but they were the
only whole structures left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire department just put out the big fires and took off,''
Pell said. ``There were still plenty of small fires and they left
them for me to take care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Using three garden hoses, Pell kept the resurgent fires off the
two properties for four hours. When he was finished, his and his
neighbor's lawns looked like nearly perfect postage stamps of green
among the smoldering black ruins of the other lots on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't talked my way back in here, there wouldn't have
been anything standing in this neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Connor, a 12-year resident and former New York City
firefighter, said: ``If Flagler County was some little
oil-producing country, they'd have the Marines, the Army. They'd
have everybody here. Where's the Army?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
