<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SWEEPING PRIVATIZATION ANNOUNCED IN SOUTH KOREA
</P>
<P>
   Looking for expedient ways to raise cash, the South Korean
government began a far-reaching effort to privatize large
industries, most notably the giant Pohang Iron and Steel Corp., the
world's second-biggest steelmaker behind Nippon Steel of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The government's shares in the steelmaker and four other
state-controlled companies and their subsidiaries are to go on sale
immediately. Six other companies will be privatized over a
four-year period. South Korea hopes to reap $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SHELL WITHDRAWS FROM RUSSIA BID
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch Shell said it was quitting a joint bid for Rosneft,
Russia's last state-owned oil company, because low oil prices would
limit returns from the project it was expected to finance. Shell,
the world's biggest publicly traded oil company, also attributed
the decision to financial turmoil in Russia that has created acute
problems for its two Russian partners in the bid, Lukoil and
Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Fyodorov, the new head of Russia's State Tax Service, has
a difficult task in a country where tax avoidance is a pastime. But
Fyodorov has embraced the challenge, going after the delinquent
Gazprom gas monopoly and even raiding warehouses of deadbeat vodka
distillers.
</P>
<P>
   IBM RETREAT IN LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   IBM said it would no longer make computer engineering deals with
Latin American governments. The change, disclosed by an IBM
executive, comes against a backdrop of a bribery investigation in
Argentina that has implicated some former IBM officials.
</P>
<P>
   VW HAS ROLLS, MAYBE NOT ITS NAME
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen completed its purchase of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars but
may be missing one of the most important parts of the deal _ the
legendary Rolls brand name. Rolls-Royce PLC, the jet engine maker,
says it still retains control of the name and VW has no right to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   ODD EFFECT OF MEDICARE RULES
</P>
<P>
   The government took a big step this week to make the business of
caring for elderly patients less lucrative, dealing a setback to
hospitals, some nursing homes and home care services. But oddly,
under new cost-reduction rules that took effect July 1, Medicare
patients are likely to spend more days, not fewer, in nursing homes
and beds for acute care in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   All financial and commodities markets in the United States were
closed on Friday in observance of the Fourth of July holiday. Most
markets overseas were open.
</P>
</TEXT>
