<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sampras, Ivanisevic finally arrive
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It was whap, thwack, boom on Centre Court
at Wimbledon on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the points went quickly on the grass of the All
England Club, the matches stretched for hours before No.1 seed Pete
Sampras and No.14 Goran Ivanisevic each won and secured spots in
Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras took 2 hours, 24 minutes to defeat Britain's beloved Tim
Henman 6-3, 3-6, 7-5, 6-3. But Ivanisevic needed 3 hours, 18
minutes to upset No.9 Richard Krajicek 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 6-7 (5-7),
15-13.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic had two chances to win at 5-4 in the fourth set. But
he lost that game after both he and Krajicek thought Ivanisevic had
served an ace and joked when the umpire called a let because it had
tipped the net. ``He was already, at 40-15, laughing at the
match,'' said three-time winner and BBC commentator Boris Becker.
``Krajicek knows it isn't over yet. I can't believe it. Terrible
move. Now the whole match could change.''
</P>
<P>
   The former king of Centre Court was accurate. The fourth set
went to a tiebreaker, which Krajicek won on his third chance.
Krajicek's service return was off all day, but both his serve and
return improved in the final two sets.
</P>
<P>
   He served 42 aces in the match _ four off Ivanisevic's record _
with 23 in the fifth set. Ivanisevic, long called the best male
player never to win a major, hit just 14.
</P>
<P>
   But Krajicek was just as surprised as all the fans waiting to
watch Henman that he remained on the court to earn his first lead
in the fifth set, although it only lasted a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already was walking to the net,'' Krajicek said. ``I didn't
hear the net cord at 40-15, so I thought the match was over. It was
a strange feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth set was a monotonous duel, with the players trading
service breaks in the fifth and sixth games and then not seeing
another break point until 15-40 in the 28th game. For the duration,
they exchanged aces and only a handful of points with more than
three hits before the point ended.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek finally put a backhand into the net to lose 15-13 after
an hour and 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, ranked an unusually low 25, knelt to the grass in
disbelief, then tossed his racket, bandanna and two towels into the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a lot because a lot of people say, `He's gone. He's
never going to be back,' and you have two ears and you have to
listen all the time,'' Ivanisevic said. ``I think it's time to
change on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a long way from Sunday late in the fourth set. He had
just blown two shots at winning and, as Becker put it, ``His
strongest point was never his concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek knew he still could win it because Ivanisevic has a
reputation for becoming destracted and destroying himself with his
temper, then jumping back alive at unexpected times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Goran,'' Krajicek said. ``The only thing predictable
about him is he's unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic did double fault 16 times and struggled with his
first serve throughout. But his volleying was strong and he took
advantage of his chances. Plus, he didn't melt into distraction or
personal aggravation. He wasn't even tempted to hurl a racket to
the ground or yell profanities in Croatian at himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strange, you know,'' he said. ``But I (was thinking),
if I lose it for just a second, I will lose the match. I don't
think anybody bet on me when I lost the fourth set.''
</P>
<P>
   He will play Sunday in his third Wimbledon and Grand Slam final.
He is seeking his first title against a man who already owns 10 and
needs one now to redeem a flagging year.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek doesn't think Ivanisevic is up to beating Sampras, who
played a nearly error-free, intense match with Henman.
</P>
<P>
   Brits filled nearly every seat on Centre Court, wearing
patriotic hats and waving Union Jack and St. George's Cross flags
of all sizes. They went wild when he won the first point of the
match but had little to say again until he won the second set and
played a strong third.
</P>
<P>
   ``(At) 6-5, I raised my level just a little bit, hit some good
shots, and that was really the key to the match,'' said Sampras,
who is seeking to tie Bjorn Borg's modern-day Wimbledon title
record of five.
</P>
<P>
   Henman was disappointed, both for himself and for disappointing
a nation that believes it suffered athletic disaster this week in
World Cup soccer and was hoping Henman could soothe the agony.
</P>
<P>
   But his fans appreciated the high level of tennis he played, and
some were even surprised he did so well. Sampras had nothing but
praise for his friend and frequent practice partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very solid player and will eventually win this
tournament,'' said Sampras, who called the match one of his best of
the year. He showed more emotion than usual, yelling several times,
arguing calls and even tossing a cracked racket over his shoulder
into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very intense,'' he said. ``I felt I was playing Tim and
the crowd, so obviously I was going to show a little more emotion
than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
