<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-NOTEBOOK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Novotna hoping `third time lucky'
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Only the English could so adore as
disastrous a loser as Jana Novotna.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Novotna is a loser, but here at Wimbledon, the finalist
today lost in royally English fashion five years ago. She was
leading 4-1, and a point from 5-1, in the third set against Steffi
Graf.
</P>
<P>
   But Novotna looked around, noticed she was about to win and
nearly stopped breathing with fear. She lost 7-6 (8-6), 1-6, 6-4
and sobbed on the shoulder of the Duchess of Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she gets her third chance to win a Grand Slam _ and make
good on what the Duchess told her when she lost to Martina Hingis
last year: ``Third time lucky.'' Novotna meets 16th seed Nathalie
Tauziat of France in the oldest final since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   And England wants Novotna to win the title almost as much as
they wanted Brit Tim Henman to triumph on the men's side.
</P>
<P>
   They love Novotna because she lost the way England so often
loses: after a big lead, clearly the better competitor, in a manner
that makes fans want to wail.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist for The Times of London explained it: ``We simply
cannot help loving anyone who has fouled up in so spectacular a
fashion. We can all identify with self-created disaster, and there
is nothing in life so gorgeous as the thought that wrongs can
somehow be put right.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna didn't discuss her 1993 collapse the day she beat Hingis
to reach the final, but she did earlier in the tournament. She
would be satisfied, she said, if not happy, to end her career
without a Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   She is relaxed about tennis and has found a way to balance hard
work with fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on the court you can just see her always laughing,''
said Lindsay Davenport, who used to play doubles with Novotna.
</P>
<P>
   Today, against an opponent who has never played a Grand Slam
final and won just four singles titles in 14 years on tour, Novotna
expects a difficult match.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat made a stunning comeback against Natasha Zvereva in the
semifinals and upset second seed Lindsay Davenport in the
quarterfinals. Despite her low ranking and lack of experience in
this situation, she has had a calm confidence this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I said my goal is Wimbledon and I want to make
it,'' Tauziat said.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna doesn't want the moon, just another good cry _ this one
for joy.
</P>
<P>
   Graf will play U.S. Open: Five-time U.S. Open champion Steffi
Graf has signed up to play the tournament again this year. Graf has
missed most of the past year with a series of injuries, and despite
speculation that she would retire after Wimbledon, Graf now sounds
determined to complete her career on a winning note.
</P>
<P>
   Lobs: Venus and Serena Williams both won again in their mixed
doubles matches, putting both in the semifinals. A win today for
the Palm Beach County sisters would put them in Sunday's final
against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams and Justin Gimelstob defeated top seeds Leander
Paes and Larisa Neiland 6-3, 6-4, and will face fifth seeds Mahesh
Bhupathi and Mirjana Lucic, while Serena Williams and Max Mirnyi
defeated unseeded Sandon Stolle and Kristien Kunce 7-5, 5-7, 6-4.
They will play second seeds Paul Haarhuis and Caroline Vis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
