<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOLLY-MAGUIRES-MEMORI     07-03 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLLY-MAGUIRES-MEMORIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING MILITANT MINERS: A DELICATE SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent with `t' code) 
 (bl)  
 By MARK BULIK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMAQUA, Pa. _ The last words of the condemned Irishmen had to
compete with a nearby karaoke singer, so the men on the makeshift
gallows raised their voices for the crowd below as they professed
their innocence or asked for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   None of the dangling nooses would be placed around a neck on
this day, though. This was Tamaqua's summer festival, and the six
men were Molly Maguire re-enactors.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a century of secrecy surrounding the Molly
Maguires, the violent confederacy of Irish-American mine workers
has become a tourist attraction in the hard coal region of
northeastern Pennsylvania. But as the region's annual Molly Maguire
Weekend encourages a new openness about this sensitive episode, it
also underlines the delicacy of recreating history where
descendants of the participants still live, memories are long and
pain runs deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``The romanticization of this era could get out of hand,'' John
Bugbee of Glen Rock, Pa., warned at a weekend discussion at Molly's
Pub in Locust Gap. ``My concern is that I don't want Frank Langdon
to be forgotten in all this'' _ Langdon being not only the mine
official whose murder in 1862 is listed as the first by the Molly
Maguires, but also Bugbee's great-great-grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bugbee moved off for a quiet word with Alice Wayne of
Girardville, the 93-year-old granddaughter of John Kehoe, the man
hanged for the Langdon murder.
</P>
<P>
   From 1862 to 1875, Irish-American militants used ``Molly
Maguire'' _ the name of a mythical woman who led resistance to
landlords during the Irish potato famine _ as a nom de guerre as
they fought other ethnic gangs and the growing power of coal
companies. The violence ended only after dozens of men had been
murdered or executed and labor activity had been crushed by troops,
private police and spies.
</P>
<P>
   Given that dark history, the Schuylkill County Visitors Bureau
has tread carefully in staging Molly Maguire events that attract
tourists ranging from Molly Maguire aficionados to fans of Arthur
Conan Doyle, who based his Sherlock Holmes novel ``The Valley of
Fear'' on events here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sensitive to the fact that there are descendants,''
said Mark Major, director of the visitors bureau. ``We don't want
it to be painful.''
</P>
<P>
   But as in Colonial Williamsburg, where a mock slave auction drew
protests in 1994, the re-enactments have caused pangs among some
who live in the shadow of the scarred anthracite hills.
</P>
<P>
   This year, plans to re-enact an 1874 riot in Mahanoy City that
led to several shootings were canceled because of objections from
current members of the two fire companies involved in the riot.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the first re-enactments _ of John Kehoe's trial, put
on by the Schuylkill County Bar Association and the County
Historical Society in 1994 _ drew anonymous phone threats in
addition to 400 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as more than 100 Molly buffs, historians and descendants of
men on both sides of the conflict gathered in June for events
ranging from the theatrical to the academic, the most remarkable
feature of the weekend was the willingness to talk about a subject
that until recently was still largely discussed in whispers, if at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Forty people turned out for a walking tour of Mahanoy City, site
of the clash between the Irish-American members of the Humane Fire
Company and the English, Welsh and German members of the Citizens
Fire Company.
</P>
<P>
   Among the walkers was George Maloney of Pittsburgh, who is
tracing a family link to Peter McManus, hanged in 1879 for the
killing of a mine watchman. Maloney recalled the silence that
enveloped the Mollies when he was growing up in the coal region.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was taboo,'' he said. ``Nobody talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The taboo was nowhere in evidence at Molly's Pub, where 100
traded information and opinions. They included Patrick Campbell,
whose 1992 account of the trial and hanging of a great-uncle, ``A
Molly Maguire Story'' (Templecrone Press), helped open discussion
of the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a native of Ireland, likened attitudes about the
Mollies to reticence about the potato famine. ``It was rooted in
people's idea of what was respectable,'' he said. ``It was not
respectable to die of hunger. The same is true of the Molly
Maguires. Murder is murder, unless it's political. They'll talk
about it now because the American-Irish are more self-confident.''
</P>
<P>
   But down the valley in the Girardville tavern that John Kehoe
once ran, his great-grandson and the tavern's current proprietor,
Joseph Wayne, had little time for Molly Maguire Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to re-enact hangings,'' said Wayne, who helped
secure a pardon for his great-grandfather in 1979. ``How do you do
that tastefully?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
