<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS &LR;      07-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic displays &QL; 
new will to prevail
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ They came to see Tim play Pete. But Goran and
Richard had their own agenda. They held the court, and they weren't
going to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Let 'em wait, Goran grunted.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Richard growled. Let 'em wait.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Ivanisevic vs. Richard Krajicek constituted the undercard
at Wimbledon on Friday, yet somebody forgot to pull the plug on
them. It was, after all, a semifinal, so you couldn't call the
fight a draw and schedule a rematch. There had to be a resolution,
and drawing straws wasn't an option.
</P>
<P>
   Like two brutes in a tough-guy competition, tennis' two biggest
servers pounded on each other for 3{ hours and some 71 games, plus
a tiebreaker. If there is such a thing as bare-knuckles,
last-man-standing tennis, that's what the stubborn Croat and the
dogged Dutchman played as the mood of the Tim Henman-crazed crowd
changed from polite interest to toe-tapping impatience to abject
boredom to, ultimately, morbid fascination.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't help themselves. This was great theater, at once
Shakespearean and absurd. In short, a typical Goran production.
</P>
<P>
   Just when we thought they might play forever, Krajicek blinked,
and, like that, he was out 15-13 in the fifth. As exhausted as the
participants, we were left to wonder if anybody has blasted 23 aces
in a set _ and lost it. That would be Krajicek's
stranger-than-fiction fate.
</P>
<P>
   Having rallied from two sets down, the 1996 Wimbledon champion
got a break ahead in the fifth set, then turned the heat up on
Ivanisevic, who has, of late, been inclined to get out of the
kitchen. Hadn't he lost four first-round matches in his past five
Grand Slam starts and stalled in the second round of the other?
</P>
<P>
   Unquestioned physical potential
</P>
<P>
   Not here, though. Ivanisevic has, somewhat amazingly, never won
Wimbledon, but he realizes he should have numerous times and he
knows he still can.
</P>
<P>
   ``If,'' as he said the other day, ``I don't lose my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Or his serve. The Ivanisevic serve is tennis' most feared
weapon, the game's one doomsday stroke. If Goran had a game equal
to his serve, he would be a bigger, better, faster, stronger cross
between Rod Laver and John McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   And we wouldn't talk about the Sampras quest to surpass Roy
Emerson as the grandest of all Slammers. No, Goran could be the guy
with one foot in the history book.
</P>
<P>
   But stuff happens to Ivanisevic that never seems to happen to
Pete. He has what he calls ``blackouts,'' in which his touch and
strategy abandon him. And although he denied it, he appeared to
have one at 5-3, 40-15 _ double match point _ in the fourth set.
After 1 hour, 48 minutes, a third Wimbledon final was in his grasp
when he smacked a serve most of us, Krajicek included, believed to
be an ace.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cyclops machine let loose with a beep _ a let! _ and
another 80 draining minutes later, he would be out there still,
trading roundhouse punches with a brute who packs practically the
same wallop he does. They finished 1-2 in the tour's ace standings
last year. Friday, they would smack 70 between them. Oddly,
Ivanisevic wouldn't win that battle. He was buried 42-28.
</P>
<P>
   But he would win the war. This was a new wrinkle for him, one
that perhaps announces a change in Ivanisevic's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody bet on me when I lost the fourth set,''
he said. ``Everybody was thinking, `Maybe it's going to be 6-2,
maybe 6-3. He's gone; he's going to lose it.' But I was just very
mentally strong today. Never was I like this in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying in control
</P>
<P>
   He didn't start muttering in Croatian. He didn't fling his
rackets around or pull out his hair. He stayed calm. Somewhat
amazingly, given his history of buckling under pressure, he kept
his brain tuned in to the business at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I wait for the one moment when I will explode,'' he
said. ``But today, what can I say? I just changed. I just say, `OK,
now you're going to be cool. You're going to keep your mind on what
you have to do, and you are going to win it.'''
</P>
<P>
   First, he got Krajicek's attention with a pair of brutal
backhand return winners in a losing effort in the 26th game. Then,
after holding easily himself for 14-13, he put Krajicek in a 15-40
vise and squeezed with everything he had, ripping a forehand return
off a second serve straight down the center line.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek flinched, poking a backhand volley into the net. It was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Brits could have their Tim. Ivanisevic was moving
on _ and perhaps on up the ladder again.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras proved too much for Henman, and he presents a far
greater challenge than Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Goran's most daunting opponent is always Goran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
