<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA FIRES FORCE EVACUATION OF ENTIRE COUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: See also FLA-FIRES-WINTER, as well as estensive coverage of
the Florida wild fires from Cox.) 
(ps) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE MARY, Fla. _ The dislocation of communities in northeastern
Florida worsened Friday when an entire whole county was ordered
evacuated as three brush fires threatened to merge into one and
trap about 35,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Flagler County fled south to hotels and Red
Cross shelters in neighboring Seminole County and Orlando as more
than 800 firefighters struggled in 100-degree heat to contain
dozens of runaway fires. The fires have been especially fierce
because they are fed by Florida's extreme drought conditions and
steered by unpredictable winds.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the evacuation of Flagler County, 10,000 other
residents were ordered out of their homes in Brevard County south
of Daytona Beach after a brush fire jumped over a highway to menace
their community.
</P>
<P>
   The fires, raging mostly through forest and rural areas in north
and central Florida since Memorial Day, have caused no deaths and
relatively few injuries or loss to property, but the potential for
disaster remained as they threatened to race into cities and towns.
The evacuations raised the number of people forced out of their
homes this week in northeastern Florida to about 85,000.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said that about 124,000 of the 453,000 acres
ravaged by the fires since May have burned in the last 24 hours
alone, primarily in the counties of Flagler, Brevard, Volusia, St.
Johns and Orange. Gov. Lawton Chiles said equipment and
firefighters were coming from 41 states. He added, ``We have about
half of the country's firefighting assets in Florida right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation of Flagler County, an agricultural area that
includes several coastal towns, came after officials worried that
three brush fires burning near the city of Bunnell and the town of
Palm Coast would ``converge and you'd get one big fire,'' said Don
North, a spokesman for the Federal Emergency Management Agency. To
let county residents evacuate, state officials re-opened southbound
lanes of Interstate 95, which remained closed to motorists for more
than 100 miles south of Jacksonville because of smoke and the
threat of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our cars packed for three days _ pictures, wills,
important papers,'' said Rosemary Ratusz, an elderly widow who left
in a caravan of six cars, eight neighbors and two pets from
Willoughby Place, a street in Palm Coast. ``We could see smoke,
red, black and white. It looked like the whole place was on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ratusz and her neighbors sought refuge at a Red Cross
shelter at Lake Mary High School in Seminole County after putting
lawn sprinklers on the roof and leaving them on to try to protect
their homes. They said they had lived with the stench of smoke for
weeks, but that until the last minute they had believed they would
be spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just figured with all these firefighters around these fires
couldn't get out of control,'' said Eddie Jensen, 40, a postal
clerk who left with his wife and two teen-age children. ``People
don't realize how rural Florida really is. They think beach, palm
trees and bikinis.''
</P>
<P>
   Help has come from the Army, National Guard, Bureau of Indian
Affairs and fire departments from across the country, and fire
officials say they are using every resource at their disposal, from
trucks and bulldozers to planes and helicopters. This includes
three World War II bombers that can drop 2,000 gallons of water
each and a C-215 tanker aircraft from North Carolina, nicknamed the
``Super Scooper,'' that can scoop up 1,400 gallons of water in 10
seconds as it skims over large lakes.
</P>
<P>
   But while the cost for battling the 1,785 fires so far this
summer amounts to more than $80 million, many firefighters on the
field say that the only resource that can ultimately help them is
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resources are here,'' said Hank Strickland, 41, a
firefighter from South Carolina fresh from a 13-hour work shift in
northern Brevard County. ``It's the dryness and Mother Nature. If I
had my way? Rain with no lightning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
