<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-PERU-PRISONER     07-03 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-PERU-PRISONER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A HARD LESSON ON THE VALUE OF LIBERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Newsletters and fliers cover the coffee table in Mark
and Rhoda Berenson's living room on Manhattan's East Side,
instruments of persuasion in a campaign to free their daughter Lori
Helene Berenson from a mountain prison in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're literally a mom-and-pop operation,'' Mrs. Berenson said.
As with most mom-and-pop operations, money does not flow freely.
The Berensons have begun to scrape the bottom of their cash barrel,
and so leaflets protesting their daughter's innocence share the
coffee table with newly printed fund-raising appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Having to rattle the cup may be necessary, but it is still
unsettling. ``We don't even want to ask our relatives,'' Berenson
said. That discomfort, though, is nothing compared with the
emotional wringer that the Manhattan couple have been put through
in recent days over whether their daughter might be released before
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst,'' the father said. ``By the end of it, my
guts were hanging out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berenson, 28, has been imprisoned for well over two years.
To be precise: two years, seven months and four days as of
Saturday, her father noted without skipping a beat. A journalist
who sympathized with Peru's pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru guerrillas, she
was sentenced to life in prison after a military trial that had as
much to do with international norms of justice as the Three Stooges
do with Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The question is not whether this New Yorker was part of a
terrorist band, as the Peruvian government claims, or simply a
left-leaning do-gooder, as her parents say. The question is
certainly not why she meddled in Peruvian affairs to begin with, as
some unsympathetic Americans have asked.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is simple. Did she get a fair trial? Considering
that she was charged with treason against Peru when she is not
Peruvian, and considering that the judges and prosecutors were
hooded and that she was not allowed to challenge evidence or
cross-examine witnesses, many Americans from President Clinton on
down say, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, some in Peru are starting to agree.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons' emotions were sent on a roller coaster last week
when out of nowhere Peru's new prime minister, Javier Valle
Riestra, said Ms. Berenson should be pardoned and sent home. Valle
Riestra, a politically independent constitutional lawyer,
essentially echoed objections that the system was repressive and
that a foreigner could not be sentenced for treason.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, the prime minister issued his call just as
Berenson was completing a visit to the prison high in the Andes
where his daughter is being held and where, he said, the constant
cold has caused her to suffer severe circulatory problems and other
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the airport getting on the plane to return to the
U.S. when he got on television,'' the father said.
</P>
<P>
   But in no time hope turned to familiar frustration when the real
power in Peru, the hard-nosed president, Alberto Fujimori, said
there was no way that the young American would go anywhere. ``There
was a combination of tremendous emotion and tremendous activity,''
Mrs. Berenson recalled Thursday. ``I think we had three meals in
five days. We still haven't caught up on sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after the sudden ups and downs, the Berensons are left to
figure out if they have made progress or lost ground. ``As far as
I'm concerned, we're way ahead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, she was heartened that the U.S. ambassador
to Peru, Dennis Jett, spoke out this week. He rebutted statements
by Fujimori that Ms. Berenson had acknowledged being a Tupac Amaru
member _ she did no such thing _ and that she would receive no
special treatment because she is an American. If anything, the
ambassador said, her nationality has worked against her.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons' congresswoman, Carolyn Maloney, said she was
encouraged that some Peruvian officials have begun speculating
about a new trial, this time in a civilian court. But over all,
some Western diplomats in Peru saw little to cheer in Ms.
Berenson's situation. ``Peruvian public opinion is 99.99 percent
against her and the president has dug in his heels,'' one of them
said by phone. ``The last person to respond to pressure is Alberto
Fujimori.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Berensons plan to hit the road this
weekend, pleading their case to a group in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, of course, is the Fourth of July. They will talk about
liberty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
