<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-WELFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OBSTRUCTING LOCAL WELFARE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 4:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani made the right moves when he required New
York City welfare recipients to work for benefits and asked new
applicants to exhaust the search for employment before asking for
aid. But as he makes it tougher to obtain welfare, he needs to make
sure that the city also has policies and programs that offer tools
to move into the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big inconsistencies are proposals to limit remedial
work at the City University of New York, tighten admission
standards and delay student workfare. All are at odds with the aim
of preparing more people to be wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
   The city's welfare rolls shrank from 1.16 million in 1995 to
about 770,000 this year, partly because of the strong economy and
partly because the city tightened screening and required
able-bodied recipients to work in exchange for benefits. The rolls
will shrink yet again when the city adopts a new system that
requires people to search widely for work before receiving public
aid. The new system has dramatically driven down applications in
places where it has been tested.
</P>
<P>
   While steering people toward the job market, however, the city
has simultaneously embraced policies at the City University that
make the transition less likely. Over the last two years, for
example, the city has steadfastly resisted a program to provide
workfare on campus, so that welfare recipients might fulfill their
work obligations without disrupting progress toward a college
degree. The city will finally begin phasing in a campus workfare
plan next fall, more than a year after the state Legislature
ordered it to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the number of welfare recipients attending the City
University has dropped from 27,000 to about 12,000, partly because
of tuition increases and aid cuts, but also because the initial
workfare policy drove them out. The new plan to limit remedial
education at CUNY will hit these students even harder, making it
less likely that they will acquire the skills they need to earn
college degrees. Without degrees, they will be locked out of all
but menial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare reform can succeed only if New York's poorest citizens
can get the skills they need to move into the mainstream economy.
For that to happen, the city needs to make sure that the people who
are being moved briskly toward the work force also have the
broadest possible access to training and education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
