<SLUG> BC-SOC-HOLLAND-ARGENTINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA, NETHERLANDS IN ATTACK MODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France _ The last time Argentina and the Netherlands
met in the World Cup 20 years ago, Maradona was a pup and Clockwork
Orange was still whirring. Argentina won, 3-1, in overtime and
claimed the title. The Dutch disappeared for a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, both sides are just happy to be at the Stade
Velodrome with a shot to get to the final four. Argentina, despite
playing a man up for the final 73 minutes, had to go to penalty
kicks to beat the English in their second-round match. The
Netherlands didn't beat Yugoslavia until the 90th minute, after
Yugoslavia's Predrag Mijatovic missed the first penalty shot in the
Cup since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, this could be one of the most entertaining matches of
the tournament if both teams play the way they say they will _ all
out. ``Against any team, our concern is to create, attack,'' says
Dutch coach Guus Hiddink, whose squad has taken 86 shots in four
matches.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Argentina, which was having a lovely open match
with England until David Beckham got himself sent off in the 47th
minute and the English threw up the wall. But the Pale Blues
wouldn't have minded playing this match Sunday, to give battered
bodies and tired legs an extra day to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch only had to play 90 minutes against the Yugoslavs.
``And they only played us for five minutes,'' says midfielder Edgar
Davids, who scored the winning goal as time was running out.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentines went 120 against the English a day later and came
out black and blue. Ariel Ortega, their gifted playmaker, is
hobbling on a bruised toe, and forward Hernan Crespo and keeper
Carlos Roa both have thigh injuries. And defensive midfielder
Roberto Sensini, who's playing in his third Cup, has been injured
for nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficult match they had to play a day after ours might
prove to be an advantage for us,'' says Dutch attacker Marc
Overmars. So the Netherlands plans to come early and strong _
before Argentina gets a chance to do likewise. The Clockwork Orange
era of Cruyff and Rep and Neeskens, with its emphasis on ``total
football,'' may be long past but the Netherlands still can pile up
goals with likes of Overmars and Dennis Bergkamp.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch scored five on Nigeria in a pre-Cup tuneup, five on
the South Koreans and two on the Mexicans in the first 20 minutes.
``I'm convinced we have the most offensive team in the
tournament,'' says midfielder Ronald De Boer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Argentines, who have also tallied nine goals in four
matches, can play pinball with the likes of Gabriel Batistuta, who
has scored five, and Ariel Ortega, the gifted attacker who can also
deal like a midfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Argentine team,'' says Hiddink. ``Football is in
their blood. It's a young and experimental side, lively, always
animated, with an enormous desire to attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pale Blues, who've been waiting for an opponent who'll joust
with them at battle speed, are getting their wish in the Dutch.
They may not be playing for table stakes, as they were in 1978. But
this one will be worth a VCR tape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
