<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-DREW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEELING AND DEALING CARDINALS PUT DREW IN HIS COMFORT ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, Mark McGwire. This year, J.D. Drew.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals pulled off the unexpected again Friday,
achieving in one month what the Philadelphia Phillies could not do
in one year after making Drew the second pick in the 1997 draft.
The Cardinals, who last season enticed the power-hitting McGwire to
stay with them rather than become a free agent, reached agreement
on a four-year, $6,875,000 contract with Drew, the supposedly
unsignable draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along it was about how comfortable I'd be where I
played,'' Drew, a 22-year-old outfielder, said at a news conference
in St. Louis. ``I felt comfortable with the Cardinals. If I had to
do it all over again, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, comfort equaled money.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott Boras, Drew's agent, the contract with the
Cardinals includes a $3 million signing bonus, salaries totaling
$3,875,000 and as much as $1,625,000 in bonuses based on roster
time. The package could be worth $8.5 million over four years,
compared with $4 million from the Phillies' basic offer, not
including bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   If based on five years, as the Phillies offered at the 11th
hour, the Cardinals' contract could be worth slightly more than $11
million compared with slightly more than $6 million from the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who was close to the Phillies' negotiations said they
had been willing to offer more money but would not make new
proposals as long as Boras stuck to his demand for a $10 million
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But a member of the Phillies' organization who was involved in
the talks said that even when Boras, at the end, sought a signing
bonus between $4 million and $5 million, the club was not willing
to go beyond $2.6 million, which was in line with the rate for high
first-round choices last year. Matt Anderson, a college pitcher who
was the No. 1 pick in 1997, signed with Detroit for a $2,505,000
bonus, then a record for a drafted player.
</P>
<P>
   The contract Drew signed 13 months after he was initially
drafted out of Florida State University is the biggest attained by
a drafted amateur. Earlier this week, St. Louis signed Chad
Hutchinson, a Stanford pitcher and quarterback, and a Boras client,
to a four-year, $3.5 million contract. Negotiations for Drew
escalated rapidly once the Hutchinson deal was completed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Drew will report to the Cardinals' Class AA Arkansas team
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
