<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CAREY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM CAREY, 82, SCIENCE GROUP LEADER, BUDGET OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   William D. Carey, a former executive officer of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science and a former assistant
director of the U.S. Bureau of the Budget, died June 24 at his home
in Washington. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was chronic lung disease, said his son, Eric.
</P>
<P>
   Carey was the association's executive officer, and at the same
time publisher of its journal, Science, from 1975 until he retired
in 1987. In that year the association, the nation's largest general
scientific organization, had 132,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in the Bronx, New York City, grew up in Boston and
received a bachelor's degree in 1940 from Columbia University and
master's degrees from Columbia in public law and government and
from Harvard University in public administration.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the Bureau of the Budget in 1942, Carey went on to
be executive assistant director from 1959 to 1966, during the
Eisenhower, Kennedy and Johnson administrations, and assistant
director from 1966 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Science published a letter from Frank Carlucci, who was
then deputy secretary of defense in the Reagan administration, that
contended ``the Soviets exploit scientific exchanges to enhance
their military posture.'' Carlucci voiced concern over the
disclosure of information to the Soviet Union through exchanges of
scholars and students, and through other conduits.
</P>
<P>
   Carey argued in an interview that Carlucci's letter ``focused
mainly on half a dozen bad cases, including some exchanges that
were discontinued because they were so one-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son, Eric, of Arlington, Va., he is survived by his
wife, the former Mary Margaret Rhodin, whom he married in 1944;
four daughters, Teresa Boswood of Oxford, England, Jane Long of
Washington, Julia Corrado of Alexandria, Va., and Elizabeth Langley
of Arlington, Va., and nine grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
