<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CAPECCHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENATO CAPECCHI, 74, WHO SANG COMIC ROLES IN TRAGIC OPERAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renato Capecchi, an Italian baritone and character actor who was
best known for his deft portrayals of comic roles, died June 30 at
his home in Milan. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from Alzheimer's disease, said Tony
Russo, his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Capecchi was a regular presence at the New York Metropolitan
Opera in the early 1950s and from 1975 , until his retirement in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   He made his Met debut as Germont, in Verdi's ``Traviata,'' in
1951. During that first Met stint, which lasted until 1954, sang
mostly serious roles: Marcello in Puccini's ``Boheme,'' Escamillo
in Bizet's ``Carmen,'' Enrico in Donizetti's ``Lucia di
Lammermoor'' _ as well as an occasional comic turn, like Figaro in
Rossini's ``Barbiere di Siviglia.''
</P>
<P>
   After his return to the Met in 1975, Capecchi specialized in the
smaller roles that add humorous touches to otherwise tragic works _
the Sacristan in Puccini's ``Tosca,'' for example, or Benoit and
Alcindoro in ``La Boheme.'' In 1986, when he was 63, he sang a
program of Italian folk songs in a belated New York debut recital
at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Outside New York, Capecchi's career was somewhat more varied. He
sang in the first Italian production of ``The Nose,'' by
Shostakovich, and he created roles in Gian Francesco Malipiero's
``Donna e Mobile,'' in Giorgio Federico Ghedini's ``Billy Budd''
and ``Lord Inferno'' and in Sylvano Bussotti's ``Inspirazione.''
</P>
<P>
   As a director, Capecchi staged ``La Boheme,'' at the
Metropolitan Opera, Donizetti's ``Daughter of the Regiment'' at the
New York City Opera and ``Il Barbiere di Siviglia'' at the
University of Colorado. He also directed productions at the San
Francisco Opera and at the Manhattan School of Music, where he
taught for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Capecchi was born in Cairo in November 1923 and studied in
Lausanne and Milan.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s he won a vocal competition sponsored by an
Italian radio station, and in 1949 he made his professional debut
as Amonasro in Verdi's ``Aida.'' He gave his first performances at
La Scala in 1950 and sang regularly at Covent Garden from 1962 to
1973.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Jeannette; a son, Marco, and a
daughter, Magali.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-HARTFORD-NYT &LR;      07-03 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HARTFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A RECORD 62, FEW ARE LAUGHING AT GUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Scott Gump's biggest claim to fame on the PGA
Tour, it seems, has been his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds would get on me and say, `Run, Forrest, run,'''
Gump said, referring to the ``Forrest Gump'' film character. ``It
was funny for the first 100 times or so, but then it got pretty
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   No one heckled the 32-year-old Gump on Friday as he shot a
course-record, 8-under-par 62 to take a 1-stroke lead midway
through the $2 million Canon Greater Hartford Open at the
6,820-yard TPC River Highlands Course.
</P>
<P>
   Without a victory in six years on the PGA Tour _ he won twice on
the satellite Nike circuit in 1994 _ the 32-year-old Gump had eight
birdies and no bogeys during Friday's round. Coupled with an
opening-round 68, the Windermere, Fla., golfer stood at
10-under-par 130, a stroke ahead of Larry Mize, who fired a 63;
Omar Uresti, another relatively unknown golfer, who shot 64; and
Stewart Cink, the event's defending champion, who shot 65.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed more surprised by his 62 than Gump, whose score
tied the lowest round shot this year. Bruce Lietzke, David Love III
and David Duval shot 62s earlier this year in tour events.
</P>
<P>
   But Gump had fired a 63 _ also in the second round _ in the GTE
Byron Nelson tournament last year. He finished 48th.
</P>
<P>
   Gump attributed his 62 to the heavy rains that left the greens
and the fairways relatively soft. ``The pace of the greens is
especially nice,'' said Gump, who has missed six cuts in 24
tournaments this year and whose best finish has been a tie for
ninth place, in the BellSouth Classic in May. Along with most of
the others on the leader board in an undistinguished field _ only
five of the top 25 money-winners entered this tournament _ Gump
ranks 127th on the money list with earnings of $100,800.
</P>
<P>
   Two strokes back of Gump were Grant Waite of New Zealand and
48-year-old Doug Tewell, a four-time winner on the PGA Tour who got
into the tournament as an alternate. Among those in a group of
five, three strokes back at 133, was Duval, the Tour's leading
money-winner who shot 65 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin, playing in his first PGA Tour event, drew the
largest gallery for the second straight day but failed to make the
cut. The 26-year-old Martin, who is permitted to use a golf cart as
a result of a federal judge's ruling, finished at 4-over-par 144
following a 73 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-six players made the cut, but they had to finish at
1-under 139 or better to do so. That tied the low-cut number this
year in two other tournaments. Among those who barely made it were
the reigning British Open champion, Justin Leonard, whose 68 put
him at 138, and John Daly, who also had a 68 and wound up at the
cutting edge of 139.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   _ The qualifier PETE MORGAN, whose 64 on Thursday gave him a
1-stroke first-round lead, slipped to a 71 to stand at 5 under 135.
...
</P>
<P>
   _ With his father, RON, as his caddie, the amateur J.J. HENRY of
Fairfield, Conn., shot a 71. Coupled with his opening-round 68,
Henry was at 139 and made the cut. Henry, a recent graduate of
Texas Christian University, finished second in the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament last spring. He will be
a member of the eight-player team that will represent the United
States against teams from Britain and Ireland in the Palmer Club,
the collegiate version of the Ryder Cup, at St. Andrews in Scotland
Aug. 3-4.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
