</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SENATE-SECRECY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CHALLENGE TO SENATE SECRECY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Iowa)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 4:
</P>
<P>
   In one of its final acts before the holiday recess, the Senate
endorsed a small but significant procedural reform. By a unanimous
vote, lawmakers added an amendment to the Defense Appropriations
bill that would end the practice of allowing individual lawmakers
to block items they object to by imposing a secret ``hold.'' The
unanimous vote may not mean much. The Senate easily approved the
same measure last September only to have it mysteriously omitted
from the final version of the spending bill it had amended.
</P>
<P>
   For that omission to take place again would be inexcusable. The
system of ``holds'' began as a courtesy to lawmakers who wanted to
put off a debate until they could be there to participate. Now
every session of the Senate gets bogged down by a proliferation of
anonymous holds, some so confusing that even Majority Leader Trent
Lott can have trouble figuring out who is causing the delays.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, senators could still place holds on
nominations and legislation. But they would no longer have the
luxury of hiding. They would be required to identify themselves by
placing a notice in the Congressional Record. That may not sound
like much. But the measure's chief sponsors, Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, are aiming to restore accountability.
Lawmakers who use their power to hold things up should be required
to stand up and defend their positions.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt many of the senators who just voted again to end
anonymous holds cherish the prerogative and would prefer to see the
reform quietly killed in the conference committee now meeting
behind closed doors. Lott has the muscle to prevent that. He should
use it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
