<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRE-MIMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents return home to surevy fire damage
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIMS, Fla. _ Pete Knox, 62, walked as fast as he could down the
dirt road he had lived on since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys fought hard,'' he said as he rounded a bend and saw
his mobile home surrounded by charred forest. Some of the siding
was torn off, apparently by firefighters working to save his
property. In the back, a shed was destroyed. But across the street
lay what he had been afraid of. A chimney and the screen enclosure
for a pool were all that were left standing of his neighbor's
house.
</P>
<P>
   Without a firefighter in sight, a lonely fire chewed on what's
left of another neighbor's shed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate them boys,'' Knox said. ``I'm going to buy 'em a
6 pack of beer, no a 12 pack. A whole damn truckload.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox was among the 9,000 people evacuated from northern Brevard
County Thursday night. Some were able to get passes to return for
two hours Friday morning, or like Knox, rode in with deputies.
</P>
<P>
   For all the devastation, the 45,000 acres burned in Brevard,
only about 30 of the 2,000 homes in the fire zone were destroyed by
late afternoon Friday. Another 20 were damaged to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers reflect the efforts of 650 firefighters from around
the state and the country. While U.S. Forestry Service officers
worked on a way to stop the fires, local firefighters did nothing
but try to save homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   One problem firefighters were not anticipating is septic tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several instances where fire trucks have crashed
through septic tanks and become stuck, immobile for 30 minutes or
even more,'' Brevard County Fire Chief Don Boykin said.
</P>
<P>
   Communication between the various agencies went moderately well.
Brevard deputies carry 800 megaherz radios, part of a statewide
system that is slowly being implemented, in part for disasters like
these.
</P>
<P>
   But very few fire departments ar
</P>
</TEXT>
