<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAFIRE-MAIN-COX     07-03 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRE-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire forces county to evacuate
 &HT;    By By Jenny Staletovich and Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUNNELL, Fla. _ An entire county _ neighbors, schools, churches,
diners, even the local hardware store _ surrendered to wildfire
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   About 45,000 residents of tiny Flagler County, 504 rural square
miles shouldered between Daytona Beach and St. Augustine, were
ordered to leave. Most took to the local highway, lined with
American flags for the holiday, and snaked west in bumper to bumper
traffic to escape fires converging on their county seat.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, the small town was nearly empty.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind were fires so fierce even firefighters gave up
trying to control them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a potential for a catastrophic event,'' Raymond
Geiger, chief of field operations for the state Division of
Forestry, said as fires marched from the north, south and west.
``It's called a firestorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Banning fireworks _ a statewide order issued by Gov. Lawton
Chiles last week _ seems beside the point here.
</P>
<P>
   If fires collide, they could suck air inward, spreading flames
even faster, a phenomenon used in Allied bombing of Nazi Germany in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't put enough resources on the fire line to stop
it,'' said Larry Scovotto, executive director of the Florida Fire
Chiefs Association.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, a dawn to dusk curfew had been set.
</P>
<P>
   Further south in Brevard County, the largest fire burned out of
control as smaller fires crept into marshes out of firefighters'
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying at the state level that this has been the
worst disaster since Hurricane Andrew,'' Titusville Fire Chief Tom
Harmer said. ``I think we're changing that. This is worse than
Andrew.''
</P>
<P>
   The fires, still most dangerous in Flagler, Volusia and Brevard
counties, claimed another 165,000 acres statewide Friday, bringing
the total to 452,876 covering 707 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Some 72,000 people in Volusia County remained under Thursday's
evacuation order, officials said. In Brevard County, of the nearly
10,000 evacuated, all but those living in about 50 houses still
threatened by fire were allowed to return home late Friday. About
200 structures from Titusville north to the Palm Coast
neighborhoods in Flagler County have been destroyed and 55 people,
most firefighter, injured.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile billowing smoke crept south, draping Palm Beach County
and the Treasure Coast in a gauze of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   And in what is becoming a depressing daily ritual, state
officials predicted worse awaits us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible day, a terrible week,'' said Sen. Bob
Graham, who came to the Emergency Operations Center in Tallahassee
with Federal Emergency Management Agency director James Lee Witt
Friday to tour scorched counties by helicopter. Gov. Lawton Chiles
later cancelled the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Still, sea breezes Friday afternoon provided a little relief and
by 7 p.m., a steady rain was falling on Flagler County. A half hour
later, the rain arrived in Volusia County. The three fires
threatening to join forces in Flagler County never met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness the Good Lord gave us some relief,'' Chiles
said.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem to matter on roads.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 150 miles of Interstate 95 remained closed from
Jacksonville to Cocoa Beach, with only a small stretch opened to
evacuees fleeing Flagler County south. In the most dangerous areas,
dozens of other roads closed. Tolls on Florida's Turnpike remained
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the Flagler evacuation was a gasoline shortage.
Fuel distributors refused to send tankers loaded with gasoline over
roads lined with flames, forcing emergency management officials to
dip into fuel stores saved for hurricane evacuations.
</P>
<P>
   And many evacuees fond Palatka shelters, expected to hold about
2,000, full and pushed on through to Gainesville, an additional 40
miles west. Elsewhere shelters opened to offer accommodations: 12
in Putnam County just west and two in Seminole County. A Disaster
Medical Assistance Team to assist rescue workers was also
dispatched to the area.
</P>
<P>
   With so many homes empty, officials ordered 1,500 members of the
Florida National Guard to report for duty and stand guard. Earlier,
562 members of the Guard arrived to fight the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Still, fighting fires remained the biggest concern. In the
northeast corner of Flagler County where the worst blazes raged,
rescue workers struggled to get close to several ritzy Palm Coast
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a difficult time even getting back there with
telephone poles and trees down,'' said Richard Wieser, spokesman
for Flagler County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile firefighters unaccustomed to fighting wildfires found
themselves facing a different enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In Volusia County, firefighters surrounded a $200,000 house in
the Hunter's Ridge subdivision. They stood, backs to the wall,
prepared to fight flames that came too close but willing to let
them burn, as long as they destroyed shrubs and fuel leading to the
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``One problem we have is that most of the firefighters are
structural firefighters, so they want to put everything out right
away,'' said Lt. Charles Davis of Coral Gables. ``That's fine, but
we're trying to teach them to be forestry firefighters, where you
only want to control and let it burn itself out. It's difficult,
but everyone's learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Further south in Brevard County, supervisors shared worries
about firefighters in unpredictable circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   They're ``taking chances they shouldn't,'' said Brevard County
Fire Chief Dan Boykin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have burned out areas all the way around homes and I know
the homes are there because (firefighters) took chances they
shouldn't be taking,'' he said. ``It's very frustrating for a
firefighter to lose a home. They don't understand it. They don't
comprehend it. Neither do I.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six firefighters have been injured in Brevard County,
most from heat exhaustion because they are working in heavy bunker
gear designed for structure fires. Wildfire gear is being flown in
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Daytona International Speedway, where today's
Pepsi 400 was postponed until October, firefighters and evacuees
found themselves housed in a posh hospitality pavilion and other
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But what a Fourth of July it will ben. Most threatened areas
have no plans for fireworks _ properly licensed public displays are
permitted despite the private ban. Still, some will go on with the
show. Disney, which mounts daily fireworks shows, will hold its
display along with many in south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The family of a teen-ager suffering from inoperable brain
tumors, who had asked for a special fireworks show in Putnam
County, considered their neighbor's ordeal and cancelled their
request.
</P>
<P>
   But common sense did not necessarily rule the day.
</P>
<P>
   Even as fires worsened and evacuations mounted, one Ormond Beach
resident ignored warnings to leave and waited until flames
surrounded his house, then called 911 for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to pull crews off and go in with a helicopter,'' said
Mike Pleus, Volusia County emergency management spokesman. ``That
really puts a strain on our resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Which even the rain won't help. As Geiger, with the state
Division of Forestry cautioned, thundershowers likes the ones that
provided quick relief late Friday, can also start more fires than
they put out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every lightning bolt that you hear in the woods is a
wildfire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
