<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIFEGUARD-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFEGUARDS LIMIT PICKS, BUT A BEACH IS A BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ESTHER B. FEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lifeguard shortage that has vexed New York City
this year, causing vast stretches of beaches to be closed, seemed
little burden to holiday bathers Friday, basking under a perfect
robin's egg sky, with just enough of a breeze to keep a kite up but
not so much that it ruffled the pages of a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Where a beach was closed with a ``No Lifeguard on Duty _
Swimming Prohibited'' sign posted, people walked, without a fuss, a
few hundred yards to the nearest section where orange-suited
lifeguards patrolled the waters.
</P>
<P>
   But to a triad of teen-agers who had set out for a day on the
beaches of Far Rockaway, the closing of Beach 74, because of a
shortage of people who had passed the city's lifeguard test, was an
affront.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the indignities that could befall a group of teen-agers
on a quest to be cool and aloof, they were stuck going to a peanut
butter and jelly sandwich of a beach, the kind of beach filled with
little children and their pails and umbrellas and those incessant
parental cries of ``Put on more sunscreen'' and ``Don't go out too
far'' that they thought they had outgrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy four is supposed to be where everyone hangs out,''
said Jose Santiago, 19, from East New York, on a day off from his
studies to be a computer technician. ``It's famous. You go to 74,
and you know you're going to bump into somebody you know. Now we
got to go there with all those kids and the pails.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to be with the FAMILIES,'' said Charlie Collazo, 15, a
sophomore at Bushwick High School in Brooklyn, with that special
sort of disdain teen-agers reserve for anything that reminds them
that they are not quite adults.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki Ramos, 16, a student at John Adams High School in South
Ozone Park, Queens, looked longingly at the swath of sand roped off
with red plastic flags, then motioned to his friends to get over it
and move on. ``It's still the beach, man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Department officials said Friday that slowly, the
lifeguard shortage was easing. Through recruiting efforts and with
high school students who had passed the test finishing their
classes, making them free for midweek shifts, the city was able to
safely open more beaches. Alas, not Beach 74.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Colasante recalled that when he was younger, all of his
friends went to Beach 116 in Far Rockaway. ``We'd hang out, listen
to rock 'n' roll, drink beer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's 32, an electrician in Local 3, married, and the father
of 3-year-old little Mike. And so, he's on Beach 119. ``It's
calmer,'' he said, swinging his delighted son in the surf. ``I'm
older.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharlene Rodriguz said she had gone out to Orchard Beach in the
Bronx looking forward to the solitude of section one, at the very
tip of the beach, which is radio-free and this year, unfortunately,
a swimming-free zone, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it was open _ it's really quiet out there,'' said Ms.
Rodriguz, a 34-year-old chef from the Bronx. She had to settle for
section two, a few feet from the orange streamers that marked the
closed area, but still, she had to admit, pretty quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Being a lifeguard used to be the ultimate summer job, said Peter
Cholakis, a handyman at Beach Channel High School in Far Rockaway,
who was swimming Friday with his children, Nicholas, 9, and
Elizabeth, 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the greatest job,'' said Cholakis, who is back at the
same beach, 119, that he went to with his parents. ``Now, not even
the kids who grow up around here go out for it anymore. Now more
kids are going to college, and they want internships in their
fields. The economy's good and there are, you know, classier jobs
for them. They don't want to be lifeguards.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jason Carey, a 20-year-old student at John Jay College of
Criminal Justice sharing duty at Beach 26, said being a lifeguard
was still the best summer job he could think of _ and this is his
fifth summer doing it. ``You can't beat this,'' he said, his nose
already burned a light shade of tomato soup. ``I'm getting paid to
sit in the sun, at this point about $11 an hour. I'm 20. I live at
home. I don't need much else.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of Marvin Mullings' friends wanted to be lifeguards; they
just could not pass the test. ``They're out of shape,'' said
Mullings, 17, a third-year lifeguard who just graduated from Far
Rockaway High School and is headed for Greensboro College in North
Carolina at summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   From his perch atop the lifeguard chair at Beach 26, the sand
was not too crowded, the day not too warm. ``Too bad for them,'' he
said of his unsuccessful mates.
</P>
<P>
   As if trying to minimize any bad publicity to the city that the
beach closings had caused, none of the city parks workers in Far
Rockaway, Coney Island or Orchard Beach would give their names or
answer anything more than basic questions about the closings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk or jog along the surf and you can hang out up to
the flags,'' said one parks enforcement officer in Far Rockaway who
declined to give her name. ``But after the flags, you can't swim or
lounge.''
</P>
<P>
   A few sea gulls disobeyed, but the officer did not seem to mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
