<DOCNO> NYT19980703.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0027 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKS-POOR-LOANS-ART-     07-03 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-POOR-LOANS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BANKS, A BIG NUDGE TO DO MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
list of Community Reinvestment Act; Allocations of CRA for 3 banks
will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (Eds: Please note sub slug for BANK-MERGERS)  
 (af)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Union Avenue between East 156th Street and
Westchester Avenue in the Bronx is a small, humble block lined with
squat apartment buildings marked by occasional splashes of
graffiti. Chain-link fences hem in some yards; nearby, subway cars
rattle loudly on an overhead track.
</P>
<P>
   Just five years ago, drug dealers controlled the neighborhood
and many of its buildings. Today, the dealers are gone, pushed out
by the police and by new residents who have rehabilitated some of
the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   One morning last week, people chatted amiably on stoops and
sidewalks. Some of them would like to see others _ particularly
banks _ share their faith in the neighborhood's future.
</P>
<P>
   George Rabel, 38, the owner of La Marketa Barioa, a tiny bodega
on Union Avenue, is among those hoping that a broader economic
revival is in store for the neighborhood. But he has his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in business for nine years and I go to the bank
looking for a credit line when I get short of cash,'' he said.
``They tell me no. To get credit you have to have a credit history,
but you can't have a credit history if nobody gives you a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As an unprecedented merger boom continues to spawn new giants in
the banking industry, the needs of borrowers like Rabel are at the
center of a heated debate among community groups, lenders and
politicians over the financial service industry's commitment to
low-income neighborhoods across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The partners in both of the biggest recently announced mergers _
Citicorp-Travelers Group and Nationsbank-BankAmerica _ recently
unveiled multibillion-dollar lending packages to low-income
communities that dwarf similar commitments previously made by other
banks.
</P>
<P>
   The pledges build upon what activists and regulators acknowledge
to be a vastly improved record by banks when it comes to low-income
lending _ one that has helped, along with a strong economy, to
bring some vitality back to many low-income communities in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   But community groups complain that some of the outsized lending
programs announced lately are designed to curry favor with the
Federal Reserve Board, which must approve the mergers, rather than
truly meet credit needs in disadvantaged areas. The most egregious
example, community advocates say, is Citicorp, the New York bank
that is merging with Travelers Group to create the world's largest
financial services concern.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their merger application, Citicorp and Travelers,
which will be known as Citigroup, have promised the Federal Reserve
that they will make $115 billion in loans to low-income and
minority communities over the next 10 years. Community groups say
that figure, large as it appears, is small relative to pledges from
other banks _ notably a $350 billion, 10-year pledge by Nationsbank
and BankAmerica Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, moreover, low-income lending programs were designed
with the needs of a bank's local market in mind. But the
Citicorp-Travelers deal is all about creating financial
supermarkets, not opening local branches. And community groups say
the lack of geographic specificity in the partners' lending pledge
may make it less meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Citicorp and Travelers are promising about $60 billion in
consumer loans, a large but unspecified portion of which will be
credit cards presumably bearing high interest rates _ hardly the
stuff that fuels home-buying or economic development, say the
companies' critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It erodes the concept of community lending to have the most
powerful financial institution in the country disinterested in
it,'' said John Taylor, executive director of the National
Community Reinvestment Coalition, a Washington organization that
represents 678 community groups. ``A substantial portion of their
commitment represents what has historically been a problem in
low-income communities: credit card debt.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Citicorp, which has been orienting its entire
business toward more affluent customers and which, until recently,
sharply scaled back its mortgage operations in low-income areas,
says regulations governing low-income lending do not specify or
favor certain types of loans. Citicorp says it considers credit
cards to be a legitimate form of low-income lending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each institution, each bank, has to pursue its business and
emphasize those things it's good at,'' said Pamela Flaherty, senior
vice president for community activities at Citicorp. ``We happen to
be good at consumer lending and student loans and credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   What gives community groups a forum is the Community
Reinvestment Act, a federal law passed in 1977 that requires a bank
to help meet ``the credit needs of its entire community, including
low- and moderate-income neighborhoods, consistent with the safe
and sound operation'' of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Because a poor record under the law offers regulators grounds
for scuttling a merger (though that almost never happens), merger
time has come to mean negotiating time for banks and community
groups. Last month, the Fed held public hearings in New York on the
Citicorp-Travelers merger, evoking a spectrum of responses,
including a protest by activists brandishing red umbrellas like
those that Travelers uses as its logo.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, community groups and Banc One have reached an
impasse in negotiations surrounding the bank's merger with First
Chicago NBD Corp. The activists would like top executives to commit
to a reinvestment plan, but Banc One says it prefers to make
commitments market by market.
</P>
<P>
   While many bankers privately say that the negotiating process
leaves them feeling shaken down by community groups, activists say
that is hardly their intention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of community groups is not to be opposed to
financial modernization, per se,'' says Matthew Lee, executive
director of Inner City Press-Community on the Move, a New York
group that often challenges big bank mergers. ``It's to ensure that
CRA doesn't get watered down by these combinations and that
low-income people retain access to the financial system.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because of ambiguities about how the Community Reinvestment Act
was to be enforced, the law lay mostly fallow until 1989, when
regulators issued clearer criteria for judging banks' compliance.
In 1992, Congress followed up by requiring lenders to make data on
mortgage applications publicly available.
</P>
<P>
   The fuller disclosure _ and heightened scrutiny by the Clinton
administration _ strengthened the hand of community groups and
contributed to big increases in banks' low-income lending.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, lending commitments under the law have totaled $875
billion, compared with just $8.8 billion in pledges from 1977 to
1991, according to the National Community Reinvestment Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that banks' volume of lending in
low-income and minority census tracts has increased dramatically,''
Lee said. ``On the downside, the CRA as written doesn't speak to
the type of loans being made or what exactly constitutes lending to
low-income areas.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a report soon to be released by the Urban
Institute, a research group in Washington, greater access to
housing loans has improved the quality of life in many
disadvantaged areas. In low-income areas in 22 of 23 cities studied
for the report, access to housing loans remained stable or went up
between 1991 and 1997. In 11 of those 22 cities, ``significant
improvements'' were registered.
</P>
<P>
   But community groups say they are concerned that other types of
lending, particularly lending to small businesses, might fall by
the wayside as big banks link up.
</P>
<P>
   Debates about how broadly the Community Reinvestment Act should
be construed have gained momentum because of the changes sweeping
through the financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed combination of Citicorp and Travelers, for example,
would mesh traditional banking with brokerage services, insurance,
mutual funds and stock and bond underwriting. But of these
businesses, only banking falls under the purview of the law. And as
such mergers continue, community groups worry that the momentum
gained in low-income lending will be undercut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the same kind of redlining problems with home insurance
as we do with lending, but insurance isn't covered by CRA,'' said
Patrick Woodall, a policy analyst with Acorn, a community group
based in Washington. ``And if you can't get home insurance, you
can't buy a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Many banks feel unfairly singled out by the law, arguing that
the responsibility for community lending should be extended to
competitors like mutual fund companies and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 70 percent of the traditional deposit dollar is now
deposited outside of traditional banks, and that issue needs to be
addressed,'' said Catherine P. Bessant, Nationsbank's president for
community investment.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, that any expansion of the law's scope
is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate's consideration of a bill that would break down
the Depression-era legal barriers separating banking and other
financial services, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and other members of
the banking committee have proposed doing away with the
community-lending law entirely.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who is chairman of the committee, all
oppose gutting the law. So observers say the law is likely to
survive without significant changes.
</P>
<P>
   Community groups, however, say the act already has been weakened
by banking regulators too willing to give high marks to the vast
majority of banks for their low-income lending.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, according to the Federal Reserve, 11 percent of the
banks it examined received ``outstanding'' ratings under the act,
and 80 percent received ``satisfactory'' marks. Only 8 percent were
judged ``need to improve'' and 1 percent deemed in ``substantial
noncompliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed during this decade. Although banks previously
given low marks receive the closest scrutiny, so far this year,
19.7 percent of the banks examined by the Fed have received
``outstanding'' marks, 78.2 percent were judged ``satisfactory,''
1.6 percent were graded ``need to improve'' and 0.5 percent were
found in ``substantial noncompliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Community activists also complain that the Fed _ one of several
agencies that can perform compliance reviews, depending on how a
bank is chartered _ is predisposed to big banking mergers. They
note, for example, that the Fed held public hearings on the
community impact of the First Union Corp.'s recent acquisition of
Corestates Financial only after the agency was pressured by
activists and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding a certain amount of grade inflation in
community-lending examinations, Edward Gramlich, one of seven
members of the Federal Reserve Board, said that does not mean the
Fed disregards banks' lending patterns when it reviews mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not as quantitative as we might like it to be, but it's
certainly not a pro forma approval process,'' Gramlich said.
``There is no formal enforcement mechanism because of the way the
law was written. The main enforcement tool is when we look at
merger applications, and from my vantage point, we look at them
pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gramlich acknowledged that the scale of some of the latest
bank mergers has complicated the regulators' ability to assess
compliance with the lending law, especially as some banks begin to
spread their wings across the entire country. The issue is what
``community'' a bank should be reinvesting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the megamergers that are engulfing the whole country, it
does become difficult to understand what the assessment area is,''
Gramlich said. ``I think the process will become one of banks
negotiating with their regulators about where their assessment area
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, anyone trying to examine a pledge under the Community
Reinvestment Act is confronted with a welter of numbers that
complicate efforts to compare banks' records or sort out exactly
what a given bank considers to be a community development loan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a study released last month by the Treasury
Department's inspector general's office criticized as unreliable
examinations in 1996 and 1997 by the comptroller of the currency,
another bank regulator. And while the comptroller's office says it
has addressed the problems, officials insist that the real issue is
not reliability, but the subjective standards of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not create a bright-line standard that establishes a
certain percentage or number of loans in a certain category to
generate a rating,'' said Steve Cross, the deputy comptroller for
community and consumer policy. ``What the inspector general
characterizes as inconsistencies, I would characterize as the
appropriate exercise of judgment by an examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   From the banks' perspective, the law results in what sometimes
seems like little more than a numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``CRA has become a volume-oriented game, with up being good and
down being bad,'' said Ms. Bessant of Nationsbank. ``I worry about
crazy pricing and crazy credit as everybody tries to generate more
loans in order to get a better rating.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nationsbank, the company's critics contend, is hardly above
playing the numbers game itself as it pursues its merger with
BankAmerica. The two banks say that their huge CRA pledge, $350
billion over 10 years, is about the same as the total amount
pledged by all other banks over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded in that pledge, however, are loans that other banks do
not typically count as community investment. For example,
Nationsbank is including mortgage loans to upper-income members of
minority groups, even though the reinvestment act emphasizes income
levels _ not race _ in its guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot in that commitment that is outside of CRA but
expands the idea of community development,'' Ms. Bessant said. ``To
the extent that minority borrowers have had a more difficult time
accessing credit, it's very relevant under this commitment to
report our minority lending at all income levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many numbers, how the lending pledges are construed
depends on who is doing the construing.
</P>
<P>
   On an annual basis, Nationsbank and BankAmerica are promising to
lend about 6 percent of their combined assets to low-income
borrowers _ a figure that the partners pointedly noted in a press
release will not include credit cards. By comparison, the new
Citigroup pledges to lend about 1.7 percent of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   But Nationsbank and BankAmerica will have more traditional
domestic retail deposits than Citicorp and Travelers, noted Ms.
Flaherty of Citicorp. Judged against that base _ which, she said,
is a better measure of a bank's local lending activity _
Citigroup's lending pledge is more formidable: about 21 percent of
the merged companies' domestic deposit base, versus about 10
percent for the combined Nationsbank-BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   However the numbers are added up, community groups say the
merger partners' big promises are too vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``A $350 billion CRA pledge could have no impact on low-income
and minority communities because CRA can be interpreted so
broadly,'' said John Gamboa, executive director of the Greenlining
Institute, a San Francisco advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Community groups say small-business loans to liquor stores or
check-cashing outfits can be part of a community-investing tally in
a low-income area, even though many residents do not see those
kinds of businesses as contributing to economic development. And
mortgage loans for low-income borrowers can be structured in ways
that make them inaccessible to the borrowers who need them _ if
required down payments are too high, for example, or repayment
schedules too swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the commitment is not tied to a specific local credit and
capital need as identified by the lender in conjunction with
community investment leaders, and does not include a mechanism that
allows for community involvement in the monitoring and evaluation
of that commitment, then it isn't real,'' said Taylor of the
National Community Reinvestment Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp, Travelers, Nationsbank and BankAmerica, he said, put
together their big pledges very quickly and with minimal input from
community groups.
</P>
<P>
   But bankers are extremely reluctant to be more specific about
the types or locations of loans they will make under their
community investment pledges, arguing, as does Nationsbank's Ms.
Bessant, that such precision would ``prevent us from having market
flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Bronx, just a few miles north of the world's banking
center, Union Avenue residents talk about the risks they have taken
putting up their own cash to renovate apartments that were once
uninhabitable. Now, they would like to advance another notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are small businesses and people going to get the money
they need to move the neighborhood to another level?'' asked
Roberto Suero, 22. ``We have initiative here, but no banks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
