<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-JULY4-BOSTON-POPS-A     07-03 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-JULY4-BOSTON-POPS-ART-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON POPS TRADITION NOW STRETCHES ACROSS THE COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Repeating to add photo note; no other changes.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 (JT)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just a modest cultural note for all the patriots whose
hearts will swell and ears will ring to the sky-lighted explosions
of the 1812 Overture on Saturday night: It all started here.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Revolution _ though that, too, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the Boston Pops tradition now practiced in scores if not
hundreds of spots around the country, that the orchestra caps its
Fourth of July concert with Tchaikovsky's (undeniably non-American,
but who cares?) 1812 Overture and air-splitting rounds of cannon
fire along with fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   It started with a quirky friendship between two men: Arthur
Fiedler, the late, legendary, curmudgeonly conductor of the Boston
Pops Orchestra, and David Mugar, a millionaire Boston businessman
who has sponsored every one of Boston's Fourth of July concerts
since they took on this explosive form 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Mugar and Fiedler bonded partly because they shared an
eccentric love: driving around the city listening in on police
radio traffic and hustling to the scenes of fires. When Fiedler
mentioned to Mugar that he was concerned about the dwindling
attendance at the Pops concerts at the Hatch Shell, the stage that
sits like a giant open clam next to the Charles River, Mugar
devised a pyrotechnical plan and provided the money to implement
it.
</P>
<P>
   Mugar persuaded Fiedler to offer the 1812 Overture, replete with
howitzer fire and the church bells Tchaikovsky had written into the
score. And, he said, ``I came up with the idea, just by luck, I
guess now, of having fireworks at the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugar said he told Fiedler he was not sure the explosive ending
could be coordinated well, to which Fiedler replied, ``Oh, don't
worry about it, just let all hell break loose at the end of the
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   The public loved it, to the point that just two years later, in
the bicentennial celebrations, an estimated 400,000 people gathered
for Boston's Fourth of July concert, gaining it entry into the
Guinness Book of World Records as the best-attended classical
concert.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance _ which depends heavily on the weather _ has never
matched that record, though organizers have hopes for this year,
given last year's audience of 375,000. More sound towers and, for
the first time, giant television screens have been added.
</P>
<P>
   If the concerts have not been getting bigger, they have been
getting more technologically ambitious and complex. Ken Clark, a
Boston-based fireworks artist, has begun creating pyro-musicals
that use exactly timed bursts to mirror the music, painting the sky
in time with it. This year, his display, which is being kept secret
beforehand, is to last a half-hour, up from 25 minutes last year.
</P>
<P>
   And so fireworks that cost perhaps $10,000 in the early years
now cost around $200,000, said Mugar, who owns several malls,
hotels and other enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   On a barge loaded with mortars in the middle of the Charles,
Clark said on Thursday that technology has so progressed that a
one-second fireworks effect that would once have taken two crews
half a day to wire up can now be done with a swipe and click of a
computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to marking the 25th anniversary of the 1812
fireworks, Saturday's concert is likely to mark the end of a
tradition. Mugar and his nonprofit organization, Boston's Fourth of
July, have been paying pretty much the entire bill for the party,
nearly $1 million this year. He has finally said that his pockets
are not bottomless.
</P>
<P>
   Probably next year, he said, he will seek the kind of discreet
sponsorship that another Boston tradition, the Boston Marathon,
has, with company logos here and there.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The change goes a bit against the grain. Peter Fiedler, Arthur
Fiedler's son, who cues the cannons at the concert, recalled that
one year, an advertising blimp ``flew over the Esplanade during the
concert and David went berserk'' because he did not want the event
commercialized.
</P>
<P>
   But injections of money would allow the Boston Pops to bring in
ever greater stars as guest performers, he said, and allow ever
more advanced technological feats, possibly including a giant
television screen mounted on a barge in the Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, asked about the direction in which he would like to take
the concerts, Mugar, their executive producer and an unabashed
aficionado of the logistics involved in such huge events, mentioned
a homey vision.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has always seen the Pops concerts as gigantic
versions of the town picnics, oompah band concerts and little
fireworks displays in smaller locales. So, maybe someday, he said,
``I think it'd great if we could give everybody free hot dogs and
Cokes and ice cream. Something real American.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
