<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX MAY BROADCAST HALF OF RED SOX GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Fox will probably be looming large in your living rooms in the
near future. Word has it that Fox-TV network's Channel 25 is
closing in on a deal with the Red Sox to broadcast half the team's
games, and farther down the road airing nearly all of them. At
present, NESN and Channel 68, owned by Boston University, split the
Sox schedule, airing 75 games each with the rest going to ESPN or
Fox's national broadcasts. Fox is looking to hunt down Channel 68
first by wrestling away the games on free TV. And then is expected
to make a deal to buy NESN. The Red Sox own half of the cable
network. Fox's goal appears to be to add the Red Sox and NESN to
its ever-expanding telecasts of Major League Baseball across the
nation. Boston has the last indepedent cable TV affiliation. The
Red Sox hope to push their local TV income well over $20 million
and then make a huge score on the sale of NESN, giving them more
money to invest in a new Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Fitch on when he knew Larry Bird was special: ``It took
about two weeks. That's how long it took for him that first year
(1979-80 season) to learn our system and what his own job was
within that system. Once he had that down, then he started to put
the Larry Bird touch on it. He was great at doing all the things he
could in his own personal game, and yet always doing them within
the system. He wasn't about doing a one-on-one thing. Larry wanted
the team to excel and to make the players around him better, and he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitch's most vivid memory of Bird: ``It was the year we went
down 3-1 in the playoffs to Philly and then came back to beat them.
The morning after we lost that third game I had to talk to the team
knowing that most of them probably thought we were finished. I
talked about winning the next game and just focusing on that.
Because if we won the second game, that would be like winning the
third game (in Boston) and if we got them to 3-3 then it would be
Choke City on them and we could beat them. Every time I said one of
these things Larry sat there nodding his head yes. And doing it in
such a way that everyone else on the team could see him nodding his
head yes. He was sending the message to the other guys that this
could be done. And then they all went out and made it happen.''
Bird announced this week that Fitch will be one of the two
presenters when he is inducted to the Hall of Fame next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Glanville, former head coach of the Houston Oilers and
Atlanta Falcons, on multi-talented outfielder Brian Jordan of the
St. Louis Cardinals who played three years in the Falcons'
defensive back field: ``Put this in the famous last-words category.
Jordan is playing safety for me on the Falcons. He wants a new
contract. I go to management and tell them: `This kid is as good at
safety, as Deion (Sanders) is at corner.' And he was. He wanted
another $100,000 more. For that, he would have stayed with us and
not gone to baseball. But (management) said, `Don't worry, he'll be
back. He can't hit the curveball. What a laugh that turned out to
be.'' Jordan has led the National League in hitting most of the
season, and is one of the best all-around athletes in pro sports.
``I coached 31 years of football and he is the only one I was ever
around I can say that he never missed an open-field tackle. And
every time he made a tackle, he came up with a smile on his face.
He loved to play that much.''
</P>
<P>
   The past couple of weeks have been big ones for Glanville, who
is a race car driver when he's not broadcasting for Fox or doing
the Patriots' exhibition games. ``I won my first race ever last
Saturday night,'' said Glanville. ``It was a great thrill for me. I
beat the guy (Ronnie Sanders) on the final curve of the final lap.
You don't see that happen and very often. And for coincidence, I'm
sponsored by a Boston outfit, Unifirst Uniforms. (Today) I'll be
racing on CBS in Milwaukee. I've got races for most of the rest of
the summer and in between I've got to do four Patriot preseason
games on TV. They like me in Boston because of my (Southern)
accent. They can't figure out what I'm saying, which makes us even,
because I can't understand them either.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra has an unsual All-Star bonus package. If he
makes the All-Star team four of the next five years, he could end
up making an additional $500,000. His contract gives the Red Sox an
option for 2003 at $10.5 million. If Nomar makes the All-Star squad
four times before then, that amount becomes $11 million. But he
missed out on the chance to get the first one this season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Bobby Orr: ``I wish (the NHL) would go back to the old
format where they seeded all of the teams in the league one through
16 for the playoffs, where you would have the chance of getting the
best two teams into the finals. There were a lot of good games in
the playoffs this year, but they were all before the finals. The
Bruins could have gotten to the final. They were better than
Washington. They just didn't win the series.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As sports fans, we have become used to owners getting their
butts handed to them whenever they square off with player unions in
labor negotiations. But this NBA lockout might be different. In the
past, the unions have threatened to decertify, but that may not
have the clout it did before. In Brown vs. NFL, a 1996 case, a a
judge's ruling made it more difficult to use decertification
(giving up a recognizied labor union to become a trade association
with no bargaining powers) as a negotiating tool. The NFL Players'
Association went this route and decertified for four years. It then
went to court on an anti-trust basis and beat the owners for $190
million in damages. However, in the Brown case (he was Antony
Brown, a practice squad player with Washington) the court opinion
frowned on using decertification as a tactic, and hinted that any
union trying to do so in the future should have to do it for a long
time and not as a charade, before being allowed to move forward on
an anti-trust basis. Right now, the owners are holding the cards.
At impasse, they can implement their own rules if the players come
back to play. The feeling is that no new deal will be done; that
the league will stay out of business at least for a month into
December. Meanwhile, the owners will be getting money from the TV
networks to keep their franchises going, and the players will be
losing big money with every missed game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Thornton went home to celebrate his 19th birthday Thursday
and to be with his mother on her 50th. ``He came here last spring
at about 195 pounds,'' says super trainer Mike Boyle. ``Right now
he is somewhere between 220 and 225. Joe showed a lot by staying
here in Boston since the end of the season and really being serious
about working out; getting bigger; and getting stronger. Joe is
always in shape. He will be stronger next season.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton was a big disappointment for the Bruins this past
season. As the No.1 choice in the draft they thought they would get
more out of him. Thornton was equally disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would do a lot more and be a lot better,'' he
said. ``It was a tough year for me. I had been used to playing a
lot and scoring a lot of goals. It was very frustrating when that
did not happen. I thought (breaking in) was going to be easier. But
I underestimated the size and the speed of the guys. Now I know
what to expect, and I'm going to do everything I can to be ready
for next season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Delaware North, owners of the Bruins and the
Fleet Center, have been talking with a developer about what to do
when the destruction of the Boston Garden is completed. Any deal is
still months away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is probably stranger than most of his novels. Tom Clancy,
noted author, tried and failed in an attempt to purchase the
Minnesota Vikings. In divorce proceedings with his wife, it was
alleged that Clancy had taken up with one Alexandra LLewellyn,
daughter of J. Bruce Llewellyn, a highly successful Philadelphia
businessman. Weeks after Clancy's bid to by the team failed, J.
Bruce Llewellyn tried to buy it. But subsequently he has needed
major surgery and has dropped out of the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the NFL, commissioner Paul Tagliabue met this week
with exiled San Francisco owner Eddie DeBartolo. DeBartolo last
year verbally agreed to step aside as owner when it was revealed
that he was the subject of a grand jury investigation in New
Orleans. In the interim, his sister, Denise, has been in charge of
the team with president Carmen Policy handling the day-to-day
operations. However, even though he reportedly could still be
indicted in Louisiana, DeBartolo wants back in with the 49ers. He
never signed the agreement that was drawn up by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the Hartford Courant, Patriots owner Robert Kraft
and Governer John G. Rowland of Connecticut have had at least 17
conversations in the last six months about the NFL team playing in
a new stadium in Hartford. Rowland is waiting to see what happens
in the Massachusetts Legislature after July 31. If there is no
agreement on the proposal to build a new stadium in Foxborough,
Connecticut will act.
</P>
</TEXT>
