<SLUG> BC-HKN-HULL-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL SIGNS WITH STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Tom Hicks went dipping into his wallet once
again yesterday and stunned the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars owner came up with his third consecutive summer of
successfully luring a major free agent to Dallas when the Stars
signed All-Star winger Brett Hull to a three-year, $17 million
contract. The move automatically answers the Stars' biggest need
for a high-scoring winger and renders moot speculation that the
team would pursue lesser stars Geoff Courtnall or Wendel Clark.
</P>
<P>
   While Stars general manager Bob Gainey said the Stars still have
interest in Clark, the signing of Hull is significantly more
important. A three-time first-team NHL All-Star with the St. Louis
Blues, Hull brings a pedigree for guaranteed scoring backed by 554
career goals in 801 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player with a great knack for scoring goals,''
Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who turns 34 Aug. 9, joins goalie Ed Belfour (three years,
$10 million) and winger Pat Verbeek (three years, $9.3 million) as
free-agent home runs hit by Hicks, who has owned the Stars since
1995. As Belfour did last season, Hull turned down more money from
another team, according to his agent, Mike Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a chance to play for a franchise like Dallas, to have a
legitimate chance to be a champion, every player wants that,'' Hull
said. ``This is a great organization that is very serious about
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars won the bidding for Hull over a host of suitors that
included the Chicago Blackhawks, who signed Doug Gilmour to a
three-year, $18 million contract yesterday, as well as the
Washington Capitals and Los Angeles Kings. Hull's father, Bobby, a
member of the Hockey Hall of Fame nicknamed ``The Golden Jet.''
played for the Blackhawks and pushed hard for Brett to follow in
his footsteps. Adam Oates, a former teammate of Hull's, plays for
the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   But still, the Stars closed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of strong ownership and good management and
quality players on our team, that has made us very attractive to
people like Pat Verbeek and Ed Belfour and now Brett Hull,'' Stars
president Jim Lites said. ``It has seemed to get easier for us as
the years have gone on. We don't have to do the big sales pitch
now. It's a part of the hockey mind-set that Dallas is a great city
to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hull joining the team, the Stars have a collection of
forwards that includes Mike Modano (21 goals), Joe Nieuwendyk (39
goals), Verbeek (31 goals) and Hull (27 goals). Toss role players
Jamie Langenbrunner and Jere Lehtinen (23 goals apiece) and the
Stars seem to have a roster that should be able to survive the rash
of injuries that cripple the team's offense in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this gives us is just one more great player to add to the
room,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I don't think you can
ever have too much talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Hull likely will be placed on a line with Modano
and Lehtinen. Hull's natural position is right wing, but he has
played the left side with the Blues for the past season and a half.
Lehtinen also could switch to left wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll experiment with things in training camp and during the
exhibition season, but that's definitely how it will start out,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who labeled himself ``primarily a goal-scorer,'' is coming
off the lowest goal-scoring season of his 12-year NHL career,
tallying 27 goals in 66 games and missing 16 games with a broken
hand. But he also had 45 assists, and his 72 points would have led
the Stars. Nieuwendyk was the Stars' top scorer with 69 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed last season that he can play in a defensive-minded
system,'' Hitchcock said, when questioned about Hull's defensive
deficiencies. ``Obviously, that was a concern, but \RSt. Louis
coach\S Joel Quenneville's system is very similar to ours, and he
played very well in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not well enough for the Blues to keep him, however. Hull was
close to signing a three-year, $15 million deal with the Blues last
month but balked when they didn't include a no-trade clause in the
contract. The Stars, while reluctant to do so at first, Barnett
said, worked a trade-veto clause into their contract, which will
pay Hull $4.5 million next season, $5.5 the next and $7 million in
2001-02. Hull also has an option for a fourth year at $7 million.
The Stars can automatically sign him at that amount, or he can
choose to take the option if he meets certain performance
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a player that we had targeted early,'' Gainey said. ``We
obviously had a need for goal-scoring, and he was the top
goal-scorer available. We didn't know what he was interested in,
and we didn't know what other teams might offer, but we were able
to come to terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms that have Hull so happy, he said he isn't disappointed to
leave St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly not,'' he said. ``I spent 11 years there and had
a great rapport with the fans. But with the new regime that came
in, there was never any real attachment to that. So I'm very
excited to be part of the Dallas Stars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
