<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HARASS-INSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS LIKELY TO PRESS FOR ANTI-SEX-HARASSMENT POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insurance companies are likely to press New Jersey employers to
develop strict policies for preventing and remedying sexual
harassment in the wake of a ruling by the New Jersey Supreme Court
that workers' compensation insurance must pay for injuries arising
from sexual harassment, insurance industry executives and lawyers
say.
</P>
<P>
   Employers, lawyers and insurance companies are still studying
the June 15 decision, which appears to have national implications.
The court ruled that as a matter of public policy, insurance
companies cannot exclude sexual harassment damages from their
workers' compensation coverage, which every employer is legally
required to buy. Such exclusions are now standard in workers'
compensation policies.
</P>
<P>
   The decision may raise the cost of workers' compensation
policies, insurance executives say, and may prompt companies and
their insurers to seek relief by lobbying the state Legislature for
a change in the law.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, insurance companies are likely to start
requiring clients to have the kind of anti-harassment policies and
remedies that were outlined last month by the U.S. Supreme Court in
two landmark decisions on employer liability in sexual harassment
cases. The court held that a lawsuit cannot succeed if a company
has an anti-harassment policy with an effective complaint procedure
in place and the employee has unreasonably failed to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between this kind of decision in New Jersey and the Supreme
Court's decision on supervisory liability, clients will have to pay
a lot of attention to developing their own internal compliance
mechanisms,'' said Carmine Iannaccone, a partner at the law firm of
Hannoch Weisman in Roseland, N.J., which represents companies that
are suing their insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Courts in several states have rejected efforts to have workers'
compensation policies cover sexual harassment damages. But rulings
by the New Jersey Supreme Court have proved influential with other
high courts around the country, said Kevin Bruno, another partner
at Hannoch Weisman.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey decision should also make it easier for victims
of sexual harassment who win damages in court to collect them, said
Elizabeth Zuckerman, a partner in the firm of Zuckerman &AMP; Fisher in
Lawrenceville, N.J. She represented Lisa Schmidt, the plantiff in
the lawsuit _ against Personalized Audio Visual Inc. and its
president, Dennis Smith _ that was at the center of the New Jersey
Supreme Court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schmidt said that Smith had fondled her and demanded sexual
favors, which caused not just emotional distress but also bodily
injury in the form of an eating disorder and an attempt at suicide.
In 1994, a jury awarded Ms. Schmidt $80,000 in damages plus legal
fees, but she could not collect because the company had gone out of
business, Ms. Zuckerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's insurance carrier, USF&AMP;G, argued that coverage for
such injuries was excluded under its workers' compensation policy,
a position that was rejected by the court because of Ms. Schmidt's
physical injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance company has asked the court to reconsider its
ruling; the lawyer representing USF&AMP;G, Kevin Wolff, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey decision comes as the number of sexual harassment
lawsuits is soaring and as companies are increasingly trying to
find ways to get insurance companies to cover the heavy costs of
defending against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is THE growth area in labor law,'' said Samuel
Estreicher, director of the Center for Labor and Employment Law at
New York University Law School, ``and these cases are expensive and
very hard to defend against.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, lawyers around the country are likely to make
similar arguments in trying to get insurance companies to cover
sexual harassment cases through workers' compensation policies.
``This creates a framework for sharp attorneys in how to get
coverage,'' said Kenneth Martino, a senior executive at the
consulting firm of Tillinghast-Towers Perrin in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies do not believe that workers' compensation
policies were meant to cover sexual harassment damages, said Doreen
Spadorcia, a senior vice president of Travelers Property &AMP;
Casualty, a leading seller of commercial insurance. ``I think this
will be a decision that most insurers will say doesn't make
sense,'' she said, adding that many companies, including hers,
offer separate policies specifically to cover wrongful employment
practices.
</P>
<P>
   If the New Jersey decision stands, insurance companies will
probably raise the price of workers' compensation policies, said
Keith Anderson, a spokesman for Travelers. Such price increases, he
added, may well prompt New Jersey's Legislature to change the law
to keep workers' compensation policies from having to cover
harassment injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
