<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-UNION-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS' UNION CHIEF STRESSES QUALITY OF PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn.)   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In his two years as president of the National
Education Association, the nation's largest labor union, Bob Chase,
has repeatedly been accused of sleeping with the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Those accusations started last year when he began to push the
union in a radical new direction, calling on it to discard its
industrial-style, us-against-them tactics and instead cooperate
with school boards to help them improve education.
</P>
<P>
   But while shunning the tactics of blue-collar unions, Chase has
often surprised his union's 2.3 million members by saying they have
an important lesson to learn from the steelworkers. For decades, he
explains, steelworkers focused on pushing their wages ever higher,
while worrying little about product quality, the result being that
customers turned to imports, the industry declined and thousands of
unionized workers lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   If public school teachers do not work to improve the quality of
their product, Chase warned, the push for vouchers might gather
steam, channeling many more children into private schools and
jeopardizing the jobs of public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If unions don't accept that quality is their issue, if they
say quality is just up to management, then problems are
inevitable,'' said Chase, a 55-year-old former social studies
teacher in Danbury, Conn. ``The best insurance there is for
members' jobs is for members to make sure their workplace is
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase even endorsed peer-review programs that pressure bad
teachers to move into other professions, or, failing that,
recommend their dismissal. For many teachers this was out-and-out
heresy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you were a social studies teacher before you became
president of the NEA,'' one outraged group of Wisconsin teachers
wrote him, ``you should understand the result of appeasement in
Eastern Europe in the '30s and '40s.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Chase is hearing a new round of accusations of heresy
as he campaigns 18 hours a day to persuade 10,000 union delegates
gathered here that they should vote to merge with the education
association's archrival, the American Federation of Teachers.
Joining the two unions together would create a colossus with almost
3.3 million members, giving the teachers even more clout in
Washington as well as a single voice to fight foes pushing for
vouchers and an end to tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders acknowledge that the delegates might narrowly
reject the merger by not giving it the required two-thirds majority
when they vote on Sunday. But Chase remains optimistic,
notwithstanding attacks from anti-merger teachers who say the AFT
is too militant.
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association was founded in 1857 as a
genteel professional association that shunned collective bargaining
for over a century. But when the teachers' federation flexed its
muscles in the 1960s and 1970s and made giant strides in wages and
benefits, the NEA quickly imitated the American Federation of
Teachers and became a regular union, although many association
members still perceive the teachers' federation to be more
confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   Many NEA members also oppose the merger because it would push
the association into the AFL-CIO, which many see as an organization
for blue-collar workers, not for lofty professionals like
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, many merger opponent love the National Education
Association as it is, and their logic is, ``if it ain't broke,
don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing what could be his biggest test ever, Chase said,
``What we're talking about is a very historic opportunity that is a
very difficult thing for a lot of members to accept. There's an
enormous amount of passion for the NEA, and many are wary of
putting together something that will mean the dissolution of the
NEA and the creation of a new organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the two unions agreed on a set of principles for
the merger, which aims to end a bitter rivalry in which the two
spent more than $100 million over the past two decades competing
with each other to recruit members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending our wasteful rivalry would enable the NEA and AFT to
serve our members and advance public education with far greater
strength, vigor and focus,'' Chase said in his keynote speech
Friday as the convention opened.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken, amiable man, Chase talks with the neat logic of
an appellate lawyer and the ease of a born politician. Born in
Wellfleet, Mass., he went to Providence College, spent two years at
a seminary, but then decided to forgo the priesthood in favor of
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   His first teaching job was at a school for delinquents in
Providence, where his salary was $4,800. From there, Chase, who is
divorced and has two grown daughters, moved to Danbury, where he
taught for 25 years, interrupted by a two-year hitch in the Army.
While in Danbury, he began his steady climb up the NEA's ladder.
</P>
<P>
   If the education association delegates approve the merger this
weekend and if the teachers' federation delegates do likewise at
their convention in two weeks, Chase and AFT president Sandra
Feldman would serve as co-founding presidents of the new
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The two often say they get along so well that they often finish
each other's sentences. ``He has played an unprecedented role in
getting out front on important issues as president,'' said Ms.
Feldman. ``He's someone who cares very much about kids and public
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase said that whether or not the merger is approved, he will
plow ahead with his plans to emphasize not just bread-and-butter
issues, but the teachers' role in improving schools.
</P>
<P>
   He has even won praise from some longtime critics of teachers'
unions, although other foes say his change in direction is mere
window dressing, complaining, for instance, that only about 30 of
the union's 13,000 locals have adopted reforms like peer review.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sort of a Gorbachev figure,'' said Chester Finn, a senior
fellow at the Hudson Institute. ``He's attempting to take an almost
completely harmful institution and at the very least put a very
different face on it and perhaps also modernize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Chase, the union has endorsed charter schools, innovative
public schools that are allowed to operate free of many of the
bureaucratic rules. While he vigorously opposes merit pay and
vouchers, he is constantly urging school districts to spend more
money on professional development so that teachers can keep up with
what is new in pedagogy and in their fields of expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Every chance he gets, Chase hails peer review, a system in which
expert teachers advise other teachers on how to teach better.
Despite criticisms that peer review throws some teachers overboard,
Chase said it is good for the profession and children if
unsatisfactory teachers who fail to improve have the choice of
finding another profession or not having their contracts renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Defending this controversial stance, he said, ``It's not an
I-gotcha program. It's good for the profession. It helps enhance
the skills of educators. Those who are unable to take advantage of
the process, it recommends that they go into other professions. The
primary focus is improved instruction. If that happens, everyone
wins.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
