<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ENTERTAINING WITH FLASH AND PANACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eddie Layton's perky organ music rises from Yankee
Stadium, wafts across the Harlem River, mixes with the blare of
hip-hop from Rucker Park at 155th Street and floats through my
dining room window.
</P>
<P>
   A Yankee home run triggers a siren that wails in celebration;
when someone dunks down below, makes a great block or a great pass,
a searing, swelling ``oooooooohhhhhhhh'' erupts from the crowd.
This is the real basketball season, a time from July and August
when the game is put outside and allowed to run without shackles or
leg irons.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Shaquille O'Neal, the Lakers' center, showed up at the
Entertainer's Basketball Classic, the annual summer tournament at
Rucker Park. There was no wild mob scene. Just kids, lots of kids,
who had never seen Shaq before. He patiently signed plenty of
autographs. Then the crowd let him be, and O'Neal sat in the stands
and took in the theater of the game as it was meant to be played.
</P>
<P>
   The Entertainer's Basketball Classic league replaced the Rucker
tournament at this location several years ago; the Rucker is now
located at 145th Street and Lenox Avenue. This is a different scene
at the Entertainer's Classic, a different crowd, much younger and
livelier and putting a premium on excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rucker crowd liked excitement, too, but was very
knowledgeable about the game,'' said Rodger Murray, an official for
tournaments at the site nearly 20 years and the scoreboard operator
for the Knicks. ``They looked for the nuances and the intricacies.
The pick and rolls, the back door. Now you have a much younger
crowd. Here we're talking about a lot of glitz, the flashy moves,
the dunks, a lot of hip-hop things.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison Avenue has taken notice. Tommy Hilfiger, Perry Ellis and
Reebok are among several sponsors whose banners hang on the fence.
The styles of the inner city fuel fashion trends throughout the
country, on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Each glitzy game has its defining moment, when the winner of the
game within the game is decided. That moment Thursday came with
Sugar Hill leading Kenny's Kings by 60-54. There had been a running
debate between the fan on my left and a younger fan on my right
about fundamentals versus glitz. The embodiment of fundamentals was
the 5-foot-10-inch Kareem Reid, of the University of Arkansas by
way of St. Raymond High in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   For the younger fan, the 5-8 Edward ``Booger'' Smith of Brooklyn
was the real truth. Smith, from Westinghouse High and an Arizona
junior college, was featured on the cover of a national sports
magazine and was part of a documentary on the Brooklyn Soul in the
Hole tournament. This was his first time he was coming Uptown with
a reputation to uphold. The older fan remarked that Reid made
smart, snappy passes; the younger fan roared each time Smith made
one of his signature passes, though not always to the right man.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Smith raced down the left sideline and tried to take
the baseline against the stronger Reid, who cut him off. Smith
tried to shake free with speedy crossover dribbles, but Reid held
his ground. The older fan shouted, ``Look at that defense, look at
that ...''
</P>
<P>
   But before he could finish, Smith picked up his dribble, reached
around Reid's neck, put up an underhand shot that he banked in and
drew a foul from a bewildered Reid. The crowd roared. The fan who
had argued Reid's case leaped out of his chair. Even Reid gave
Smith five.
</P>
<P>
   Reid tried to get even. He drove and drew a foul on Smith, but
the crowd was still buzzing over Smith's Globetrotter-like shot.
</P>
<P>
   The older fan boasted that Reid's team won, 102-93. The younger
fan said: ``Who cares? Booger won the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the deejay/public address announcer was building the thunder
for Monday's game featuring the Bad Boys: Ron Artest, a bruising
forward, and Eric Barkley, the freshman guard who will be his
teammate at St. John's next season. The fans filed out, some
mingling with the players, others talking about who did what to
whom, most simply enjoying the ambiance of a summer with good
basketball. They'll come back full force Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the crowd had thinned, four of us stood around
talking about the evening's events, wondering what it all meant.
</P>
<P>
   The best of these players go off to big colleges. The cream will
sign contracts and probably won't be back. Madison Avenue rides the
wave of urban chic. This generation's legends _ the Boogers, the
Alley Mo's, the Skip to My Lou's, the Black Widows of Harlem _ will
provide more fodder for some other explorer's documentary, someone
else's book.
</P>
<P>
   And cheers will flow eternally over Harlem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
