<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA FEDERAL BANK PARENT TO REFINANCE DEBT, PREFERRED STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The parent company of California Federal Bank
said it plans to refinance $1.8 billion worth of debt and preferred
stock to take advantage of lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   First Nationwide Holdings Inc., a privately held financial
institution based in San Francisco, expects to replace
substantially all of its long-term debt and California Federal's
preferred stock with new notes, or debt.
</P>
<P>
   The notes will be issued under a new company that will be formed
when it completes its merger with Golden State Bancorp, the parent
of Glendale Federal Bank, based in suburban Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, in which new shares of Golden State will be issued
to First Nationwide's owners, is expected to close by Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Thrift officials said Thursday they're refinancing the debt to
take advantage of lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's expected to be significant savings in interest expense
to do this,'' said Richard Terzian, chief financial officer of
California Federal.
</P>
<P>
   First Nationwide will take a refinancing charge in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Wagner, a fixed-income analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's
in New York, said the refinancing will improve overall cash flow
for the company.
</P>
<P>
   First Nationwide's balance sheet already benefits from the
merger with Golden State, which does not have any long-term debt,
Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger announcement, First Nationwide's notes were put
on S&AMP;P's credit watch with positive implications, meaning they
could be given a higher rating. The higher the rating, the better
the capability of the company issuing the debt to repay it.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's, another New York rating agency, on Thursday upgraded
First Nationwide's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Terzian said the new debt will be issued in the next few weeks
or months. Terms of the notes were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to refinance is good for investors because it will
lower interest costs for the new company.
</P>
<P>
   As for its institutional bondholders, who benefit from higher
interest rates, Terzian said they will receive a premium for
holding the debt in the past.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
