A0052 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-LADN     07-03 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATS BUILD RELATIONSHIPS WITH SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Since splitting off from Yugoslavia seven
years ago, Croatia has made its name on the world's sporting field,
in basketball and soccer and tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing it has accomplished rivals what it can achieve tonight
when it takes on Germany at Lyon's Stade Gerland for a berth in the
World Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nearly incomprehensible possibility for the tiny Balkan
nation of 4.7 million people, something that would reverberate far
beyond sporting boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just sport there are political repercussions, too,''
says Miroslav Blazevic, who has guided the surprising Croats into
the elite eight of the world's greatest soccer tournament. ``Before
(the victory over Romania in the second round), maybe 5 percent of
the people knew Croatia. Now, maybe 15 percent know. So, of course,
that is important to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   It is vital as the Croats continue to build relationships with
the rest of the world, an enterprise it has been pursuing since its
bloody civil war with the Serbians who wouldn't let go. That
Yugoslavia, better touted than its rival, has been eliminated from
the Cup while Croatia plays on is a matter of significant national
pride.
</P>
<P>
   And as unlikely as reaching the final four might appear Germany
has reached the World Cup final in five of the previous eight
tournaments Croatia is confident it can pull off an upset. Its
faith is built on what occurred two years ago, in the its first
major soccer tournament since the war. The Croats reached the
quarterfinals, where they lost to Germany, 2-1, in a controversial
match that left many in the country feeling they'd been cheated.
Avenging that defeat is certainly part of the motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's revenge,'' Blazevic admits. ``We'll do everything to beat
Germany. The Germans are our friends, and there's nothing better in
sport than beating your friends. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this German phenomenom. That's annoying for them. I
hope I know what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Croats' key figure is Zvonimir Boban, a playmaking
midfielder regarded in his country the equal of any ``freedom
fighter'' for his actions one night in 1990. It occurred at a match
between Red Star Belgrade, the top Serbian club, and Dynamo Zagreb,
Croatia's No. 1 team, in which the tensions between the peoples
spilled out into fighting between the clubs' fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Zagreb supporters were chased onto the field by Red Star
fans, where they were met by Belgrade police, who began swinging
batons. Boban, then only 21, attacked an officer he saw beating a
couple Zagreb fans. He was punished by the Yugoslav federation but
hailed as a hero in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what any normal person would do and defended innocent
people who had no way of protecting themselves from their
attackers,'' said Boban, who has starred the past seven years at AC
Milan. ``I love my country, and I love my people, and anyone who
takes them on takes me on as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's ready to take on the Germans, unlike in '96, when he
let his overwhelming passion prevent him from having any impact on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotblooded player of 1990 returned, and I lost it
completely,'' he admitted. ``Maybe it was the occasion and
thinking, `Wow, Croatia is on the verge of something big in our
first major tournament,' and I just let my patriotism get the
better of my reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that having come through the (World Cup) group matches,
that I will be a lot calmer and able to give the German midfield a
real run for their money. This is yet another historic occasion for
our young nation, and I want them to feel proud about it, and not
ashamed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
