<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-455&AMP;AD     07-03 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-455&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL SIGNS WITH STARS; HAWKS LURE GILMOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mo., Ill., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars finished with the best record in the 1997-98
regular season and were among the final four teams in the National
Hockey League playoffs. But one of their best attackers, Joe
Nieuwendyk, was injured early in the tournament, and the rest of
the Stars did not have enough scoring punch in the third round to
get past the Detroit Red Wings, who went on to win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to correct one of their few deficiencies, the Stars on
Friday signed Brett Hull, the biggest star among the unrestricted
free agents. They will pay the 33-year-old right wing, who had been
with the St. Louis Blues since 1988, $17 million for three seasons.
The contract also includes a fourth season, at the Stars' option,
and a no-trade clause, something Hull wanted but could not get from
the Blues last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was not the day's only major signing. Chicago paid center
Doug Gilmour $18 million for three years to leave the New Jersey
Devils and try to revive the Blackhawks. In 63 games last season
with the Devils, Gilmour had 13 goals and 40 assists. He scored
five times in their six playoff games. The Devils were eliminated
in the first round by Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who scored 86 goals in his best season seven years ago,
scored only 27 in 1997-98. He has 554 goals and 987 points in 801
NHL games, and he was also wooed by Chicago, the city where his
father, Bobby Hull, was a superstar. ``Things couldn't get worked
out,'' Brett Hull said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So he signed with the Stars. ``We needed to improve our goal
scoring,'' said Tom Hicks, the owner of the Stars. ``I think we did
that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said: ``I have an opportunity to play with a strong team
with so many character players. They are the closest to anyone of
winning the Stanley Cup. The main thing is to win and be a
champion. I wanted to do it in St. Louis, but I'm not in St. Louis
anymore. I thought this was the best opportunity for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Hull earned $4.2 million with the Blues. Although
it was widely reported that the Rangers had tried to sign Hull, a
team spokesman emphatically denied that the New York team was
involved in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour, paid $3.55 million by the Devils last season, will get
$6 million per season from Chicago. He recently celebrated his 35th
birthday. The Blackhawks apparently decided to concentrate on
Gilmour when the bidding for Hull went beyond what they wanted to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Murray, general manager of the Blackhawks, said: ``We took
the guy who is going to help the hockey team the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Gilmour at center, the Devils have Bobby Holik, Bob
Carpenter, Denis Pederson, Petr Sykora and Brendan Morrison.
However, Holik and Sykora are restricted free agents in the Group 2
category.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Friday's Hull and Gilmour deals were the biggest in the first
three days of the signing season, which began on Wednesday. In the
previous two days, defenseman Steve Duchesne got about $15 million
for four years to leave St. Louis for the Los Angeles Kings and
defenseman Gary Suter got $10 million for three years to leave
Chicago for San Jose. Left wing Geoff Courtnall got $10.5 million
to stay with St. Louis for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from goalies, the most sought players still available in
the unrestricted category are center Ron Francis of Pittsburgh and
defenseman Uwe Krupp of Colorado. The Rangers have talked with
representatives of both players. They also have negotiated for Marc
Bureau, a checking center with Montreal last season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unrestricted goalies on the market are Mike Richter of
the Rangers and Curtis Joseph of Edmonton. The Rangers and the
Philadelphia Flyers will probably bid the highest for both,
although neither team has aggressively pursued either player yet.
Both players are thought to be seeking from $5 million to $7
million per season on multiyear contracts.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the slow pace of bidding for goalies might be the
supply and demand realities of the market. Teams failing to sign
either high-profile goalie have a safety net of several others,
including Florida's John Vanbiesbrouck, Edmonton's Bob Essensa, San
Jose's Kelly Hrudey, Vancouver's Arturs Irbe, and Philadelphia's
Sean Burke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
