<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINK BETWEEN TCE, ILLNESSES NEARLY IMPOSSIBLE TO PROVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melody Baker says tainted groundwater in west Phoenix caused her
rare blood disorder. The companies she blames for the contamination
point to other possible culprits: cigarettes, maybe even her hair
dye.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Phillips says trichloroethylene in the water gave her
grandson leukemia. But the companies say she should worry more
about the cigarettes she smoked, the power lines near her home or
the pesticides sprayed around the house to kill bugs.
</P>
<P>
   People across the Phoenix area _ and across the country from
Simi Valley, Calif., to Webster, N.Y. _ say TCE silently is
attacking their neighborhoods. They say the solvent used by
industrial companies for years is making people ill, and sometimes
killing them.
</P>
<P>
   But despite years of litigation involving millions of dollars in
attorneys' fees, proving a connection between the two has been
nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants in most lawsuits involving TCE appear to have gained
the upper hand. The outcome is especially important in Phoenix and
Scottsdale, where plumes of groundwater containing the solvent have
spread through parts of the aquifers underneath the cities,
potentially affecting hundreds of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their cases, Phoenix-area defendants, who include
Motorola and the city of Phoenix, have researched many of the
plaintiffs' lives. &UR; In stacks of documents filed in Maricopa County
Superior Court, the lawyers point to everyday habits they say could
be as much to blame for health problems as TCE, or more so: using
breast implants, smoking cigarettes, pumping gas, being exposed to
chemicals at work. And don't forget using coffee, anti-lice
shampoo, saccharin or oral contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone is subjected to so many possible
environmental contaminants, they say, that it's difficult to pin
the blame on TCE.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The defendants also have produced expert witnesses with
impressive credentials who say the amount of TCE in the drinking
water was not nearly enough to cause cancer, leukemia or other
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The legal arguments paid off this month for the defense when a
Maricopa County Superior Court judge all but dismissed part of
``Lofgren vs. Motorola,'' a lawsuit against Motorola, Phoenix and
numerous other defendants involving tainted groundwater. &UR; Judge
Steven Sheldon ruled that, in the case of 18 east Phoenix and
Scottsdale residents, they failed to link TCE in the water near
their homes to their health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the outcome has been much the same. There is not
enough scientific evidence &UR; to &UR; show TCE is responsible for cancer,
leukemia and other diseases blamed on the solvent, says Dr. Ginger
Gist, senior environmental health scientist for the Agency for
Toxic Substances and Disease Registry in Atlanta, a sister agency
of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a number of things,'' she said. ``If they fill
their own gas tank, they've been exposed to pretty high levels of
benzene (a carcinogen). Or if they pick &UR; up the dry cleaning . . .
tetrachloroethylene is a common agent in some dry cleaning. Or if
they're smoking. . .''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency is reevaluating its
cancer classification for TCE pending further studies, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon's decision will be appealed, the residents' attorneys
promise. But the ruling suggests trouble ahead for related
TCE-contamination cases working their way through Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, residents of west Phoenix, east Phoenix and Scottsdale
believe TCE will be identified as the source of their medical
problems. &UR; Something attacked their bodies and lowered their
property values, they say, and it must have been TCE.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So far, one thing is certain: TCE did contaminate the
groundwater in portions of Scottsdale and Phoenix. &UR; Phoenix shut
down about 10 drinking wells and at least one park well in the
1980s after TCE was discovered. The solvent was popular for decades
as a way to clean industrial components such as circuit boards. It
allegedly was dumped into septic tanks or onto the ground and
quietly made its way into the water in parts of Phoenix and
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Six lawsuits filed over TCE contamination in the Phoenix area
have been consolidated in Maricopa County Superior court, leaving
``Lofgren vs. Motorola'' and ``Baker vs. Motorola.'' &UR; Both suits
involve Motorola and target numerous defendants. The stakes are
enormous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So far, the city of Phoenix alone has spent more than $8
million defending the lawsuits. &UR; Attorneys for those who sued have
suggested that defendants could have to pay $1 million to $3
million for each person who died or became seriously ill because of
TCE exposure. &UR; Plaintiffs also want programs set up to monitor the
health of people who may have been exposed. One estimate for the
cost of such a program was $40 million to $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   And others want to be paid for damage to their property values.
One estimate filed with the court said the ``stigma'' from
contamination in the West Phoenix area triggered a $300 million
drop in the area's property values.
</P>
<P>
   But the plaintiffs' chances of being awarded large amounts of
money may be fading in the wake of Sheldon's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Melody Baker, the lead plaintiff in ``Baker vs.
Motorola,'' has no doubt that the demon that took her health away
is TCE.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, 44, lived between four wells in west Phoenix _ two at
39th Avenue and Earll Drive and two at 47th Avenue and Indian
School Road _ that were among those contaminated with TCE and shut
down in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Her symptoms started out as spells of blurred vision and
numbness on one side of her face. There were headaches and slurred
speech. Seizurelike episodes. She eventually was diagnosed as
having a blood disorder that can lead to leukemia and other
diseases. The disorder causes blood clots, like one last year that
blocked a vein that serves her liver.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baker is certain TCE caused her illness, she
acknowledges that even her doctor can't say the chemical is to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my doctor what could have caused it. He said he truly
didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nationally, there have been some high-priced settlements
involving TCE cases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Xerox agreed to pay $4.75 million to two families who
said TCE from a New York plant harmed their health. Without
admitting fault, the company relocated the families and bought
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s in Woburn, Mass., a high number of leukemia
cases appeared. TCE was found in the water, and W.R. Grace Co. and
Beatrice Foods were sued. In 1986 a jury absolved Beatrice, but
found Grace guilty of polluting wells. The company settled for $8
million; another company paid $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Hughes Aircraft Co. settled for $84.5
million with 1,620 Tucson residents who sued because of TCE-tainted
water.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has a regulatory limit of five parts per billion for
TCE.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phoenix-area cases, plaintiffs say in court records that
levels of TCE in drinking water reached 79 parts per billion in
Scottsdale and up to 32 parts per billion in east Phoenix. They say
maximum readings for drinking water in west Phoenix reached up to
148 parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials say those numbers are ``greatly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds &UR; Jim Lemmon, a former state hydrologist who worked for two
decades on groundwater contamination cases: ``I never found
anything in a drinking-water well in the Phoenix area much over 40
(parts per billion) that I can remember, and those were often wells
that had already been disconnected for other reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon said most drinking-water wells he tested registered far
less.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, state health officials completed a years-long study of
the Tucson TCE problem and could not link the TCE to health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Others have their doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Horacek of Phoenix isn't part of any of the lawsuits. But
living by ``the pond'' where used TCE was dumped by a nearby
company, he looks at his own neighborhood and worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my street, within one city block, we have nine deaths from
cancer,'' he said. He can't prove TCE caused the deaths, ``but it's
not just a coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old Horacek acknowledges he ``used TCE like water''
for decades to clean circuit boards as a worker at that nearby
plant, but has no medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Defendants in the Phoenix area-cases say the TCE fears are
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen a connection between our operations and
those illnesses,'' said John Godec, director of issues management
for Motorola. He said ``nine independent studies'' confirmed that
the public is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials say the rate of diseases in the affected areas
is virtually the same as among the ``unaffected'' population.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The city has met or exceeded all standards for drinking water,
adds Deputy City Manager David Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``There's no question some people are very ill, some have
passed away. They had pretty drastic problems,'' Garcia said. ``The
leap we are being asked to make is that those people were ill
because of very low levels of TCE over a limited time. That's been
a hard case to make.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Expert witnesses with impressive credentials agree. The
president of the American Cancer Society and the director of the
toxicology program at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
said the levels of TCE found in Phoenix drinking water and air
could not have caused the health problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Because of Sheldon's decision to dismiss part of ``Lofgren,''
defendants in the rest of ``Lofgren'' and in ``Baker'' are
confident. They say much evidence in other cases is the same as in
the portion discounted by Sheldon. &UR; And Baker admits the judge's
ruling floored her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I afraid? Oh yeah,'' she said. ``Am I afraid medically and
financially, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; She believes her problems all started with the groundwater. She
knows it is difficult to prove. But just to be safe, she drinks
bottled water these days. &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at 444-8697, or at
chris.fiscus(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
