 Some short thoughts for a long weekend  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Marketplace musings for a long weekend: The mandated
closing of liquor stores in Kansas on Saturday just because it's
the July Fourth holiday shows how much further the state must
progress before it emerges completely from the Dark Ages.
</P>
<P>
   - Why is Pfizer wasting its money developing an ad campaign for
a product that sells itself as readily as Viagra does?
</P>
<P>
   - If the national debt still is growing and federal taxes can't
be cut despite a projected budget surplus, what was the point of
trying to end budget deficits?
</P>
<P>
   - Sports fans who resent the antics of Dennis Rodman fail to
appreciate how his genius for marketing himself makes him a
legitimate candidate for a case study by the Harvard Business
School.
</P>
<P>
   - If a company appreciates my patronage enough to want to send
me a ``free'' gift, they'd better appreciate me enough to be
willing to pay the postage and handling costs involved in sending
it.
</P>
<P>
   - You're getting old if you can remember when most cars had
white-sidewall tires.
</P>
<P>
   - Would somebody tell the technical people at KCTV not to put
the weather watch graphic over the ``Wheel of Fortune'' puzzles?
</P>
<P>
   - If somebody gets a cell phone call at a restaurant on a
weekend night, it's hard to resist the notion that they've asked
somebody to ring them up so they can appear important.
</P>
<P>
   - The only really interesting aspect of the World Cup soccer
tournament has been the dustups by the fans.
</P>
<P>
   - When you see how Kansas income tax revenue is soaring, the
thought occurs that the state should adopt the song with the
refrain ``Workin' for the Man'' as its official anthem.
</P>
<P>
   - One of my main goals in life is to never spend more than
$39.95 on a pair of what my generation calls ``tennis'' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   - While the odds against winning the lottery are long, they
aren't impossibly long because /{somebody/} always wins sooner or
later.
</P>
<P>
   - Whatever happened to Atlee Hammaker?
</P>
<P>
   - Those who have nothing better to worry about than the
environmental consequences of complimentary shampoo bottles in
hotel and motel rooms have too much free time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   - Somebody tell ``Chain Saw Al'' Dunlap he would have been
smarter to wait until after he retired to write /{Mean Business/},
his autobiographical encomium to himself.
</P>
<P>
   - What's wrong with the Learning Channel running
Anheuser-Busch's beer history docu-mercial?
</P>
<P>
   - College baseball will continue to be a national sports joke
until its stewards decide to go back to wooden bats.
</P>
<P>
   - What law of the universe dictates that the telephone call
you're waiting to be returned always will come while you've stepped
away from your desk?
</P>
<P>
   - The more advertising inserts a magazine has cluttering its
innards, the less interesting its editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   - The apparent success of those multimedia Rambo-style marketing
blitzes by golf club manufacturers selling miracle clubs represents
the ultimate triumph of hope over experience.
</P>
<P>
   - Wake me when the NBA lockout is over.
</P>
<P>
   - Were local bankers kidding when they said federal banking
regulations from the Depression era prevented them from closing for
a three-day July Fourth holiday weekend?
</P>
<P>
   - Sam's Town as a name for a casino never did make sense.
</P>
<P>
   - Did anyone notice when Congress recently bumped up the
national debt limit by $400 billion, to $5.95 trillion?
</P>
</TEXT>
