<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACTOR-MAKER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLAN CORP., A TRACTOR MANUFACTURER, GETS BIG JOBS DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ When it comes to moving the biggest and
heaviest commercial loads, standard tractors just don't make the
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes. Ammunition. Auto parts. They all have to be hauled
somewhere. And every day, across the world, tractors designed and
built at Harlan Corp. in Kansas City, Kan., are getting the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   These are no ordinary tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines such as American and Qantas use Harlan tractors to push
aircraft and pull baggage trailers. Auto manufacturers such as
General Motors, Ford and Chrysler use Harlan tractors to transport
parts. A Las Vegas casino recently ordered a Harlan tractor to move
large trees and plants in an atrium.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government uses hundreds of Harlan tractors. The
military uses them to move supplies and nudge fighter planes out of
their hangars. NASA uses them in its work, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian air force has 250 Harlan tractors, and the
country's army recently purchased 18 to supplies and munitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll find Harlan tractors on all fronts,'' said Stephen
Jacobs, a program analyst for the U.S. Defense Logistics Agency. In
fact, Harlan machines are used by airlines, businesses and
governments in 80 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Company founder Jim Kaplan first demonstrated a talent for
tinkering more than 50 years ago by transforming scrap parts and a
washing machine motor into a motorcycle. The motorcycle is history,
but since then Kaplan has managed to steer Harlan from a small
surplus business into a company of international reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan, which employs 106 persons in its Kansas City, Kan.,
plant and a half-dozen in its China offices, celebrates its 40th
anniversary this year. Kaplan is currently chairman of the company;
his son Jamie Kaplan is president; and John Revere, whose career
includes a stint as a Chrysler executive, is chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kaplan established the company as a seller of surplus items,
including forklift parts. But the focus changed in 1962 when a
company forklift was severely damaged and a forklift company gave
no guarantee about the cost of repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan rebuilt the forklift himself. That work was seen by
another company, which then asked him to rebuild other forklifts.
That led to a request by a GM executive for Harlan to supply
forklifts to area plants. Kaplan rented forklifts, then leased them
to GM.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing an opportunity, Harlan soon was making parts for
forklifts. Today, Harlan is a leading parts supplier to forklift
manufacturers such as Clark and Caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   From this opportunity came a greater opportunity. Forklifts,
Kaplan pointed out, are cousins to the type of tractors that move
aircraft at airports. So in the early 1970s, Kaplan decided to
undercut competitors in that very market.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kaplan said, the company is poised for growth and he
expects it to bring in $100 million in annual sales within four
years. Last year, sales were up nearly 50 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly line currently makes two tractors a day, with plans
to increase production to eight tractors a day.
</P>
<P>
   The tractors are about the size of a compact car. One model is
4.5 feet wide and nearly 10 feet long. But small doesn't mean
lightweight. Because they're built to move heavy loads, the
tractors must be heavy to transport and stop the loads.
</P>
<P>
   The largest and newest model is made with slabs of steel up to 8
inches thick. That model weighs 14 tons. Other models start at
6,000 pounds. A Harlan tractor costs $20,000 to $60,000, depending
on the model.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the engine and transmission, the Harlan plant makes
all the parts for the tractors. And the company plans to soon begin
manufacturing the tractor's transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The work is done by a diverse work force that includes Russians,
Cambodians and Vietnamese. Recently, two Bosnian refugees came to
work for Harlan.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring refugees and immigrants has become something of a
tradition at Harlan in part because Jim Kaplan's grandparents
emigrated from Russia in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hire them because we were once immigrants, too,'' Kaplan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The tractors are fitted with diesel, electric or gasoline
engines and fitted with other options ordered by customers _
including seat belts, turn signals, even air-conditioned cabs.
 &LR; brk:Getting the job done  &LR; tx:Then there are the special touches
that have helped burnish Harlan's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say they go out of their way,'' said Jacobs of the
U.S. Defense Logistics Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Air Force, for example, likes a special pivot hitch
that allows one person to attach a load to the tractor. Once the
government asked for tractors to be sent to Alaska with snowplows.
They got them.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian army recently asked for tractors that could safely
go into underground munitions bunkers and be powerful enough to
move over difficult terrain when they left the warehouse. The
specially built Harlan tractors have electric and diesel engines,
which the driver can switch between, depending on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Harlan can cater to these requests is because it
makes the parts, Kaplan said. The Las Vegas casino order, for
example, required a tractor that could move with a heavy load at a
low speed up an incline. Harlan made a drive axle that could handle
the stress of that assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to build and design tractors also allows Harlan to
go after more civilian business _ in particular, supplying tractors
for airlines. Harlan has about five to 10 percent of the market for
these type of tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Properly powered tractors are a crucial concern for airlines as
they strive for on-time performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that people take for granted, but I'm in the
middle of it and I can't,'' said Bob Cool, national manager for
ground support for Continental Express, a subsidiary of Continental
Airlines. MORE
</P>
<P>
   Continental Express recently needed tractors that could push at
least 50,000 pounds, and much more in inclement weather. Large
tractors made by Harlan competitors would do the job but at a cost
near $100,000. The smaller Harlan tractors then being made were
cheaper but not large enough.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan ended up designing a tractor to push the load and still
save Continental money.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the company expects to bring in even more
civilian orders while not ignoring its government work, said Jamie
Kaplan. That means more Harlan models to meet various types of
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest renditions has features such as high-low beam
headlights and a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really slick tractors,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
