<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-CHILDREN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN FROM BELARUS ARRIVE IN U.S. FOR MEDICAL AND DENTAL CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Olga Borisova is a child of Chernobyl. The
world's worst nuclear disaster occurred when she was seven months
old, in 1986. Seventy percent of the radioactive fallout drifted
her way, to Belarus, a small country 75 miles north of Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   Now Olga deals with the aftereffects: a contaminated land where
food, air and water are suspect. Her village of 700 people, Maisky,
has only two stores, both general stores, and one automobile for
everyone. ``It is difficult'' there, a translator says.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, when Olga arrived at Kansas City International
Airport, she weighed 80 pounds. On Thursday, at the doctor's office
in Kansas City, the 12-year-old was up to 89 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good!'' exclaimed Olga's host mother, Sharol Young of
Lee's Summit, Mo. She gave the girl a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Olga is taking part in the ``Children of Chernobyl'' program
sponsored by Project Restoration, a non-profit group started in
1994 by Laurann Schlapper of Merriam to help Belarussians. Eleven
other youngsters from Belarus, ages 10 to 12, also are here.
</P>
<P>
   The children are receiving medical and dental care, taking a
respite from low-level radiation and reveling in swimming pools,
stuff they can buy at stores and newfound friends. All of them got
their medical checkups at Pediatric Associates in Kansas City; the
final four children got their checkups Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are slender but not terribly malnourished and
otherwise seem to be in good spirits,'' said Michael Kasper, the
physician who has examined all the children.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Chernobyl, he said, the children have weakened immune
systems and are at increased risk for various cancers, particularly
thyroid cancer. All the children checked out fairly well, he said.
One girl had an enlarged thyroid; she will see another doctor about
that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the World Health Organization reported that thyroid
cancer among children had increased 200-fold since the disaster in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Olga and two other girls who visited Kasper's office Thursday
seemed to be having a fine time together in the waiting room. They
stood next to each other, two of them holding hands, all of them
smiling broadly.
</P>
<P>
   All their clothes were new, they said through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   The children arrived in Kansas City with very little, said
Young, Olga's host mother. It took Olga a while to adjust, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ```She wouldn't eat or drink anything the first 48 hours we had
her,'' Young said. ``I cried, she cried, my daughters cried. It
broke our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Young's husband called a friend who lives in the
Ukraine. The friend told Olga that the Youngs wanted to be her
friends and that she should drink the juice they wanted to give
her. Olga did. Then he asked her to tell him what she wanted next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hot dogs, no bun and mashed potatoes,'' was her reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got that for her and after that everything was just fine,''
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year that Project Restoration has brought
children from Belarus to Kansas City. Last year's group received
prosthetic limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Schlapper became interested in Belarus after visiting the
country in 1991 on a mission trip. Operating from her home, she has
persuaded individuals and groups to donate services, products and
money.
</P>
<P>
   Families on both sides of the state line are acting as hosts to
the children this year, she said, and many in the medical and
dental field have offered their services free. St. Luke's Hospital
is providing free labwork and free physicals for the two
translators who accompanied the children.
</P>
<P>
   Schlapper said some families in Belarus are so poor that they
cannot afford toothbrushes or must use the same one for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven-year-old Yulia Alekhina had 18 cavities, Schlapper said,
and she was scheduled for four extractions today, which she didn't
know about Thursday. Through a translator, Yulia said she brushes
her teeth twice a day and doesn't know why she needs so much dental
work.
</P>
<P>
   Does she like going to the dentist?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said. Is she afraid of the dentist? ``I'm not
afraid,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The children will leave July 16 to return to Belarus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
