<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANCIENT-SANDAL-KAN &LR;      07-03 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCIENT-SANDAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR LEADS TEAM THAT ANALYZES 8,300 YEAR-OLD SANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHASHANK BENGALI  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Using a cutting-edge carbon dating technique, a
University of Missouri-Columbia researcher has determined that a
prehistoric sandal is more than 8,300 years old, making it the
oldest shoe discovered east of the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Brien, a professor of anthropology, led a team that
studied six sandals in the university's collection that were
excavated between the mid-1950s and 1981 in central Missouri's
Callaway County.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent shoe was determined to be about 800 years old.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the findings, detailed in this week's issue of
Science, shed light on the resourcefulness of early inhabitants of
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This very early shoe construction shows how people were making
use of environmental resources,'' he said. ``And it shows that the
knowledge to build shoes is ancient.''
</P>
<P>
   The sandals, especially the more recent ones, were built much as
they are today, with support for the heel and toes connected by a
softer sole.
</P>
<P>
   And like their modern-day descendants, prehistoric Midwesterners
wore their shoes until they fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoes in our collection are worn out in the same places as
today's shoes: on the heels and the balls of the feet,'' O'Brien
said. ``And many of them have been repaired.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandal makers then favored a native plant called the
``rattlesnake master,'' a relatively durable weaving material.
</P>
<P>
   The finding is significant for this part of the continent,
O'Brien said, but older artifacts have been discovered west of the
Rockies on the Colorado Plateau, where the arid environment is more
favorable to preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The university's collection of 35 ancient shoes had for almost
two decades sat on display in an archaeological museum.
Researchers, though long eager to determine the shoes' age, didn't
think they would withstand the rigorous dating process.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien's team took advantage of a technique called
accelerator mass spectrometry, which requires just a thread to be
taken from the material, as opposed to the several grams that
less-advanced carbon dating methods need.
</P>
<P>
   The technique was developed in the mid-1980s to date the Shroud
of Turin, the cloth that some believe Jesus Christ was wrapped in
after the Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   For the dating process, the team selected six shoes from the
collection that represented different types of construction.
O'Brien said they were in somewhat poor condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sandals are perishable, and the fact that we had any
material at all was really good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said there are no plans to date any of the other shoes
in the university's collection. The process is expensive, costing
$600 per shoe.
</P>
<P>
   The next task for O'Brien's team is creating a database on this
and similar cultural construction materials.
</P>
<P>
   Although pleased with the findings, O'Brien is keeping them in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the cure for cancer,'' he said, ``but a lot of people
are interested in prehistory. It shows that ancient peoples weren't
that different, in a lot of ways, from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
