<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GOVERNOR SIGNS BILL TO KEEP SEX PREDATORS IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Murder victim Stephanie Schmidt would have
turned 25 on July 4. And Thursday, with July 4 approaching, her
parents watched the signing of a new law giving Missouri some of
the toughest sexual-predator laws in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan signed a bill to allow the state to keep
``sexually violent predators'' confined beyond their prison
sentences if they seem inclined to repeat their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is called ``Stephanie's Law'' in remembrance of the
former Pittsburg State University student and Leawood resident who
was murdered by an ex-convict and repeat sex offender five years
ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy and Gene Schmidt crusaded successfully for laws that allow
Missouri and Kansas to keep predators confined longer than their
prison sentences and to require released predators to register
their whereabouts. Missouri passed predator laws in 1996 and this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this legislation, I think we now have the strongest
one-two punch in the country in dealing with sexual predators,''
House Speaker Steve Gaw said Thursday of the two recent Missouri
laws. Gaw credited the Schmidts for changes in Missouri and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have turned their tragedy into something positive so that
others may not have to go through what they did,'' Gaw said. ``It's
a good day for Missouri families and for safer streets and safer
homes in our state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schmidts said they are working in eight other states to pass
laws similar to those in Missouri and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of states are taking baby steps,'' Peggy Schmidt said
after the bill-signing. ``We say, `Why do you want to do that?'
We're talking about saving lives. Missouri is taking giant steps.''
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 of the approximately 24,000 prison inmates in
Missouri are confined for sex-related crimes, said Corrections
Director Dora Schriro.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, a committee appointed by mental health and
corrections officials would review an inmate's record before the
person's scheduled release.
</P>
<P>
   If the inmate is deemed to have a ``mental abnormality'' that
will continue to make that person a violent sexual predator, the
state's attorney general could seek to have a judge order the
detainment and treatment of the offender. The court would then
conduct an annual review of the committed person's case. If there
is sufficient progress in the opinion of state mental health
officials, then the person could be released.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the law say it could punish people for crimes they
may or not commit in the future, but the U.S. Supreme Court last
year upheld the law in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill said it would make predators more likely
to seek treatment so they can be released when their sentences end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation provides a legally sound, very structured
system for identifying potentially violent sexual predators and
assuring they remain away from Missouri citizens, particularly our
children,'' Carnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had strong support from Republicans and Democrats,
including co-sponsor Rep. Carson Ross, a Republican from Blue
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the father of three daughters and the grandfather of
five,'' Ross said. ``This is important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of Stephanie's death and her birthday are only
three days apart. The Schmidts said the week is always difficult
but that this year it was special because of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reliving of the tragedy happens every year this time of
year,'' Gene Schmidt said. ``I don't know if the reliving of it is
(as important) as doing something about it so that it doesn't
happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
