<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAK ROLLS ON WHILE LOPEZ MAKES EXIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.C., S.Korea)  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ For Se Ri Pak, Friday's round was another
impressive performance by an extraordinary 20-year-old from South
Korea who seems to save her best golf for the biggest tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   For Nancy Lopez, Friday ended with a tearful goodbye, her
career-long quest to win a U.S. Women's Open still unfulfilled
after a horrific 12-over-par 83 sent her home for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was that type of roller-coaster day at the Open, with a few
high moments and many high scores. Double-bogeys and 3-putts were
plentiful. Subpar rounds were precious commodities. And, as the
pressure mounts, with pin placements expected to get tougher at the
already challenging Blackwolf Run course, whoever wins the
tournament may do it over par.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a 1-under-par 70, and threatening to win her
second consecutive major, Pak was the clubhouse leader by one
stroke at 3 under par (139) when second-round play was suspended by
darkness. Liselotte Neumann, who also shot 70 Friday, was in second
place at 140 and Brenda Corrie Kuehn, an amateur from Fletcher,
N.C., shared third place with Chris Johnson, Mhairi McKay, and
Dottie Pepper at even par (142).
</P>
<P>
   There was a 51-minute suspension because of lightning in the
area, and 21 players were still on the course when play was halted.
The second round will be completed Saturday morning. After the
second round, the 36-hole cut will be made, and when Friday's play
ended the projected cut was 8 over par (150).
</P>
<P>
   Pak and Neumann were the only players under par when play ended,
as one by one, competitors were foiled by undulating greens that
made putting and approach shots tricky and treacherous. Laura
Davies, who started tied for the lead with Kim Williams, shot a
4-over 75, falling to 1 over for the tournament. Williams fell out
of contention with a horrendous 81, while Pat Hurst, who started
the day at 2 under, shot a 75.
</P>
<P>
   But Pak played like a seasoned veteran, putting together a
steady round that featured three birdies and two bogeys. Having
already won the LPGA McDonald's Open in May, Pak could become the
first woman to win back-to-back majors since Meg Mallon won the
LPGA Championship and the Open in 1991. Pak could also become the
first rookie to win two majors in the same year since 1984, when
Juli Inkster won the Nabisco Dinah Shore and the du Maurier
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel nervous,'' said Pak, who said she enjoyed playing
in front of Friday's gallery, estimated at more than 25,000 by the
U.S. Golf Association, setting a record for Friday. ``I feel
confident.'
</P>
<P>
   Lopez meanwhile handled her worst round at an Open with the
class that has made her the most popular player in women's golf.
With Lopez's huge gallery watching in disbelief but still cheering
as she approached each green, she found it even more difficult to
show her anger.
</P>
<P>
   After making par on the first four holes, Lopez shot 11 over par
during the next eight holes, and never made better than a bogey.
From the fifth hole through the 12th hole, Lopez's card read bogey,
double-bogey, bogey, bogey, double-bogey, double-bogey, bogey,
bogey.
</P>
<P>
   With her playing partners, Mallon (11 over) and Jane Geddes (15
over) also struggling, the disappointed threesome made light of
their plight as they approached the 18th green, holding their
putters aloft with a towel attached to the top, giving the
white-flag surrender sign. The crowd gave them a standing ovation,
but after her 22nd attempt to win the Open without a victory, Lopez
cried, knowing she had no chance to make the cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
