<HEADLINE>
ARRESTED SENATOR BLAMES OFFICER FOR SCUFFLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ada Smith, the veteran New York state senator whose
occasionally erratic behavior has sometimes overshadowed her
political work, on Friday denied biting a police officer as he
tried to arrest her in Brooklyn, instead accusing the officer of
roughing her up and making racial comments.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said she planned to file a lawsuit against the city
and a complaint with the Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I can be boisterous and loud, but this time I was
dumbfounded,'' Ms. Smith said Friday. ``He threw me against the car
and I was handcuffed. I was told by witnesses that I was hit in the
face. The handcuffs were so tight that they cut off the circulation
to my left hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said the officer, Seth Kaufman, who is white, also
made disparaging remarks about Puerto Ricans. Ms. Smith is a
light-skinned African-American.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that Kaufman sprayed Ms. Smith with Chemical
Mace and handcuffed her during the exchange at an intersection at 8
p.m. Thursday. They said Ms. Smith had become annoyed at the
officer and his partner, Michael Nemes, as they questioned the
driver of the car ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith was charged with resisting arrest, a misdemeanor
punishable by up to a year in jail, and with disorderly conduct and
failing to comply with a lawful order, both violations punishable
by up to 15 days in jail, said Detective Joseph Pentangelo, a
department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Smith, who represents parts of Brooklyn and Queens, gave
a drastically different account of the altercation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not bite Officer Kaufman,'' Ms. Smith said in a
telephone interview Friday. ``I'm still waiting to see these teeth
marks. If I bit him, don't you think he would have gone to the
hospital to get some medical attention?''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman refused medical attention from emergency workers who
arrived at the scene that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who in 1988 became one of two black elected state
senators and who once served as an aide to former Rep. Shirley
Chisholm, has earned a reputation for being somewhat volatile,
mostly with staff members. But she is also known among colleagues
in Albany for her high attendance rate and her committee work on
education, criminal justice and women's health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whom Ms. Smith endorsed over Democratic
mayoral candidate Ruth Messinger last fall, and Martin Conner, the
Senate minority leader, of Brooklyn, declined to comment on the
incident Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police account, Ms. Smith became upset when she
was stopped behind another car whose driver was being questioned by
Kaufman and Nemes. Ms. Smith, who was driving her private car, a
1987 black Lincoln Continental with state Senate license plates,
told the officers they were blocking traffic and demanded that they
move.
</P>
<P>
   An argument followed, and when the officers asked Ms. Smith to
produce her driver's license and registration, she refused,
Pentangelo said. She then refused to step out of her car, and when
Kaufman attempted to pull her out, she bit him on the hand, the
detective said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Smith gave this account: She was on her way home from a
butcher shop when she saw the police cruiser ahead with flashing
red and yellow lights. She pulled over to the side of the street
because she was unable to pass the cruiser. After Kaufman had
finished questioning the driver of the other car, he walked to her
car and asked if she was trying to intimidate or distract him from
his duties. When she explained that she could not pass his cruiser,
an argument ensued and the officer demanded her license and
registration. She refused, saying that he knew who she was, because
he had referred to her by name.
</P>
<P>
   The officer grew more argumentative, Ms. Smith said, and tried
to pull her through the car window. She said he then opened her car
door, sprayed her with Chemical Mace and handcuffed her.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said Friday that she did not deserve her reputation
for being erratic and difficult to work with. She said some of the
stories told about her were untrue or had been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 she was accused of threatening an aide with a knife. In
1995 she reportedly refused to move out of a district office,
though the lease was up and the state had stopped paying rent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, at a Black and Puerto Rican Legislative Caucus campaign
reception, she threw a cup of coffee at a former campaign worker
for Mayor David Dinkins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
