<HEADLINE>
GARDNER PATTERSON, 82, EX-WORLD TRADE OFFICIAL  
 FRANK GOFFIO, 82, EX-LEADER OF CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.J., Conn., Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Gardner Patterson, a prominent trade economist and a prolific
writer who helped negotiate several important international
treaties, died at his home in Washington, on June 26. He was 82.
 &HT;    Patterson died from lymphoma.
 &HT;    A native of Burt, Iowa, Patterson had a doctorate in economics
from Harvard University.
 &HT;    In 1946, at the age of 30, Patterson was one of two advisers to
a currency committee that took control of Greece's imports and
exports. He left that post in 1949 to become a professor of
economics at Princeton University.
 &HT;    While teaching at Princeton, Patterson served in various roles
on U.S. government economic missions in Tunisia and Turkey and was
a consultant to the State Department. He became director of the
Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs at
Princeton in 1958.
 &HT;    Patterson left Princeton in 1965 to become deputy director
general of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or GATT, in
Geneva, now the World Trade Organization. He returned to Princeton
two years later, but in 1969 he went back to GATT as director
general for trade policy.
 &HT;    He retired from GATT in 1981 and moved to Washington, although
he remained actively involved with the organization, assisting in
the resolution of four international trade disputes before the
group.
 &HT;    Patterson wrote several books, including a number of editions of
the ``Survey of United States International Finance'' and more than
63 articles on international economic issues.
 &HT;    He is survived by his wife of 57 years, Evelyn, and one
daughter, Eliza Patterson.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Goffio, a former executive director of CARE who helped
shape its present mission of sending disaster relief and assistance
for self-help projects to the far corners of the world, died on
June 27 at a nursing home in Avon, Conn. He was 82 and lived in
Farmington, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Goffio retired in 1972, after 17 years as executive director.
Altogether he spent 30 years at CARE, the Cooperative for American
Relief Everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit and nonsectarian, the organization began its work in
1945, with a shipment of CARE Packages to war-ravaged Europe. It
soon extended a helping hand to the hungry in underdeveloped
regions of Africa, Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   During Goffio's tenure, CARE became one of the world's largest
international relief and development organizations, with an annual
budget of some $350 million to help people recover from disaster.
Goffio took the lead in making self-help projects a priority and
putting a food-for-work concept into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Goffio was a native of New York.
</P>
<P>
   His survivors include his wife of 57 years, Evelyn Wilburger
Goffio; a daughter, Christine May of Melrose, Mass.; and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-98 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
