<HEADER>
A0090 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-03 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERILOUS FIGHT VS. SINGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The national anthem survived Jose Feliciano, whose
Latin jazz stylings at a World Series 30 years ago sent
traditionalists into apoplexy. It survived Roseanne, whose
rendition at a San Diego Padres game was too ghastly to relive
here, and Lucy ``Xena'' Lawless, whose display at an Anaheim Mighty
Ducks playoff game wasn't ghastly at all.
</P>
<P>
   It survived Johnny Paycheck (``What so loudly we sang, as the
daylight's last cleaning...!''), Willie Nelson, Bobby Vinton, Carl
Lewis and the famously forgetful Robert Goulet. It survived Stevie
Ray Vaughn, who sang the anthem before a Dodgers game at the
Houston Astrodome while accompanying himself on air guitar. It
survived Tommie Smith's and John Carlos' political protest and
Mahmoud Abdul-Rauf's religious stand _ or sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' is a tough old guy, like the
Star-Spangled Banner, tattered and powder-burned but still waving.
</P>
<P>
   But now on the Fourth of July, the question to ponder is whether
the anthem can survive all the nameless, faceless ``recording
artists,'' off-Broadway actors, players' wives and screeching
7-year-olds whose oh-so-personal interpretations cause ears to
bleed and eyes to roll in stadiums and arenas from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame singers who pull a Goulet and forget the words are only
amusements, not the real threats to the anthem. The real threats
are all the wannabe Barbra Streisands and Lou Rawlses who treat
their moments at midcourt as personal auditions. It's not unusual
to see the too-cool anthem singers at Lakers games walk off the
court and into the stands with a stack of business cards to hand
out to music-industry executives.
</P>
<P>
   Is this just nostalgia, or didn't the anthem always used to be
sung by Robert Merrill or Kate Smith or somebody else of stature,
not by any garage band looking for a break?
</P>
<P>
   I make no claim to have conducted scientific research on the
subject, but in 15 years of listening to anthems from press boxes
and press rows, I'd estimate that a patriotic 76 percent of singers
find some way to screw it up.
</P>
<P>
   A sportswriter friend of mine agreed, saying, ``Jose Feliciano
never knew what a disservice he was doing'' in 1968 when he
pioneered the do-it-your-way approach to honoring the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing that fans stand still for it.
</P>
<P>
   An admission of some hypocrisy: I don't sing along with the
anthem and I don't always pay rapt attention to it, although I do
always stand up for it. I'll chat with a neighbor, write the
lineups on a scorecard, or mark the scratches in a racetrack
program.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not one of those people who, at the sound of the ``Oh
say...,'' stop walking in the middle of a ballpark parking lot and
face a flag they can't even see with hands on their hearts. A rule
to live by: If you can't see the flag, you aren't obligated to
salute.
</P>
<P>
   It's partly a generational thing, most of those who do sing
along have literally been through the wars. And, if I may shift the
blame, it's largely because the performers and the teams that hire
them demand so little respect.
</P>
<P>
   If the playing and singing of the anthem were truly a patriotic
occasion, instead of a publicity stunt for the cast of ``Smokey
Joe's Cafe,'' a lot of people like me would show more reverence.
</P>
<P>
   There are two possible solutions to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Stop playing the anthem before every sports event, a ritual that
apparently began with major-league baseball during World War II.
Make it special again by saving it for national holidays _ today,
for one _ and truly national events like Super Bowls, World Series,
Indy 500s and U.S. soccer coach firings.
</P>
<P>
   Or raise the standards for anthem singers. Establish some rules:
</P>
<P>
   __ If celebrities are going to be allowed a microphone, make
sure they're real celebrities with reputations to lose if they mess
up.
</P>
<P>
   __ Every anthem singer must carry to the mike an index card with
the lyrics printed on it, just in case. Anybody who's too proud to
do that is too self-centered for the job.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a ``perilous fight,'' not a ``perolis night,'' as half
the anthem singers seem to think. !arrow!!off!Remember, it's a
90-second song. Maximum: two minutes. You don't get paid by the
note, so see if you can chop a few syllables out of ``Oho say does
thahat star-spahanguhulled bahaneher yehet waihahaihave oer the
lahand of the freeheeheehee and the hooome of thuhuhuhuhuh
brahahahave!''
</P>
<P>
   __ No sound effects. At Edison Field, they set off fireworks,
``bombs bursting in air,'' jolting singers into sour notes and
introducing younger fans to the concept of shell shock.
</P>
<P>
   __ Singers should not bow, say ``thank you'' for applause or
wave to the crowd. ``Hello, Cleveland!'' is inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   __ In short, adopt the philosophy of the Los Angeles Kings, who
review tapes and preseason auditions, according to media-relations
director Mike Altieri, with a preference for those who ``just get
up there, sing the song, and sing it the way it's supposed to be
sung.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Remember: The anthem is not about you. Want to impress the
impresario in the front row? Just sing the blessed song crisply and
clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Leave your personal flair at home, right next to your business
cards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
