<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CLINTON-1STLD-W     07-03 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRAISES JIANG AS LEADER WHO COULD BRING CHINA TO
DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add graphics note; and to fix pick-up words between
takes.)   (ART ADV.: a graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling 212
556-4204.) 
 (ps) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton Friday called Jiang Zemin, the
president of China, a visionary leader who could be the figure who
brings China to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a news conference that closed his nine-day trip to
China, gave what amounted to a vigorous personal endorsement of the
Chinese president, saying Jiang had the imagination needed to
transform China from a single-party Communist state to a
pluralistic democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The president also praised Premier Zhu Rongji, architect of
China's current economic policies, saying, ``There's a very good
chance that China has the right leadership at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has sounded increasingly hopeful about China's future as
his trip progressed, offering his most optimistic assessment of the
nation's political prospects just before departing to return to
Washington to celebrate Independence Day. But Clinton's words could
come back to haunt him should repression in China harden, leaving
Clinton open to the charges that he was taken in by a seemingly
open Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there will ever be democracy in China, Clinton
said, ``Oh, yes. I believe there can be, and I believe there will
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what I would like to see is the present government, headed
by this president and this premier, who are clearly committed to
reform, ride the wave of change and take China fully into the 21st
century and basically dismantle the resistance to it,'' he added.
``I believe they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The president answered questions for 43 minutes, most of them on
his trip to China but others touching on the troubled Japanese
economy, the prospect of violence in Ireland this weekend and the
continuing ethnic bloodshed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered an overwhelmingly positive summation of his
five-city journey through China.
</P>
<P>
   He said that profound differences remained between China on the
United States on questions of individual liberty, and he warned
that powerful forces still oppose change here.
</P>
<P>
   But he defended his engagement with the Chinese leadership as
the course most likely to yield progress on a range of issues from
human rights to the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The coming months and years will tell whether these few days in
early summer were the beginning of a positive new epoch in
relations between the United States and China or merely a sidestep
in an ambiguous relationship. There are groups in both countries
with a political investment in confrontation rather than
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Clinton and Jiang say or do as their nations' leaders,
they are but one part of a complex interplay between two diverse
and dynamic societies, a nexus that will be shaped as much by
transnational corporations, the media, the church, and even the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried to reflect that diversity in his appearances here,
meeting with villagers, middle-class homeowners, young
entrepreneurs, scholars and students.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the president's schedule was any session with
outspoken opponents of the government. Clinton defended that
decision Friday, saying that he sought to deal with human rights
concerns in China ``in a way most likely to yield progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my best to meet with people who represented all elements
of Chinese society,'' Clinton said. ``The decisions I made on this
trip _ and, I remind you, the first trip by an American president
in a decade _ about with whom to meet and how to handle it were
basically designed, were based on my best judgment about what would
be most effective in expanding human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have said that Clinton did not want to
risk retaliation against those who met with him and that he
believed that pressing Jiang to release groups of political
prisoners would be more effective than a theatrical encounter with
dissidents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, looking weary from a grueling schedule, said in his
opening remarks that his trip to China _ the longest of his
presidency to a single country _ had shown him ``the glory of
China's past in Xian, the vibrancy of its present in Beijing and
the promise of its future in Shanghai and Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone who was on this trip could fail to
appreciate the remarkable transformation that is underway in China,
as well as the distance still to be traveled,'' the president said
in the news conference, held in the ballroom of the Grand Hyatt
hotel in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly was struck by the city's wealth and vitality, and
said the region, which reverted to Chinese control just a year ago,
could be the model of China's development.
</P>
<P>
   He gave his most extensive assessment of Jiang and Zhu, praising
them in elaborate language.
</P>
<P>
   The president said of Jiang: ``After I met with him for the
first time, I felt very strongly that his chances of becoming the
leader of China for a sustained period were quite good because he's
a man of extraordinary intellect, very high energy, a lot of vigor
for his age, or indeed for any age. And I think he has a quality
that is profoundly important at this moment in history when there's
so much change going on. He has a good imagination. He has vision.
He can visualize. He can imagine a future that is different from
the present.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton acknowledged that Jiang has
``constituencies'' who oppose him and who distrust U.S. motives in
engaging China.
</P>
<P>
   To them, Clinton said: ``I hope more of them understand that
America wishes China well, that we are not bent on containing China
and that our human rights policy is not an excuse for some larger
strategic motive. It's what we really believe. We believe it's
morally right, and we believe it's best for them as a practical
matter over the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to another question, he noted that ``democracy is a
universal aspiration,'' an answer to Jiang's assertion that China's
history and culture have led it to different definitions of human
rights from those accepted in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The president welcomed the recent release of several well-known
dissidents, but said that he now looked to Beijing to release whole
classes of prisoners. He particularly cited the 150 people still
held on charges related to the Tiananmen Square democracy
demonstrations that were brutally put down by the government in
June 1989. He also called on Beijing to release an unknown number
of prisoners held for political activities that the government has
declared no longer criminal.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had raised with Jiang charges that China imposes
abortion on women to enforce China's one-child policy. ``They all
say the same thing,'' Clinton said. ``They say that that is not
Chinese policy, and it violates Chinese policy.'' Clinton added
that his view was that ``there may be an insufficient monitoring of
what's being done beyond the capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offended many in Taiwan this week when he repeated
Beijing's preferred formulation of U.S. policy toward Taiwan, which
Beijing considers a breakaway province. But he defended his
decision, saying that he had not changed the substance of U.S.
policy, which is to oppose Taiwanese independence and support
peaceful reunification with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I did the right thing,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question from a reporter from the Irish Times,
Clinton deplored the recent burnings of churches in Ireland and
called for high-level talks among Catholic, Protestant and British
authorities in advance of the annual sectarian marches scheduled
for this weekend that have led to violence in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered tempered praise for a package of banking and
financial reforms announced by Tokyo in recent days. He said that
Japan's economy had substantial underlying strength and expressed
hope that the recession there would bottom out soon and growth
would resume ``in a reasonable amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   On Kosovo, the president offered nothing beyond a hope that
Belgrade would show restraint. ``There is some uncertainty about
who is willing and who is not willing to even negotiate about it,''
Clinton said. ``And we're working on it as best we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
