<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLING ON DESPITE BRUISES  
 TRIP TO FLORIDA FOR WILLIAMS  
 ROUGH GOING FOR IRABU 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees carried a 58-20 record, some bumps and
bruises and a thinner roster into Friday night's series opener with
the Baltimore Orioles at Yankee Stadium. But as usual this season,
they were also on the verge of reaching another milestone.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees were to sweep Baltimore this weekend, as they did
in May, they would enter the All-Star Game break with a 61-20
record and match the best 81-game mark this century, shared by the
1902 Pittsburgh Pirates and the 1907 Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Yankees were to win half of the 84 games that
remained before Friday night's contest, going 42-42, they would
reach 100 victories for the first time since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees were playing a few bodies short against the
Orioles Friday night, and Bernie Williams might still be a week
from returning from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' starting second baseman in all but
two games, was out of the lineup with a sore right knee. Knoblauch
slid hard into second base on a force play in the 10th inning
Thursday night against the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre and General Manager Brian Cashman said the
injury was not considered serious and they did not expect Knoblauch
to require an extensive examination. Torre indicated there was a
chance Knoblauch could play Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Bush, who normally starts in place of Knoblauch, returned
to his home in Illinois after learning that his father-in-law had
died. That made Luis Sojo the starter at second base, despite a
hyperextended left elbow, an injury he sustained while taking
batting practice Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Trip to Florida for Williams
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams took batting practice and ran the bases before
Friday night's game, and he is not quite at full speed. The plan
seems to be to send Williams to Florida and have him play at least
two games in the Florida State League, on an injury rehabilitation
assignment, on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams does well, he could be activated in time for the
series against Tampa Bay that starts Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rough Going for Irabu
</P>
<P>
   After an outing on Thursday in which Hideki Irabu gave up five
runs and failed to get an out in the fourth inning against the
Phillies, opposing batters have an .894 slugging percentage against
Irabu over the pitcher's last three starts, raising his ERA from
1.68 to 2.91.
</P>
<P>
   Torre and Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankee pitching coach, spoke with
Irabu before Friday night's game to explore reasons for the slump.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
