<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HULL-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL WILLING TO TRADE BIG STATS FOR CUP RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Is Brett Hull the missing piece for the Stars in
their search for a Stanley Cup?
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to think so.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who earlier in the playoffs accurately predicted a certain
defeat for the Stars in their series with the Detroit Red Wings,
had to eat his words yesterday. Then again, the gregarious Hull
never truly eats his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that because I know how good \Rthe Red Wings\S are, and
I also know how to beat them,'' Hull said after signing a
three-year, $17 million deal with the Stars. ``Hopefully, now we
can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cocky? Nah. Just good ol' Brett Hull honesty. Ask around the NHL
about the favorite to win the 1999 Stanley Cup, and Dallas has to
come up high on the list. And signing Hull is a big reason why.
</P>
<P>
   Hull has 554 career goals and 987 points in 801 games. Of those,
62 goals and 101 points have come against the Stars _ more than any
other team he has played against. A naturalized citizen of the
United States born in Belleville, Ontario, he has been a standout
performer in international competitions, including one of Team
USA's best players in the 1996 World Cup victory. He has never
played in a Stanley Cup Finals, but that's one reason, he said, he
joined the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to win and to be a champion,'' Hull said.
``They were as close as anybody to winning a Stanley Cup and to
have them want me to be a part of that I thought is a great
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions will, of course, come. Are the Stars now loaded
with too many stars? Will one puck be enough? Can Hull fit into
coach Ken Hitchcock's scheme, which calls for short shifts, rolling
four lines and everyone playing Q5 &LR; 9M? Will he be a distraction in
the locker room?
</P>
<P>
   All the answers yesterday were positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to win,'' center Guy Carbonneau said. ``Whatever you
want to say about Brett Hull, he's coming here because he wants to
win now. And that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau played one season with Hull for the Blues and said
Hull's reputation as outspoken or tough on management stemmed from
his role as an icon in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy. When he was in St. Louis, he took a lot of
blame for things simply because he was sticking up for other
players,'' Carbonneau said. ``He got into a lot of trouble because
he was constantly taking on management, but I don't see that
happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said he was ready to come in and be a piece in the Stars'
puzzle. He will no longer have to carry a franchise, simply help it
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how much I score, as long as we win,'' he said.
``I don't care if I play left wing, right wing or defense, as long
as we win.''
</P>
<P>
   He already is taking a step in the right direction. Hull has
worn No. 16 throughout his career, but said he had no intentions of
taking that number from Stars winger Pat Verbeek.
</P>
<P>
   ``New team, new house, new city, might as well make it a clean
start and get a new number, too,'' he said. ``I'll probably have my
wife pick it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that doesn't sound like the kind of guy who would be a
disturbance in any locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one has Brett Hull stories about things he's said or
done,'' said center Joe Nieuwendyk, who was Hull's linemate when
the two were rookies with the Calgary Flames in 1987. ``But the
bottom line is nobody wants to win more than Brett Hull. He plays a
lot harder than people give him credit for. He plays a lot better
defense than people give him credit for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll fit right in here,'' Nieuwendyk added. ``This
might be just what he needs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
