<SLUG> BC-BBA-GRIFFEY-CHASE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Stats lose luster for Griffey 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ken Griffey Jr. doesn't need the newspapers
to keep up with Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa. He also insists he
doesn't check out ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to do than watch television,'' Griffey said.
``I'd rather spend a couple hours talking on the telephone, or on
the computer, surfing the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey said he usually gets his updates on the Great Home Run
Chase from the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will bring radios to the game or see it on the
scoreboard and yell, `Hey, he hit another one!'' Griffey said.
``I'll just sit there and shrug my shoulders. What do you want me
to do about it? It's not like I'm the one throwing it up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The race to break Roger Maris' home-run record is going full
blast as baseball approaches the All-Star break. McGwire is leading
the field with 37 home runs, going into last night's game, but
Griffey is coming on strong. He came to Texas with 35, having hit
four in his past four games. Sosa, who set a major-league record
with 20 in June, has 33.
</P>
<P>
   All of baseball seems to be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, I keep up with it,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``I think it's great for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey insists he's not keeping up or getting excited by it.
His perception of the season to date is colored by what has
happened to the Mariners, a team that started the year with World
Series aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Those aspirations are fading as the summer progresses. A team
that won two division titles in the past three seasons entered a
three-game series with the Rangers in last place in the American
League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's frustrating,'' Griffey said. ``It would be
frustrating to anybody when they're doing what they like to be
doing and the team isn't doing what they're supposed to be doing,
and that's winning. I don't like to lose. Sometimes I have to when
I'm playing my son, but that's different. Other than that, I want
to win at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is not the only Mariners who feels that way. Shortstop
Alex Rodriguez, who will join Griffey in Colorado for the All-Star
Game, began last night's game hitting .310 with 27 home runs and 23
stolen bases. The possibility exists he could join Barry Bonds and
Jose Canseco in the exclusive ``40-40'' club for home runs and
stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez doesn't care, not when the Mariners are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Griffey Show, the Rodriguez Show or the Randy
Johnson Show,'' Rodriguez said. ``This is the Mariners Show. This
is about a team, not individuals. I get sick of people who look at
us as individuals and not as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Griffey, ``Do you see a calculator in my locker? I just go
out there, see the ball, hit it and run. I don't look at numbers.
That's for you guys sitting in your little offices, comparing who
is doing what and who's not doing what. I don't think there's
anyone in this locker room who has a stats book.''
</P>
<P>
   As for McGwire and Sosa, Griffey said, ``I don't care about
them. I don't care about anybody outside this locker room. What am
I supposed to do. Call up Dionne Warwick and find out when they're
going to hit another home run? I've got 24 guys I worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers might mean more if the Mariners were winning, and
both Griffey and Rodriguez insist it's not too late. The Mariners
remember 1995, when they made up 14 games in the second half of the
season and won their first division title by beating the Angels in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Rodriguez said. ``We still have three months of
baseball left. We've got a talented team, and there's great parity
in this division. Obviously, the Angels and Rangers have a great
advantage because they're so far ahead. But I don't think they're
in a position to take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners want to be in a pennant race. The Great Home Run
Chase holds no interest, particularly for the man involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win,'' Griffey said. ``What's so hard about that?
What's so hard about going out there, playing hard and winning?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
