<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SHAKE UP ORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ With his offense slumping to the offbeat tune
of a .176 batting average, manager Johnny Oates shook up both the
lineup and the pregame routine.
</P>
<P>
   He moved Will Clark from the No. 5 spot, where he had batted all
season, to No. 3. Clark was one of the few Rangers not slumping,
with a .444 batting average in his past seven games. Oates wanted
him batting in front of Juan Gonzalez, who had gone five games
without a run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will's been swinging the bat well, and Juan hasn't had a
chance to swing the bat with people on base lately,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Oates also moved Mark McLemore to leadoff and dropped Tom
Goodwin, who was batting .147 in his past 10 games, to ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The change in routine came when Oates elected to cancel outside
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to change it up, mix it up a little bit,''
Oates said.
Greer stays out
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer missed his third consecutive game because of a tight
left oblique muscle, which continues to heal slowly. Oates said if
Greer isn't ready today, he probably won't play until Friday in
Oakland, the Rangers' second game after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Even if healthy, the left-handed-hitting Greer wouldn't play
tomorrow against Mariners left-hander Randy Johnson. The Rangers
expect to face Athletics lefty Kenny Rogers on Thursday, the first
game after the break.
</P>
<P>
   There might come a time when Greer becomes a candidate for the
disabled list, but that decision wouldn't come until after the
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be that,'' Oates said. ``But I've said
that before and it ended up being that.''
Drew fallout
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals' signing of J.D. Drew figures to have an
impact on teams that haven't signed their first-round draft picks,
including the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will make it harder for everybody else to sign their
guys,'' Rangers general manager Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Pena, the 10th overall choice in the June draft, hasn't
responded to the Rangers' offer of a $1.35 million signing bonus.
His asking price probably went up when the Cardinals signed Drew to
a four-year, $7 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Drew's contract could be worth as much as $8.5 million over the
four years. On a per-year basis it's not much less than the $11.5
million over five years Drew was asking last year, when he was
drafted second overall by the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Drew refused to sign, and went back into the draft this year.
The fact he got close to what he originally wanted even after
sitting out a year concerned Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to prevent a guy sitting out a year, saying I can get
what I want anyway?'' Melvin said.
Pitching plans
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' tentative post-break rotation has John Burkett
pitching Thursday in Oakland, followed by Rick Helling on Friday,
Aaron Sele on Saturday, Darren Oliver on Sunday and Todd Van Poppel
on Monday in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That flip-flops Helling and Sele, on the assumption Sele will
pitch at least one inning in the All-Star Game on Tuesday night.
Hull impact
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' signing of free agent Brett Hull caused rumblings
down the freeway with the other team owned by Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he the player to be named later in the Bobby Witt deal?''
one front-office wag wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   One-liners aside, the signing of a premier free agent is another
indication Hicks is willing to do what it takes to put together a
winner. However, it doesn't mean there's help for the Rangers
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have patience,'' Oates said. ``There's no such
thing as a free agent in baseball in July. At least not a quality
one.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's the one-liners. Like the one from
Melvin as Hull was about to throw out the first pitch last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll sign a guy and let him drop the puck,'' Melvin
said.
Farm report
</P>
<P>
   Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific Coast League): The RedHawks defeated
Albuquerque, 7-2, Thursday, snapping a season-worst seven-game
losing streak. Terry Clark pitched six innings for the victory, and
Jeff Granger pitched the final three innings for his first save.
Rene Gonzales hit a grand slam and had five RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): The Drillers lost at Midland,
10-5, snapping a six-game winning streak. Ruben Mateo went 3-for-5
with two doubles to extend his hitting streak to 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Charlotte (Florida State League): The Rangers lost their
third consecutive game, 8-5, to Clearwater despite Shawn
Gallagher's 15th homer and three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): The Sand Gnats lost to
Charleston, 13-2. Reliever David Lundberg gave up nine runs _ five
earned _ in the ninth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
