<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-EVACUEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEEING TOWARD ... SOMEPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also FLA-FIRES and FLA-FIRES-WINTER) 
(mk) 
 By CINDY SWIRKO The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALATKA, Fla. _ This was ground zero for chaos Friday as
thousands of people fleeing fire endured a snail-paced procession
of vehicles full of pets, clothes and anything else that could be
crammed in or lashed on for the journey to someplace safe.
</P>
<P>
   Many evacuees said they had no idea where they were going.
Hotels rooms were as rare as rain showers, directions were scarce,
shelters were late in opening, families were split and worry was
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worrisome. It's scary. You don't know where you are going
and what you are going to go back to, if anything,'' said Pat Reed
of Palm Coast, standing on a Palatka sidewalk with her cockatiel,
Rascal, and dog, Rocky. ``I guess we'll find someplace, maybe
Gainesville, but we don't know the route.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Flagler County, at least 30,000 people, was ordered
evacuated Friday. They joined about 40,000 others who had been
ordered out of their homes in two other East Coast counties,
Brevard and Volusia, earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   State Road 100 west and Interstate 95 south were the only roads
open to Flagler evacuees. Palatka is the first city on SR 100 past
the Flagler County line.
</P>
<P>
   Some people left quickly, packing just a few belongings. But
State Road 100 resembled Route 66 during the Okie exodus of the
1930s Dust Bowl _ these modern trucks and cars loaded with lawn
mowers, bicycles, barbecue grills and lots of other household
items.
</P>
<P>
   Many were towing boats packed with belongings. Horse trailers
were also numerous, and it seemed every other car had a dog lapping
at hot air out the windows and cats ensconced in pet carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a guy with his riding lawn mower and his dog and I
thought, this guy knows his priorities,'' said Putnam County
sheriff's deputy G.L. Bowling, standing in the middle of State Road
100 to flag on motorists and answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just asking about motel rooms and directions.'' he
said. ``A lot of them just don't know where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Palatka hotel rooms filled up quickly. The Holiday Inn was
commandeered by the Federal Emergency Management Agency, forcing
owner-manager Connie Revels to deny rooms to reservation holders.
</P>
<P>
   Revels said she would open the banquet room for cots if
necessary to accommodate firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some firefighters here all week,'' Revels said.
``Last night, a lady firefighter got in late and saw the pool and
said she would love nothing better then a swim. The guard let her
in, even though the pool had been closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Laveda Frieze of Jesup, Ga., was one of those reservation
holders who found herself roomless. In fact, she was out of an
entire vacation because of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to go to the Pepsi 400 in Daytona, but that got
canceled because of the fires, `` she said. ``But I don't feel
sorry for myself. These fires are a terrible thing and the
firefighters need this hotel more than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people said they had gotten no information or wrong
information about the availability of shelters in Palatka.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience store parking lots were packed with evacuees
stocking up, exchanging information or looking for family and
friends. Hotel driveways were a parade of drive-by room seekers
who, instead of stopping, would call out to others about room
availability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a nightmare. What's most difficult is that we can't
find a motel,'' said Bertha Reddin of Palm Coast in a car with four
adults and two kids. ``They gave us 15 minutes to get out. We don't
even know where any shelters are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross did not establish a shelter in Palatka, though
several churches were taking in people and a school was open. The
Red Cross did open a shelter in Melrose, in Gainesville, and in
Waldo. Waldo had been evacuated by wildfires last month.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a place to stay was only part of the stress for
evacuees. Worry about what they left behind and will find when they
get back was also a heavy weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just grabbed what we could and threw it in the car,'' said
Pat Reed. ``What do you pick? How do you go through things and say,
`This treasure means more'? I'm worried about friends. I don't know
where any of them are. I just hope we have something to go back
to.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Swirko is a reporter for The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun.
This story was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
