<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves edge Mets, up lead to 10 1/2
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Mets might have come to make an issue of the NL
East, a dormant thing these past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Glavine winning his 12th, the Braves opened a weekend
series with a 3-2 victory that left them in their most commanding
position of the season. Atlanta increased the division lead to a
season-high 10 1/2 games, moved to a season-high 28 games above
.500 while the Mets lost for the fifth time in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made it a one-run game in a wild eighth with a run off
Dennis Martinez, who with two outs gave up an infield single to
Luiz Lopez, a bloop single to Carlos Baerga and an infield single
off the plate to Rey Ordonez that scored Lopez to make it 3-2. But
when Brian McRae singled hard to center, Andruw Jones preserved the
lead by throwing out Baerga at the plate for Jones' 10th assist of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (12-3) allowed one run through seven innings, permitting
eight hits while walking two and striking out four. He is now 8-1
in his last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets broke through with a run in the sixth off Glavine. With
two outs, Butch Huskey singled and Luis Lopez followed with an
infield single on a 3-2 count to bring up Baerga, who was hitting
.325 with runners in scoring position and two outs. He sent a
dribbler up the middle to bring in Huskey to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta scored twice in the fourth for a 3-0 lead and Glavine
was right in the middle of it. He followed up a Tony Graffanino
double with a single (his fourth hit in his last eight at-bats),
giving the Braves runners on first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss next brought in Graffanino on a suicide squeeze and
when Gerald Williams served an opposite-field single to right,
third-base coach Bobby Dews waved Glavine around. From right field,
Huskey's throw to the plate may have been in time but it
short-hopped catcher Mike Piazza and Glavine slid past for the
third run while the ball bounced to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves went out 1-0 in the third but also lost a run on a
call against Williams, who laid down a fine bunt on the left side
and wound up on second after third baseman Lopez's throw went all
the way to the tarp down the right field line. But plate umpire
Greg Bonin called Williams out for running inside the baseline _
both feet appeared to be in the infield grass as he neared first _
bringing an angry protest from Williams and manager Bobby Cox, who
argued that the ball was not catchable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
