<TEXT>
<P>
   Tough course doesn't faze Stacy
</P>
<P>
   By Glenn Sheeley
</P>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ No stranger to stout U.S. Women's Open
performances, Savannah native Hollis Stacy made her presence known
Friday with a 3-under-par 68 in the second round. While others were
surrendering to the Blackwolf Run Golf Course and cursing designer
Pete Dye, Stacy demonstrated how she become a three-time U.S.
Women's Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy started briskly in her morning round, making birdies at
the first two holes and repairing some damage from Thursday's
opening 76.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to play the weekend, especially because I've
missed the last two cuts (at the Open),'' said the 44-year-old
Stacy, a resident of La Quinta, Calif. ``Since I birdied the first
couple of holes, I felt more like I could just play golf and not
sweat bullets about the cut.''
</P>
<P>
   None of what bothered other players _ wind, length, tight
approaches, undulating greens _ seemed to faze Stacy Friday. She
birdied the 10th and 13th and bogeyed only the 17th, finishing 36
holes at 2-over 144. Had it not been for the local wildlife, Stacy
might have played a flawless round. She 3-putted the 17th green
after waiting for deer prints to be fixed there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' she said, ``he wasn't (going) spikeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy, who told the U.S. Golf Association this year that she did
not want an exemption, made it here as a qualifier from the
Broadmoor sectional in Colorado Springs. It's the 29th consecutive
Open appearance for Stacy, who has six USGA championships _ Opens
in 1977-78 and 1984; and U.S. girls junior titles in 1969-71.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy's play was more solid than her physical condition. She's
been on a daily regimen of strengthening and stretching exercises
since injuring her back in February ``from hitting lots of golf
balls with my new equipment, playing in cold weather and a lovely,
six-hour flight to Hawaii and lifting up a 40-pound golf bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stacy, ``I'm not 24 anymore, where I would walk out onto
the practice tee, hit one ball and go to the first tee. I have to
stretch for 15 minutes to hit a bucket of balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar impersonation
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the performance of another ACC player, Georgia
Tech's Matt Kuchar, in the Masters and U.S. Open, Duke senior-to-be
Jenny Chuasiriporn shot an even-par 71 for 143. She made the cut
last year, also, eventually tying for 56th at Pumpkin Ridge. ``It's
always nice to see another amateur do well,'' said the Curtis Cup
player from Baltimore, who met Kuchar playing junior golf. ``He is
actually a good friend of mine. It will be nice to see what he does
from here.'' Chuasiriporn's parents, who are natives of Thailand,
are in attendance, having closed their restaurant, the Bangkok
Palace, in Baltimore. ... Karen Noble eagled the par-4, 340-yard
first hole Friday, holing out from 110 yards with a 9-iron. ...
Early Georgia finishers: Cindy McCurdy, Newnan (77-74_151);
Stephanie Lowe, Lawrenceville (74-75 _ 149); Nanci Bowen, Tifton
(77-74 _ 151).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
