<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENSOPEN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie holds lead at halfway point
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ South Korea's 20-year-old Se Ri Pak, who already
owns a major championship in her rookie year on the LPGA Tour,
could be moving into position for another one. With a 1-under-par
70 Friday, Pak assumed a one-stroke lead at 3-under-par 139 after
36 holes of the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of a United States Golf Association event, par has
become an enviable score. Only eight players broke par on the
demanding Blackwolf Run Golf Course Friday and only two are under
par through 36 holes -- Pak and her closest challenger, Sweden's
Liselotte Neumann.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, 32, who made the 1988 U.S. Women's Open her first U.S.
win, shot her second straight 70 Friday and is a stroke behind Pak
at 2-under 140.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament drew a another record crowd Friday, about 26,000
people -- 7,000 more than the average for the tournament's second
day. With 47,000 attending for two days, the first major ever held
in Wisconsin has a chance to break last year's four-day Women's
Open record of 109,000.
</P>
<P>
   The only LPGA rookie to win two majors in the same season was
Juli Inkster, who captured the Nabisco Dinah Shore and du Maurier
Classic in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ''This course, you miss one shot and it is really difficult to
make a par or bogey,'' said Pak, who won the McDonald's LPGA
Championship in May. ''I have two days left. I do not know what
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament is over for Albany's Nancy Lopez, 41, who
collapsed to a 12-over-par 83 Friday and will miss the cut at
18-over 160. Also gone is defending champion Alison Nicholas
(78-78--156). The projected cut is 8-over-par 150.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she's doubting whether an Open win ever will
materialize, Lopez said, ''No, I don't want to think that. I've
never been a negative person. I just have to keep trying.''
</P>
<P>
   First-round co-leader Laura Davies, who shot a 68 Thursday,
slipped to a 75 Friday and is four shots back at 143. After a round
that included two water hazard penalties, Davies, after a restless
Thursday night, was pleased with her position.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't sleep all that well last night,'' Davies said. ''I've
won 52 times and here I am worrying about a cut from the leading
position. But that's what this game does. It works on your
mind....I supposed it's just because it (the Open) means so much to
me. When you miss four of the last five cuts over here, it tears
you completely apart and just destroys your confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Neumann, ''I'm extremely happy just being on contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Three shots off the lead at 142 are Dottie Pepper, with a second
71; Scotland's Mhairi McKay, whose 70 came after a back-nine 32;
Chris Johnson (72-70); and amateur Brenda Corrie Kuehn, who bogeyed
the 18th hole for 72.
</P>
<P>
   Statesboro native Dale Eggeling (71-72) is in a group of five
players at 143, a shot better than three-time champion Hollis Stacy
of Savannah, whose 68 was the day's low round.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time champion Annika Sorenstam is at 146 after a 75..
</P>
<P>
   First-round co-leader Kim Williams dropped to an 81 after an
opening 68.
</P>
<P>
   Seven groups failed to finish play because of darkness and will
complete their second rounds at 6:45 a.m. today, followed by the
cut to the top 60 and ties. Play was suspended earlier for 51
minutes because of lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
