<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko visits team but still feels pain
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Ryan Klesko dropped by the clubhouse Friday afternoon
and, following a routine of bed-rest and a diet of sherbet, did not
appear to be ready to lace up the cleats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling better,'' he said, four days after his
appendectomy. ``The doctors want me to walk around so I was up
doing that for about an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be OK once he gets a little food in him,'' said manager
Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's return remains unsettled. Though Cox had anticipated
getting his left fielder back for the first post-All-Star series in
Florida, Klesko said he did not expect to even try batting practice
until next Thursday, when that series is scheduled to open at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question,'' Klesko said. ``Yesterday, I couldn't
get out of bed. I don't know. I'm feeling a lot of pain. I'm not
supposed to do a lot for a couple more days.''
</P>
<P>
   He walks very stiffly, in part due to the three small incisions,
and says most discomfort comes from ``laughing, coughing and
burping,'' which would impose deeply into Klesko's daily routine.
He will spend the All-Star break at his North Palm Beach home and
then join the team in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if doctors saved the appendix for Klesko for a souvenir,
team trainer Dave Pursley said, ``They couldn't find a jar big
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Family affair
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss returned home Thursday night to find son Brody, 3,
was also returning home after 13 nights at Scottish Rite Childrens
Medical Center, where he fought off a serious E. coli infection.
The family was exploring with doctors the chance Brody might be
able to attend the All-Star game in Denver next week, where his
father will be the starting shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a while until he's his old self,'' said
Weiss, ``but the worst is behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth day . . .
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wohlers did not pitch for the Richmond Braves Friday night
and Atlanta officials were glad of it. Wohlers made a third
straight appearance against Charlotte Thursday and gave up another
run, walking two, striking out two and allowing a runner to score
on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish (Richmond pitching coach Bill Fischer) will handle it
from now on,'' said Cox, ``because if you leave it up to Mark,
he'll want to pitch every night. If his arm falls off, then you've
got nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   After three outings in Richmond, Wohlers worked 2 2/3 innings,
allowed seven runs on five hits while striking out four and walking
six. He has also thrown two wild pitches. This is hardly the stat
line of a pitcher who is close to returning to the major leagues.
The Braves have no clue when to expect him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has the answer to that,'' said general
manager John Schuerholz. ``What we're going to do is keep throwing
him for as long as he can, until he gets to the point where, in our
opinion, he'll be a useful amenity for us. To be honest with you,
Mark will know the right time before we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
