<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood back on fat-free diet
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The sabbatical was brief but well-spent.
</P>
<P>
   A few encouraging side sessions, no unnecessary overtime out of
the bullpen and a diagnosis by Dr. Leo should restore Kevin
Millwood's fat-free fastball.
</P>
<P>
   After missing one turn in the rotation, Millwood returns to the
mound tonight for the first time in 10 days and the last time
before the All-Star break. In his first career start against the
Mets, he also hopes to return to the form that produced a 7-1 start
before his ERA jumped a run-and-a-half in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody goes up and down during the season,'' said Millwood.
``I think that's what separates young pitchers from (Greg) Maddux.
Consistency, that's what I've got to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first two months of his first full big-league
season, he consistently impressed and improved. A May 25 win
against the Cubs was Millwood's fourth straight and left him 7-1,
with a 3.27 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning with a May 30 shelling in Chicago (three innings,
nine hits, six earned runs), Millwood has lost three of his last
five decisions, his ERA ballooning to 4.78. In those five starts,
he's allowed 32 hits (including six homers) and 23 runs (all
earned) in 23 1/3 innings, an ERA of 8.87.
</P>
<P>
   The last two outings have been painful. Millwood lasted just 1
1/3 innings in Montreal June 19, giving up seven runs on seven hits
(two homers). On June 24, he got a quick 2-0 lead over the Yankees
and led 2-1 entering the fourth inning before they knocked him out
with four runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun when you're having outings like that,'' said
Millwood, who was charged with five earned runs on seven hits.
``But everybody has 'em. Not always two in a row, but everybody's
had 'em. I think it has something to do with not knowing how to get
out of some situations.''
</P>
<P>
   And even more with a fat fastball. ``My fastball's cutting a
little bit, coming over the plate,'' said Millwood, who was
bypassed in the rotation when the Braves had an off-day last Monday
and became available for spot bullpen duty the next two nights in
St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to have a couple of days off, to work in side
sessions on my mechanics,'' he said. ``Just trying to get
everything in sync.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Dr. Leo. ``His arm angle was too low,'' said pitching
coach Leo Mazzone. ``Because he's striding out too far, getting all
spread out. That causes him to go underneath the ball.'' Thus
causing his fastball to stay up, and fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying too hard. When you do that, you drop your
backside, which makes his pitches up or out _ fat,'' said Mazzone.
``He got boxed around in Montreal. His way of trying to get better
is with super stuff and super control. When you try to do that, you
overexert, you muscle up, you get spread out.''
</P>
<P>
   You get hit hard. Now, Mazzone says, ``He looks fine. All
pitchers go through those things over a period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying not to overthink the whole thing, not make it
something it's not,'' Millwood said. ``Just stick to basics and get
back on a roll again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
