<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS GET 12 HITS BUT LOSE TO BRAVES, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The all-star game break cannot come soon enough for
the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when it looked as though the Mets' offense, which
produced 19 runs in the previous two games, might be getting on
track, Edgardo Alfonzo was scratched from the starting lineup
shortly before New York's first meeting Friday night with Atlanta
because of soreness behind his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mets banged out 12 hits, eight against the starter,
Tom Glavine, but lost, 3-2, to the Braves at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Andruw Jones preserved the victory for the Braves
in the eighth inning when he threw out Carlos Baerga at the plate
as he was trying to score on a Brian McRae single with two out.
</P>
<P>
   It was surprising that the Mets were even in the game by then,
after they had failed to get to Glavine early. The New Yorkers left
the bases loaded in the top of the first and could not score with
runners on first and second with one out in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Glavine (12-3), who allowed just one run in his
seven innings, became stronger as the game went along. And then,
after the Mets came up one run short against the 43-year-old
right-hander Dennis Martinez in the eighth, the Braves had pulled a
season-high 10 1/2 games in front of the second-place Mets, who
more than likely have only the wild card to look forward to the
rest of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Mets (44-37), who have dropped five of their last
seven games, can regroup after the break, which begins this Monday.
Because there has been a lack of continuity to their lineup,
because of injuries and trades, almost since the season began.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe Todd Hundley's presence, which could manifest
itself as soon as next week, can bring some stability to a talented
group that, aside from its starting pitching, has underachieved for
much of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Bernard Gilkey _ one of the main underachievers _
hit lead-off for the first time this season and only the third time
in two years. Once Alfonzo, who is listed as day to day, went down,
Benny Agbayani batted second in the injured third baseman's place.
He singled off Glavine with one out in the top of the first, before
being thrown out on an attempted steal of second for the second out
of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud, who has caught fire again in the three games he has
hit in front of Mike Piazza, followed with a double inside of
third, before Glavine issued one of those so-called
``unintentional'' intentional walks to Piazza to give the Mets
runners on first and second. Butch Huskey then walked, and the Mets
had a chance at a big inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Luis Lopez, who was playing at third for Alfonzo, grounded
back to Glavine to end the threat. And then with the teams still
scoreless in the top of the third, Huskey grounded into a
second-to-short-to-first double play to end the inning, as
consecutive one-out singles by Olerud and Piazza went for naught.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta responded with a run off Brian Bohanon _ he was making a
spot start of his own in place of the injured Al Leiter _ in the
bottom of the third. And it was almost if the Braves needed
something controversial to get them going.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, the former Yankee Gerald Williams appeared to beat
out a bunt, as Bohanon threw wildly past John Olerud at first. But
with Williams standing on second thanks to the apparent error, home
plate umpire Greg Bonin ruled that Williams had run inside the
first-base line and ruled him out, bringing an angry Bobby Cox out
of the Atlanta dugout to argue.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets won the argument, but lost the battle. Chipper Jones
followed with a two-out double. After an intentional walk to Andres
Galarraga, Javy Lopez singled Jones home. And it was 1-0 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta scored twice more in the fourth on a Tony Graffanino
double, the first of Glavine's two singles, a perfectly executed
suicide squeeze bunt from Walt Weiss to score Graffanino, and a
single by Williams to score Glavine. The pitcher beat Huskey's
throw from right field, which skipped away from Piazza at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, it was 3-0 Braves. And now, the Mets' only hope
was to get to the Atlanta bullpen, which has been just as shaky as
the Mets' pen this season.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, the Mets pushed across a sixth-inning run against
Glavine with a two-out rally that was capped by a run-scoring
Baerga single (both Baerga and McRae _ who are switch-hitters _
batted left-handed against the left-handed Glavine Friday evening).
</P>
<P>
   Then came Martinez _ and the Mets' best chance to tie. With two
out, Lopez reached on an infield single, and Baerga moved him to
third with a bloop single to left. Rey Ordonez followed with a chop
over the mound for a run-scoring infield single, and it was 3-2.
But Jones threw the head-first sliding Baerga out on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga argued. So did manager Bobby Valentine. But this time,
the argument went against the Mets. And so soon would the game.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Mets announced they have reached a verbal agreement with
outfielder Jason Tyner, their No. 1 pick in this summer's draft
(21st overall). A 21-year-old left-handed hitter from Texas A&AMP;M, he
will sign his contract pending a physical in Manhattan next
Wednesday. Tyner will join the Mets here and take batting practice
with them before Saturday night's game ... As expected, the Mets
announced that 19-year-old left-hander Geoff Goetz is the player to
be named later in the May 22 trade that brought Mike Piazza to the
Mets from Florida. Goetz, the Mets' top selection in last season's
draft (sixth overall), was 5-4 with a 3.96 earned run average in 15
starts with Class A Columbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
