<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     07-03 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT ORIOLES, 3-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baltimore Manager Ray Miller said he wouldn't
hesitate to use Armando Benitez in Yankee Stadium, in spite of
Benitez's status of Public Enemy No. 1 following the brawl the
relief pitcher instigated with the Yankees on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller would not use him in a situation tailored for Benitez
on Friday night, and the Yankees took advantage to win the game in
the ninth inning, 3-2, when Scott Brosius singled home Chad Curtis
from third base with one out. Andy Pettitte pitched nine innings
for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 59-20. Should the Yankees sweep Baltimore here
this weekend, as they did in May, they would be 61-20 and match the
best 81-game records in the 20th century, tying the 1902 Pittsburgh
Pirates and the 1907 Chicago Cubs. Even if the Yankees won just 41
of their remaining 83 games _ less than .500 ball at 41-42 _ they
would win 100 games for the first time since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines pinch-hit for Darryl Strawberry to start the ninth
inning for the Yankees, and the Baltimore left-handed reliever
Jesse Orosco plunked him in the thigh, the first time in two years
Orosco has hit a batter. Curtis chopped a grounder to the right of
Mike Bordick at shortstop, a ball that could have resulted in a
force play at second. But Bordick fumbled the hop _ the play was
scored a single _ and the Yankees had first and second and nobody
out.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Sveum pinch-hit for Ricky Ledee and bunted into a force
play at third. With four right-handed hitters in a row due to bat,
it was a natural situation to use the right-handed Benitez. Miller
stayed with Orosco.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, leading off second, took advantage of Orosco's
deliberate delivery and swiped third base. Miller went to the mound
to discuss the situation, with Benitez ready in the bullpen. But
Miller stayed with Orosco _ though he needed a strikeout _ and
Brosius popped a single over second base, to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken opened the Oriole ninth with a walk and was removed
for a pinch-runner, Jeff Reboulet, churning up memories from May 1,
1996, when Manny Alexander pinch-ran for Ripken in a game against
the Yankees, the first time Ripken had been replaced with the
outcome of a game still in doubt during his record-breaking
consecutive game streak.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander immediately was picked off that night _ and Reboulet
was promptly picked off by Pettitte Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk that the Orioles' front office will begin major
restructuring and trade Roberto Alomar and possibly Rafael Palmeiro
later this month and try to inject some youth into its aged roster.
</P>
<P>
   On a given night, in a given inning, however, the Orioles can be
formidable, particularly when Mike Mussina, their ace, has a good
fastball and a darting curveball, as he did Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   He held the Yankees to just six hits in the first seven innings,
often making them look foolish. Scott Brosius struck out on three
pitches with a runner at second and one out in the second, and
Mussina zipped a two-strike fastball past the next hitter, Joe
Girardi, for a strikeout. Girardi, normally reserved, threw his
helmet and bat angrily, barking at home plate umpire Marty Foster
about the call.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill chased a neck-high fastball in the third, Tino
Martinez waved weakly at a curveball in the fourth; Mussina had a
2-1 lead, but that one-run mountain seemed to steepen with every
strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   When Chad Curtis batted with two out in the Yankee fourth,
having doubled in his first at-bat, he fell behind 1-2 after he
fouled off a fastball. But he kept fouling off pitches, four in a
row. Mussina tried getting him to chase a high fastball, Curtis
didn't. On the eighth pitch of the at-bat, Mussina threw a
belt-high pitch that appeared to be a fastball and Curtis _ not
overswinging, keeping his weight back _ drove the ball to deep
right center, where it cleared the wall by a few feet, tying the
score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had retired the first six Baltimore hitters, breezing
through the first two innings with only 22 pitches. But the Orioles
jumped on him in the third, pulling inside pitches down the lines.
Joe Carter opened by looping a single to left and Chris Hoiles
smacked a 2-0 fastball into the left field corner for a double,
Carter stopping at third.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick then muscled a high fastball to deep left center,
where Ricky Ledee ran down the ball against the fence. Carter
tagged up and scored, Hoiles ambled to third. Two batters later,
B.J. Surhoff smashed a double past the first baseman Tino Martinez,
and Hoiles scored, giving Baltimore a 2-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees swept Baltimore here in May, and as badly as the
Orioles have played, they must have had some sense of doom in the
very first inning, after the Yankees scored the game's first run in
their first turn at bat. Derek Jeter hit Mussina's first pitch to
right field for a single _ before the game, Jeter had said he would
swing at the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Sojo was next, filling in for sore-kneed Chuck Knoblauch,
in Sojo's first appearance since June 21. Sojo faked a bunt on
Mussina's first pitch, and then perfectly executed a hit-and-run:
Jeter broke for second, Sojo hit the ball behind him, through the
first base hole, and Jeter scampered to third.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neill drove a fly to deep left, Jeter tagged up and
scored. All very neat, efficient, the sort of stuff you expect from
a team that has won nearly three-quarter of its games.
</P>
</TEXT>
